<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-JAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT JAYS, 10-6  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Logic says Jason Grimsley is not really this good. His
first 14 years in pro ball were undistinguished. He won fewer than
half his 149 minor league decisions, and before this year, his
earned run average in the majors was 5.39.
</P>
<P>
   So why is it that at age 31 Grimsley has become unhittable?
</P>
<P>
   He relieved Andy Pettitte with runners on base and the tying run
at the plate Friday night, and while throwing one type of pitch
almost exclusively _ a fastball that sinks a foot or so _ Grimsley
pinched off a Toronto rally before the Yankees hitters blew open
the game with four runs in the seventh inning en route to a 10-6
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter had three doubles and a sacrifice fly and has
reached base in every game this season, Scott Brosius drove in
three runs and Joe Girardi had two of the team's 16 hits. The 1999
Yankees are emerging from the shadows of '98: they have won six of
their last eight games, their offense is stirring, they are playing
terrific defense, running the bases aggressively and getting great
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley represents the significant accomplishment of Don
Zimmer's tenure as the Yankees' interim manager. When Jeff Nelson
got hurt and Mike Stanton pitched erratically, Zimmer ignored
Grimsley's pedigree and gave him the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two months into the season, Grimsley's stuff is as dominant
as any pitcher's in the American League. Mariano Rivera blew away
opposing hitters with his high fastball in 1996; like Rivera,
Grimsley is throwing an overpowering pitch, but his dives in the
strike zone. Opposing batters are hitting .150 against Grimsley,
and he is 4-0 with a 1.98 e.r.a.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it's like trying to hit a sinker like that _ it's
like trying to hit a shot-put,'' said Chuck Knoblauch, who laughed
when asked about the movement of Grimsley's fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's Homer Bush said, ``It was the best sinker I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored three runs in the top of the sixth inning to
assume a 6-3 advantage, but Pettitte (3-2) was nearing 100 pitches
and allowed back-to-back hits in the bottom of the sixth. With one
out, Yankees Manager Joe Torre waved to the bullpen for Grimsley.
</P>
<P>
   What Grimsley is doing could not be more simple. He grips the
ball with his right index and middle fingers close together,
between the seams, his fingertips resting in the spot where a
player might sign an autograph, and he throws as hard as he can.
There is no mystery. There is no deception. The hitters read
scouting reports and see videotape, and they know that he throws
his sinker 95 percent of the time. They cannot hit it.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Lennon struck out on six pitches, Bush whiffed on four,
all sinking fastballs. Grimsley looked like a 15-year-old giant
pitching against tee-ball players.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush walked away from the plate, stunned, he turned and asked
the home plate umpire, Marty Foster, if any of the pitches Grimsley
threw him were strikes. Later, Bush recalled his at-bat against
Grimsley, holding his hand waist high and said, ``The ball started
out here.'' Bush lowered his hand to just below his knees. ``And
went to here.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley's sinker is unusual in that it moves vertically,
straight down, rather than at a downward 45-degree angle, like that
of Ramiro Mendoza. The movement on Grimsley's pitch is so violent
that scouts sitting behind home plate have asked one another if
Grimsley is throwing a split-fingered fastball. Seattle Manager Lou
Piniella accused Grimsley of scuffing the ball, which is illegal.
Boston's Jose Offerman grabbed the ball after striking out against
Grimsley on Wednesday and checked it for cuts. There were no marks,
no spit; there was nothing to be found. ``It's like a dry
spitter,'' Stanton said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Mel Queen, Toronto's pitching coach: ``If the ball is being
scuffed, he ain't doing it; somebody's doing it for him, because I
was watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley got two ground-ball outs in the seventh, and with a
no-ball, two-strike count, Shannon Stewart looked for a sinker, and
Grimsley spun a curveball for the third strike. Unfair, players
like to say.
</P>
<P>
   He had always had good stuff, Torre remembered, but it was
always a question of consistency. Rather than throw three or four
different pitches, Grimsley began throwing his sinker on almost
every pitch last year, after moving to the bullpen. Recently, he
began to work with a sports psychologist, who has given Grimsley
several specific keys to think about, to focus on, as he pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley did not pitch in the majors in 1997 or '98, and the
Yankees signed him to a minor league contract before the '99
season, giving him a $10,000 signing bonus. It's safe to say he's
been worth the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``His sinker is unbelievable,'' Girardi said. ``The movement is
so hard, and it's so late.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter said, ``His pitches are moving so much right now, he
probably has no idea where it's going.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Toronto right fielder Shawn Green was hit by a pitch from Andy
Pettitte in the fourth inning Friday night and sustained a small
fracture in the wrist.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are expected to trade catcher Mike Figga shortly.
The Los Angeles Dodgers may or may not be his destination, but the
Dodgers want to trade first baseman Eric Karros and shift the
struggling catcher Todd Hundley to first base. In preparing for
that, the Dodgers could be in the market for a catcher.
</P>
</TEXT>
