<HEADLINE>
ALL THE LITTLE THINGS ADD UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Los Angeles Dodgers third baseman Adrian Beltre
back-pedaled on a grounder and Atlanta scored two runs. Second
baseman Eric Young dropped a ball on a play in which manager Davey
Johnson thought a baserunner would be thrown out stealing.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers won't be able to put together a significant winning
stretch until the little things are executed properly, and
Johnson's patience is waning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't give runs away,'' Johnson said after the Dodgers' 4-2
loss to the Braves on Friday. ``I thought (catcher Todd) Hundley
had the guy at second and (Young) drops the ball. Beltre retreats
on a ball we could have a double play on. We have to make those
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Both plays came in the fifth inning when the Braves scored twice
to take a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never get mad at a guy for making a physical error,''
Johnson said. ``But (Beltre's) play, that's a borderline mental
error because he retreats. We have some learning to do, some
growing to do. But we have to get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of the Dodgers' losses on the current nine-game road can be
attributed to not making the little plays at a crucial time.
</P>
<P>
   The first loss came in Cincinnati when Hundley dropped a third
strike and threw wildly to first. The problem was compounded when
first base Eric Karros couldn't get to a grounder to his right that
led to two in a 3-2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it's been so far on this road trip,'' Karros said.
``Before then it was a little pitching, some other little things.
We haven't put it all together. It seems like it's one thing or
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Dejection in Vero Beach: The news that Florida governor Jeb Bush
vetoed a bill Thursday that would appropriate $7.5 million in funds
to the city of Vero Beach and Indian River County and aid greatly
in keeping the Dodgers in Dodgertown brought disappointment to the
area.
</P>
<P>
   It leaves the local government with $13 million worth of funding
for a project estimated to cost more than $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stunning,'' said Dodgertown managing director Craig
Callan, a Vero Beach resident. ``Completely out of nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general counsel Sam Fernandez and director of business
development Fred Coons will travel to Vero Beach next week to meet
with city and county officials. But Callan, an employee of the
Dodgers, said the outlook wasn't very good for keeping the Dodgers
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to meet with city and county officials to make
sure we haven't left any stones unturned,'' Callan said. ``When the
$7.5 million was identified (as being a possibility) I thought we
were heading in the right direction with the city and state. Now,
it makes it a lot tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   It could make it virtually impossible. Callan said when the
meeting takes place it could be a situation in which the city and
county say they've done all they can do for the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a spokesperson for Fort McDowell Indian Community
president Bernadine Boyd said it was possible the Yavapai Tribe,
located near Phoenix, could cut the cost from $50 million to near
$35 million for a proposed spring training complex for the Dodgers.
Most of the expenses would be cut if the project didn't include a
second set of practice fields and amenities for a second
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Precautionary X-rays on Dodgers
outfielder Todd Hollandsworth's ailing rib cage were negative. He's
expected to miss the remaining to games against Atlanta after
straining his rib cage while swinging Thursday in Cincinnati....
Dodgers utility infielder Jose Vizcaino, on the disabled list with
a left hamstring strain, remains in Los Angeles rehabbing. He can
be activated Tuesday in Pittsburgh but Johnson said he's not sure
whether that will happen. ``He's still just jogging,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
