A5827 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-RICE-LOSES-TEX     05-29 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-RICE-LOSES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK _ Although Jerry Augustine spent nine seasons pitching
for the Milwaukee Brewers, it is doubtful that anything ever moved
him to the descriptive heights he reached yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we're a little nervous ... you know, being around all
these media people,'' he said. ``Normally, we got one guy that
writes something every four or five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second, this is probably the biggest moment in the history of
this school _ ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach spoke after watching his Wisconsin-Milwaukee Panthers
roll to a stunning 8-4 victory over top-seeded Rice in the opening
round of the NCAA regionals.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls (52-12) came into the tournament as the top-ranked team
in the nation in two of the four major polls. The Panthers (31-27),
who lost their first eight games and got off to a 1-11 start, are
the first team in the history of the Midwestern Collegiate
Conference to make the NCAA playoffs. They are the first team from
the state of Wisconsin to enter postseason play in a half-century.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher-designated hitter Chad Sadowski, who had three of his
team's 15 hits and threw eight shutout innings after the Owls
scored four times in the first, acknowledged that ``this was
definitely the biggest game of my college career. I threw the last
three innings on adrenalin.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss marked the first time in five regionals that Rice has
lost the opening game, and broke an eight-game winning streak for
the Owls at Dan Law Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were ready to play, but that guy pitched a heck
of a game and they did a great job hitting the ball,'' said Rice
coach Wayne Graham, who withheld staff ace Mario Ramos for the
presumably more crucial second game of the tournament. The Panthers
drove starter Jeff Nichols (13-3) from the mound in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kinda fired us up, knowing that they underestimated us,''
said right-fielder Brett Huebner, who led the Panthers' attack with
four hits. ``During the first inning, I was thinking, `Oh, no _ I
don't want to end up saying we're just happy to be here.' But after
we got out of that and started getting a few hits, I felt real
good.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Sadowski, who kept mowing down the Owls. Meanwhile, the
Panthers kept scoring runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what his pitch count was, but I told him after
the sixth he'd thrown 40 and not to worry about it,'' Augustine
said. ``Seriously, what this tells us is that we can play with
anyone.''
Texas Tech 5, Rutgers 2
</P>
<P>
   Defense was the key in the second game _ Texas Tech (41-15) had
it, Rutgers (37-20) didn't, and the Red Raiders walked off with a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we may have found ourselves,'' said Tech coach Larry
Hays, who practiced his team hard for a week after going 0-2 in the
Big 12 tournament. ``I thought we played tremendous defense, and I
liked our approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers starter James Wilson pitched well but made throwing
errors on three bunts that led to three unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   Tech got stellar play in the outfield, as center fielder Marco
Cunningham made three outstanding catches, left fielder Ryan Ruiz
killed a rally with a diving catch, and right fielder Chris Sampson
picked up a potential single and threw the batter out at first.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Wright (10-4) gave up two unearned runs while becoming the
first pitcher in Tech history to hit double figures in victories
for three consecutive years.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
