<SLUG> BC-OFFICER-DUI-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-POLICE OFFICER TO PLEAD GUILTY TO CRASH THAT KILLED ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRACY JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A former Bellevue police officer will plead guilty to
charges of vehicular homicide and vehicular assault for a deadly
car wreck that stunned the community in the first hours of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Thomas, 29, told the Seattle Post-Intelligencer Friday he
accepts responsibility for the Jan. 1 wreck that killed one
passenger in his car and left the other, a Washington State Patrol
trooper, facing a grueling rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas knows he will spend time in prison. King County
prosecutors want him to serve four years.
</P>
<P>
   He will live with the guilt of lives devastated and the nagging
wish he had called a cab.
</P>
<P>
   He never again can be a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who will enter his guilty plea in King County Superior
Court Tuesday morning, wants people to realize an alcohol-related
tragedy could happen to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a police officer, I was trained to know what the effect of
alcohol was, and I made a bad judgment, anyway,'' he said. ``It
doesn't matter who you are _ if you get behind the wheel when
you've been drinking, you take the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was out to celebrate the New Year and the birthday of his
best friend, State Patrol Trooper Jeremy Reid. He was driving that
night, and he thought he was being careful.
</P>
<P>
   He finished his last drink three hours before he left a Seattle
party early Jan. 1, he said. He felt sober, and he even tested
himself with the portable breath test he used in his job as a
Bellevue police officer.
</P>
<P>
   It was not enough to avert tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he ``had a couple drinks'' at his house on New
Year's Eve before he and his friends, Reid and Reid's childhood
friend, Brian Grooms of Ohio, went to a dance party promoted by a
Seattle radio station at the Seattle Center.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he had ``a couple'' more drinks _ he would not say
what kind _ and they stayed for several hours. When they decided to
leave, Thomas said they passed around the portable breath test.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he blew a 0.07 percent, which is just below the
state's legal limit for intoxication. He said both of his friends
failed and unanimously affirmed Thomas would drive.
</P>
<P>
   He admits he was speeding _ prosecutors say he may have doubled
the posted 40-mph speed limit _ when his 1998 Dodge Stratus veered
out of control on south Bellevue's Coal Creek Parkway and crossed
the center line just after 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   It smashed into a Ford Expedition driven by John Bell, a
Bellevue man police say also was intoxicated. Bell was not hurt,
but his wife suffered neck and leg injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Grooms, 26, who was riding in the back seat, died at the scene.
Reid was so badly hurt he remained in a coma for 19 days.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas suffered broken ribs and a concussion, and a Bellevue
police officer who responded said his off-duty colleague smelled of
liquor and appeared intoxicated, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   A blood test indicated Thomas' blood-alcohol level was 0.08
roughly two hours after the crash. By new legal standards that had
just gone into effect at midnight, prosecutors say Thomas was
drunk.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for his guilty plea, King County prosecutors agreed
to recommend that Thomas spend four years in prison, the middle of
the approximate 3{- to 4{-year standard sentencing range.
</P>
<P>
   A sentencing hearing probably will be scheduled during the next
two months.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' attorney, John Wolfe, said he will ask the judge for a
sentence lower than the standard range. Victims' consent can be
mitigating in the eyes of the law, said Wolfe, who could argue Reid
and Grooms knew Thomas had been drinking when they climbed into his
car.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Thomas' apparent alcohol level being near the legal
borderline, he said did not want to go to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was responsible for the accident, and knowing that, it would
not be right to fight it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has little recollection of the predawn wreck, which stunned
the Bellevue Police Department and the community. He has only
blurred memories of an ambulance ride and awakening, painfully, at
Seattle's Harborview Medical Center to the bitter reality he'll
live with the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   The guilt still racks his thoughts and occasionally steals his
sleep at night. He has told both Reid and Grooms' mother he is
sorry.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of being an officer and being involved in the first
alcohol-related fatality under new state drunken-driving laws
thrust Thomas into the spotlight _ and onto the side of the law he
thought he'd never be.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life I wanted to help people, and now to be considered
a criminal by society _ it's tough,'' he said, slowly shaking his
head.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after the crash, Thomas resigned from the Bellevue
Police Department, where he had worked 2{ years.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a solemn interview yesterday in his attorney's Seattle
office, Thomas' eyes lighted up to talk about Reid _ and the latest
hurdle in his recovery. Friday, Reid was released in a wheelchair
from Ohio State University Medical Center and allowed to go home
with his mother, who lives in the small town of Washington Court
House.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was thrilled Reid, his best friend whom he calls every
few days, was improving. Reid is learning to walk with a cane and
will undergo extensive physical and speech therapy, according to
State Patrol spokesman Capt. Eric Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeremy's stubborn. He'll walk again, and he says he's going to
come back and be a trooper,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and Reid met several years ago at Fort Lewis in Pierce
County, where they were stationed in the Army. A strong friendship
and playful rivalry grew out of their shared love of sports.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Reid's mother would discuss her son's condition only
through Robertson. But she has previously expressed support, not
blame, for her son's friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other punishment or prison time will change the life
sentence Eric will live with,'' Carol Reid said in a statement in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Thomas has picked up a few odd jobs. Once envisioning
becoming Bellevue's police chief someday, he now does not know what
his life will hold. ``I made a terrible mistake,'' he said. ``I
wish I could change it, but I can't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
