<SLUG> BC-MEDVET-ANIMALS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN PETS HURT, TIME IS OF THE ESSENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSION, KAN. _ It is 7 p.m. Wednesday when the clinic
loudspeaker blares: ``Tech to the front!'' a call that often
signifies an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Hamill, an assistant, runs from the clinic's treatment
room, returning in moments with a small animal carrying case.
</P>
<P>
   Inside it is a beautiful white cat named Cody. The owner,
Roseann Granda, had raced to the clinic when Cody suddenly
collapsed after a dramatic hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   At Mission MedVet such dire moments are almost routine.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic treats animals hit by bullets and hit by cars. In
recent days it treated a dog with a locust thorn lodged deeply in
its back; a dog that swallowed a fish hook; a cat with a jagged
piece of chain-link fence through its face; a puppy that ate fly
poison.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the treatment room, two vets, Katherine Spry and Robin
Wall, hover over the semi-conscious white cat. Wall quickly shaves
the cat's left front leg with clippers and takes his vital signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lousy arterial pulse,'' she says to Spry. ``What do we know
about this case?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 8 years old. He had his vaccinations today. No other
history of recent illness. It may be anaphylaxis (an allergic
reaction) caused by the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Spry looks up suddenly. ``Whoa, the pulse just plummeted,'' she
says. ``It's down to 80 from 180.''
</P>
<P>
   Blister packs containing disposable medical equipment start
flying around the table as the vets and technicians reach for
tubes, syringes, needles, medication bottles and bandages.
</P>
<P>
   Wall injects atrapine to stimulate the cat's heart. She inserts
an IV shunt in the cat's left rear leg. Hamill holds an oxygen mask
over Cody's face. Wall attaches EKG monitor leads.
</P>
<P>
   Spry takes blood samples and rapidly runs a series of tests.
</P>
<P>
   The cat's blood glucose is so low the lab machine cannot measure
it accurately. The blood protein level is at one-sixth the normal
level. The red cell count is low and dropping.
</P>
<P>
   Wall injects glucose, drips lactated ringer's solution through
the IV. She begins a blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's bleeding into its gut,'' she says. ``I want to
call in another specialist.''
</P>
<P>
   She calls Janet Peterson, a veterinary internist and a senior
member of the clinic staff. Peterson arrives at 8:32. She stares at
the cat for a long time. She feels his pulses, orders an X-ray,
injects steroids, shakes her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very strange,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later the cat vomits blood. His temperature drops to
95, five degrees below normal. He is hemorrhaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we may be seeing a syndrome called D.I.C.
(disseminating intravascular coagulation),'' Peterson says. ``That
means the cat has developed so many small clots that it's used up
its clotting factor. Now it's bleeding everywhere. This is a
dramatic case.''
</P>
<P>
   At 9:45, a technician places the cat in an incubator to fight
the lowering body temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson attends other cases, but always returns to the
incubator. There she paces back and forth for almost an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what else to do for this poor cat,'' she murmurs
to herself. ``I don't know what else to do.'' New trend
</P>
<P>
   Mission MedVet was created six years ago by a veterinary surgeon
named David Allen. It is one of four emergency animal treatment
clinics in greater Kansas City and represents a new trend in animal
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the last 10 years or so, you didn't find many veterinary
specialists outside universities,'' said Robin Wall, a specialist
in critical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're set up to handle nighttime emergencies and to treat
referrals from other veterinarians.''
</P>
<P>
   The clinic, which has two operating rooms, a radiology
department and a special procedures room, is staffed by 10
veterinarians, seven of whom are board-certified specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the problems it sees are considered life threatening.
Many involve toxins. Puppy in trouble
</P>
<P>
   At 9:15 Monday evening, Randa Rawlins of Kansas City knew her
puppy, Callie Jo, was in real danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was cowering in a corner, foaming at the mouth,'' Rawlins
said. ``She seemed terrified. She was having trouble walking. She
was trembling all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Rawlins carried the dog, an 11-month-old border collie mix, down
to her Ford Explorer and drove rapidly to Mission MedVet.
</P>
<P>
   The veterinarian on duty that night was Thomas Mick. He examined
the dog immediately. She seemed to be in the throes of a seizure:
intense spasms, disorientation, rolling eyeballs, constant
salivation.
</P>
<P>
   Her temperature was 107.9. The normal temperature for a dog is
between 100 and 102 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Mick suspected a toxic substance and questioned Rawlins
carefully. Could the puppy have eaten anything unusual?
</P>
<P>
   ``We put out some slug bait...'' Rawlins said, and even as she
spoke those words she saw what she later described as ``bright
lights going on in Dr. Mick's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mick knew instantly that Callie Jo had ingested a poison called
metaldehyde.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the main ingredient in slug and snail bait,'' he said.
``And it induces symptoms that look exactly like a seizure. But
what's really happening is that the poison is blocking certain
muscle inhibitor cells, and so the animal's muscle fibers begin
firing constantly and uncontrollably.''
</P>
<P>
   The animal's intense, ceaseless muscle spasms generate
tremendous body heat, a kind of self-induced hyperthermia that can
exceed 110 degrees. Untreated, the condition causes severe brain
and liver damage and then death.
</P>
<P>
   To stall the tremors, Mick injected Valium. He ordered a cooling
bath to decrease the dog's temperature, and started an intravenous
drip of pentobarbital to anesthetize the animal and calm the
spasms.
</P>
<P>
   He kept the dog anesthetized all night.
</P>
<P>
   Mick and several technicians took turns sitting with Callie Jo
through the night and into the following morning. The puppy was
never alone. Success and failure
</P>
<P>
   At 5 a.m. Thursday, Cody the cat died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have been a reaction to its vaccinations,'' said
Peterson, ``but I suspect septic shock caused by some underlying
condition that simply overwhelmed its system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really sorry about that little guy. He fought very hard,
didn't he?''
</P>
<P>
   Callie Jo, the puppy who ate slug poison, went home late
Wednesday afternoon. She was wobbly but alert and happy. There were
no signs of permanent damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wouldn't have made it without this place,'' said her
owner. ``They knew exactly what to do.''  &LR; tag1:To reach Joe Popper,
columnist for the Star, call (816) 234-4756 or write Joe Popper,
Kansas City Star, 1729 Grand Blvd., Kansas City, Mo. 64108.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
