</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPE-HAZARDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETROLEUM SPILLS REMAIN A HAZARD, AS RECENT SPILL IN KANSAS SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When it comes to petroleum disasters, the
textbook example occurred in the wilds of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The Exxon Valdez ran aground and leaked crude oil, causing an
environmental catastrophe that grabbed the national limelight.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, however, the potential for another kind of
calamity lurks underground, along 157,000 miles of pipelines that
transport hazardous liquids around the United States.
</P>
<P>
   What happened recently near Atchison, Kan. _ a pipeline breaking
and dumping diesel fuel into a creek _ isn't rare.
</P>
<P>
   Usually the spills don't involve much petroleum. But in 1998,
U.S. Transportation Department statistics show, an average of three
pipeline incidents occurred each week in the United States. The
combined weekly damage toll exceeded $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what can happen, when things go awry as petroleum
products flow beneath the ground:
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, a spill in southeast Kansas sent 34,000 gallons of
light crude oil down the Verdigris River, polluting water into
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, oil from a spill in Missouri flowed along the
Chariton River south of Kirksville, fouling the banks for 35 miles,
coating beavers and killing fish.
</P>
<P>
   Pipeline breaks can claim human casualties. In 1996, a pipeline
transporting liquid butane ruptured in Texas. A truck drove into
the resulting vapor cloud, an explosion occurred, and two persons
died.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the threat from pipelines could be downplayed before
environmental concerns took center stage and before petroleum
mishaps were telecast live into people's homes. But no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The era of buried pipelines operating out of sight and out of
mind is over,'' said Kelley Coyner, a Transportation Department
administrator in Washington who oversees the Office of Pipeline
Safety.
</P>
<P>
   The office, she told a congressional hearing earlier this year,
has taken an assertive approach to safety, while at the same time
addressing the industry's need for flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Pipeline operators say they spend large sums to head off the
threats. Environmental groups, faulting both federal law and
federal regulators, say a lot more should be done.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has worsened recently, according to the
Environmental Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Office of Pipeline Safety has an extremely poor record of
enforcing existing and developing new safety requirements,'' said
Lois Epstein, senior engineer with the environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, she said, pipeline incidents spilled 7.7 million
gallons of hazardous liquids, more than any year since 1991.
Cleanup efforts recovered some of that.
</P>
<P>
   Office of Pipeline Safety experts say the agency has increased
spending and employees, and has been striving to improve its
performance. Pipelines, they point out, remain the safest way of
transporting petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   When spills do happen, the causes vary. Corrosion is one
culprit. So is damage caused by construction companies working near
pipelines. Natural disasters such as floods can damage pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Williams Pipeline Co., which operated the
pipeline that ruptured north of Atchison on May 10 and spilled
200,000 gallons of diesel fuel, use a variety of techniques to head
off trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're doing more of the right things in the right
places,'' said Mike Pearson of Tulsa, manager of the refined
products control center for Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Using satellite communications, the company monitors the flow of
petroleum in each pipeline 24 hours a day, he said. When a drop in
pressure occurs _ an indication of a spill _ the pipeline can be
automatically shut down from the Tulsa center.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent corrosion, the company runs a small electric charge
through its pipelines, he said. Also, he said, the company employs
``smart pigs,'' devices that are run through a pipeline to check
for such things as cracks and deteriorating steel.
</P>
<P>
   Of 12.2 billion barrels of petroleum transported by pipelines in
one recent year, the Office of Pipeline Safety says, only about
0.00127 percent spilled.
</P>
<P>
   The office wields clout over pipeline companies but draws
criticism for not being aggressive enough.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board, Jim
Hall, said that the office deserves a failing grade.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Klinger, spokeswoman for the Office of Pipeline Safety,
said: ``We are working very hard to improve our program, and we
continue to work hard. We've doubled our staff, we're doubling our
efforts in a lot of ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Defense Fund recommends several steps, such as
toughening standards on pipeline leak detection systems, granting
states more authority over pipeline safety, and giving citizens new
power to take enforcement actions by filing lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency regional office in Kansas
City, Kan., which has been overseeing cleanup of the Atchison
spill, keeps specialists on call 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Experts from Kansas agencies are also keeping watch in Atchison.
The Missouri Natural Resources Department increased its hazardous
spill staff two years ago. Some of those experts are in Atchison,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Cleanup work, performed by the pipeline company and its private
contractors, is nearly complete.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly the worst pipeline incident in Kansas history occurred
10 years ago, north of Wichita, when construction equipment
accidentally caused a rupture in a line operated by Kaneb Pipe Line
Co., state officials say.
</P>
<P>
   More than 450,000 gallons of gasoline flowed out. The petroleum
was kept in a confined space, away from water.
</P>
<P>
   Damage was far greater in central Missouri in 1988, when a
pipeline carrying crude oil across the Gasconade River ruptured and
sent 840,000 gallons of crude into the Gasconade and Missouri
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McKinney, a spokesman for Shell in Houston, still remembers
witnessing the damage.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later the Anheuser-Busch brewery in St. Louis shut
down because of worries its beer might be tainted.
</P>
<P>
   These days, McKinney said, inspectors for Shell and Texaco,
which jointly operate the pipeline, fly along its route about twice
a month looking for construction or other activity that might cause
trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
