A5839 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-ILLEGAL-KAN &LR;      05-29 0242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-ILLEGAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ACCUSED OF BUILDING ON SOMEONE ELSE'S LAND WITH STOLEN
MATERIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHAWNA A. HAMEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Someone apparently wanted his own hunting
cabin in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, police say, is that he was using someone else's
materials to build that cabin on someone else's property.
</P>
<P>
   Adam A. Park, 21, of Kearney this week pleaded not guilty in
Clay County Associate Circuit Court to a felony stealing charge. He
also has been charged in Platte County with two misdemeanor counts
of stealing.
</P>
<P>
   Police say that in the last month someone stole thousands of
dollars worth of building materials _ lumber, windows, doors,
roofing and even a skylight _ from seven Northland construction
sites to build a 576-square-foot, one-story cabin on 200 acres of
woods in Kansas City, North.
</P>
<P>
   Police said that when the man who is leasing the land for
farming noticed tire tracks on the land, he investigated.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered the construction site. By that time, the cabin was
partly framed with corner posts.
</P>
<P>
   The man telephoned the property owner in California to ask when
he had decided to build a house on the land.
</P>
<P>
   The owner said he had not.
</P>
<P>
   The man who was leasing the property called police and told them
that he knew Park had hunted on the land and that he had seen
Park's truck on the property several times recently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5840 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITTON-MERGER-LADN     05-29 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTON-MERGER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTON-NEWPORT NEWS DEAL SCUTTLED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Pentagon on Friday torpedoed Litton
Industries Inc.'s proposed $1.9 billion acquisition of Newport News
Shipbuilding Inc., saying the potential cost savings to the
government are not big enough to justify less competition among
shipbuilders.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with reporters in Washington on Friday, Defense
Secretary William Cohen said a Litton-Newport News combination
would be ``contrary to our interests in maintaining separate
facilities'' for naval shipbuilding.
</P>
<P>
   And although the government's stance is based on the U.S. Navy's
preliminary assessment of the deal, Cohen said it is probably the
final word on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the government indicated it would not object
to Litton's proposed $500 million cash acquisition of Avondale
Industries Inc., a New Orleans-based builder of amphibious assault
vessels, support ships for the Navy and commercial ships.
</P>
<P>
   That news, coupled with the fact that Litton's offer for
Avondale tops an earlier bid from Newport News, indicated to Wall
Street that Litton probably will win the bidding for Avondale.
Shares of Litton and Avondale increased, while Newport News shares
lost 16 percent of their value Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Woodland Hills-based Litton took the news in stride, noting that
no formal proposal regarding its offer to Newport News has been
submitted to the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to believe the combination of Litton and Newport
News and Litton and Avondale are good for the companies, for the
stockholders, the employees, the country and the Navy,'' said
Litton spokesman Randy Belote.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the department's assessment is still a preliminary
one and that there have been ongoing discussions between the
company and the government.
</P>
<P>
   Litton now plans to revisit the cost savings issue to see
whether a satisfactory resolution can be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Litton made separate bids for Newport News and Avondale on May
6. The offers came after anti-trust regulators rejected a bid by
General Dynamics Corp. for Newport News on grounds that potential
cost savings to the government did not warrant a reduction in
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Litton's Ingalls Shipbuilding subsidiary builds destroyers and
other surface ships and Newport News is the Navy's only builder of
nuclear-powered aircraft carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators appear troubled that if the companies combine, there
would be two, rather than three, contractors for battle-worthy
ships.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Hansen, a Defense Department spokeswoman, said Friday that
the agency has not been asked to send any documentation regarding
the merger to the Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assessment was based on Litton representing its intentions
as opposed to a formal acquisition proposal. But you've got one
`go' and one `no go' here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the deal was announced some analysts thought
Litton's offer stood a better chance of passing regulatory muster
than did General Dynamics' bid.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Newport News, based in Newport News, Va., took a
neutral position on the issue Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really up to Litton to try to determine if they want to
investigate the concerns that have been expressed,'' said Newport
News spokesman Mike Hattfield.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators already had approved Newport News' $470 million
stock-for-stock merger with Avondale, which continues to evaluate
both offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Avondale has made no decision on which of the two offers it
would accept but the company is still closely studying both merger
proposals,'' said company spokesman Ed Winter. ``There is no
timetable or deadline to make such a decision and we can't say when
that might occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Litton increased $2.1875 to $64.9375 Friday on trading
volume three times heavier than normal. Newport News lost $5.25, or
16 percent, to close at $27.50 on eight times normal volume.
Avondale increased 25 cents to $36.50.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
