<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5846 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOT-STANDOFF-SPI &LR;      05-29 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOT-STANDOFF-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SNIPER KILLS GUNMAN AFTER DEADLY RAMPAGE THROUGH
NEIGHBORHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HEATH FOSTER AND PHUONG LE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHORELINE, Wash. _ Police killed a 22-year-old man Friday night
who fled an accident on Interstate 5 and terrorized two blocks of a
North End neighborhood near Seattle, fatally bludgeoning an elderly
woman, breaking another woman's neck and spraying bullets at
police.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say the rampage began earlier in Brier, a
Snohomish County suburb where the man's mother and his 2-year-old
nephew were found slain inside a house on a quiet cul-de-sac.
</P>
<P>
   Before it ended, the melee sent at least four people _ including
a King County sheriff's deputy _ to hospitals and shut down I-5 in
both directions, gridlocking holiday travelers leaving early for
the Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   As a precaution, children at a nearby elementary school were
confined by police to the building until 8:30 Friday night, after
it was confirmed that a police sharpshooter had killed the suspect.
Anxious parents waited outside the school for hours.
</P>
<P>
   King County Sheriff Dave Reichert refused to identify the man,
but said the suspect may have had a $10,000 warrant out for his
arrest. Reichert would not say what the warrant was for.
</P>
<P>
   As the man darted from house to house, he came upon Erma Spence,
63, whom he attacked with a gardening tool. She was pronounced dead
at Seattle's Harborview Medical Center at 2:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman, 82-year-old Irene Z. Hilton, suffered a broken
neck after she was attacked in her backyard garden.
</P>
<P>
   Police say the suspect fled south on I-5 in his slain mother's
car, speeding wildly through holiday traffic. Washington State
Trooper Tom Foster said at about 1:30 p.m., the suspect swerved
suddenly and collided with Anthony Venegas, 64, of Everett, Wash.,
who was riding a motorcycle. The impact almost severed one of
Venegas' legs, which doctors later amputated below the left knee.
</P>
<P>
   The mangled, stolen car caught fire and skidded to a halt just
north of 195th Street Northeast in Shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect ran, and may have used a pedestrian bridge to cross
over a thick sound wall that separates the busy freeway from a
quiet neighborhood of suburban ramblers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a warm, sunny afternoon, and police believe Spence was
outside in her garden, which bordered her one-story home, when she
was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-year-old neighbor heard Spence crying for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was screaming, `Help me!','' the neighbor said. ``It
sounded like she was being beaten because it was the sound of
something hitting'' her.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old woman frantically called 911 and then headed for
Spence's house. She said she saw a young black man leaving and
asked him what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked sketchy, and he didn't say anything back,'' she
said. Then, the man jumped a chain-link fence bordering Spence's
property, and the neighbor said she became afraid and ran back to
her house.
</P>
<P>
   John Wayne, a 28-year-old neighbor, was one of the first to come
upon Spence. He said Spence was lying in a pool of blood, with what
looked like a broken posthole digger near her body.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not looking good,'' Wayne said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before, Wayne had been standing on a footbridge,
surveying the scene from the car accident. When he looked back
toward his neighborhood, he said he saw a disturbed-looking man in
his early 20s sporting braids or dreadlocks looking at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was acting very, very agitated,'' Wayne said. ``He was
looking around paranoid.''
</P>
<P>
   The man then disappeared, and that's when Wayne heard neighbors
shouting for help from Spence's home.
</P>
<P>
   After the assailant left Spence, he moved across Seventh Avenue
Northeast. He marched through the unlocked doors of the home of
John Berger, and his roomate Michael Barker, who live at 525 N.E.
195th St.
</P>
<P>
   Face to face with the threatening man, who wore a baggy shirt
and was bleeding at the mouth, Berger and his roommate went for
their guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was talking very irrationally like he lost his way,''
Berger said. ``I told him to get out. There was craziness in his
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to scare the man away. He then moved south down
Seventh Avenue Northeast, navigating through the backyards of
several homes. His next victim, police say, was 82-year-old Hilton,
a widow in poor health who was puttering in her yard.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton's next-door neighbor of more than four decades, Gerald
Gehret, heard Hilton screaming his name.
</P>
<P>
   He peered over his fence and saw the man grabbing Hilton by her
hair. As soon as the man saw him, Gehret said, he hit her with what
looked like a flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   Gehret ran inside to grab a gun. He went out his front door and
spotted police outside. He pointed them to Hilton's house and put
away his gun. King County Sheriff's officers had by then responded
to a 911 call from the neighborhood, spokesman John Urquhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing police, the assailant fled, leaving Hilton behind, her
neck broken. Hilton was listed in critical condition Friday night
at Harborview Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Police say the assailant then moved two houses south, to the
four-bedroom home of Fred and Chrystine Westphal, who have lived on
Seventh Avenue Northeast for 11 years. Neither the Westphals nor
their three children were home.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect found the Westphal's gun collection and barricaded
himself inside their home, police said. The Westphals kept three
semi-automatic handguns, two rifles and two shotguns in rifle bags
or boxes, according to 16-year-old Austin Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   Police quickly surrounded the home. Over the next three hours,
police estimate the suspect shot at them 50 or more times.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, the suspect changed weapons and went to a
higher-caliber weapon _ a rifle of some type, said Washington State
Trooper Phillip Davidson, who was one of the first officers on the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Five or six officers took cover behind a Jeep Cherokee near the
house and ordered the suspect to come out and drop his weapon. They
gave the suspect two warnings on the bullhorn.
</P>
<P>
   There was no response, Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking cover behind the Jeep, King County Sheriff's Deputy Diana
Russell received cuts to her face and her skull was fractured after
the suspect opened fire. Two Montlake Terrace Police officers
received minor injuries from flying glass.
</P>
<P>
   After that, an armed personnel carrier provided by the Seattle
Police Department's SWAT team was sent in.
</P>
<P>
   While SWAT teams extricated deputies pinned down by gunfire,
other officers helped evacuate nearby homes and secure six blocks
around the scene. Children at nearby North City Elementary School
were ordered to stay in their school throughout the evening until
they could be safely released.
</P>
<P>
   The stand-off between police and the suspect culminated at about
5:30 p.m. when snipers moved in closer to the home, said Reichert.
He said one sniper fired a shot through a window, hitting the
suspect. The man, who was holding a firearm, fell back and his gun
dropped from the window into the yard.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 p.m., officers approached the house and threw in tear gas
cannisters from two sides. They repeated that at 6:15 and again at
6:30 p.m. and were hoping to flush the suspect out, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Then robots from the Seattle Police Department's bomb squad,
with cameras attached to them were sent into the house to search
for the suspect, who was found dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
