<HEADER>
A5847 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICKEN-POX-KAN &LR;      05-29 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-POX-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICKENPOX CAN BE SEVERE, AND VACCINE IS AVAILABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Four-year-old Cody Spruyt never got
chickenpox vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   His doctor didn't insist on it. His parents didn't think it was
a big deal. After all, every kid gets chickenpox.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Lenexa, Kan., boy got chickenpox last month, it
wasn't the simple childhood illness his parents expected.
Chickenpox can turn into something dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The disease made Cody vulnerable to strep bacteria that invaded
his heart and ate away at a vital heart valve. Now Cody faces major
surgery to repair the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, if I could do it all over again, I wouldn't take
the chance of not vaccinating him,'' Cody's mother, Wendy Spruyt,
said. ``I relied on the medical profession for guidance. I feel I
was let down.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention took
action to make chickenpox vaccine a routine part of every child's
health care.
</P>
<P>
   It issued new recommendations calling on states to require that
children be vaccinated for chickenpox before being allowed to
attend day care or enter school. It is up to each state to
implement the requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Such rules are long overdue, said Mary Anne Jackson, an
infectious disease expert at Children's Mercy Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's one of the most under-utilized vaccines,''
Jackson said. ``If you ask people to describe chickenpox, they'll
say it's benign and inevitable. It's time the medical community and
the lay community learn the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Before chickenpox vaccine became available in 1995, about 4
million people got the illness each year, according to the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention. For most it's an uncomfortable
four or five days of fever, malaise and hundreds of small itchy
rashes covering the body from scalp to feet. Getting chickenpox
confers lifetime immunity.
</P>
<P>
   But about 100 people, almost half of them children, die of
chickenpox complications each year. And about 10,000 are
hospitalized with chickenpox complications.
</P>
<P>
   Although no chickenpox deaths have been reported in Kansas in
recent years, in Missouri there have been 18 deaths reported since
1993, including one Kansas City area child this year.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers like these make chickenpox the most deadly childhood
disease that's preventable by vaccine, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts recommend that all children be immunized for chickenpox
around their first birthday.
</P>
<P>
   But because chickenpox is seen as a mild disease and experience
with the vaccine is limited, doctors have been slow to recommend
it, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, for example, although more than 80 percent of
2-year-olds are up to date on required shots for such illnesses as
measles, polio and tetanus, only about 28 percent have been
vaccinated for chickenpox, the most recent data show.
</P>
<P>
   National data are more encouraging; about 48 percent of children
under age 3 have been vaccinated for chickenpox, according to
unpublished federal figures for the third quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ten states and the District of Columbia now require chickenpox
immunization to attend school. Kansas and Missouri are among the
majority of states that don't require it.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's Advisory
Committee on Immunization Practices called for mandatory
immunization for school and day care entry after reviewing new
evidence on the safety and effectiveness of the vaccine, said Jane
Seward, a physician with the federal agency's national immunization
program.
</P>
<P>
   The most common side effect, which occurs in less than 1 percent
of cases, is a mild rash, according to the advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also recommended that people exposed to chickenpox
who aren't immune get the vaccine in order to prevent outbreaks of
the disease. And it also said teen-agers and adults who've never
had chickenpox should be immunized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have a product that we know works, we can't accept
children dying or developing serious complications. It's not worth
taking the risk anymore,'' Seward said.
</P>
<P>
   But taking risks with chickenpox is still common, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still hear from parents, `The kid down the block has it.
I'll expose my kids to get it over with,' '' Jackson said. ``I
cringe when I hear that. We've seen too many complications in
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Chickenpox can become dangerous in several ways.
</P>
<P>
   The chickenpox virus itself can enter the central nervous system
and cause the brain inflammation encephalitis. Fever from a
chickenpox infection can lead to dehydration serious enough to
require hospital treatment. In pregnant women, chickenpox can cause
serious birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   The most common complications occur when chickenpox sores become
a portal to virulent staph or strep bacteria. The bacteria can
cause toxic shock or infect the bloodstream or organs.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to Cody Spruyt.
</P>
<P>
   Cody broke out on April 27 with chickenpox that covered his head
and body. About four days into his illness, his temperature spiked
at 105.2 degrees. His parents were able to his fever down, but Cody
didn't get better. He felt listless. He had persistent nose bleeds.
His left foot ached.
</P>
<P>
   For days, Cody was in and out of hospitals and doctors' offices.
Finally, his parents took him to Children's Mercy, where his
condition was diagnosed. The foot pain turned out to be an
infection that required surgery. An echocardiogram found the heart
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of something I thought so benign, the chickenpox, it's
something my son will have to deal with the rest of his life,''
Wendy Spruyt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
