<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS GIVES GLAUS CHANCE TO RECOVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels manager Terry Collins elected
to rest slumping third baseman Troy Glaus after Thursday's 0-for-4
performance against Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Jeff Huson, who started at first on Thursday, played
third on Friday, but Collins said he just wanted to give Glaus a
breather. Glaus has just three hits in his last 43 at-bats and only
one RBI since May 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten to the point where he just needed to get away,''
Collins said. ``He's getting so much advice from everyone, it can
be a bit much. But he's going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, the Angels' top pick in the 1997 draft, made the big
leagues in just 109 games. This season he won the third-base job
from Dave Hollins, who was traded to Toronto during spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Glaus batted .341 (28 for 82) with five homers and 14
RBI. He still leads the club with 15 doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you don't have to worry about is the effort,''
Collins said. ``He was out there early, hitting like he always
does. He probably was trying too hard. No big deal. I looked up
this morning and I realized there is still four months of baseball
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher makes the call: When he was struggling a month ago,
Angels right-hander Tim Belcher received a pick-me-up phone call
from his former Dodgers catcher Rick Dempsey. Now, Belcher is
pitching well, in part because of some mechanical adjustments
Dempsey suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, it was Belcher on the phone to Dempsey in Atlanta, where
the Dodgers are playing the Braves. Dempsey was moved from
third-base coach to bullpen coach on Wednesday when pitching coach
Charlie Hough was fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I think it is a good move,'' said Belcher, who will
make his next start Monday against Minnesota. ``Who knows pitchers
better than an old catcher. But he wants to be a big-league manager
and I think he's wondering what a move like that will do to his
career.''
</P>
<P>
   As for straightening out his pitching, Belcher said his location
has improved since getting pounded in three consecutive starts
during the last week of April and the first week of May.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey had suggested Belcher turn his body more during his
delivery, showing the catcher the number on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't very many guys who know my mechanics like him,''
Belcher said. ``Now when I have a bad inning, it's one or two runs,
not six like it was before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
