<SLUG> BC-REFUGE-FAMILY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANXIETY CLOUDS REUNION OF ALBANIAN FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STACY DOWNS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It has been 18 years since Edmond Rugova's
family was together.
</P>
<P>
   A photo from that time shows him, his brother and his sister _
all Albanians from Kosovo _ smiling in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova points out the irony: He was part of the Yugoslav Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same army that's killing us now,'' said Rugova, a former
Comets soccer player living in suburban Overland Park, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade Rugova helped bring his brother and parents
from Kosovo to live in the area. Discrimination against Albanians
had forced his parents out of jobs, but the ethnic cleansing had
not begun.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday his sister and her three children _ Kosovo refugees
_ arrived in Kansas City to complete the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no words. We just stood there embracing,'' Rugova
said. ``It was overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon his sister Diana Dalipi's daughters Agnesa, 15,
and Dafina, 10, and son Ligrid, 5, played with Rugova's daughters
in the living room. The adults exchanged smiles and spoke in
Albanian about childhood memories.
</P>
<P>
   But sorrow and anxiety clouded the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova's family stayed up until 3 a.m. Friday talking. All
shared the shock that hundreds of thousands of people had lost
their homes and that a nationality was being erased.
</P>
<P>
   Dalipi, her husband, her two daughters and son recently were
forced out of their home in Gilan, Kosovo. They had 10 minutes to
pack their belongings and leave.
</P>
<P>
   Dalipi and her children became separated from her husband. She
and the children walked 30 miles and crossed the Kosovo border into
safety. They slept on concrete floors and lived on the few supplies
they could carry.
</P>
<P>
   Thick, dark circles line Dalipi's eyes, and she is much thinner
than she was in the family photo from 18 years ago. Her mother's
eyes fill with tears when she looks at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get over how much she has aged and what she has gone
through,'' Rugova said. ``My mother keeps telling me this isn't the
daughter she remembers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rugova and his brother, Veton, have been trying for years to
bring their sister and her family to live in the Kansas City area.
But hopes for peace and other complications kept her and her family
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   When the masses of Kosovo Albanians were forced from their
homes, the family prayed for Dalipi and her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew there would be suffering for her and her children _
they would be tired, thirsty, hungry and sleeping in open places,
but we were most afraid about them being raped,'' Veton Rugova
said. ``Luckily that did not take place.''
</P>
<P>
   The worrying is not over. The family still waits to hear from
Dalipi's husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope and pray the worst has not happened,'' Rugova said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rugovas are trying to help other relatives and friends who
are refugees. Rugova's wife, Qefsere, wants her mother to leave and
live with them. Because of the frequent contacts, the Rugovas'
phone bills range between $600 and $1,100 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Cosmos youth soccer club, which Rugova formed,
has held several fund-raisers to help the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't emphasize how important everyone's help has been,''
Rugova said. ``The people here have given us so much support.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
