<HEADER>
A5850 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1STLD     05-29 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC INDICTMENT COLORS TALKS WITH RUSSIAN ENVOY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for refinements throughout)   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The day after President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia was indicted on war crimes charges, a
search for a negotiated solution to the conflict in Kosovo
proceeded on Friday, clouded by uncertainty and recriminations.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian envoy voiced some hope, but the United States
withheld judgment.
</P>
<P>
   After nine hours of talks with Milosevic about a Kosovo
settlement, the Russian special envoy to the Balkans, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, pronounced himself ``very pleased,'' but added, ``We
face the most difficult negotiations in the next few days.''
</P>
<P>
   The sticking points remain the shape of any international force
to police a settlement, the command of such a force and the size of
the Yugoslav army and police contingents allowed to remain in
Kosovo. The Russians are said to be willing to supply soldiers of
their own, and to be exploring the idea of German troops acting as
the center of a NATO contingent.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere of the talks was colored by the indictment of
Milosevic and four top aides by the international tribunal at The
Hague on Thursday on charges of responsibility for war crimes in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin said he hoped to return to Belgrade next week with
President Martti Ahtisaari of Finland after further talks with
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin said that Ahtisaari did not travel to Belgrade
today because of the indictments announced on Thursday. But
Yugoslav officials said he may have stayed away waiting to see if
the prospects of success improve.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, Talbott took pains to say that Chernomyrdin was not
representing the United States or NATO; Ahtisaari is their
designated negotiator. Finland is not a member of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, NATO defense ministers were holding an unpublicized
meeting in Germany to discuss what kind of force would be needed to
carry out a ground invasion of Kosovo. A force as large as 150,000
troops was reportedly discussed.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Friday evening, the Yugoslav government
said it accepted the principles for a settlement issued two weeks
ago by the Group of 7 industrial countries and Russia. Yugoslavia
``agrees that the U.N. Security Council should pass a resolution
based on those principles,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   It also said that ``the return of all the refugees to their
homes should be insured as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade has accepted the principles before, but putting them
into a substantive, detailed peace settlement is the current
difficulty. Even the United States and Russia still disagree over
those details.
</P>
<P>
   The principles call for a halt in the violence and oppression in
Kosovo, the withdrawal of Yugoslav forces from the province and the
deployment of an international security ``presence,'' now
understood to be an armed force under a United Nations flag with
members from at least some NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
   The principles also call for the return of ethnic Albanian
refugees to Kosovo, the establishment of an interim administration
before new elections and the opening of Serbian-Kosovar talks on
the province's future.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin flew on Friday to a Belgrade that was without
electricity after renewed NATO attacks on the nation's power grid
in what NATO officials said proudly was their heaviest day of
bombing yet, with 792 sorties, a record in the air war, which began
on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived in a sour mood, in part a function of what Russian
officials described as a very difficult two days of negotiations
with Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin said he was ``unsatisfied that all of our
negotiations have failed to achieve results'' and added, ``If they
continue in this vein, then their continuation would be
senseless.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the talks were the only hope of a peaceful
resolution and called again for a halt to NATO's bombing as an
important prerequisite for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Moscow, he told reporters about the war crimes
indictments: ``We knew, we warned, we asked, `Don't do this,
because it will simply complicate the process.' But we are flying
to Belgrade. We deal with the lawfully elected president of
Yugoslavia and will go on dealing with him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Talbott, briefing NATO ambassadors in Brussels Friday, chose
to emphasize that Chernomyrdin was representing only the Russian
government in talks with Milosevic and not NATO or the United
States. Talbott spoke one day after the indictment and a day after
leaving Moscow, where anti-NATO sentiment has escalated in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized Chernomyrdin for an Op-Ed page article in The
Washington Post in which the Russian complained about NATO policy,
called the Kosovo issue a ``domestic conflict'' and said Russia
would cease its efforts unless the bombing stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Chernomyrdin is not negotiating for NATO or the United
States,'' Talbott said. ``He will also refer to what he understands
to be the position of the U.S. government.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin is bringing further ideas on the makeup of an
international force under U.N. auspices to police a Kosovo
settlement. The Russians may be willing to supply up to 10,000
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade would prefer NATO troops from countries _ like Germany,
Italy, Greece and Spain _ that are not associated in the public's
mind with the air attacks on Yugoslavia, as the United States and
Britain are.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a dispute over who should command such a force,
with Russia wanting a neutral country, and over how many Yugoslav
troops and Serbian policemen should be allowed to remain in Kosovo,
even as a symbol of sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians predict, as Belgrade does, that if all Serbian
forces pull out, the vacuum will immediately be filled by the
Kosovo Liberation Army, the secessionist guerrilla force, which is
supposed to be disarmed in any settlement.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO says it wants a strong force with NATO at its core to
protect ethnic Albanians from Serbs and to prevent a reinfiltration
of Serbian forces, Yugoslav officials _ and even some with NATO _
predict that the biggest threat to the international force will be
the Kosovar rebels and are skeptical that NATO will disarm them.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have complained bitterly, as have the Chinese, the
Yugoslav democratic opposition and even Western officials, about
the timing of the Hague indictments.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Clinton administration viewed the Belgrade
reports cautiously. ``Milosevic has made numerous statements in the
past,'' Mike Hammer, a National Security Council spokesman, said
Friday. ``There's a level of detail that Milosevic has to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Yugoslav leader must accept is ``clear, verifiable
withdrawal'' of Serbian forces from Kosovo, and a peacekeeping
force with NATO at its core, Hammer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like we're really there yet,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer said that while the White House welcomed any hopeful
signs, administration officials must confer in depth with
Chernomyrdin before determining whether there are concrete reasons
for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   American diplomats hope to speak with Chernomyrdin as early as
Saturday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
