<HEADLINE>
MAN ADMITS CHARGE INVOLVING HANDGUN THAT CHILD FIRED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Kansas City man faces up to 10 years in
jail after admitting Friday to leaving a loaded handgun that a
6-year-old boy fired, killing his 1-year-old playmate.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Circuit Court Judge Thomas Clark said it would
take several weeks to decide how much time Terrance Hoard should
serve on the two counts of child endangerment. No sentencing date
was set.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Miller, assistant prosecutor, said he believed he had been
lenient by not charging Hoard, 20, with felony murder. He refused
to offer a plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so incensed by it,'' Miller said afterward. ``When a child
dies, the case is more difficult than others. There is no one more
innocent than a child.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 11, 1998, a 6-year-old boy shot Darian D. Hinds in an
apartment in midtown Kansas City. The boy told police that he
pulled the handgun from a bag that contained video games.
</P>
<P>
   He said he pointed the .38-caliber semiautomatic toward the wall
and pulled the trigger. A bullet struck Darian.
</P>
<P>
   The boy told police that a man called ``T'' had placed the gun
in the bag before leaving the residence. Police later identified
Hoard as ``T.''
</P>
<P>
   At the court appearance Friday, Hoard, in a halting voice,
explained that he had the gun because he had been robbed.
</P>
<P>
   Miller pointed out that if a 6-year-old could fire the gun so
easily, it was likely the safety was not on. Hoard said he thought
it was.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said Hoard should have known ``that a child will get a
hold of something and play with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
