<HEADLINE>
TWA SUBMITS ``BEST AND FINAL OFFER'' ON NEW CONTRACTS TO UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Trans World Airlines submitted what it called
its ``best and final offer'' on new contracts to the Machinists
union Friday, less than two weeks from a possible strike deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Union negotiators indicated they would provide details of the
latest package to 16,000 members at TWA and submit it for a vote,
the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest offers to TWA's three employee groups represents a
move by the company to bring their wages within 90 percent of
industry standards earlier than previously proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Machinists union officials could not be reached for comment late
Friday. However, they previously have been adamant that a contract
bringing wages to within 90 percent of the industry average was
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new proposal, which would remain in effect till
January 2002, the employees would see their wages reach the 90
percent standard by July 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, all Machinists employees would receive a lump-sum
payment ranging from $2,100 to $5,000, distributed in intervals
over the first two years of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   William F. Compton, TWA's president and chief operating officer,
said management originally proposed bringing the employees' wages
up to the 90 percent standard by September 2002. Then the company
moved to January 2002 before its latest offer.
</P>
<P>
   Though TWA's pilots reached a contract in 1998 that is expected
to bring their pay to within 90 percent of the industry over four
years, TWA's Machinists members would reach that level by July
2001, slightly more than two years away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really pushed the envelope as to what we can afford in
making this offer,'' Compton said. ``The employees certainly
deserve more, but it's as much as we can afford at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Compton said the value of the wage and benefit package was
$356.2 million through January 2002, about $100 million more than
the company initially proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Compton said union negotiators did not indicate whether they
would make a recommendation to the membership on how to vote on the
new contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
