<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO EVENS SERIES ON DRURY'S OVERTIME GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ St. Patrick spoke, and the skies opened.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe they didn't open, but at least the Colorado Avalanche
can see a nice beam of sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   One day after Patrick Roy, the Avalanche's inimitable goalie,
criticized his teammates for not scoring more, for not getting
traffic in front of Stars goalie Ed Belfour, for not putting more
shots high, the Avalanche listened just enough and won a 3-2
overtime thriller in Game 4 of the Western Conference finals before
an invigorated crowd of 16,061 at McNichols Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche rookie Chris Drury hit the game-winner with 31 seconds
remaining in the overtime period to tie the best-of-seven series at
two games apiece _ something Stars players said doesn't surprise
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think they were going to just give up,'' Stars
defenseman Shawn Chambers said. ``They played a great game. And
after the first five minutes, I thought we played a great game.
It's just a great series and I don't think there's one player on
this team that has lost a bit of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   No, but the Avalanche has gained a ton. Backed to the wall and
needing a victory to avoid a 3-1 deficit in the series, Roy showed
no shyness in calling out teammates Joe Sakic and Theo Fleury for
their lack of scoring and generally berating his team for making
life too easy for Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche responded.
</P>
<P>
   Sakic, who had been without a point in the first three games,
scored the opening goal at the 4:06 mark of the first period _ the
earliest the Stars have been touched in 14 playoff games. In fact,
the Stars had allowed only three first-period goals before last
night, but gave up two in 48 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Shjon Podein garnered the second goal as his shot deflected off
the stick of Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig and over the shoulder of
Belfour at the 4:54 mark of the first.
</P>
<P>
   On both plays, the Avalanche was able to get traffic in front of
Belfour. On both plays, Stars' defensemen had their sticks in front
of Belfour and deflected pucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were fluky, but that's what happens,'' Ludwig said. ``In
any playoff series, those things are going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But what was key, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said, was that the
Stars didn't panic. They bounced back from the shocking goals _
goals that enlivened a testy crowd _ and basically matched the
Avalanche shot for shot, scoring chance for scoring chance and
punch for punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough way to lose,'' Hitchcock said. ``But both teams
played hard, both goaltenders were excellent, there were a lot of
quality chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a whale of a hockey game and I'm proud of my team and
the way we battled back,'' Hitchcock added.
</P>
<P>
   After fighting back, the two teams finished with 45 shots apiece
and Belfour and Roy were embroiled in a vicious goaltender
showdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars finally cracked Roy in the second period when Jamie
Langenbrunner sent a soft wrister through the crowd on a power play
goal. Like the Avalanche, the Stars finally were able to get some
traffic in front of Roy. In fact, the Avalanche goaltender never
even saw the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Roy did see the second goal, it went right between his legs as
Langenbrunner made a great play to steal the puck from Sylvain
Lefebvre and that set up Brett Hull for a slap shot with 3:53
remaining in regulation and sent the game to overtime.
</P>
<P>
   There, the Stars did everything but win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got what we came for, it's now best of three and we have
home ice,'' Hitchcock said. ``We've played great every game in this
series. You have two teams giving everything right now. Nothing is
left in the tank for anybody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
