r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      05-29 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN DROPS AMENDMENT ON ARIZONA WILDLIFE REFUGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. John McCain has dropped a proposal that
environmentalists feared would open the Cabeza Prieta National
Wildlife Refuge to the rumble of tank treads.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's withdrawal of an amendment that could have let tanks
and armored personnel carriers cross the largest intact expanse of
the Sonoran Desert was greeted warmly by wildlife and wilderness
groups, who said it strengthens their chances of eventually turning
the wildlife refuge, and the surrounding Barry M. Goldwater gunnery
range, into Arizona's newest national park.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said it was never his intention to expose the wildlife
area in southwestern Arizona to military ground maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain rattled environmentalists and tribal officials
earlier in the week with an amendment to the proposed 2000 National
Defense Authorization Act. That amendment would have allowed the
Goldwater range to be permanently reserved for military use.
</P>
<P>
   The range covers much of southwestern Arizona _ nearly 3 million
acres _ including the wildlife refuge and parts of the Tohono
O'odham Indian Reservation. It borders Organ Pipe National
Monument.
</P>
<P>
   The military's use of the bombing range was last authorized by
Congress in 1986. That 15-year authority is nearing an end, and
Congress is debating whether to extend its military use. And, if
so, for how long.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental and tribal groups read McCain's proposal as not
only allowing the desert land to be permanently removed from public
use, but they also saw language that could allow the military to
conduct ground maneuvers in the currently protected Cabeza Prieta.
</P>
<P>
   McCain argued that his intent was misconstrued.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language originally included in the bill was intended to
be neutral on the few controversial aspects of the proposed
withdrawal,'' he said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   But such groups as the Land and Water Fund of the Rockies, the
Sierra Club and the Wilderness Society saw nothing neutral about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We read the language as authorizing military ground
training,'' said Jim Waltman, director of refuge and wildlife
programs for the Wilderness Society. ``Sen. McCain and his staff
tell us they did not intend that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tohono O'odham tribe, which has three parcels of sacred
lands within the current boundaries of the bombing range, also
protested to McCain, saying the bombing range covers more turf than
is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal Chairman Edward D. Manuel, in a letter to McCain this
week, said the land included 141 archaeological sites, with
artifacts dating back at 7,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe wants the lands returned, especially since the Air
Force said that they are not needed for military purposes.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, McCain met with members of the Wilderness Society,
the National Audubon Society and Defenders of the Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Based on their objections, and those of Sen. Jeff Bingaman,
D-N.M., McCain dropped his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he submitted an amendment that says the Senate needs to
decide the issue before it adjourns its session this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Waltman praised the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cabeza Prieta is really the crown jewel of the Sonoran
Desert,'' he said. ``It has spectacular wildlife and incredible
scenery.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups still want to see the Cabeza Prieta left
out of any military use. Environmentalists have sparred with the
Air Force for nearly a decade over low-flying jets and their impact
on reproduction for the endangered Sonoran pronghorn antelope, of
which fewer than 200 remain. Intensified military use in the area
would spoil the chances of making it a park, Waltman said.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain told the groups he wants to ensure that the current
situation with the Cabeza Prieta _ which allows for military
overflights and the aerial maintenance of several telemetry sites _
continues.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Ives, press secretary to McCain, said the senator is
waiting for a proposal from the Clinton administration. That is
expected within two weeks, and will set the stage for the next
round of discussions on how much of the range should be reserved
for military use, and for how long. &QL; 
Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at (602) 444-8963 or at
maryjo.pitzl(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
