<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN IN DEFEAT, STARS RETURN AS THE FAVORITE TO ADVANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Eddie Belfour deserved better, much better. But after a
long evening of body-pounding playoff warfare, it can also be said
the Colorado Avalanche truly earned some new postseason life. And
finally achieved just that.
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 of the NHL's Western Conference finals seemed headed the
Stars' way, which meant this series was all but over.
</P>
<P>
   And on 60 minutes of style points, combined with overall
dominance, Dallas was the best team in regulation, crawling slowly
back from a very quick two-goal deficit. When Brett Hull whistled
the puck through Patrick Roy's 5-hole with 3:53 left in the third
period, the Avs had every reason to panic. The game was tied, and
the Stars were in control, wearing down Colorado with muscle and
four lines.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the Avs' playoff existence was at stake. This was
a can't-lose-contest for them. Being down three games to one and
going back to Dallas for Game 5 was almost the same as being
vacation bound.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Stars had answered every question Colorado threw
at them for three consecutive games. And now, overtime did not
appear to bode well for the desperate Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   But...
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise, sudden death seemed to suit Colorado. For the
most part, they were the aggressive outfit, although both teams had
to survive power plays.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final minute of OT, the Avs came up with a turnover
off defenseman Darryl Sydor, allowing the puck to stay in Dallas'
zone. With Colorado's Sandis Ozolinsh it's usually either feast or
famine. He can make the great play or the stupid one.
</P>
<P>
   This time he looked brilliant in sliding the puck to an
uncovered Chris Drury. The rookie unloaded on Belfour, going high
side-right side, and the puck found net.
</P>
<P>
   With a mere 31 seconds remaining in overtime, Colorado won, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   That new life did belong to the Avs, with the series now tied
after four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was another great game for us,'' said Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock, and that's true. ``But it was a great game for both
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars came to Colorado to regain home-ice advantage in the
series and did just that in Game 3. But the burial of the Avs could
have come last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in very good shape _ it's now who can win two out of
three and two of those will be on our ice,'' noted Hitchcock, as
Game 5 tomorrow afternoon at Reunion Arena now becomes yet another
pivotal moment in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was gonna be this kind of series all along,'' added
Hitchcock. ``It was going to come down to six or seven games all
along.''
</P>
<P>
   And, obviously, the winner will be determined by which goalie
played better. And for the record, Belfour bested Patrick Roy for
the third consecutive game, except this time there would no be no
W. Roy was outstanding, just not as good as Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   `The Eagle,' however, happened to be very unlucky in the opening
minutes of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado had a 2-0 lead before five minutes was gone. The Avs
would go another 75 minutes before scoring again, but that goal was
the game winner.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the overtime ending, the Stars actually lost the game
way back in that opening period.
</P>
<P>
   The first shot put up by the Avs came four minutes into the
contest, but Joe Sakic's blast from the point appeared harmless.
Belfour was in position until the puck deflected off the stick of
Sydor, who was wrestling Theo Fleury in the slot. The re-direction
slid past Eddie for a 1-0 Avs lead. Suddenly, Sakic became a
playoff factor after a long slump, but he needed help from Sydor's
stick.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, there was a replay less than a minute later,
although this time it was winger Shjon Podein who found a Stars
stick. His shot also appeared to be no trouble until Craig Ludwig
lifted his stick, trying to knock down the puck before it reached
Belfour. But that resulted in yet another re-direction into the
goal, and the lead was 2-0 for Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour could have cracked at that point. So could have the
Stars. Instead, both took over the game. And when Hull tied it,
Colorado was in shock.
</P>
<P>
   But that's also why the Avs' strong overtime play, while
surprising, was also inspired.
</P>
<P>
   The ``hate'' factor also surfaced last night, which pushed the
physical play in Game 4 to the same level as the Edmonton series.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, the Stars come back home as the best team in
the series. To stay that way, they now have to win Game 5.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
