<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-DEATHS-ECUADOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER ARRIVES TO CLAIM TRAIN VICTIMS' BODIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., also filed in `i' category)  
 (HLW)  
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A man whose family was struck and killed by an Amtrak
train earlier this week arrived in New York from Ecuador Friday
night and said that he intended to take the bodies of his wife and
their four sons back home.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a frayed suit and looking bewildered, the man, Carlos
Urgiles, a farmhand from a rural Andean town, said he planned to
give his family a Catholic burial in their native country, perhaps
as early as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But relatives of his estranged wife, Julia Toledo, have been
planning to bury the family in Connecticut, and according to the
Mormon faith. Maria Toledo, Julia's sister, encouraged the family
to convert to Mormonism about 18 months ago. Urgiles has said the
conversion provoked the breakup of their family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come to bring the bodies back home,'' he told reporters
at Kennedy International Airport. ``I don't want to have problems
with my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Urgiles' antipathy toward Mormonism, church leaders in
Trumbull, Conn., said they would go ahead with the funeral service
on Monday morning as planned _whether the bodies are buried in
nearby Easton or taken back to Ecuador. Kenneth Openshaw, a church
leader, said that the Mormon faith usually honors the father's
wishes, but that in this case, the needs of other surviving
relatives could not be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens, that won't stop us from memorializing this
family, which was greatly loved and cherished not only by the
church and the boys' school, but by the entire community,''
Openshaw said. ``There is a need for closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who knew Ms. Toledo recalled her as a devoted
mother and were mystified why she was walking along the tracks with
her children at 2:20 Tuesday morning. Although she used to live
with her sister, Ms. Toledo, 47, a custodian at Fairfield
University, recently moved to a homeless shelter at a Y.M.C.A. in
Bridgeport. Several friends have said that she might have been
afraid that her sister would take her children away, claiming that
she was mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Although they still do not know why she was on the tracks at
that early morning hour, investigators say Ms. Toledo was killed
when she suddenly realized a train was approaching and tried to
grab one of her sons from the path of the train. The other boys,
they said, followed her and all of them were struck. One of the
boys survived, but died two days later of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Urgiles, whose trip was paid for by an Ecuadoran television
station and the state airline, said he had yet to absorb what had
happened to his family. ``I feared something terrible would happen
to them here,'' he said. ``I am destroyed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0025 </DOCNO>
