<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5861 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     05-29 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS FOUGHT BACK THEIR WAY: BATTERING, BRUISING THEIR FOE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ With a sudden 2-0 deficit staring them in the chops,
the Stars were forced to revert to their inner selves last night.
</P>
<P>
   You know the drill. ``Concussions _ Half-Off.''
</P>
<P>
   For the ensuing 55 minutes and then some, the corners and ends
of the McNichols Arena ice might as well have been lined off with
that yellow police tape. Just as their coach sermonizes, the Stars
were going to earn their way back into the hockey game one
purposeful shoulder at a time.
</P>
<P>
   They won't be coming home with the road sweep that they worked
so hard for in Game 4 of this NHL Western Conference final series.
But given the couldas, wouldas and shouldas of the first five
minutes, the Stars' 3-2 loss in overtime to the Colorado Avalanche
seemed almost a swallowable consolation prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got what we came for,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said,
seeing the bigger picture of a series knotted at two games apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a best-of-three now, and two of the games are on our
ice.''
</P>
<P>
   The words weren't just post-game fluff. Hitchcock wasn't trying
to spin-doctor what turned out to be a disappointing ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played great in every game of the series,'' the coach
went on. ``The two goals they had in regulation were both
`seeing-eye dogs.' We're playing with a tremendous amount of energy
and emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a great series _ exactly what we thought it would
be.''
</P>
<P>
   What Hitchcock knows is that after the Avs' two early
``seeing-eye dogs'' found the other side of Ed Belfour, it was the
Stars who patiently dictated the flow of play for the remaining 55
regulation minutes.
</P>
<P>
   They did it the way that Hitchcock preaches _ winning individual
battles and not abandoning the game plan. They did it with
persistent checking in the neutral zone, which continues to fluster
the Avalanche. They did it with Mike Modano and Joe Nieuwendyk
again outplaying Colorado's Joe Sakic and Peter Forsberg.
</P>
<P>
   They did it with defenseman Derian Hatcher, tattooing Avs onto
the corner boards all night long.
</P>
<P>
   After Sakic's and Shjon Podein's deflected ``seeing-eye dogs''
gave the home team the lead, Hatcher became a dog with a different
bite.
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what will win this series, if the Stars
continue to follow their own script. And why wouldn't they? If
there ever was an itch to scratch, an urge to flex their wings and
answer the Avalanche's early salvo, last night was the night.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, they didn't. They shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   The series is even. Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   After the Avs' second goal, the Stars killed off a power play
for the 10th time in 11 tries in this series. Colorado scored six
times (out of 30) with the manpower advantage in its semi-final
series with Detroit. But against the Stars, the Avs are now
1-for-16.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado still looks uncomfortable with the attention that it's
getting while trying to traverse between the blue lines. For two
nights at McNichols, the fans have roared whenever Theo Fleury or
another Avs winger have grabbed the puck in the neutral zone and
set sail up the ice.
</P>
<P>
   But each time, a Stars defenseman _ usually Richard Matvichuk,
Darryl Sydor or Hatcher _ has rushed up to greet the onrushing Av
and poke him harmlessly off the puck. The crowd's oohs have turned
into a night-long chorus of awws.
</P>
<P>
   It's called Stars hockey. Hitchcock preaches it. The team
believes it, as it reminded us last night.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, once handed a two-goal deficit, the Stars
turned up the heat on the game's physical play. Matvichuk was lost
in an aggressive collision with Forsberg behind the end line. Guy
Carbonneau wobbled off at one point, but returned.
</P>
<P>
   Deserving credit should go to Colorado's Adam Foote for trying
to match the Stars, stick for stick, check for check. But now,
really. Aside from Claude Lemieux, the Avs' resident weasel,
Colorado still doesn't have the bodies or the commitment to play a
rugged, patient hockey game with the Presidents' Trophy winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much become a war,'' said Chris Drury, who poked
in the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   But there's Colorado's mountain-sized problem. The war began in
Game 1, as far as the Stars are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   They head home bloodied, but not all that unhappy. Actually,
they like the blood, if you've been paying attention.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
