<SLUG> BC-ADOPT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOPTION RING ARREST SURPRISES DOUGLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 and GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOUGLAS, Ariz. _ In Spanish, they call Mario Reyes ``Capi'' _
The Captain, the man who runs things.
</P>
<P>
   He was the American lawyer who made a mint with his practice
across the border in Agua Prieta, Sonora.
</P>
<P>
   He was the lector at Immaculate Conception Catholic Church who
had breakfast daily with the priest.
</P>
<P>
   He was the candidate for Douglas City Council two years ago who
ran on a platform of better education and family values.
</P>
<P>
   He was the business leader who owned a gas station and liquor
store.
</P>
<P>
   So, this border city was shocked when federal agents swooped in
late Wednesday and hauled Reyes, 40, away.
</P>
<P>
   The government alleges that he and two women from the New York
City area ran an illegal adoption ring in which they paid Mexican
women for 17 babies, spirited the children out of the country and
then sold them to couples on Long Island for as much as $22,000.
</P>
<P>
   The news had tongues wagging at the restaurant of the historic
Gadsden Hotel, said Aida Moulinet, a shift supervisor and friend of
the Reyes family.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing is just shocking, like getting hit in the head with
a board,'' Moulinet said. ``No one is more respected in this town
than he is.''
</P>
<P>
   But Moulinet, like many other Douglas residents, said they never
really gave much thought to what kind of law practice Reyes had in
Agua Prieta. His office was a cubbyhole storefront next to his
family's liquor store, a block away from the border crossing
station.
</P>
<P>
   They had seen him a lot more in Douglas the last few months.
That's curious, some thought.
</P>
<P>
   He took a job as a substitute English teacher in nearby Bisbee
for $50 a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an interesting guy who left a very good impression on the
students,'' said Anna Marie Salmon, office manager for Bisbee High
School. ``But we never had a clue that he was this interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   As law officers on both sides of the border closed in on Reyes,
his world began falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   First, his Douglas businesses went belly up.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the church distanced itself from him last year after the
Mexicans issued a warrant for his arrest on charges of illegally
trafficking in children.
</P>
<P>
   His fear of arrest in Mexico left him unable to take up the
cases of Mexicans who claimed to be abused by U.S. immigration
officials, an effort that had made him very unpopular over the
years in U.S. Border Patrol and Immigration and Naturalization
Service circles.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes was spending a lot more time on the U.S. side of the
border.
</P>
<P>
   A large lock is now on his law office door. Two panes of glass
are broken, and debris is scattered throughout the building.
</P>
<P>
   Those around Reyes faced trouble, too.
</P>
<P>
   Margarita Soto de Smith cared for the babies in Reyes' home.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, her name appeared on the birth certificate as the
birth mother of a child given for adoption. But she told
authorities, the child was not hers.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Mexican authorities arrested Soto in Agua Prieta
when she attempted to cross the border with the child. That baby is
still being cared for by the Mexican government's child protective
agency, known as the DIF, in Agua Prieta.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report from ``El Imparcial,'' a leading Mexican
newspaper, the birth mother was a 16-year-old girl from the state
of Veracruz on the Caribbean coast.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican Attorney General's office, which began investigating
the baby ring last March, issued a warrant charging Reyes and two
other individuals with trafficking of minors, unlawful detention of
a minor and conspiracy. Authorities refused to name the other
suspects because they are not yet in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Charges eventually may be brought against another eight to 10
individuals, said Ernesto Garcia Guerrero, the head of the federal
attorney general's office in Sonora.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence so far Reyes paid for any of the 17
children he put up for adoption, nor evidence that any of the
babies were stolen, according to Mexican officials. Investigators
have located only three of the 17 birth mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes did not pay the women who gave up their babies
voluntarily, but he covered the costs of their delivery, said
Rafael Flores Cardenas, the federal attorney for Agua Prieta.
</P>
<P>
   Flores said Reyes told him that he arranged the adoptions out of
compassion because the women could not afford to raise their
babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a Catholic lay minister and would give communion in
church, so many people trusted him,'' Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   No one has yet requested that the children involved in the
illegal adoptions be returned to Mexico, and no parent has stepped
forward with a claim to the babies placed with American couples,
U.S. and Mexican officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Murphy, U.S. consul in Nogales, said, ``Mexican authorities
have been conducting their own extremely thorough investigation of
the Mexican side of this case. They have been very helpful in
sharing information with American investigators. The information
from the Mexican side was extremely important in developing the
case against Mr. Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exploitation of small children is something that simply
will not be accepted,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   According to an interview Reyes gave to ``El Imparcial'' after
Soto's arrest last year, he estimated he had arranged about 40
adoptions of children born mostly in Agua Prieta or the state of
Sinaloa. He insisted all the adoptions were legal.
</P>
<P>
   Salvador Cassian-Santos, the Mexican consul general in Phoenix,
said Mexico takes adoption very seriously and every adoption
application is reviewed to ensure the birth parents are voluntarily
giving up their child to a suitable home.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of ``express adoptions'' conducted by Reyes exploited
the desires of the prospective parents to have a child but skipped
Mexico's arduous adoption process, Cassian-Santos said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a lengthy and complicated process followed to protect
the interests of the children and the parents, both natural and
adoptive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The DIF oversees all adoptions in Mexico. ``They conduct a
socioeconomic study of the couple interested in adopting to prove
they are of good moral character, can provide an adequate home
environment and have sufficient resources to feed and educate the
child properly,'' Cassian-Santos said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also check to be sure that the child is being
given up voluntarily by the birth mother or parents. If everything
squares, a family court judge will issue an adoption certificate at
a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a transaction that can be handled long-distance or
by mail. They can hire a lawyer to represent them in court, but
they must be present,'' Cassian-Santos said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his office has not processed any recent requests from
Americans interested in adopting.
</P>
<P>
   The last time most Douglas residents saw Reyes was earlier this
week when he delivered a prayer to open the city's Little League
baseball season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes from a very reputable family in Agua Prieta and has
been a very dedicated family man,'' said Douglas Mayor Ray Borane.
``It's very sad to see something happen like this to a man who had
so much to offer.'' &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at (602) 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
Graciela Sevilla can be reached at (602) 444-4783 or at
graciela.sevilla &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
