<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE PLUS SIDE: MARINERS WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mariner 500, seemingly a two-year race to nowhere,
took a pit stop Friday night. Put the brakes on. Screeched to a
halt.
</P>
<P>
   For just the third time in 207 games, the home club climbed
above the break-even mark, pushing forward with a 6-1 victory over
Tampa Bay before 25,421 fans at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Huskey's three-run home run and Russ Davis' solo shot
backed another precocious effort by one-third of Randy Johnson's
trade bounty, rookie pitcher Freddy Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome left the Mariners at 24-23, their first peek at the
top side of the ledger since they were 4-3 on April 12. They
experienced a winning record only once during the 1998 season, at
19-18 on May 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hope it continues,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``It
coincides with pitching. Our pitching has gotten better.''
</P>
<P>
   Said first baseman David Segui: ``We're a lot better than a .500
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskey pointed the Mariners in a positive direction when he
crunched a two-out homer in the first inning, scoring Alex
Rodriguez and Ken Griffey Jr. The others had reached base on a pair
of Texas Leaguers, balls softly landing in right and center fields,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing light and breezy about Huskey's connection.
</P>
<P>
   On a 2-0 pitch, the Mariner right fielder took a cut so
forceful, he looked like a high handicapper letting one rip off the
first tee at Jackson Park. He nearly fell over. One hand flew off
the bat. The ball was pulled dead left. But in this instance, he
didn't have to tee it up again. The blast landed about 20 rows up
in left field, 401 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Huskey said he felt sick all day, but not enough to come out of
the lineup. Sometimes you play better that way, he reasoned. A
misplaced Wilson Alvarez changeup was the right tonic in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you go up to the plate for, you want to hit a
mistake,'' said Huskey, who has eight homers and 30 RBIs. ``I just
saw it and hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   As Huskey circled the bases, unsubstantiated trade rumors were
circulating in Los Angeles that he would soon become a Dodger in a
three-way trade that included the New York Yankees. In the
exchange, the Mariners and Yankees supposedly would receive
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Piniella nor Huskey was aware of any such deal being
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' the Mariner manager said. ``I doubt it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Me to the Dodgers?'' Huskey said. ``I haven't heard
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis used a more restrained swing than Huskey, but launched a
longer homer in the fifth inning. His two-out poke to left-center
traveled 422 feet, hitting halfway up the dark blue background
tarp. It was his 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey and Segui didn't find the fence on this night, but each
singled, extending their respective hitting streaks. Griffey is now
at 16, Segui 13.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia (6-1) went just the minimum five innings, his outing cut
short by an inexplicable case of wildness. But when he was out
there, the Devil Rays couldn't hit him, collecting just four
singles. Two hits and Miguel Cairo's sacrifice fly produced the
only run off him.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander struggled mightily in the fifth, walking the
bases full with two outs. He threw balls in the dirt. He took off
his hat and paced behind the mound. But rather than suffer a
complete meltdown, he retired Jose Canseco on a 2-1 pitch, getting
him to ground to third for an easy forceout.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco had other unpleasant moments as well. Early on, he had
words with a heckler who was escorted out of the stands by three
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's hasty exit was prompted by poor mechanics. Piniella's
law finished him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk three hitters like that, you give up runs; we
were fortunate,'' the manager said. ``He started opening up his
front shoulder and lost his control. ... We expect all of our
starting pitchers to give us six or seven innings. But Freddy's
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Garcia, who had no problem with the early hook: ``I lose my
mechanics. I open my shoulder. I don't follow through.''
</P>
<P>
   Another rookie, Jordan Zimmerman, replaced Garcia and threw two
shutout innings, permitting only a harmless walk to his first
batter, Fred McGriff.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Jose Paniagua finished it off with two more shutout
innings, with McGriff's single the only interruption.
</P>
<P>
   It was a win-win situation. For Seattle, a victory and a record
on the plus side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to keep it up,'' Piniella said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
