<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5899 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN     05-29 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
 
McDONALD RALLIES FOR VICTORY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Be careful what you wish for, it just might
come true.
</P>
<P>
   It did for Dusty McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   The Simi Valley resident pulled off the near-impossible when he
edged Gerrit Cromsigt to win the NASCAR Late Model feature Friday
night before a sparse crowd at Irwindale Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Other winners were La Verne's Scott Porter in Mini Stocks and
Mike Price in Super Stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just speechless,'' said McDonald, who overcame a 10-car
length deficit to eke past Cromsigt by about a foot at the finish.
``I really don't know what to say. I guess I know how Jeff Gordon
feels now.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, it appeared Cromsigt, who increased his points lead
with the second-place finish, would win his fourth event in five
tries.
</P>
<P>
   The Pine Mountain Club resident grabbed the lead on the
backstretch of the opening lap and increased his advantage to
nearly 600 feet near the middle of the 40-lap event.
</P>
<P>
   But McDonald kept plugging away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very confident with my car,'' said McDonald, who sliced
Cromsigt's advantage to a mere car length with three laps to go.
``My crew chief is a set-up genius. I just pushed it as hard as I
could so I could catch up with (Cromsigt). When I did, I was kind
of amazed. I just kept running different lines, hoping he would
mess up and I could take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   That came as both drivers took the white flag.
</P>
<P>
   Then as both approached turn 3, McDonald took an inside line,
and slipped just in front of Cromsigt as both exited turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed in front for the victory, although at first the
scoreboard showed Cromsigt as the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really couldn't tell you what happened that last lap,''
McDonald said. ``I was trying to get underneath him because I knew
I had more coming out of the turn. He had more going into the turn,
but I seemed to have more coming out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was praying to God that I'd won because I couldn't see his
front end past mine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mini Stock feature was dominated by Porter, who won for the
second time in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Suchy finished second, with Fontana's Kevin Bernhardt
third.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach's Garry Kenyon, who finished 0.589 seconds behind
Porter, was disqualified following a postrace inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Porter, the son-in-law of Winston West racer Kenny Smith, did
receive some challenges in the 20-lap race.
</P>
<P>
   Both came from Kenyon, who started third before moving up to
second when he bumped Richard Yanker Jr. on the front stretch of
the third lap.
</P>
<P>
   Twice Kenyon was able to rub the back bumper of Porter's Ford
Pinto, the last coming on lap 16.
</P>
<P>
   Porter, who moved up to fourth in points with the victory, then
slowly increased his lead over Kenyon before winning by about three
car lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Price won a thrilling 25-lap fight in the Super Stock feature.
</P>
<P>
   The San Pedro resident, who started sixth, took advantage of a
late caution to beat North Hills' T.K. Karvasek by 0.248 seconds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 0245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
