<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 08:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      05-29 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, May 30, will move Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-REVIEW (Undated) _ Now that a congressional committee has
released its three-volume, 872-page techno thriller on what it
believes was the theft of atomic secrets by Chinese spies, much of
Washington is agog. But the uproar overlooks an arresting fact. For
more than half a decade, the Clinton administration was shoveling
atomic secrets out the door as fast as it could, literally by the
ton. Free to all takers, including China's bomb makers, were
millions of previously classified ideas and documents related to
nuclear arms. The tale of that giveaway and what it helped
accomplish, its architects say, is more subtle and perhaps
ultimately more important than the congressional nail-biter. By
William F. Broad. (a category)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   STUDENT-BEHAVIOR-REVIEW (Undated) _ As the nation's school year
limps to an anxious close, with teachers and principals exhausted
from worry about safety and undetected rage, educators and
psychologists say they are re-examing adolescent behavior _ the
moods, the cliques, the barely repressed violence _ and finding
that American society has failed to come to terms with how such
behavior has changed in recent decades. By Ethan Bronner. (a
category)
</P>
<P>
   GUN-RIGHTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Second Amendment, the orphan
of the Bill of Rights, has been written off as a legal backwater
for decades. Judges and legal scholars have glossed over its
guarantee of the right ``to keep and bear arms'' as if it were so
much propaganda for the National Rifle Association. But now, just
as gun control is gaining momentum, the provision one legal scholar
calls ``the embarrassing Second Amendment'' is being taken
seriously for the first time in modern memory, with some scholars
and at least one federal judge saying it may guarantee individual
citizens some rights to guns, after all. By William Glaberson. (a
category)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SHOOTING-REVIEW (Washington) _ It did not happen after the
bullets flew and the bodies fell at a high school in West Paducah,
Ky., in December 1997, nor did it happen on the heels of the
gunfire and bloodshed at schools in Jonesboro, Ark., or
Springfield, Ore., last year. But after Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., became a deadly shooting gallery on April 20, the
earth finally moved, at least politically speaking, in subtle but
undeniable ways. By Frank Bruni. (a category)
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE-LAWYERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Should defense counsel do
everything in their power to defend a client? Defense lawyers say
that obligation includes suggesting almost any scenario that can
possibly create doubt in a juror's mind. By Laura Masnerus. (a
category)
</P>
<P>
   NATO-REVIEW (Undated) _ NATO's bombing campaign in Yugoslavia
has exposed more than policy differences between the European and
American alliance partners. As never before, it has revealed the
vast technological gulf that separates American military
capabilities from those of Britain, France and the others. And
that, in turn, shows just how much the Europeans remain militarily
dependent on the United States for their own defense _ dependent,
and resentful. By Craig R. Whitney. (i category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REVIEW (Undated) _ Is Kosovo a liberal cause? A
conservative one? Actually, it's hard to tell. By Patricia Cohen.
(i category)
</P>
<P>
   WEST-CODE-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Spokane (Wash.) County
Commission this month published a pamphlet called the ``Code of the
West'' to forewarn new and prospective residents about the pitfalls
of supposedly idyllic country life. You might also call it ``How
the West Is Not Fun.'' Here are excerpts. By Tom Kuntz. (a
category)
</P>
<P>
   SYMPHONIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Imagine being Franz Xaver
Suessmayr. Your teacher, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, is dying, just as
he's writing one of his greatest works. On his deathbed he explains
how he envisions completing it. The rest is up to you. Poor
Suessmayr. No one can say which parts of the ``Requiem'' he had to
make up, and he never wrote anything particularly good after that.
The ``Requiem'' case suggests that finishing the unfinished
artworks of the dead has never been an easy business, and recent
news from the art and literary worlds confirms it anew. By Jenny
Lyn Bader. (a category)
</P>
<P>
   POETRY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Now that the fanfare around National
Poetry Month in April has died down _ the readings, the poetry
slams, the tractor pulls _ there is time for a little serious
contemplation about the future of the form. Questions abound: Is
there a hot genre? What will the new millennium bring? Are the
poetry wars over? Have the Nuyoricans, those anti-establishment
esthetes, sold out? And, finally, will it ever be OK to rhyme
again? By Jesse McKinley. (a category)
</P>
