<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      05-29 1624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, May 30:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-INAUG (Abuja, Nigeria) _ In an exuberant ceremony of
martial music and marches, Nigeria's military ruler handed over
power to an elected leader Saturday, opening an era of civilian
government in the nation where one in six Africans live. By
Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIBET (United Nations) _ The United States appears to be
heading for another clash with China, this time over a divisive
World Bank development loan that would help Chinese authorities
resettle tens of thousands of Chinese in regions traditionally
inhabited by Tibetans and Mongolians. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   SLOVAKIA-ELECTION (Bratislava, Slovakia) _ Slovaks faced a
simple choice in the second round of their presidential election:
vote for further democratic progress and joining Europe, or slide
back into international isolation.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECTION (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ One year after former
Suharto's forced resignation, an extraordinary spectacle is
unfolding on the streets of Indonesia's cities: a true festival of
democracy _ a free and contested campaign with 48 parties, an
unpredictable outcome and giddy daylong rallies with all the
exuberance of a carnival. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-LEAD-POISONING (Torreon, Mexico) _ The mothers who live
just downwind from a towering lead-smelting plant have begun
describing their children by numbers. After living for decades with
grit from the great smelter, the families living near the plant
have discovered that their children are contaminated with dangerous
levels of lead. Recent tests of children from one corner of the
neighborhood were so high that authorities ordered 393 families to
be evacuated and their houses demolished. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (Washington) _ The United States is warning that
fighting between India and Pakistan in the icy mountains of Kashmir
risks ``spinning out of control'' and could result in the fourth
war between two nations that last year declared themselves to be
nuclear powers. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-POLITICS (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ The party whose
slogan used to be ``one settler, one bullet'' is trying to stay in
office by appealing to the nostalgia vote. The Pan Africanist
Congress now preaches ``non-racialism'' and says it welcomes anyone
who considers himself an African first, including white Afrikaners.
But it insists it is the true torchbearer of the ideals upon which
the African National Congress was founded in 1912. The ANC, it
argues, went off track in 1959 when it embraced the Communist
Party, Indians and mixed-race voters, thus diluting what was then
supposed to be a black nationalist struggle. By Donald G. McNeil
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-POLITICS (Buenos Aires, Argentina) _ As the race to
replace President Carlos Saul Menem of Argentina heated up in
recent weeks, the two major candidates thought they had found an
ideal campaign theme: blame the incumbent's free market economic
policies for rising unemployment and promise major changes if
elected. But investors got so nervous that rumors swirled of an
impending devaluation of the peso, and the already jittery local
stock market took a nose dive. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ The civilian at the top of the
U.S. military, Secretary of Defense William Cohen, rarely speaks
directly to Gen. Wesley Clark, the commander waging America's
longest war since Vietnam. The soldier at the top, Gen. Henry
Shelton, is the general who is said to be unwilling _ or unable _
to air the Pentagon's misgivings about the war. By Steven Lee Myers
and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Radiovce, Macedonia) _ The Macedonians and
Albanians living in this village of 1,500 people till their soil
side by side. But they inhabit separate worlds, speaking different
languages, sending their children to different schools and never
intermarrying. NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia and the arrival of more
than 230,000 ethnic Albanian refugees in Macedonia have widened the
distance between the dual worlds of Radiovce. About 260 refugees
from Kosovo have been taken in by Albanian families here. Not one
has been taken in by Macedonians. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MISSING-MEN (Kukes, Albania) _ What happened to the
thousands of Kosovar Albanian men _ from boys barely of fighting
age to grandfathers _ who were separated from their families in
recent weeks in Kosovo, shoved into trucks and who then
disappeared? A partial answer to one of the scarier questions in
the devastation of Kosovo has been staggering across the border
here. The fear was that the men were killed by Serb militias, and
perhaps some were. But in the last week, about 2,000 men crossed
the border into Albania, most unshaven, some weeping, with no money
or belts around pants. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MICH-WELFARE (Detroit) _ In a controversial and unusual effort
to move more welfare recipients into the work force, Michigan plans
a pilot program that would require thousands of those applying for
aid to take drug tests to qualify for benefits. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   FARM-PSYCHOLOGIST (Harlan, Iowa) _ After hauling oats to his
cattle before sunrise on the Iowa prairie, Michael Rosmann drives
to an office and sits down with farmer after farmer to listen to
their troubles. A fourth-generation farmer as well as a clinical
psychologist, he speaks the language of men and women on the verge
of losing their place on the land. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-BLACK-BOX (Undated) _ A newly developed data box being
installed in hundreds of thousands of GM cars this year records not
only the force of collisions and the air bag's performance, but
also captures five seconds of data before impact. It can determine,
for example, whether the driver applied the brakes in the fifth
second, third second or last second. It also records the last five
seconds of vehicle speed, engine speed, gas pedal position and
whether the driver was wearing a seat belt. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ANTISMOKING (Albany, N.Y.) _ New York, until recently
considered a leader in combating smoking, is rapidly becoming a
laggard, as other states leapfrog past it in the size and
aggressiveness of their efforts. By Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   BRONX-ZOO-GORILLAS (New York) _ The new Congo Gorilla Forest at
the Bronx Zoo opens June 25, and its gorilla occupants are still
getting used to the lush surroundings and the newfound freedom. By
Douglas Martin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Beginning next week, the Forbes
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination is opening an
usually early and heavy multimillion-dollar advertising offensive
nationwide, with an emphasis in primary battleground states, that
is intended to repackage Forbes. The message: Forbes, far from the
monotonous advocate of a flat tax who ran in 1996, has the breadth
and the personality to sit in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VOUCHERS (Washington) _ Exposing the sharp debate over
school vouchers among black people, two long-time allies from the
civil rights struggle in Florida find themselves on opposite sides
on whether the state should help pay for some children to attend
private schools. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   FLAG-BURNING-AMENDMENT (Washington) _ One of these days _ not on
Flag Day, June 14, and not even by the Fourth of July, but probably
sometime this year _ Republicans in the Senate will bring up a
proposed constitutional amendment that would permit laws banning
flag-burning. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENT-SALARY (Washington) _ Despite repeated requests, fewer
than half the candidates commented last week on a proposal in
Congress to raise the pay of the President to $400,000. The salary
has been $200,000 since Richard M. Nixon took office in 1969. By
David Stout
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Here at the Ardsthorpe. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (New York) _ A cop who cared. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
