<SLUG> BC-NATO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, ALLIES, FOLLOW ME. I'VE GOT ALL THE NEW TOYS. 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jt) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATO's bombing campaign in Yugoslavia has exposed more than
policy differences between the European and American alliance
partners. As never before, it has revealed the vast technological
gulf that separates American military capabilities from those of
Britain, France and the others. And that, in turn, shows how much
the Europeans remain militarily dependent on the United States for
their own defense _ dependent, and resentful.
</P>
<P>
   For Europe these days, the word ``defense'' means the ability to
deal with problems like Kosovo on their own continent. But that,
more and more, means the ability to bring technology to bear. And
since the Americans have most of the technology, the Americans call
most of the shots on strategy and tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Take the way the air war has developed.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, all the allies hoped a ground war would be
unnecessary. But nobody except the United States had enough
sophisticated F-14, F-15, F-16 and F-18 fighters and
fighter-bombers to launch the kind of campaign that might avoid a
ground war.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody but the United States had the ``stealth'' F-117
fighters and B-2 bombers whose strange shapes and composite
materials make it hard for Yugoslavia's sophisticated air defenses
to shoot them down.
</P>
<P>
   So the allies agreed on an air war but had to accept American
ideas about how it should be fought.
</P>
<P>
   The primary American concern was to minimize allied losses, and
the allied losses have been negligible. But the bombing campaign
has not prevented continued ethnic cleansing in Kosovo, and now
this is widening fissures that were probably there from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Consider one reason the B-2s fly their missions all the way from
Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri: The United States does not
want even most of its European friends to get a close look at the
planes.
</P>
<P>
   And among all its allies, the United States has judged only
Britain trustworthy enough to acquire any of the satellite-guided
American-developed Tomahawk cruise missiles, which can carry out
precision attacks from ships hundreds of miles away. Even the
British got only 65, while the United States has hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   Having to deal with Kosovo the American way, with bombing
instead of ground troops, had advantages for the Europeans, but
also drawbacks. The longer the bombing drags on inconclusively, the
greater the frustration and resentment in both Europe and America.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as some military thinkers are beginning to say a ground
campaign may become necessary before autumn, all that the allies
have been able to agree on is a plan to put 50,000 troops in Kosovo
as peacekeepers if Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan Milosevic,
finally backs down and lets international troops escort Kosovo's
refugees back home.
</P>
<P>
   But even that plan, calling for perhaps 7,000 American ground
troops, would not dull the edge that technology gives the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   If tens of thousands of fresh troops must be flown in quickly as
peacekeepers, only the United States has enough giant C-5, C-141
and C-17 air transports to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   And if the allies decide this summer that air power alone is not
enough to make Milosevic back down _ which might or might not be
more likely now that he has been indicted as a war criminal by the
international tribunal in The Hague _ only the United States could
quickly fly in or provide the 100,000 or more troops required to
drive Yugoslav forces out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's ability to move around huge numbers of troops is
``deplorably slow,'' in the words of NATO's recently retired senior
military officer, Gen. Klaus Naumann of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the United States continues to dominate the skies over
Kosovo, with up to 815 aircraft (including Apache anti-tank
helicopters still waiting for combat and KC-135 refueling planes).
All 18 other allies together provide 277, with more than half of
those coming from France (102 Mirage, Jaguar, Super-Etendards and
other planes), and Britain (38 Harrier GR-7 and Tornado GR-1
fighter-bombers and support aircraft).
</P>
<P>
   One result is that Europeans are talking again, as they have
been doing for years, about a need to fix the imbalance.
</P>
<P>
   And as flaws in the American air-war strategy emerge, some
Europeans are blaming its failures on the Clinton administration's
reluctance to expose air crews to danger. Most allied pilots fly
only above 15,000 feet, beyond the reach of conventional Yugoslav
anti-aircraft artillery. But they are far less effective against
Serbian armor than they would be if they flew lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Military pilots are paid to risk their lives, and most of ours
feel frustrated a lot of the time,'' a French official said. ``But
the United States has a zero-deaths policy, and the United States
is running the show.''
</P>
<P>
   A reluctance to take casualties is only one factor. The
availability of an alternative is another. As Naumann pointed out,
most European countries lack the Americans' ability to launch
laser- and satellite-guided bombs at a safe distance from ground
fire. ``Most European planes,'' he said, ``have to fly more or less
over the targets, which is the most stupid thing you can do, since
you expose yourself to the enemy air defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain and France agreed late last year that one lesson of
previous wars in the Balkans was that Europe needed to build up
autonomous defense capabilities within the alliance. The day would
come, the French argued, when the United States might tire of
entanglements and the Europeans would have to act alone.
Paradoxically, it is American involvement in Kosovo, rather than
withdrawal, that has revived the issue now.
</P>
<P>
   But in order to achieve real change, Europeans would have to
spend billions of dollars to catch up with the technological
revolution that the American military achieved in the 1970s and
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Naumann said, spends $36 billion a year on
defense research and development, while all the European allies and
Canada together have been spending only $10 billion. Last year,
according to NATO figures, the United States spent the equivalent
of 3.2 percent of its gross domestic product on defense, 27 percent
of it on equipment and infrastructure; the European allies averaged
2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't want a European military organization that can get
along without the Americans and reduce military budgets,'' a
retired French general, Pierre Gallois, said. And the United States
is increasing military spending, while the Europeans are
continually cutting back.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of spending, they vow at NATO summit meetings like the
one in Washington in April to build a stronger European security
and defense identity within the alliance. They will probably make
another one at a summit meeting of the European Union in Cologne at
the end of this week, now that NATO has agreed to let European
countries use NATO facilities for future operations that the United
States doesn't join.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Naumann commented, these arrangements exist only on
paper. ``What we now need to see are deeds, and it is urgent that
something is done,'' he said. Kosovo might finally make the allies
actually do something.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
