   NY-ANTISMOKING (Albany, N.Y.) _ New York, until recently
considered a leader in combating smoking, is rapidly becoming a
laggard, as other states leapfrog past it in the size and
aggressiveness of their efforts. By Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 2 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ The civilian at the top of the
U.S. military, Secretary of Defense William Cohen, rarely speaks
directly to Gen. Wesley Clark, the commander waging America's
longest war since Vietnam. The soldier at the top, Gen. Henry
Shelton, is the general who is said to be unwilling _ or unable _
to air the Pentagon's misgivings about the war. By Steven Lee Myers
and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 2 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   2-graf refer:
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-LEAD-POISONING (Torreon, Mexico) _ The mothers who live
just downwind from a towering lead-smelting plant have begun
describing their children by numbers. After living for decades with
grit from the great smelter, the families living near the plant
have discovered that their children are contaminated with dangerous
levels of lead. Recent tests of children from one corner of the
neighborhood were so high that authorities ordered 393 families to
be evacuated and their houses demolished. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
