<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Sunday, May 30, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Stew Slavin at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   GALLEGLY-ROCKETDYNE (Los Angeles) _ For almost decade, as
community concern has built over Rocketdyne's field lab, Elton
Gallegly has been the Congressman representing the Simi Valley area
that includes the hilltop test site. As lawmakers have pressed to
investigate and clean up the facility, sometimes stretching across
their districts to join the debate, the six-term Congressman has
been among the quieter legislators. But he says he and his staff
have been active behind the scenes, working with other lawmakers
and using the system to make sure the clean-up gets done. By Lisa
Mascaro. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTHY-COLUMN _ Their jaws jut out in pride at the mention of
their old Marine outfit, and they get this look in their eyes that
says even 50 years later, they're still watching each others'
backs. Not as young, fighting men in the freezing foxholes of North
Korea anymore, but as retired guys more interested in how their
flower beds are doing, and if their arthritis is flaring up. They
are called the Chosin Few, and if you haven't heard of them before
its because they fought in one of those wars this country has been
trying hard to forget happened _ the Korean War.
</P>
