<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEWS OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Clash Over Kashmir, India Sends In Its First Jets
</P>
<P>
   Two Indian jets were lost in airstrikes against a large force of
guerrillas dug into the mountains of Kashmir. It was the first time
New Delhi has used jet fighters and helicopters gunships in its
decade-long dispute with Pakistan, sharply increasing tensions in
the nuclear-armed subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
   India's ground troops have so far failed to dislodge 500 to 600
Islamic militants who have seized strategic places in the Himalaya
Mountains. India says the force is operating with Pakistan's
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   _ BARRY BEARAK
</P>
<P>
   Cloned Sheep's Cells Aging
</P>
<P>
   The genetic material in Dolly, the sheep that was the first
animal to be successfully cloned from an adult, may be showing a
sign of aging, in effect appearing older than the sheep itself,
said the scientists in Scotland who created the animal. If
confirmed, the finding would be the first sign of possible genetic
abnormalities in cloned animals.
</P>
<P>
   Leading investigators said they were not yet convinced by the
preliminary data, which were published in a letter to the journal
Nature. ``It's premature to draw rock-solid conclusions from this
scant amount of data,'' said Dr. Robert Weinberg, a cancer
researcher at the Whitehead Institute of the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   An Unlawful Donor
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three years after John Huang emerged as a central figure
in the furor over how Democrats financed President Clinton's
re-election, the Justice Department announced that Huang would
plead guilty to a single felony charge of conspiring to make
illegal contributions. Republicans dismissed the plea agreement as
a sweetheart deal: Huang will receive no jail time in exchange for
his continuing cooperation with authorities. Federal prosecutors
will also clear him of charges contained in congressional reports
on the fund-raising issue that he may have had an espionage
relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   A School's Responsibility
</P>
<P>
   As the Supreme Court interpreted federal laws over the years to
provide protection against sexual harassment, uncertainty remained
over whether any law even applied to harassment of one student by
another. Now, as a result of a bitterly fought 5-4 ruling, school
districts are on notice that they can be sued for failing to stop
severe and pervasive harassment in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   The court's dissenters said the ruling opened the door to
massive federal intrusion. But school board lawyers said that it
was clear the ruling applied only to egregious behavior and that
they could live with it.
</P>
<P>
   _ LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire's New Holiday
</P>
<P>
   As one civil rights advocate put it, New Hampshire won the race
to be last. It effectively agreed to become the 50th state to adopt
a holiday honoring the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. The state
House of Representatives, which had resisted in the past, voted
solidly to attach King's name to the existing Civil Rights Day, and
no further hindrances remained to the new holiday. Most other
states approved a Martin Luther King Day in the 1980s. So what took
New Hampshire so long? Some holiday advocates said it was not
racism that resisted the change but the tradition-bound,
independent-minded nature of residents.
</P>
<P>
   _ CAREY GOLDBERG
</P>
<P>
   Embryo Research
</P>
<P>
   Should scientists be allowed to experiment on abandoned human
embryos, the tiny spheres of cells often generated in excess by
fertility clinics? The National Bioethics Advisory Commission
signaled it would approve a specific use: the removal from embryos
of the all-purpose stem cells, which generate all the tissues and
organs of the body. Biologists hope these cells may directly
replace damaged tissues, including brain cells lost in Parkinson's
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of abortion and their allies in Congress are likely to
resist the decision.
</P>
<P>
   _ NICHOLAS WADE
</P>
<P>
   Charges Dropped
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr said he would not seek to retry Susan McDougal and
Julie Hiatt Steele, whom he had accused of giving false or
misleading testimony about President Clinton (Ms. McDougal about a
Arkansas real estate ventures, Ms. Steele about sexual
indiscretions). Both trials ended in deadlock. The independent
counsel is still pursuing Webster Hubbell, an old Clinton friend
and former Justice Department official. Starr's associates have
said he may yet try to prosecute Clinton himself.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID STOUT
</P>
<P>
   SWEET CHARITY
</P>
<P>
   Last year was good for charity: Americans donated a record $175
billion, 11 percent more than in 1997, according to Giving USA
1999, put out by the American Association of Fund-Raising Counsel's
nonprofit arm. The only area that declined was the arts, culture
and humanities (down about 1 percent). But donations jumped by 20
percent or more in environment and wildlife, health, human services
and public benefit organizations (which includes civil rights
groups, public affairs, consumer protection and scientific
development).
</P>
<P>
   _ KAREN W. ARENSON
</P>
<P>
   Day and Night Trading
</P>
<P>
   Citing demand from individuals who want to use the Internet to
trade stocks outside the normal market hours of 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m.
the Nasdaq stock market is planning an evening trading session,
lasting as late as 10, to begin later this year. The New York Stock
Exchange's board will consider a similar proposal when it meets on
Thursday. Some Wall Street professionals expect that stock markets
will soon be open around the clock _ just like casinos.
</P>
<P>
   _ EDWARD WYATT
</P>
<P>
   Diplomacy and Betrayal
</P>
<P>
   The balance of power between the United States and the United
Nations is always tricky. And now former Secretary General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali, in his book ``Unvanquished: A U.S.-U.N. Saga,''
writes of his 1996 ouster, blaming it on caving in to Bob Dole's
``claim that American troops served under my `command.''' He feels
especially betrayed by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, he
says, accusing her of lecturing instead of doing ``the difficult
diplomatic work of persuading.'' Albright's spokesman, James Rubin,
said Boutros-Ghali had neglected his core duty: ``Smooth
cooperation with the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   A Respite (Sort of) for Springer
</P>
<P>
   Many fans of ``The Jerry Springer Show'' were angered when the
episodes ``Guess What? I'm Bisexual'' and ``My Daughter Wants to Be
an Adult Film Star'' were yanked, replaced by tamer, 6-year-old
reruns. Some station owners were peeved, too, because the show
mesmerizes viewers at a Nielsen-rating level second only to
``Oprah'' and ``Judge Judy,'' earning scads of money.
</P>
<P>
   But Studios USA, the show's owner, was getting political heat
again about the daily format of sexual confrontations leading to
fights. And a Chicago alderman, Edward M. Burke, wanted to know why
off-duty Chicago policemen working as security guards don't arrest
guests for assault and battery.
</P>
<P>
   So executives at Studios USA got righteous _ again. First, they
announced they would ``control'' the violence (April 1998). Then
they said they'd ``eliminate'' it (June). They were also going to
``edit it responsibly'' (July). But the ratings fell. So breast
baring and hair pulling resumed. Now they say ``violence, physical
confrontation or profanity'' will again be edited out.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   Former Soviet, American-to-be
</P>
<P>
   Nikita Khrushchev, his son Sergei said, once told Richard Nixon,
``Your grandsons will live in a communist America.'' To which Nixon
replied, ``No, your grandsons will live in a capitalist Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, long after that quintessential nugget of Cold War
bluster, who has come closest to winning the bet? It would be a
stretch to say capitalism has truly taken root in Russia. America
hasn't gone communist, but it did lure a Khrushchev to its shores _
and in one generation, not two.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Sergei N. Khrushchev and his wife, Valentina Golenko,
became legal residents of Rhode Island. Khrushchev, unable to
venture abroad for 25 years after his father's ouster in 1964, said
one overriding attraction was the freedom to travel. Khrushchev had
been a member of the Soviet Communist Party, but Nixon, who spent a
good part of his career demonizing communists, supported his
resident-alien status.
</P>
<P>
   Now Khrushchev, 63, a rocket engineer turned Brown University
research scholar, and his wife are applying for American
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
