<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A COP WHO CARED 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Detective Investigator Juan Rodriguez, who died a
little over a week ago, was the kind of cop you don't hear much
about. He was 46 years old, skinny, wiry, tough, relentless and
incorruptible. He was soft-spoken and a sucker for kids. He didn't
strut, and he never engaged in macho games. But if you were a
criminal or a corrupt cop and Juan Rodriguez knew about it, you had
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez worked for the Queens district attorney's office. For
a while he was assigned to the Special Victims Bureau, which
handles sex crimes and the physical and sexual abuse of children.
</P>
<P>
   One of his toughest cases involved a woman who was a drug
addict. She was grabbed by a group of guys as she emerged, high,
from her apartment in Queens. She was badly beaten and then dragged
into an abandoned house, where she was held prisoner and gang raped
over a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
   When police were finally notified, there was very little in the
way of clues to work with. And, frankly, for a lot of officers, a
woman who is a drug addict is not a particularly sympathetic
victim. But Rodriguez pursued the case as doggedly as if she had
been a society matron.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Karen Migdal recalled the case last
week: ``He worked with her and met with her so many times, trying
to help her remember or figure out what had happened. He was able
to put together a phenomenal case and got almost everybody involved
arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years Rodriguez was a senior investigator in
the district attorney's Integrity Bureau. In 1997, he and his
partner, Detective Sgt. Richard Scantlebury, played key roles in
the arrest of Paul Voss, a police officer who robbed banks,
sometimes while on duty.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was one of the many cops in the district attorney
offices around the city and in the Police Department who do their
jobs quietly and competently, and often bravely, without abusing
people or bringing shame to their badges.
</P>
<P>
   He was particularly good with crime victims. He was
compassionate and empathized with their suffering and their fear.
And he had a knack for explaining to them, clearly and
convincingly, why it was so important for them, despite their fear,
to do all they could to nail the criminals who had victimized them.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of screaming headlines and pulse-pounding police
dramas on television and in the movies, it is the very ordinariness
of Rodriguez's life and his death at too early an age that is
striking. He died at home of a heart attack on Saturday morning,
May 22.
</P>
<P>
   ```Flamboyant' was a word that had nothing to do with Juan,''
said Scantlebury. ``He listened to people, and he treated everyone
respectfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's colleagues remembered him as much for his love of
his family as they did for his dedication to his job. Just 8{
months ago his wife, Patty, gave birth to their fourth child,
Nicholas. Normally reserved and always dignified, Rodriguez
couldn't help going about the office flashing pictures, smiling,
and in the words of one assistant district attorney, ``even
giggling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He always wanted to be a police officer, ever since he was a
little kid,'' said Mrs. Rodriguez. ``He would get upset when he
heard stories, you know, about what some of the bad cops would do.
He took the public's trust very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   On the night before he died Rodriguez arrested a lawyer who had
been disbarred in California and was not licensed to practice in
New York. She was emotionally troubled and, in the words of
Scantlebury, ``started acting up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting hot under the collar,'' the sergeant recalled,
``and Juan admonished me a little. He said, `Richie, you've been
doing this a lot of years now. This shouldn't bother you.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Queens district attorney, Richard Brown, described
Rodriguez's death as a tremendous loss. ``I was the one who
transferred him to the Integrity Bureau, which covers all
violations of public trust,'' said Brown. ``He had a great
reputation and his colleagues felt he was a very special guy.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Patty and Nicholas, Rodriguez is survived by a
daughter, Christina, 17, and two sons, Joseph, 15, and John, 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' said Patty Rodriguez. ``I sit back and I still
sort of feel like he's at work and I'm waiting for him to come
home.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
