<SLUG> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE DOCKS AT SPACE STATION AND CREW PREPARES TO WALK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BETH DICKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Hours after arriving at the international
space station aboard the first craft ever to dock there, the space
shuttle Discovery astronauts prepared Saturday for a spacewalk
outside the orbiting outpost to mount cranes and other tools for
use by future construction crews.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery docked with the space station at 12:24 ET Saturday
morning, concluding a 41-hour chase that began with the shuttle's
launching from Florida on Thursday. The shuttle and the unfinished
station _ consisting of a Russian control module and an
American-made connecting hub _ were flying at 17,500 mph 235 miles
above Russia when they made contact.
</P>
<P>
   Five men and two women from the United States, Canada and Russia
are preparing the station to accommodate its first permanent
occupants, a crew of two Russians and one American who are
scheduled to arrive early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been six months since anyone came to visit. Welcome
aboard,'' an unidentified engineer radioed from Mission Control in
Houston when the seven shuttle astronauts reached the space
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole station looks beautiful and we're happy to be
visiting and give you some work to do again,'' answered Daniel
Barry, one of two astronauts who planned to spend six hours outside
attaching to the station's exterior an American crane and parts of
another one manufactured in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The spacewalk called for Barry to float free and Tamara Jernigan
to attach herself to the shuttle's 50-foot robot arm and maneuver
up the outside of the station, which towers about 70 feet above the
cargo bay.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the spacewalkers nor their five crew mates have entered
the outpost yet. They opened the entrance briefly to remove some
obstructions Saturday morning. But they planned to wait until
Sunday to start unloading 3,600 pounds of clothing, computers,
tools and housekeeping supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're joined firmly tonight. The crew is working on starting
the ingress steps to the international space station,'' Wayne Hale,
the shuttle flight director, said in a news conference three hours
after Discovery had parked. ``We're preparing to start transferring
logistics in two days.''
</P>
<P>
   The station flight director, Paul Hill, said the six-hour
spacewalk will kick off six hectic days of cargo transfers and
maintenance and repair work on power and communication systems.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts will replace 18 batteries in an electrical system
inside the Russian control module. They will repair or replace a
radio system in the American node, which provides several ports for
space station systems to be added in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   When construction is finished, the $60 billion space station
will include 100 components and cover an area twice the size of a
football field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
