<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARM-PSYCHOLOGIST-ART     05-29 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-PSYCHOLOGIST-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PSYCHOLOGIST-FARMER HELPS HIS FELLOW FARMERS COPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Neb., Wash.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARLAN, Iowa _ After hauling oats to his cattle before sunrise
on the Iowa prairie, Michael Rosmann drives to an office and sits
down with farmer after farmer to listen to their troubles. A
fourth-generation farmer as well as a clinical psychologist, he
speaks the language of men and women on the verge of losing their
place on the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are good people who feel like terrible failures,'' said
Rosmann, who knows what it is to endure sleepless nights spent
worrying about crop prices and peril to family tradition.
``Somebody needs to tell them it's not their fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosmann, a big man in a leather vest and cowboy boots who lost
part of a foot in a farm accident, sees most of his patients at his
office, off the town square in this small western Iowa town. But he
will counsel wherever the need takes him, practicing psychotherapy
while standing in a cornfield or leaning against a tractor tire and
talking to a farmer in bib overalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week I took a guy fishing,'' Rosmann said. ``He's so down
he had stopped talking. So we sat. And we fished.''
</P>
<P>
   A quiet desperation shrouds the countryside in places like
Harlan, where plunging corn, bean and livestock prices are bringing
ruin to farms nurtured by families for generations. But if troubles
are in plentiful supply in much of rural America, psychological
help like Rosmann's most often is not.
</P>
<P>
   So, with the farm economy lurching toward the dreadful
conditions of the early 1980s, when suicidal gunshots rang out from
red barns, rural social and church groups are trying to extend
solace to men and women on the verge of breakdown, both financial
and emotional.
</P>
<P>
   Rosmann himself recently helped organize the Sharing Help
Awareness United Network, or SHAUN, named for Shaun Petersen, a
13-year-old Iowa boy killed in a farm accident in 1989. The
nonprofit group promises to find counseling for farm families that
need it, regardless of their ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
   In rural Adair County, east of here, a group of scholars, social
workers and clerics gathered the other day for an Ecumenical
Retreat on Family Farm Stress, where they mapped mental health
strategies to help people faced with financial ruin.
</P>
<P>
   In Nebraska, a series of workshops called Working With
Distressed Farm and Ranch Families, for clerics, families and
social workers, is set for July 6-9 in Lincoln, Kearney, Omaha and
South Sioux City.
</P>
<P>
   And in the rural communities of eastern Washington, social
workers have been counseling farmers' children and checking for
signs of strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a farmer, your work is your home, and there is no
escape from the suffering,'' said Fred Moskol, a researcher in
rural mental health at the University of Wisconsin Medical School.
``And the poor kids, they're watching it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The root of the suffering is a market that has sent the prices
of crops like corn and soybeans to 12-year lows. Livestock, too,
has been hit hard. At the end of last year, hogs were selling for
as little as $9 per hundredweight, barely a fourth of what a pork
farmer with little debt would need to break even; hog prices have
since rebounded to $35 or $40 per hundredweight, but that is only
half their mid-1990s highs. The U.S. Department of Agriculture
reports that average farm income dropped 33 percent from 1996 to
1998 and that an additional dip of 10 percent is expected for this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Without psychological help, says Larry Barber, a rawboned
57-year-old patient of Rosmann who recently lost a farm that had
been in the family for more than a century, he would have lost his
mind as well. For patients who can afford it, Rosmann charges $100
an hour. But he has charged some distressed farmers as little as
$20 for a two-hour session. And others he has not sent a bill at
all.
</P>
<P>
   A week before Barber was forced to sell his cattle, he sat and
cried, tears streaming down his face, making no sound, his body
shuddering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost all desire to do anything,'' Barber said, tears now
again in his eyes as he drew hard on a cigarette. ``This is like a
death, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Riding the agricultural economy's roller coaster, farmers like
Barber saw record prices for their crops just three years ago,
before the Asian economic crisis stifled demand for American
agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Drabenstott, a vice president of the Federal Reserve Bank
of Kansas City, said: ``It's a classic tale of supply and demand.
When prices hit records in 1996, farmers responded by bringing more
product to market. Just then their best customer, Asia, starts
going into terrible financial problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Drabenstott said that while the American farm economy was now
``clearly in the throes of a serious downturn,'' the severity was
not yet that of the 1980s, when interest rates, always a crucial
index to a way of life that runs on borrowed money, soared to
nearly 20 percent and land prices plunged, leaving many farmers
without sufficient collateral to back their loans. The value of
farm acreage has lately been holding steady, Drabenstott said, and
interest rates have been relatively low.
</P>
<P>
   A steep drop in income has nonetheless meant disaster to farmers
already working on slim margins.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the low commodities prices, Drabenstott said, American
agriculture is seeing ``substantial structural change,'' with more
farmers working under contract with big processing companies,
especially in the hog business. Since the processors find it most
efficient to deal with large farms, the smaller, family farms,
particularly those with big debt loads, have been the ones most
often squeezed out.
</P>
<P>
   While farmers like Barber and his wife, Linda, may understand
that it is forces beyond their control that are driving them out of
business, that knowledge does little to relieve a certain guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tell me, `It's not your fault,''' Barber said, ``but it
is a little like driving a car, then skidding on a bad patch of ice
and hitting a child. It wouldn't be your fault, but you'd live
every day with the doubts and thoughts of how could I have avoided
this terrible thing.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Farmers tend to be an independent breed, of course, and many are
reluctant to ask for psychological help.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a small town,'' said Moskol, the University of Wisconsin
researcher, ``you walk into the mental health center and everybody
sees you do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, Rosmann said, farmers understand the
benefits of psychotherapy and drugs in treating depression and
anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are smart people,'' he said. ``They're stubborn, but
they're also innovative. They've got to be. A good manager will try
anything that helps the operation. If that means going to a
psychologist, then fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The big problem, he said, is making the time out of a busy
schedule, especially if you are forced to drive 50 miles or more to
find a counselor.
</P>
<P>
   His caseload growing with the worsening of the farm economy,
Rosmann rented out his corn and bean acreage this year so that he
could devote more time to his patients. He says farmers appreciate
that he can talk about the ins and outs of agricultural work as
well as the emotional pressures. Other psychologists, he notes with
a smile, might be at a loss should the discussion turn to crop
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Rosmann, a native of Harlan who taught psychology at the
University of Virginia before returning here to farm, says the
suicide to which financial pressures sometimes drive farmers tends
to differ from suicide among city dwellers, or even among rural
people in other occupations.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he said, farmers who try suicide are far more
likely to achieve it. While suicide attempts among nonfarmers often
occur after a Friday or Saturday night drinking bout, farmers are
more likely to be sober and deliberative, taking their lives on a
Sunday morning when their wives are away at church.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then we have a lot of `accidents' on the farm,'' Rosmann
said, referring to those cases that could be suicide and presumably
are. ``They want to make sure the insurance will be paid to their
families.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber, who is now on antidepressants, said he would never have
taken his own life. But his wife believes he would have been driven
to the grave by stroke or heart attack had it not been for Rosmann.
</P>
<P>
   Barber still struggles terribly with the changes in his life,
swallowing hard when he is asked about his new job in a lumberyard.
His wife was once active in volunteer work, winning awards for her
efforts on behalf of shelters for battered women and in helping the
poor with their taxes. Now she is looking for a job, as a
receptionist or a secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also go to Rosmann,'' Mrs. Barber said. ``There are a lot of
things I need to work through.''
</P>
<P>
   When they farmed, Mrs. Barber liked to do the disking in the
fields. She would ride her tractor and talk to her husband on a
walkie-talkie as he rode a combine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waving to each other across the field,'' Mrs. Barber said, her
voice breaking, ``I miss that so much.''
</P>
<P>
   The old Barber farm is a pretty place, with bur oaks, ponds and
rolling prairies. The Barbers were able to hold on to their modest
house there, and these days they often sit at the kitchen table,
looking out at the countryside when they are not just staring into
their coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Simply getting from one day to the next has been such a
struggle, they said apologetically on one recent evening, that the
housekeeping has suffered a bit lately. A stack of newspapers,
magazines and files leaned against a computer in the kitchen, and
in the living room stood an artificial Christmas tree, still
wrapped in tinsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Christmas tree in May _ it doesn't belong,'' Barber said.
``That's how I am, I guess. Just out of place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
