<HEADER>
A5958 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ANTISMOKING-ART-11     05-29 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ANTISMOKING-ART-1120(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Calif., Conn., Fla., Mass., Minn., Miss., Mo., Ore.,
N.J., N.Y., Texas)  
 OTHER STATES' EFFORTS TO CUT SMOKING LEAVE NEW YORK FAR
BEHIND  ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York, until recently considered a leader in
combating smoking, is rapidly becoming a laggard, as other states
leapfrog past it in the size and aggressiveness of their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, New York was one of just four states that
financed advertising and education programs aimed at persuading the
public, particularly teen-agers, not to smoke. Now, eight states
have such programs, and 11 others, including New Jersey and
Connecticut, expect to begin theirs within the next year. With one
possible exception, all those states anticipate spending far more
than New York on the programs, when adjusted for the states'
populations.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, a Republican whose party has reaped major
campaign contributions from the tobacco industry, has proposed
spending $8.4 million on New York's anti-tobacco program over the
next year, up from $8.2 million in the last year. California, in
contrast, is spending $120.1 million in the current fiscal year,
Florida, $70.4 million, and Massachusetts, $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of other existing state programs ranges from Oregon,
which spends $2.59 per person in its current budget, to
Mississippi, which spends $11.26 per person. New York spends 45
cents per capita.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about like throwing a mosquito at an elephant,'' said
Michael Moore, Mississippi's attorney general, who led the
multistate six-year legal fight against tobacco companies. ``It has
no effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael McKeon, Pataki's press secretary, defended New York's
program. ``We could probably spend a zillion dollars, and there's
always going to be advocates who say we could do more,'' he said.
``But we think we have a good plan and a good program, and we're
always open to new ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Pataki, New York began anti-tobacco advertising on radio
and television three years ago. Those ads have been dismissed by
anti-smoking groups as all but useless, mostly because they do not
appeal to young people, and they are broadcast so infrequently that
many people have never seen or heard them.
</P>
<P>
   One shown last year featured then-Attorney General Dennis Vacco
speaking earnestly of the dangers of smoking. The most prominent
part of New York's current campaign is billboards with a collage of
celebrity faces and the line, ``We choose not to smoke,''
reminiscent of the ``Just Say No'' anti-drug campaign of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ads in other states often have a slap-in-the-face
tone, aiming to be shocking or darkly funny. One television ad
shown in Florida depicts a ceremony held in Hades, with Adolf
Hitler in the audience, to award tobacco the prize for most deaths
caused, ranking ahead of other contenders like murder and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   John Signor, a spokesman for the New York state Health
Department, which administers the anti-smoking program, noted that
some of the advertisements used by New York were produced by other
states or by the federal government. ``We have a very comprehensive
plan of advertising, education and enforcement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Timothy Nichols, director of governmental affairs for the
American Lung Association, said: ``New York pales in comparison to
these other states. What they call an anti-tobacco program, they
might as well not even spend the money.''
</P>
<P>
   While anti-smoking groups in New York direct most of their
criticism at the governor, the leaders of the Legislature, in both
parties, have put little pressure on him to strengthen New York's
program.
</P>
<P>
   The rush by states to start anti-tobacco programs has been
propelled in part by research showing that aggressive advertising
can be highly effective in reducing smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Several studies have reported that in the 1990s, smoking has
declined more than twice as fast in California, which has the
oldest such program, as nationwide. A report this year showed that
just one year into Florida's effort, middle-school students there
were 19 percent less likely to smoke, and smoking by high school
students had dropped 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention called
the results one of the largest documented one-year changes in
smoking rates anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, as in the rest of the country, adult smoking has
declined in the 1990s. A 1996 study found the rate at 23 percent of
adults in New York, while in California it had dropped to 18
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of having billions of dollars to spend from
settlements with tobacco companies has also motivated states to
embark on new anti-tobacco campaigns, a trend that has taken on
particular intensity this spring, as states draft their budgets for
the next fiscal year. Some states have also been swayed by the
argument that the programs will save money, because the decline in
smoking could cut health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Gov. Christie Whitman has proposed $18.6 million
for anti-tobacco advertising, education and law enforcement in the
fiscal year that starts July 1, and legislative leaders have agreed
in principle. In Connecticut, Gov. John Rowland has proposed just
$200,000, which would make it the only state spending less per
capita than New York. But leaders of the Legislature are pressing
in budget talks for a much higher figure.
</P>
<P>
   In creating comprehensive anti-smoking programs, it was the
public that led the way. Voter-approved initiatives in California,
Massachusetts and Arizona created the first three programs, in each
case paid for with higher taxes on tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine states with such an effort, the bulk of the money
goes toward advertising, and to educational programs carried out by
schools or by private organizations that win state grants. Some
states also put some of the money toward better enforcement of laws
prohibiting the sale of tobacco products to minors.
</P>
<P>
   There have long been anti-smoking public service advertisements,
promoted by private groups and government agencies. Since 1991, the
National Cancer Institute has financed anti-smoking advertising and
education programs in 17 states, though they were small in scope.
</P>
<P>
   Large-scale advertising paid for by the states began with
California, in 1990. Those first ads featured striking images, like
a skeleton posing coyly with a cigarette clutched between finger
bones, or a room full of tobacco executives, choking on their own
smoke, scheming how to ensnare young people. Massachusetts followed
in 1993, and Arizona in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   New York's ads, which began in 1996, are far too tame, critics
contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to work,'' Moore, of Mississippi, said of ads
like New York's. ``Kids aren't going to listen to someone like me
talk about smoking. What kids want to see is other kids talking to
them. You have to make it cool. Our ads look like MTV.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry contributed almost $400,000 to state
political races in New York in the 1997-98 election cycle,
three-quarters of it to Republican Party committees and Republican
candidates, according to a report by the New York Public Interest
Group. In that cycle, for the first time, the two most important
Democratic committees, the state Democratic Committee and the
Democratic Assembly Campaign Committee, did not accept tobacco
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the political money of the tobacco
companies has been a major factor in stalling action in New York,''
said Blair Horner, legislative director of the New York Public
Interest Group, which promotes anti-tobacco legislation. ``New
York, once the nation's leader in taking on the tobacco menace, has
done virtually nothing in the past several years.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Pataki has not been pushed by the Legislature to
expand the state's anti-tobacco advertising. This year, the
Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, a Democrat, has said that some of
the tobacco settlement should be used for anti-tobacco programs.
But he has not specified a figure, and it is not an idea he has
actively promoted. A group of Assembly Democrats last month called
for New York to spend more than $80 million, but Silver has not
responded to their plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s and early 1990s, New York took the lead in
regulating tobacco use and sales, measures pushed primarily by
former Gov. Mario Cuomo. The state banned smoking in the workplace,
and then on school grounds and buses.
</P>
<P>
   It instituted civil penalties, including the possible loss of a
liquor license, for any business selling tobacco to someone under
18. It banned cigarette vending machines, a favorite way for minors
to buy cigarettes, except in places like bars and liquor stores,
where minors were not allowed. And it raised the cigarette tax from
39 cents a pack to 56 cents, one of the higher rates in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But no significant anti-tobacco legislation has been enacted
since Pataki became governor in 1995. And since then, many other
states and local governments have caught up to New York's
anti-tobacco laws.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, to settle a group of lawsuits, the tobacco industry
agreed to pay 46 states, the District of Columbia and U.S.
territories $206 billion over 25 years, to reimburse states'
tobacco-related health-care costs. The other four states _
Mississippi, Florida, Minnesota and Texas _ reached independent
settlements totaling more than $37 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the distribution of the $206 billion settlement has been
held up by legal wrangles in California and New York, including the
dispute between Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and the Pataki
administration over how much of the state's share New York City
should receive.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, payments cannot be made to the states
until states accounting for 80 percent of the money have resolved
all their internal legal disputes, or until June 30 of next year,
whichever comes first. California and New York each account for
almost 13 percent of the money, so if they remain tangled in court,
none of the 46 states will be paid for another 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   If either California or New York resolved its disputes, the
money would begin to flow immediately. New Jersey and Missouri also
have pending lawsuits, but they do not account for enough of the
money to affect whether the 80 percent mark is reached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
