<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Sunday, May 30, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEEKEND DUTY EDITORS ARE:
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA: Tom Oder at (office) 404 526-5456 or (pager)
800-495-2461 or pagetom(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Elliot Jaspin on his mobile phone 703 725-7031.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TIANANMEN-REMEMBER _ Michael Browning, a staff writer for The
Palm Beach Post, lived in Beijing for nine years as a correspondent
for The Miami Herald and Knight-Ridder Newspapers. He covered all
the events leading up to and coming out of the massacre at
Tiananmen Square on June 4, 1989. Now, at a decade's distance, he
says he has trouble believing it ever happened, more trouble making
up his mind about what it actually meant. In his own words: ``I was
there, but today in an era when Chinese students are throwing rocks
and bottles at our embassy in Beijing and Chinese spies are
apparently ferreting out our nuclear secrets, I am not really sure
where there was. Tiananmen seemed mythical, even during the moments
it was unfolding. It was like living inside a movie whose
screenplay was being written off-camera, someplace else. The actual
shooting script came to us minute by minute.'' A first-person
remembrance of the massacre. (Browning, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With photos: A mug of Browning and a photo of artifacts
from the siege.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-COFFEE _ TAKIUKUM, Mexico _ In an obscure village in
southern Mexico, Manuel Gomez proudly shows guests horse manure
spread beneath a tangle of vines on his modest coffee farm. Manure,
ironically, is offering a healthier and more prosperous life to
this Mayan Indian farmer, who uses it to fertilize organic coffee
he grows for consumers tens of thousands of miles from his home. In
Takiukum (pronounced, ``Ta-kee-a-KOOM'') and other isolated hamlets
nestled in the hills of politically-troubled Chiapas state, more
and more subsistence farmers are growing organic coffee for export,
which provides them with about 80 percent of their cash income. The
farmers' organic coffee is ending up as brew or beans found in
American and European cafes, health food stores, grocery chains and
specialty shops from Germany to Atlanta, Ga., from Italy to Austin,
Texas. (Ferris, Cox News Service). 30. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COFFEE-BOX _ Data on coffee consumption/production. (Ferris, Cox
News Service). 10. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO-CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA _ TIRANA, Albania _ Albania, The United States'
new best friend, apparently has horrendous human rights practices
including locking up death-row inmates in iron masks and suspending
them from the wall during the day. This falls under the category of
our strange new bedfellow of convenience. Developing. (Roughton,
Cox News Service). 30. WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ALBANIA-BOX _ A primer on Albania. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
10. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CIVILIANS _ WASHINGTON _ Putting civilian casualties due
to the U.S.-led NATO bombing campaign against Yugoslavia in
perspective. How many civilian death are acceptable? We take a look
at the numbers, military focus and effect of politics and press
attention. Also, what effect the advances in technology, geographic
theater, racial bias and even policy have had. Developing. (Deans,
Cox News Service). 35.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved in (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CIVILIANS-BOX _ WASHINGTON _ Numbers of civilian deaths in other
U.S. conflicts. (Deans, Cox News Service). 6.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved in (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO _ VENICE, Italy _ As the U.S.-led NATO bombing
campaign against Yugoslavia continues to escalate, the alliance
that President Clinton has tried to present as unified from the
outset continues to appear more and more frayed. The combination of
shuttle diplomacy on the part of the Russians and ongoing civilian
casualties has put more pressure on the alliance in countries like
Italy, which was never completely together on the air campaign to
begin with. Many NATO are flat out asking themselves, ``Why are we
still bombing Yugoslavia?'' Developing. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
30. WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   LOCK-BOX _ WASHINGTON _ As lawmakers left the Capitol for a long
Memorial Day holiday, Republicans boasted they had protected Social
Security from government ``raids.'' Democrats grumbled nothing has
been done _ or is likely to be done _ to reform the system.
(Lipman, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   Moved Friday.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE-WARS _ WASHINGTON _ The rhetoric and budgetary salvos
have quieted since President Clinton appointed two Southerners,
Bill Ivey and Bill Ferris, to head the National Endowment for the
Arts and the National Endowment for the Humanities. In interviews,
the two talk about how they changed their agencies' cultural focus.
(Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moved Thursday in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment
categories.
</P>
<P>
   LOBBYISTS _ WASHINGTON _ Some members of Congress never go back
home after they leave office. It's just too tempting to stay on
Capitol Hill and get rich. Former members are everywhere in D.C.,
often lobbying for the industries they worked with while in
office.Texans on that list include Marvin Leath, Jim Chapman and
Charlie Wilson. We'll find out what they're up to. (Moscoso, Cox
News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   LOBBYISTS-LIST _The former members and their biggest clients.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Friday.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ The federal antitrust suit against
Microsoft Corp. enters a critical phase this week with the
presentation of expert ``rebuttal'' witnesses. (Glass, Cox News
Service). 25
</P>
<P>
   Moved Friday in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-SOUTH _ WASHINGTON - The front-runners in the 2000
presidential campaign developing themes and issues of importance to
the South. But just how much do Vice President Al Gore and Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, both of whose Southern roots have been
questioned, relate to the region? (Shepard, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   Moved Friday in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-BUYBACK _ On Saturday, in response to recent school
shootings, the SCLC resumes its gun buyback program, paying $50 for
all guns turned in. Parents of Isaiah Shoels, killed at Columbine,
will be on hand.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EXPECTATIONS _ As he emerges from the cocoon and morphs
into full- fledged presidential candidate, Gov. George W. Bush is
about to run head-first into a formidable foe who hasn't raised a
dime, doesn't have a bumper sticker and has been even less specific
on issues than Bush. ``Expectations,'' says Bush adviser Karl Rove,
without missing a beat when he's asked to name his guy's most
challenging opponent. Bush, proclaimed the frontrunner by poll and
press, is about to try to meet those expectations, an effort that
has derailed more than one high-flying politician. As he hits the
road, don't look for Bush to offer much in the way of specifics on
issues. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   KASICH _ DERRY, N.H. _ John Kasich will not simply read a
speech. Or he can't. Or both. ``When I read,'' he said, ``it just
doesn't come from the heart.'' If you're looking for a single word
to explain why this modestly well-known congressman from Columbus,
Ohio, is campaigning for the Republican nomination for president,
this is it. Heart. (Montgomery, Cox News Service). 70. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Moved Monday in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   BARR-WITCHES _ Bob Barr faces toil and trouble as witches,
wounded by his slings and arrows, stir up his town meeting
Saturday. (Visser, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-PREVIEW _ Preview of the 1999 hurricane season that
begins June 1, focusing on worries in the main target of recent
years_the Florida Panhandle. (MWilliams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WHITEWATER-REOPENS _ White water opens for the season this
weekend. What has changed there, how is the public's confidence in
white water, how are ticket sales going, etc. Walt Weiss is being
used as a way to get us into the story. (Farber, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WHITEWATER-WEISS _ Walt Weiss, most visible relative of a
Whitewater victim and unofficial leader of the parents, talks about
life a year after the e coli scare. (Farber, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EXTREME-TV _ Television is both more violent and less violent
than it used to be. Top-rated prime-time shows have very little
violence, yet Extreme TV grows around the fringes: pro wrestling,
Fox's violence-verite, Jerry Springer (they promised to tone down
the violence before, and didn't) and even local TV news and network
newsmgazines. What's causing Extreme TV? The audience
fragmentation, the hard-to-capture but lucrative market of young
men and teenaged boys, and overall social trends. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   RIVALS-MAIN _ The battle between the two major pro wrestling
groups, WWF and WCW, may not have killed Owen Hart, as his family
claims, but it has helped shape the ``sport'' in the '90s, its most
prosperous era. WWF is on top for now, but both it and Ted
Turner-owned WCW are doing very, very well. (Thomas/Scott, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30-35.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
