<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5974 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANES-FORECAST-C     05-29 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANES-FORECAST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurricane forecast has true believers on Atlantic, Gulf coasts
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENSACOLA, Fla. _ Baker Clark doesn't need any weather expert to
remind him that hurricane season begins Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He keeps a photo album under the reception counter at the Five
Flags Inn filled with scenes of terrible destruction from 1995's
Hurricane Opal, which devastated his 49-room motel and 100 miles of
Panhandle beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family has owned this motel since 1965 and we've seen
hurricanes before,'' he said, paging through the photos of
sand-filled rooms and twisted debris. ``But it seems like we've had
more than our share lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts confirm his observation, saying the crowded Atlantic and
Gulf coastlines could be in for a cycle of punishing storm activity
that could last years _ even decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been saying ... we may be heading back to a period
like the '40s and '50s when we really had heavy hurricane seasons
with a lot of major hurricanes,'' says National Hurricane Center
Director Jerry Jarrell. ``I think it's no longer speculation. I
think we are in it now.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers bear him out: 1995 to 1998 was the most active
four-year stretch on record, spawning 53 named storms in the
Atlantic basin, with 33 hurricanes and 15 of those reaching major
status. Storms are named when winds reach 39 mph, become hurricanes
at 74 mph and are deemed major at 111 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the long-term predictions are based on research by
William Gray, a Colorado State University forecaster who tracks
tropical systems and the forces that create them.
</P>
<P>
   Gray's 1999 forecast, which will be updated this week, calls for
14 named Atlantic storms this year, with 10 reaching hurricane
strength and four growing into major storms.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most worrisome: Because of a complex mix of factors,
Gray thinks the Gulf Coast has a 150 percent greater chance of
being hit by a major storm than in a statistically average year,
while the Atlantic Coast has double the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful storms like Opal and last year's Mitch and Georges have
always done the most damage. But unlike the last period of high
hurricane activity, from roughly 1940 to 1960, the population of
the nation's eastern coastline has swelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's such a buildup of population and property values along
the Southeastern coast,'' Gray told The Associated Press. ``You're
going to see hurricane damage like you've never previously seen it
because there's just so much more there.''
</P>
<P>
   Panhandle residents know about the damage firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   Hit by powerful Hurricane Frederic in 1979, the region escaped
major hurricane damage the next 15 years, which also was a time of
unprecedented growth. High-rise condos, golf resorts, marinas and
new neighborhoods sprouted from Gulf Shores, Ala., to Panama City
Beach, Fla. Even the long-neglected Mississippi coast boomed in the
1990s with the advent of casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane drought ended in 1995, when Erin slashed across
the region, leaving significant damage. Four months later Opal
roared ashore with winds approaching 150 mph, leveling homes,
tearing up docks, snapping power lines and eating away dunes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, first Earl and then Georges came calling, once again
filling streets with sand, blowing out windows and undermining
foundations. Georges also pummeled several Caribbean islands and
the Florida Keys.
</P>
<P>
   The repeated storms scoured away sand dunes along much of the
Gulf Coast, leaving buildings exposed to sea water. Governments
scrambled to rebuild the dunes, pumping sand from offshore, setting
up sand fences and planting sea oats to hold the dunes in place.
</P>
<P>
   But the work can't compare to the slow, natural process of dune
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sand dunes used to be so high you couldn't even see the
water from here,'' Clark said, pointing out his office window to a
pool deck that drops directly to a flat beach. ``They renourished
our beach after Opal, but last year Georges took all that sand
offshore. Now there's nothing out there to protect us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray thinks the weather patterns that control hurricanes have
shifted, part of a long-term cycle that sees hurricane activity wax
and wane. As part of his prediction theory, he tracks everything
from ocean temperatures to large-scale current movement and
rainfall in Africa, where many tropical systems are born.
</P>
<P>
   The La Nina weather phenomenon _ a cooling of ocean waters off
South America that began last year _ could also contribute to an
upswing in this season's activity.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, La Nina's ``brother,'' El Nino, may have inhibited
storm formation for a while. But it broke down in the fall, and two
powerful late-season storms, Georges and Mitch, roared ashore.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch did unparalleled damage in Central America, where torrents
of rain triggered massive flooding in the mountains of Honduras and
Nicaragua. At least 10,000 died, 2 million were left homeless, and
much of Honduras' infrastructure was wiped out, along with its
banana crop.
</P>
<P>
   Despite getting hit by four storms in four years and the
disturbing predictions, the explosion of coastal building along the
Gulf Coast continues.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Dagenais, (cq) and her family who moved to Navarre from
Chicago five years ago, is now a hurricane veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Opal sent waves washing over low-lying Navarre Beach, destroying
dozens of homes and leading to a painstaking yearlong cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   But the area has bounced right back, with new high-rise condos
going up with high-priced homes. Gulf-front lot prices have
skyrocketed, with 100-foot parcels fetching $400,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't scared anybody off,'' said Dagenais, who lives on
the mainland but has learned to take evacuation notices seriously.
``People just love the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
