<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5977 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-2TAKE     05-29 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONALITY AND POLICY IN THE U.S. BALKANS CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Utah, Neb.)  (mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The civilian at the top of the American military,
Secretary of Defense William Cohen, rarely speaks directly to the
commander running the war in the Balkans. Aides to the commander,
Gen. Wesley Clark, derisively call the secretary ``Senator Cohen,''
since he spends more time advising and cajoling his former
colleagues in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier at the top, Gen. Henry Shelton, is the general who
speaks when spoken to. He is said to be unwilling _ or unable _ to
air the Pentagon's misgivings about the war, though during a recent
White House meeting he bluntly ended a discussion about sending
ground troops into a ``semi-permissive'' situation in Kosovo
without a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being a little bit pregnant, sir,'' Shelton, the
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, told President Clinton,
according to an official familiar with the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Cohen and Shelton are Clinton's top military advisers
as the Balkans war grows into its third month, but in a sense they
are not its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their predecessors from the Persian Gulf War, Dick Cheney
and Gen. Colin Powell, who drew up war plans and gave Gen. Norman
Schwarzkopf, the commander in the field, more troops and weapons
than he wanted, they have an entirely different relationship with
their field commander.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton serves as commander in chief, responsible
through Cohen and Shelton for American forces, the war is not being
run from war rooms at the White House or at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clark, an American, is charged with running it from
Belgium. But he must answer not only to his own political leaders
but also to the leaders of an often unwieldy NATO alliance of 18
other nations that demands consensus even if the United States is
its dominant power.
</P>
<P>
   That has turned Cohen and Shelton more into managers than war
strategists or policy-makers, trying to balance the various
domestic and international demands while helping retain support for
the effort. How they have played their parts has shaped some of the
day-to-day conduct of the war. The nature of the campaign has
shaped their roles as well.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, perhaps, tensions have emerged. Clark's aides say
that the Pentagon's penchant for bureaucratic checks and balances
simply clashes with his war-fighter's urgency to press the fight.
But for Cohen and Shelton, the immediate concern is less to wage
war than to maintain the fragile consensus behind it both at home
and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen says his role is to rally support not only within NATO but
also within the Pentagon and, he adds, on Capitol Hill, where he
was a Republican lawmaker for 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never purport to be a military strategist, where I was
going to start drawing military plans,'' Cohen said in an interview
in his office. ``What I've done, as part of what I see as my job,
is to hold a group of teams together.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the war itself, Cohen and Shelton have
supported some of Clark's requests, aides say, whether for weapons
or for more ambitious tactics. But they have also acted as a brake
on Clark's most aggressive proposals _ from his eagerness to use
Apache helicopters to his desire to base rockets in Croatia to fire
into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, they review Clark's bombing targets and, despite the
intensification of the air war, still reject some as too risky.
``You always want to make sure that you have civilian oversight of
an operation like this,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   For Cohen, who has served as secretary since January 1997, and
Shelton, who took over as chairman nine months later, NATO's air
war will be a lasting mark on their terms, which have already seen
the running military confrontations with Iraq, including last
December's four-day miniwar, and the cruise missile strikes against
the Sudan and Afghanistan last August.
</P>
<P>
   How their stewardships are judged, though, will largely depend
on the outcome of a war they have overseen but, by Cohen's own
account, would have fought differently ``if this were simply a U.S.
operation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been wider and more intense from my
perspective,'' Cohen told a group of reporters on Friday. ``Any
time you're dealing with an alliance you have to take into account
the need to hold that alliance together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to the United States acting unilaterally,'' he added,
``this was certainly the best option and the only option.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen has always seen himself as a consensus builder _ from his
days as mayor of Bangor, Maine, to his tenure as the only
Republican in Clinton's Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, at 58, is erudite, dapper and detached, leading a
department inclined to brawn and backslapping. He did not serve in
the military, in the years leading up to the Vietnam War, because
of student and marriage deferments.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, though, he developed an expertise in military
issues, driven in part by the importance of defense contracts to
Maine's economy, from the B-52s at Loring Air Force Base to the
warships built at Bath Iron Works. He also dabbled with literary
aspirations, publishing several books, including two volumes of
poetry.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Baker's Nickel'' (1986, William Morrow &AMP; Co.), Cohen
wrote a poem about flying in the backseat of an F-15.
</P>
<P>
   We were quicksilver
</P>
<P>
   sliding on the blue
</P>
<P>
   water of thought,
</P>
<P>
   unmindful, almost, that
</P>
<P>
   on the gleaming wings
</P>
<P>
   of the death machine
</P>
<P>
   hung the terrible paradox
</P>
<P>
   of peace.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been his long experience in Congress that has helped
the administration immensely in fending off the worst of the
Republican attacks on the war and on other issues, both
administration officials and lawmakers say. Cohen constantly briefs
his former colleagues in the House and Senate on the war's
progress, both in formal committee hearings and in private
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, rose on the Senate
floor and, revealing the deep ambivalence many conservatives feel
toward the war, called for the bombing to stop. The next morning
Cohen invited Bennett and half a dozen other senators to his office
in the Pentagon for breakfast with him and Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Bennett sounded tempered, if not completely won over.
``I was more tempted to believe the optimistic reports'' on the
war's progress ``when it was Cohen and Shelton describing them to
us, with no keepers from the White House to monitor what they were
saying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican senator, Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, said Cohen
had been effective at explaining and defending the administration's
policy because ``he knows all the back alleys over here.'' With the
air war now into its third month, however, he said he was far from
convinced that Cohen and Shelton were overseeing a sound strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Cohen has bought this president some additional time,
just because of who he is,'' Hagel said, ``but I think that time is
running out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's lobbying in Congress has limits, though, as was clear
when the House, in a split vote last month, refused to support the
administration's war effort. Cohen noted that the House only
narrowly endorsed the Gulf War before it began and claimed that it
was more important that the House has since supported an increase
in military financing intended partly to pay for the Balkan
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Cohen, Shelton appears far less comfortable with
his public role of articulating _ and defending _ the war effort.
As chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, he serves as the senior
uniformed adviser to the president and secretary of defense. But
compared with his predecessors, Gen. John Shalikashvili and before
that Powell, he has had a profile so low he is almost absent from
the public debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not uncomfortable being silent,'' one aide said.
</P>
<P>
   He is widely respected as a soldier, a former commando and
paratrooper who led two of the Army's most coveted combat commands:
the 82nd Airborne Division at Fort Bragg, N.C., and the entire 18th
Airborne Corps. In the Persian Gulf War he led a helicopter assault
deep into Iraq. As commander of the 18th, he oversaw the American
intervention in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton declined to be interviewed about his role, but officials
have described him as deeply ambivalent about the use of military
force in the Balkans, reflecting misgivings that many uniformed
officers have about the strategy and what they see as a lack of a
clear exit strategy.
</P>
<P>
   However, he does not consider it his role to advocate strongly
for one position or another, but rather to provide precise, clear
military advice, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In briefings on Capitol Hill, Shelton sticks to the operational
details, which has led to frustration and criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us would like to hear more from Shelton, to have him
step forward more and give the real soldier's view,'' Hagel said.
``A lot of us here would just like to hear him talk for five
minutes about what the concept is.''
</P>
<P>
   As chairman, Shelton is the military conduit between Washington
and the commanders fighting the war.
</P>
<P>
   While Clark is the supreme allied commander, he also serves as
commander of American forces in the region, a dual role that often
proves awkward since he must also answer to the NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, as one of the nation's nine commanders in chief,
Clark reports directly to Cohen, but in practice he has dealt day
to day with Shelton, particularly on military matters and
operational updates. Cohen said he prefers it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Shelton meet virtually every morning at 7:30 in the
secretary's office, along with their deputies, John Hamre, the
deputy secretary of defense, and Gen. Joseph Ralston, the vice
chairman of the Joint Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Twice a week, Cohen receives a briefing from Clark through a
video camera in a highly secured conference room deep inside in the
Pentagon's national military command center. Several weeks into the
campaign, he began inviting the chiefs of the Army, Navy, Air Force
and Marines, even though they have no direct war-fighting role. It
is another of his efforts to forge consensus, this time within the
Pentagon, where senior officers were becoming increasingly critical
of Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Although both are Army four-stars, Clark and Shelton could
hardly be more different in style and temperament.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 54, is a former Rhodes scholar who, as he rose through
the ranks, became savvy in the bureaucratic battles of Washington.
He served as Richard Holbrooke's top military aide in the 1995
Dayton negotiations over Bosnia, and as an officer on the Joint
Staff he developed a close relationship with Sandy Berger, then the
president's deputy national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides say that Clark and Berger, now the senior
adviser, talk regularly, but that this is not a back channel, as
some at the Pentagon suspect. When Clinton met with his senior
advisers at the White House last week on the same day Clark was in
town for consultations, Clark did not attend, but Shelton did,
honoring Cohen's insistence on communicating through the chain of
command.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions that have emerged between the Pentagon and Clark's
staff often reflect institutional differences over approach and
strategy, but they also involve the personalities and egos of the
men involved.
</P>
<P>
   On matters of strategy, Clark feels the Pentagon has not been as
responsive as it could be, second-guessing and nitpicking his
requests.
</P>
<P>
   Top aides to Shelton say that NATO's planning staff in Mons,
Belgium, is inexperienced in the art of war-planning, and should
appreciate Pentagon aid. ``The SACEUR's staff is not a war-fighting
staff,'' a Shelton aide said, using the military acronym for the
staff of the supreme allied commander in Europe. ``It's never
fought or planned a war.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton must also balance Clark's requests for forces with the
demands from other American field commanders around the world.
``We're stretched,'' Hamre said. ``We can't have any marginal
requests for forces.''
</P>
<P>
   In other respects, though, Cohen has strongly supported Clark,
cajoling his counterparts in the NATO allies to approve more
bombing targets and resisting calls for pauses in the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   For Cohen, this is a turnaround. As a senator, he opposed
sending American troops to Bosnia, but as secretary of defense he
was ``an early and strong advocate'' for bombing Yugoslavia,
according to Berger. Cohen said his view changed last fall when he
saw that the Yugoslav campaign was forcing hundreds of thousands of
ethnic Albanian rebels to flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the air war drags on, Cohen said that it was essential
to preserve unity _ both in NATO and among American commanders _
even if that sometimes required strategic compromises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more important,'' he said, ``to have a consensus to take
some action than to have a disagreement and take no action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
