<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5982 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORBES-CAMPAIGN-2TAKE     05-29 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FITTING FORBES FOR OVAL OFFICE FALLS TO ADMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis.)  (See also FORBES-AD) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ William Eisner, who heads an advertising agency in
Milwaukee, is best known for his commercials about Mrs. Paul's fish
sticks, including one that features a sloppy little boy lassoing
his head with spaghetti. ``Not impressed with pasta anymore?'' the
announcer asks. ``Break the monotony with fish sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Eisner is turning his handiwork to another product that he
says needs sprucing up: Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Forbes campaign for the Republican presidential
nomination is opening an unusually early and heavy
multimillion-dollar advertising offensive nationwide, with an
emphasis in primary battleground states, that is intended to
repackage Forbes just as Eisner repackaged fish sticks. The
message: Forbes, far from the monotonous advocate of a flat tax who
ran in 1996, has the breadth and the personality to sit in the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to resuscitate brands all the time that lost
their luster with consumers,'' said Eisner, who is known for his
quirky, offbeat work. ``We're doing the same with Steve.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the campaign, Eisner said, is a drive to
overcome voters' twin misgivings about Forbes, a wealthy publisher:
They cannot imagine him as president, because he has never been
elected to anything, and they think he is a rich man running on a
lark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first, most important, fact is having people see Steve in
the position of president, which they have trouble seeing right
now,'' Eisner said. ``A lot of people who don't understand Steve
would probably say, `He's got money so he can afford to do this to
satisfy his ego.' So it's something we have to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, some commercials were shot in black and white and
with Forbes against backdrops that resemble the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a study of presidential archival photography,'' Eisner
said. ``The way people are used to seeing a president is in that
context _ black and white. We also put him in environments that
look presidential, offices that resemble the Oval Office. The
gathered drapes and plastered ceilings, all the architecture is
very similar to the presidential office so they could envision him
in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertising campaign, which includes 30- and 60-second
commercials on matters from Social Security to taxes to values,
underscores why no one should underestimate Forbes' quest for the
White House. By dipping into his vast fortune, Forbes can guarantee
that he will be a potent force in the Republican campaign until the
very end.
</P>
<P>
   His decision to forgo federal subsidies so he can disregard the
spending limit of $33.5 million in the primaries may be driving
what appears to be an increasingly likely decision by the early
favorite for the Republican nomination, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, to also forgo the limits.
</P>
<P>
   If other Republican candidates deplete their resources, it is
not unthinkable that the race could end up as a competition between
Forbes and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' advisers said they were primed to spend up to $50
million in the primaries. Once the advertising begins on Wednesday,
the advisers said, assorted commercials will run almost
continuously until voting in the primaries and caucuses begins
early next year. They said the campaign could put $10 million into
commercials this summer.
</P>
<P>
   William Dal Col, Forbes' campaign manager, would not confirm
those figures but said, ``Whatever resources Bush has for the
campaign, I can assure you we will be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of Forbes' aggressive, early efforts to stake out
stands, there is one overriding reason he is a player in the
presidential race: money, buckets of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be one of the last guys at the table, because he can
always write a check,'' said Alex Castellanos, a Republican media
consultant here, ``even if the American people are never going to
accept him as a serious candidate for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Jacobson, a political science professor at the University
of California at San Diego, was blunter: ``He has no political
base. He has no claim to any kind of political experience. If he
didn't have any money, he'd be considered a crackpot.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week at his headquarters across the Potomac
River in Virginia, Forbes, 51, scoffed at such comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could ask that about anyone in terms of circumstances of
birth, circumstances of life,'' he said. ``You don't often control
those things. But the key is, what foundations are you willing to
build on? What are you trying to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Saying his message would overcome concerns that he was not
presidential, Forbes added, ``Ronald Reagan, one of my heroes, he
didn't seem the stuff of a formidable, forceful president before he
got elected governor of California.''
</P>
<P>
   Practically an overnight sensation, Forbes surged in the polls
soon after he burst onto the political scene in the 1996 campaign
for the Republican presidential nomination. He lavished more than
$35 million on that race. But his appeal faded as his opponents
depicted him as a Johnny-one-note on the flat tax who was out to
savage other candidates in his commercials.
</P>
<P>
   He scored victories in the Delaware and Arizona contests, but
ranked fourth in the all-important Iowa caucuses and the New
Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   While money did not buy Forbes the nomination then, he insists
that in 2000 his prospects are far brighter because he has devoted
the subsequent years to following a methodical plan to reposition
himself. He has crisscrossed the country building political support
and offering generous fees to attract some of the best political
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who once wrote that Pat Robertson, the founder of the
Christian Coalition, was a ``toothy flake,'' has managed to win
many converts among social conservatives. These days, Forbes says,
prohibiting abortion is more important than overhauling the tax
code.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than dwell on the flat tax, Forbes formed an advocacy
organization, Americans for Hope, Growth and Opportunity, which has
spent more than $2 million on advertisements to help him become a
voice on moral issues like abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the advertising campaigns his group sponsored on
issues like taxes in Iowa and Virginia, Forbes said, ``Even though
I may not have held a political office, I've had as much or more
impact shaping the political landscape and making real things
happen on the federal level than many of those who hold formal
office.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his campaign, Forbes has set out positions on an assortment
of issues. Recently he announced an ambitious plan for the
privatization of Social Security. Last month, he put forth a
proposal to promote patient choice in health care. With the help of
voice coaches, Forbes has also loosened up a bit on the stump. And
his new close-cropped haircut and wider-framed glasses make him
look less like a stiff club chair and more like a cozy recliner.
</P>
<P>
   Because of all those efforts, Forbes probably made more progress
than any other candidate in 1997 and 1998. Even so, the preparation
has yet to yield perceptible results: He is mired in single digits
in most early popularity polls. And despite his high-profile
courting of religious conservatives, he is losing endorsements to
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes insisted that his early preparation would pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of a campaign based on message, in terms of
principles, we're light-years ahead of the others,'' he said. ``And
the longer they wait, the more the window of opportunity they give
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, other Republicans are eyeing Forbes closely.
Anticipating that Forbes will go negative again in his
advertisements, they are making public calls for clean campaigns.
Even the party's national chairman, Jim Nicholson, who clearly had
Forbes in mind, issued an early plea that candidates not speak ill
of one another.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers said they were bracing for Forbes to go after
the governor as he did in 1996 with Bob Dole, who emerged as a
battered nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed my favorable rating in Iowa from about 80 to 60 in
five weeks,'' Dole said in an interview. ``He'll say it's nothing
personal. But if you're running at what, 6 percent in the polls,
and if you've got somebody at 53 percent, where Bush is, who knows
what will happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Forbes' advertisements in 1996, Bush said: ``I can
only go from what Senator Dole told me: They were really negative
as far as he was concerned. I think it's important to run positive
campaigns.'' Yet in the next breath, he suggested that he would not
sit still if attacked, saying, ``I'm vowing to defend myself.''
</P>
<P>
   While his first round of commercials does not mention other
candidates, Forbes would not say whether he would be more cautious
in the tone of his commercials than in 1996, saying, ``We're going
to have some forceful ads.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner said, ``It is too early to get in a fist fight'' with
Bush. But, he said, in the future there will probably be
commercials that the press would label negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negative ads work,'' he said. ``That's why people do them. You
can spike your numbers pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Forbes, Eisner said, ``Until they learn to like him
and accept him'' as a president, ``it doesn't matter what he says
on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthering the expectation that Forbes will not shy away from
lambasting his rivals, his pollster, John McLaughlin, said he had
recently conducted focus groups of prospective voters and found
that Forbes had no lingering scars on his image from his attacks in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these focus groups, there were no negative perceptions from
the last campaign,'' McLaughlin said. ``There were positive
perceptions about where Steve stood, positive perceptions on the
flat tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Several candidates hope that the Forbes commercials will cripple
Bush and provide them with an opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, a negative barrage of attack ads will only reflect
poorly on the candidate that chooses to issue those attacks,'' said
Howard Opinsky, a spokesman for the campaign of Sen. John McCain of
Arizona. ``But with this many candidates in the race, it is unclear
how it could enhance your chances or diminish someone else's.''
</P>
