<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: COUNTING ON `OUTSIDER' APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ariz., Iowa, N.H.)  (With FORBES-CAMPAIGN) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign is planning to begin broadcasting a series
of 30- and 60-second commercials nationwide on Wednesday, with the
heaviest barrage in California, Arizona, Iowa and New Hampshire _
all important states in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   This commercial, titled ``Dream,'' is 60 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: William Eisner
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: Opens on black-and-white film with Steve Forbes
talking directly to the camera. He is in a high-ceiling room with
gathered curtains, made to resemble the Oval Office. The frame
freezes and these words flash on the screen: ``Steve Forbes for
America.'' Forbes continues talking until the end, when these words
appear, ``Steve Forbes for President.''
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION SCRIPT: Forbes: ``You know the American people, God
bless them, spend most of their time concerned about their
families, their communities, their work. They don't always pay a
lot of attention to politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at a time like this, America's direction is being decided
each and every day. It's going to take an outsider, who's not part
of the political process, who's not caught up in the day-to-day
give-and-take of compromise with special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take someone with executive experience, who
knows how the world works and doesn't work, who has an appreciation
for the greatness of the American people, but also knows what the
barriers are to people truly moving ahead, truly realizing the
American dream, which, as you know, is allowing each of us and all
of us the chance to discover and develop to the fullest our
God-given talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``And anything that stands in the way of the dream we must
fight. And anything that enhances the dream we must support.''
</P>
<P>
   SCORE CARD: The commercial attempts to make the most of the fact
that Forbes has never held public office by depicting him as a
Washington outsider and playing up his background as a publishing
executive. It also works to appeal to people who are not focused on
politics and seeks to portray Forbes as more thoughtful and warmer
than he was in 1996, when he dwelled on the flat tax. The Oval
Office-like setting is intended to make him appear presidential.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
