<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRONX-ZOO-GORILLAS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORILLAS' NEW HOME CHARMS YOUNG, AS ELDERS STAY BACK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ohio)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A large gorilla sits on top of a tree, gazing toward
infinity, while two young gorilla twins hug each other, then
scamper playfully up a rock. Others concentrate purposefully on
peeling tasty leaves off branches. A tall female stands as erect as
a human and dances a jig. Youngsters pound their chests like little
King Kongs.
</P>
<P>
   This is the new Congo Gorilla Forest at the Bronx Zoo, which
opens June 25, and its occupants are still getting used to the lush
surroundings and the newfound freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Unseen, but far from forgotten, are three senior apes, including
Dan, the ``silverback,'' as dominant males are called; Pattycake,
who became an instant city celebrity when she was born at the
Central Park Zoo in 1972, and Julia, who has pretty reddish hair
and relishes being the center of attention.
</P>
<P>
   These three have not ventured from the indoor bedroom where they
have lived since early February, even as the seven younger gorillas
now frolic daily outside in romps that exceed an hour.
</P>
<P>
   James Doherty, the zoo's chairman of mammalogy, thinks Dan will
ultimately be seduced by curiosity, a trait he says no gorilla
lacks. Then the females will follow him. Then, again, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan may just decide he doesn't want to go out,'' Doherty said
with the weakest of smiles. ``We're not going to push him.''
</P>
<P>
   These are frantic but heady days at the zoo, celebrating its
centennial with the new exhibit, the most ambitious and costly in
the history of this zoo, and probably, any zoo, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   It cost $43 million and, at six and a half acres, is larger than
the entire Central Park Zoo. For the first time, the zoo will
charge extra for an exhibit _ $3 on top of the $7.75 to get into
the zoo _ but all of the $3 will go to African conservation
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will be able to view the forest through soaring
windows, intended to give a sense of being within touching distance
of the gorillas. In part of the exhibit, visitors are in a tunnel
and can watch gorillas above them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to set the new standard for exhibits,'' said
Cynthia Vernon, a vice president of Brookfield Zoo in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Congo, as it is nicknamed, includes 300 animals of 75 species,
and all are gradually being introduced to their new digs. The first
okapi, a graceful deerlike creature with horizontally striped legs,
is gobbling up everything vegetative, including the rather
expensive bamboo, which she was not supposed to like.
</P>
<P>
   The red river hogs are using their snouts like rototillers,
obliterating any hope that grass would be part of their landscape.
A female hornbill of stable disposition is being allowed to adapt
to her monkey neighbors, well before her mate, who is considerably
more skittish, is introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're spending a lot of time staring at the animals to see
what's working and what's not,'' said Rob Halpern, the director of
horticulture who 10 years ago started a nursery to grow 15,000
plants of more than 400 species found in Congo. (The initial
finding: almost all plants are distressingly tasty.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the undisputed stars _ the ones for whom Congo with its
11 waterfalls, 55 artificial rain forest trees, misting machines
and soundtrack of eerie jungle sounds is simply a terrific stage _
are the gorillas.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Africa. Only for eight months or so a year will
gorillas be outside. In winter months, they will be on display in
more traditional circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Dan's group of 10 prowling 22,000 square feet,
there is another group of nine, this one led by Timmy, who moved to
the Bronx from Cleveland. Because work is being completed on
plantings, they have so far been prevented from checking out their
new 28,000-square-foot forest. Three babies born last year are in a
separate bedroom, but will ultimately join one of the two main
groups, probably Tim's.
</P>
<P>
   Easing animals' acclimation to a new environment is common to
all new exhibits, and it can be tougher when the animals are of
different species. In 1990, zoo officials decided to put ibexes, a
kind of mountain goat, and baboons in the same exhibit.
Immediately, the leaders of both groups eyed each other.
</P>
<P>
   The baboon bared his teeth as his hair fluffed up, making him
appear larger and more menacing. The ibex pawed the ground, lowered
his head and charged. The two butted heads _ not exactly
traditional baboon behavior _ looked at each other for a long
moment and wobbled away. Doherty said the two, and others of their
species, then got along fine.
</P>
<P>
   The gorillas are actually making their second move. In February,
they were removed from the old Gorilla House, a throwback to an
earlier zoo era that has already been torn down. It was a place of
bars, cold porcelain tile, little light and less than one-tenth the
space the gorillas will have in their Congo environment.
</P>
<P>
   When Gorilla House opened in the early 1950s, it quickly became
the scene of death: a gorilla drowned in the 6-foot-deep moat. That
was how keepers, who quickly lowered the water level, learned that
members of the species couldn't swim.
</P>
<P>
   Last February's move to the new bedrooms was considerably
smoother. The gorillas immediately took to the rooms, which had
high ceilings, hammocks and plenty of vegetation to build nests, as
all do each night.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Kalko, collection manager for mammals, said young gorillas
immediately began swinging from artificial vines and playing a game
she said looks remarkably like break-dancing. ``It was very
stressful for us, but they didn't seem to exhibit stress at all,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing aiding the first transition was the decision not to
change the groups in any way.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last quarter-century, wildlife scientists say, this is
the most important factor helping gorillas to thrive and breed in
zoos. They point out that when William T. Hornaday, the first
director of the Bronx Zoo, said at the turn of the century that
gorillas would never survive in captivity, his only experience was
with gorillas as individuals or couples. But since groups were put
together with a dominant male and his harem, more than 300 gorillas
have been born at North American zoos, including 44 in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Another strategy was assigning the same keepers from the old
gorilla exhibit, giving the animals a strong sense of continuity.
They know all their keepers as individuals, Ms. Kalko said. The
courtesy is reciprocated by keepers, who eagerly describe
15-year-old Tunko's sweetness or Pattycake's independent
middle-aged habits or 5-year-old Tuti's devotion to the role of
self-appointed big sister to the other youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   So keepers, curators and William Conway, president of the zoo's
parent, the Wildlife Conservation Society, were on hand when the
metal door of the gorillas' bedroom first slid open at 3 p.m. on
May 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time waiting for this,'' whispered one
keeper, Wendy Camino, smiling like it was Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Then nothing happened. All the gorillas stared at the lush
expanse outside. They made a rumbling sound, and looked at each
other, then back out the door. Suddenly, Holli, a 10-year-old
female who is known for her confidence, leapt out. Tunko, known for
her hesitant, but sweet, demeanor, followed daintily. Soon all but
the three most senior gorillas were out. The 4-year-old twins,
Ngomo and Tambo, emerged and amazed curators by separating to
explore on their own. They are usually inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be human and not be moved by this,'' said Colleen
McCann, associate curator of primates.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Conway, who is retiring in September and pushed Congo as the
culmination of his long career at the zoo, seemed to prove her
point. ``Look at that little devil,'' he said as Ngomo scurried up
a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Dan remained unfazed. He came to the door and took a long look.
He took a tentative step outward, as he has several times since.
Then he turned around and went back inside. Though zoo officials
would be thrilled if he wanted some time alone with the two females
closest to his own age, 30, he has shown no interest in their
advances. He remains disturbingly childless.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty does not profess to know why the older gorillas have
stayed inside, though when food begins to be hidden around the
exhibit he thinks interest may heighten. He also suggests that
there might be some evolutionary logic to their decision. On one
hand, he said, younger animals need to practice such gorilla skills
as climbing and foraging. On the other, he said, more mature
animals might be taking extra care because they are more likely to
reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   He added that gorillas, unlike chimpanzees, feel no need to make
people happy. ``Chimps are like dogs and want to please you,'' he
said. ``Gorillas are like cats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
