<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, May 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Very warm weather with plentiful sunshine will cover a large
area from the northern Mississippi Valley to the East Coast states
as expansive high pressure remains strong. A few cooling sea
breezes will develop near the Northeast and Middle Atlantic coasts,
otherwise afternoon temperatures will average 6 to 12 degrees above
seasonal values. Humidity will remain comfortable in much of the
Northeast, but sticky air will gradually spread into the Ohio
Valley and Great Lakes states as breezes from the south become
established.
</P>
<P>
   Sultry air and a mixture of clouds and sunshine will prevail in
the Gulf of Mexico states. Scattered afternoon thunderstorms will
develop, especially in central and eastern Florida where sea
breezes force the very warm, moist air to rise rapidly. Farther to
the north and west, a weak jet stream disturbance will combine with
humid air to produce a few thunderstorms from eastern Texas and
Oklahoma to the central Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Periods of cool rain will dampen northern parts of the Rockies
and Dakotas in the wake of a slow-moving cold front. South of the
front, some potent thunderstorms will erupt during the midday and
afternoon from western Minnesota to western Nebraska and Wyoming.
Scattered afternoon thunderstorms will form over many peaks in the
central and southern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Offshore winds will favor abundant sunshine near the Washington
and Oregon coasts. In California, there will be morning coastal
clouds and a few afternoon thunderstorms over the Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: When Summer Begins
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures will gradually rise in much of the East during the
Memorial Day weekend, which is traditionally seen as the start of
the summer season. Nevertheless, for ease of record-keeping,
climatologists consider summer to be the months of June, July and
August. The warmest 90-day period in most of the contiguous United
States begins around June 6th. On the calendar, the season will
begin on June 21st, when the summer solstice occurs. The solstice,
an astronomical event, is when the noontime sun is directly
overhead at the Tropic of Cancer, 23.5 degrees of latitude north of
the equator.
</P>
</TEXT>
