<HEADER>
A5992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      05-29 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONALIST GROUP FIGHTS FOR IDENTITY IN SOUTH AFRICA
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The party whose slogan used to be
``one settler, one bullet'' is trying to stay in office by
appealing to the nostalgia vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Pan Africanist Congress now preaches ``non-racialism'' and
says it welcomes anyone who considers himself an African first,
including white Afrikaners.
</P>
<P>
   But it insists it is the true torchbearer of the ideals upon
which the African National Congress was founded in 1912. The ANC,
it argues, went off track in 1959 when it embraced the Communist
Party, Indians and mixed-race voters, thus diluting what was then
supposed to be a black nationalist struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Its leader, the Rev. Stanley Mogoba, reminds voters that, like
President Nelson Mandela, he too was imprisoned on Robben Island.
</P>
<P>
   In its early days, the party was a serious challenge to the ANC
for leadership of the struggle. It led the 1960 Sharpeville
demonstration that ended in the massacre of 69 protesters by
police. It, too, had a guerrilla army in exile. It tended to hit
soft targets like bars; in 1993, its partisans stabbed to death Amy
Biehl, a California college student dropping friends off in a black
township.
</P>
<P>
   Having formally abandoned violence, the party still seems
stranded on the banks of the river of history. Pollsters say it
will get only 1 percent of the vote on Wednesday. It got 1.2
percent in 1994. Since then, its five members in the National
Assembly did not really make names for themselves by taking the
government to task as, for example, the seven members from the
Democratic Party did.
</P>
<P>
   Mogoba, a Methodist bishop, did bring the party back into the
headlines recently by publicly musing that murderers and rapists
should have their offending parts amputated. He said the party had
not ``worked out the details,'' such as whether the chopping would
be done in an operating theater or a public square.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't say we'd like to cut people's limbs off,'' he said.
``But rather than allow criminals to cut throats, to rape, we'd
contemplate it.''
</P>
<P>
   He argues that the present government is soft on crime and soft
on corruption, has let moral standards decline so children no
longer defer to their elders, and has developed a ``trickle down''
economic policy while he prefers a focus on the poorest of the
poor. He also favors aggressive redistribution of white-owned land.
</P>
<P>
   He and his secretary-general, Ngila Michael Muendane, reject
their lowly 1 percent poll rating, saying some poll sponsors are
controlled by the ANC. They accuse the national television network
of giving them short shrift on the evening news. ANC members tear
down their posters and even threaten gullible farm workers,
Muendane said, ``by saying they can see their vote, and if they
vote PAC, they'll lose their housing or their pension.''
</P>
<P>
   In its literature, the party assures voters that ``the PAC has a
plan'' for every ill of the country: crime, disastrous public
schools, overwhelmed hospitals, the housing shortage. The plans
apparently involve ``investing massive resources,'' although it is
not clear where the money would come from.
</P>
<P>
   Its literature contains a seven-stanza poem honoring the
struggle of the homeless, the jobless, the worker, the student, the
woman and the aged. One verse:
</P>
<P>
   You can't earn a cent
</P>
<P>
   And all your money's spent
</P>
<P>
   So you think about crime
</P>
<P>
   But why do time?
</P>
<P>
   For you the jobless,
</P>
<P>
   The struggle continues.
</P>
<P>
   There is an odd echo to the party's platform. With its emphasis
on renewing morality and zero tolerance for crime, it sounds like
the other angry opposition parties, including even the National
Party, the latest incarnation of the party that instituted
apartheid but which now also proclaims itself multiracial, and
would probably back all the PAC goals except farmland
redistribution and aggressive affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition is fragmented and the ANC is expected to sweep
more than 60 percent of the vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
