<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-29 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING OVER THE EDGE, AND APPLAUDING IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Owen Hart, a 33-year-old professional wrestler known as the
Blue Blazer, plunged more than 50 feet from the rafters of a Kansas
City arena to his death in the ring last week, fans thought it was
part of the show, the kind of grand entrance they had come to
expect. They cheered as his body was carried off. After all, the
World Wrestling Federation had billed the nationally televised
pay-for-view event as ``Over the Edge.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy enough to dismiss this tragedy as a circus accident
without much resonance in ``real'' sports. State athletic
commissions conveniently delineate between an exhibition such as
pro wrestling and a so-called true competition such as boxing (in
which the occasional ``accidental death'' is actually caused by the
purpose of the sport, not by a faulty harness hookup). Exhibitions
don't carry the same legal and moral weight as real sports, so we
think we don't have to care if the bouts are scripted or if the
obviously scripted racism, sexism and violence should be
investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we should think again. This popular entertainment may be
a glimpse of a future toward which most of sports is inexorably
slouching. It is getting harder to figure out where ``over the
edge'' begins, and how soon that dangerous territory on the other
side will become our home field. One season's coach-choker becomes
another season's sentimental star. I, too, want to know why Latrell
Sprewell has not been starting for the Knicks. But then I'm filled
with strange new questions. Why doesn't my heart jump anymore when
a hockey goon slams an opponent's face into the Plexiglas? Do I
need teeth spilling out like Chiclets? When the racing car spins
into the crowd, will they show replays? Am I ghoulish or just
jaded? How soon will Mike Tyson be ready to bite someone's head
off?
</P>
<P>
   Are we already beyond Rollerball? Is it time to start getting in
line for Christians and Lions in their Garden update?
</P>
<P>
   Pro wrestling, most notably the WWF, made a conscious commercial
decision to push out its boundaries to include an audience that
wanted more intense bangs. Pro wrestlers are wondrous athletes,
traditionally in better shape than baseball players and even most
football players, and they work harder at entertaining us. But they
have always seemed cartoonish, from the campy Gorgeous George
through the earnest Bruno Sammartino right up to Hulk Hogan of this
fading ESPN Ironic Age in which we can enjoy all the thrills and
chills of the true believer while pretending we're too hip for the
hype.
</P>
<P>
   But those good and evil 'toon characters of wrestling were
Disneyed off. Video games, animated and computer-enhanced movies,
were all more exciting than large men, women, dwarfs, in Halloween
costumes snarling at each other and obviously pulling their
punches. We needed riskier scenarios and more outrageous
characters. Evil versus Worse in increasingly vile little psychotic
dramas.
</P>
<P>
   As wrestling was pushed into more violence by technology, were
other sports pushed by wrestling or just by their own marketing
projections to expand their boundaries of bad behavior and even
violence? Were they fearful of being left behind by a down-market
trend?
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe, for example, that hockey methodically set
out to make the games more physical, more damaging to players, more
breathtaking to the increasing number of warm-climate fans who did
not grow up skating on ice and appreciating finesse. Yet the
high-sticking and the league's relentless merchandising of thumping
checks feels something like a trend. (For all the eulogies to the
Great Gretzky, he will not be missed by this generation of fan.)
</P>
<P>
   The epidemic of concussions in football, of exploding
physicality in basketball, of head-hunting in baseball, were these
sales-conference conspiracies, a reflection of the times, a natural
expression of the gladiator classes coming into sports? Keep
watching the officiating or lack of it; risky business is easy
enough to stop.
</P>
<P>
   No question the stakes are much higher now, reason enough for
cities to bribe those Olympic officials with their hands already
out, for Dave Checketts to lie about negotiations like any other
business executive or politician, for Robbie Knievel to dare the
Grand Canyon. So why wouldn't some poor kid put a helmet in
someone's stomach, an elbow in a chest, a stick in a groin?
</P>
<P>
   Especially if coach and the market approve. In our ongoing forum
on Jock Culture and its effect on common sensibilities, pro
wrestling is worth discussion. It may still be a cartoon, but the
pressure it puts on other live entertainments to crank up the
action is real.
</P>
<P>
   Owen Hart was not a cartoon, he was a real person who died in a
choreographed stunt while making a living trying to entertain the
fans. It almost feels like a cheap shot to mention that the
headliners of his last show (which went on as planned) were the
Undertaker vs. Stone Cold Steve Austin or that Hart learned his
craft in the Dungeon, as his father's basement training school was
called. Hart often wrestled with his brother, the Hitman.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably worth noting that the WWF's chairman, Vince
McMahon, is interested in building a New York arena for his
traveling show, and in taking the company public. Risky business
like Hart's last leap should send the stock through the roof.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
