<HEADER>
A5995 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITEWATER-REOPENS-CO     05-29 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEWATER-REOPENS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Year after E. Coli outbreak, White Water expects a busy summer
 &HT;    WITH STORY SLUGGED: WHITEWATER-WEISS
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Henry Farber
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Vicky Hawkins of Woodstock says she has a memory for
dates, and she knows where she was June 11, 1998. She was at White
Water in Marietta, watching her two children splash around the
giant play pool known as Captain Kid's Cove.
</P>
<P>
   Little did she know _ nor could anyone have known _ that dozens
of children visiting the giant water park that day were being
infected by a deadly strain of E. coli bacteria. Twenty-six of them
would be hospitalized, and some would end up on respirators or
dialysis machines. One would die.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins and her children were lucky. They had no symptoms at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what was she doing back at White Water 11 1/2 months
later, again with her two children, now 5 and 10?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a one-time fluke,'' Hawkins, a labor and
delivery nurse at Northside Hospital, said of last year's outbreak.
``It could happen in a subdivision pool just as easily as it could
happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   She's just the kind of customer White Water is counting on as it
resumes its full summer schedule this weekend, operating seven days
a week through Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   As the anniversary of White Water's E. coli crisis approaches,
park officials are confident they've delivered their message to
potential customers: The park is safer than ever because of changes
that have been made. It's even a part of the recorded message
callers hear when they phone for park hours and prices.
</P>
<P>
   Park administrators won't release attendance figures, but crowds
have been thick since the park opened for weekends May 1. And
executives say season tickets are being sold at a pace that will
make 1999 the second-busiest summer ever. About 40,000 season
tickets were sold last year, a park record.
</P>
<P>
   Safety signs are the first thing visitors see after they park.
At the ticket windows, a new clock tells the time when chlorine and
pH (acidity) levels were last checked.
</P>
<P>
   Deedie Dowdle, White Water spokeswoman, said the clock shows
that the levels are checked every hour. But actually, she said,
that's just how often readings are taken by hand. Computerized
chlorine readings are registered every six minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Chlorine levels have been the main focus of allegations that
White Water bears responsibility for the outbreak. The park's
accusers say the levels were allowed to dip, permitting bacteria to
flourish. Park officials say industry standards were met.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the additional signs, some changes at the park affect the
way children play _ and even the way parents change diapers:
</P>
<P>
   _ Captain Kid's Cove, the shallow pool that was ground zero of
the outbreak, is off-limits to anyone thought by lifeguards to be
younger than 4. It is widely believed that the outbreak was caused
by a child soiling his or her diaper in the pool, although park
officials contend the spread of the infection probably started
outside the pool.
</P>
<P>
   _ Little Squirt's Island, formerly a pool adjacent to Captain
Kid's Cove, has been filled in so that it is a wet, flat surface
with fountains and large plastic animals. No longer can infants put
their heads underwater and risk swallowing water.
</P>
<P>
   _ Day care groups of children younger than 5 are forbidden.
``What we're pushing for is parental supervision _ not a baby
sitter situation,'' Dowdle said. ``Parental supervision is going to
be far superior.''
</P>
<P>
   _ There are more diaper-changing areas, and they include faucets
for washing babies and the changing surface. Poolside diaper
changes are forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   _ Restrooms are ``no-touch'' zones. Faucets turn on and toilets
flush automatically. There are no outside doors to push open;
privacy is ensured by angled entrances.
</P>
<P>
   _ Water is changed every half-hour and recirculated just as
quickly by a new filtration system.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Marek Cyzio of Duluth felt comfortable watching
his 5-year-old daughter splashing in Captain Kid's Cove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is related to money in this country, and I think
White Water's operators will do the best to make sure it doesn't
happen again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there were no water parks in his native Poland, and
he's making up for lost fun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
