<HEADLINE>
WRIGHT GETTING REPUTATION AS A HEADHUNTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ At the age of 27, Pedro Martinez is not exactly the
wise old veteran offering the benefit of his experience to the
youth sitting at his knee. But 23-year-old Jaret Wright would
probably do well to heed Martinez's advice because he knows whereof
he speaks.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, the Cleveland Indians' hard-throwing pitcher, is fast
gaining a reputation as a head-hunter. He was suspended for five
games earlier this season, was fined $500 last week and has been
summoned to the principal's, that is, the American League
president's, office in New York this week to discuss his
``deportment on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   When Martinez was a raw flamethrower with the Montreal Expos, he
quickly gained a reputation himself. He hit batters, just missed
some others and precipitated a series of brawls. Now he is a
full-blown star with Boston, leading the major leagues in victories
(9), earned run average (1.98) and strikeouts (108) before his
start against the Indians Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he has to do is not what I'm doing right now, talking,''
Martinez said. ``It's do what I did then, shut my mouth, listen to
what they have to say, put up with everything they have to do and
improve. I never quit pitching inside. I still hit some people, but
I did it in the right position, I got a lot better with my control.
All he has to do is improve himself as a pitcher, prove that he's
able to pitch inside and do it effectively without hurting
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   In spring training last year, Luis Sojo of the Yankees suffered
a broken hand when he tried to protect his face from a Wright
pitch. Last October Wright hit Darren Lewis of Boston in the head.
A week ago Saturday he hit Tony Clark of Detroit in the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day when he hit Clark in the head,'' Martinez said,
``I don't know what the reason was; I don't know what the situation
was. I just know it's dangerous. I don't go along with hitting
people in the head. I don't do it. I don't like anybody doing it to
me. I think a lot about the players as human beings. Those people
have families. They have to be there for their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was sympathetic toward Wright's plight, Martinez
candidly said no. ``Not really,'' he added, ``because I don't know
what the reasons are that Jaret Wright is hitting people in the
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright, son of former major league pitcher Clyde Wright, has
exacerbated the ill feeling toward him with his combative gestures
after he has hit a batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to control that anger,'' Martinez said. ``That's why I
can't tell you I'm sympathetic. If he is doing it on purpose, boy,
he's going to get his butt kicked. Somebody's going to get him out
of baseball. All they have to do is drag the ball down the first
base side and step on one ankle.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, no heavyweight at 5-feet-11 and 170 pounds, avoided
injury in his early Wright-like experiences. There was the episode
in 1994 when he had a perfect game going into the eighth inning and
hit Reggie Sanders with a pitch. Sanders charged the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``What in the heck could you be thinking when you charge the
mound in a perfect game in the eighth inning?'' Martinez asked.
``The ball just barely ticked him in the elbow and the guy charged
the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Derek Bell incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a ball close to his chin,'' the Dominican Republic
native related. ``Then he dared me to throw a fastball. He said
throw that stuff over. I did throw it over, I struck him out and I
said go sit your butt down. He got upset after he was in the
dugout. He charged the mound. All of a sudden the word spreads
around. I'm pitching in and people are charging the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those and other incidents, Martinez said, his and
Wright's situations are not comparable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time he has in the big leagues,'' he said, ``he's got way
far more starts than I had. I came up as a reliever, never really
got a chance to start. I got in all this trouble trying to become a
starter in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright has made 65 starts in the majors. His 6.95 earned run
average in 10 starts this season, though, indicates an obvious need
for much more experience. One experience he seemed to have against
Boston Friday night matched another of Martinez's experiences.
</P>
<P>
   The attention focused on throwing inside, Martinez said, can get
to a pitcher mentally. ``It did get to my mind sometimes,'' he
recalled. ``I was afraid sometimes to give up a home run or throw a
fastball in.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Alomar, the Indians' second baseman, thought Wright
suffered from that mindset Friday night when the Red Sox battered
him for eight runs in 3 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he didn't want to throw nothing close inside,'' Alomar
said. ``As a pitcher, you have to throw inside, especially against
good hitters like Boston. But today he tried to stay away.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he overcame that problem and added that Wright
can, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he has to do right now is focus on his work,'' Martinez
said. ``If he wants to do what I did, it's up to him. He's going to
have to learn to act different. If you give up a homer, stay away
from the batter. Stay away from the anger that you get when you
give up that homer. You keep yourself poised enough to get that
batter out, make your pitch and stay out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The advice is probably sound. It has worked for Martinez.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   INTERLEAGUE PLAY ON DECK
</P>
<P>
   American League pitchers were in the batting cage swinging alien
instruments last week, meaning only one thing: Interleague play is
here for the third season.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase begins Friday and runs for 10 days, through June
13. Mets-Yankees, Angels-Dodgers, Athletics-Giants, Expos-Blue
Jays, these are the natural rivalries that will be featured next
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' pitchers won't have to bat against the Mets in the
first of their two three-game series because the games will be at
Yankee Stadium, where the designated hitter is permitted to play
under the most bizarre split rule in professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   But David Cone and friends began hitting last week in an
exercise of futility that didn't even command the attention of
Chris Chambliss, the Yankees' hitting coach. ``It's a lost cause,''
Chambliss said. ``I think it takes a guy a lot smarter than me to
teach these guys how to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone was the most impressive with a bat in his hands, although
that's a relative term. He hit one pitch into the right field
stands, strutted out of the cage and said to his fellow pitchers,
``All you got to do is look at the back of my bubble gum card.'' He
alluded to his World Series hitting record _ 3 hits in 8 at-bats
for a .375 average.
</P>
<P>
   WRONG WORDING
</P>
<P>
   On an ESPN baseball cablecast last week, Rick Sutcliffe
suggested that Trevor Hoffman, San Diego's talented closer, and not
Tom Glavine of Atlanta should have won the National League Cy Young
award last season because he gained 53 saves in 54 save
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ought to get hold of one and see what it says on it,''
Sutcliffe, the 1984 winner, said. ``I know because I was fortunate
enough to win one. It says most valuable pitcher, and who was a
more valuable pitcher than Trevor Hoffman last year?''
</P>
<P>
   Sutcliffe was correct to an extent. His award and many others
indeed say the award was given to the most valuable pitcher. But
they weren't supposed to say that. The wording subsequently was
changed to reflect what the award has always represented: the most
outstanding pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   HEADS ARE ROLLING
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Hough paid the price last week for the Los Angeles
Dodgers' $105 million expenditure on Kevin Brown. Not that Brown
has been a pitching flop; he has a 5-3 record and a 2.39 earned run
average, losing a compete-game five-hitter, 3-2, to Cincinnati last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the team's pitching staff as a whole has disappointed the
people who made that expenditure, among other high-priced
decisions, so Hough, the pitching coach, was fired. It's a practice
that George Steinbrenner made popular in the '70s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' braintrust wasn't thrilled with the team's
run-scoring rate either. Rick Dempsey, the third base coach,
apparently couldn't get enough runners to the plate so he was
banished to the bullpen, replaced by Glenn Hoffman, Trevor's older
brother and the team's manager last year after Bill Russell was
fired.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' defense hasn't been terrific either, but they
didn't fire the defensive coach.
</P>
<P>
   BAD TIMES IN COLORADO
</P>
<P>
   Jerry McMorris, manager partner of the Colorado Rockies, is
having a bad year. He filed for bankruptcy 10 days ago for one of
his three trucking companies, and his team's pitching staff
continues to be bankrupt despite his decision to fire Don Baylor as
the team's manager and hire Jim Leyland for $2 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   McMorris could take some of the Teamsters whose salaries he has
been unable to pay, put them in the Rockies' pitching rotation and
the team could still have the National League's highest earned run
average.
</P>
<P>
   NO LEAD IS SAFE
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Pirates weren't happy last week when Roger Cedeno
stole second base in the eighth inning with the Mets leading, 7-2.
The old unwritten rule is that teams with big leads don't rub it in
by stealing. But the game's offensive explosion has rendered that
gentlemen's agreement archaic.
</P>
<P>
   No lead seems to be safe anymore. Most dramatic example of that
development came earlier this month when the Cleveland Indians fell
behind Tampa Bay, 10-2, after 5 1/2 innings, then erupted for 18
runs in the next three innings and won, 20-11. Larry Rothschild,
the Devil Rays' manager, only wishes he could have had a chance to
run up the score even more.
</P>
</TEXT>
