<HEADLINE>
RISKS ARE HIGH IN KASHMIR CLASH, U.S. EXPERTS WARN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States is warning that fighting between
India and Pakistan in the icy mountains of Kashmir risks ``spinning
out of control'' and could result in the fourth war between two
nations that last year declared themselves to be nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials and American-based specialists
say they see little threat of a nuclear confrontation, but they
also say that little is ever predictable in a confrontation over
Kashmir, the disputed Himalayan territory that stirs passions in
both countries like little else.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always the possibility of events spinning out of
control,'' said Karl Inderfurth, assistant secretary of state for
South Asian affairs. ``Clearly the ingredients are there for
miscalculation. Our hope is that both sides will take steps to move
this in a peaceful direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials say that U.S. diplomats in
India and Pakistan have offered their services as mediators in the
dispute and that Inderfurth called in the Indian and Pakistani
ambassadors in Washington on Thursday to encourage a peaceful
resolution of what may be the most dangerous confrontation between
the two nations in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Still, American officials acknowledge that the United States and
other nations may ultimately have little influence in ending the
fighting in Kashmir, over which India and Pakistan have fought two
of their three wars since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to help them find a solution to Kashmir for
50 years, and they're still at it,'' said a senior U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think history suggests that there's not much we can do. We
are very much of the view that this should be resolved by the
parties themselves. And we think they are capable of resolving it
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighting intensified seriously on Wednesday when India
turned to airstrikes to drive out several hundred Islamic
separatists who have taken up positions inside the
Indian-controlled part of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   India lost two fighter jets Thursday on the Pakistani side of
the cease-fire line under disputed circumstances. On Friday, India
confirmed that one of its helicopters was destroyed by a portable
Stinger missile, killing all four crewmen. The use of the Stinger
by the separatists, who have dug themselves in on high ground,
introduced a new and lethal element into the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Inderfurth said in an interview that he believed the fighting
would end only after the Muslim separatists who entered
Indian-controlled Kashmir had left of their own accord or been
forced out.
</P>
<P>
   Indian officials have alleged that the insurgents are being
supported by the Pakistan military, and many scholars of the region
say it is almost impossible to imagine that the guerrillas could
operate in such treacherous terrain without such help.
</P>
<P>
   Inderfurth would not comment on the question of possible
Pakistani backing for the separatists.
</P>
<P>
   But he said: ``Clearly the Indians are not going to cede this
territory that these militants have taken. They have to depart, and
they will depart, either voluntarily or because the Indians take
them out. And the use of air power was a very clear demonstration
that the Indians are serious about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Askari Rizvi, a professor of South Asian studies at Columbia
University, said he thought the confrontation was the most
dangerous since 1971, when India and Pakistan went to war, leading
to the creation of Bangladesh from what had been East Pakistan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It is potentially very dangerous in the sense that it could
escalate,'' said Rizvi, who was born in Pakistan. ``I think both
countries have to share the blame for this, in the sense that they
have been fighting a kind of proxy war in Kashmir for some years,
and now this proxy war is gradually becoming a real war.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stephen Cohen, a South Asian specialist at the Brookings
Institution, noted that Kashmir had been the scene of a ``whole
series of little roller-coast bumps like this'' and that ``my
judgment is that the risk of war is not greater than it has been
before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course if I'm wrong,'' he added, ``the miscalculation could
be ghastly, because both countries have the ability to kill at
least 100 million on the other side.'' He was referring to the
Indian and Pakistani nuclear arsenals. ``The cost of a
miscalculation is infinitely greater than it was before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
