<HEADLINE>
RIVALS IN ARGENTINA RALLY AROUND THE PESO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ As the race to replace President
Carlos Saul Menem of Argentina heated up in recent weeks, the two
major candidates thought they had found an ideal campaign theme:
Blame the incumbent's free market economic policies for rising
unemployment and promise major changes if elected.
</P>
<P>
   But investors got so nervous that rumors swirled of an impending
devaluation of the peso, and the already jittery local stock market
took a nose dive.
</P>
<P>
   So in recent days the candidates _ the mayor of Buenos Aires,
Fernando de la Rua, and the Buenos Aires provincial governor,
Eduardo Duhalde _ have joined Menem in circling the wagons to
defend the peso and even to coordinate economic policies in the
Congress. The display of unity has eased concerns of instability
leading up to the October election and the December change in
government, and helped to calm a still turbulent local stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua and his top economic advisers in the left-of-center
Alianza opposition coalition have publicly pledged to keep the peso
pegged one-to-one to the dollar, an eight-year-old policy that is
the linchpin of Menem's successful efforts to end years of
hyperinflation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, de la Rua's allies in Congress quietly ended a
campaign to restore hundreds of millions of dollars in spending
cuts ordered by Menem to control a growing budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   In a further gesture intended to reassure investors,
congressional members of the governing Justicialist Party and the
Alianza coalition are putting the final touches on legislation that
would cap the budget deficit at 1.5 percent of gross domestic
product in 2000 and 1 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Duhalde, who seems virtually certain of the official
Justicialist nomination, has also pledged to retain the currency
peg. He has dropped the mantra of his stump speech that ``the Menem
model is exhausted,'' although he still yearns to return the party
to the populism that was its trademark before his bitter rival,
Menem, took charge.
</P>
<P>
   Duhalde had been as much as 20 points behind de la Rua in some
polls over the last year. But by distancing himself from the
increasingly unpopular Menem, he has bridged the gap.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Duhalde publicly buried the hatchet with Menem's
economic policies by meeting with Domingo Cavallo, the former
economy minister who conceived those policies, including the peso's
one-to-one peg with the dollar, known here as ``convertibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Argentina should not abandon convertibility,'' Jorge Remes
Lenicov, a senior economic adviser to Duhalde, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   His words were echoed by Adalberto Rodriguez Giavarini, a top
Alianza economist expected to play a major role in a de la Rua
government, who said, ``It is highly irresponsible even to discuss
the possibility of abandoning convertibility.''
</P>
<P>
   After dropping 18 percent between May 10 and May 24 and pausing
for a holiday on Tuesday, the Argentine Bovespa stock index climbed
4.5 percent between Wednesday and Friday. The bond market also
steadied.
</P>
<P>
   The Argentine stock market became turbulent after the government
conceded a month ago that it could not meet the International
Monetary Fund target for a $2.95 billion fiscal deficit, saying
that a deepening recession and lower tax receipts would expand the
deficit to $5 billion. The fund eased its restraints, but only
after the government promised to make $1 billion in cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market woes increased after student demonstrations
around the country persuaded the Congress two weeks ago to restore
more than $300 million in cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The market slide then gathered momentum after Cavallo suggested
that Argentina could eventually float its currency. He quickly
clarified that such a move could be a decade or more away. But the
damage was furthered when George Soros, the international
financier, suggested that an overvalued peso was hurting
Argentina's competitiveness on world markets, especially after the
Brazilian devaluation in January. Soros later said he did not
support a devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Menem and his aides have said they will never
devalue. In a dire emergency, they say, Menem will do away with the
peso altogether and make the dollar Argentina's currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
