<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA SUFFERS GLADLY THE CHAOS OF THE COMING VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Former President Suharto used to call them
``festivals of democracy'' _ ritual one-candidate elections in
which vocal opponents were jailed, voters were pressured and the
results were manipulated at his whim.
</P>
<P>
   One year after Suharto's forced resignation, an extraordinary
spectacle is unfolding on the streets of Indonesia's cities: a true
festival of democracy _ a free and contested campaign with 48
parties, an unpredictable outcome and giddy daylong rallies with
all the exuberance of a carnival.
</P>
<P>
   After a yearlong interregnum during which Suharto's vice
president, B.J. Habibie, held the presidency, many voters are
clearly eager to do what they were never allowed to do before: vote
against Suharto, even though he is not running.
</P>
<P>
   His incumbent party, with Habibie as its presidential candidate,
is still a major player, with the strongest nationwide
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   But it appears to be on the run, opposed by a cluster of
opposition parties with different agendas but a common theme: Throw
out the old order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is changed; everything is upside down,'' said Jusuf
Wanandi, who heads the Center for Strategic and International
Studies, a policy institute.
</P>
<P>
   That change is all the more extraordinary given that only
Suharto left office last year. His once subservient legislators
remained in place, but laid the groundwork for the election that
may soon cost them their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the first freely contested general election in more
than 40 years and, if it is successful, will bring democracy to the
world's fourth-most-populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   If it fails, political analysts fear that Indonesia could plunge
back into the disorder and violence of the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would argue that we genuinely have open politics now,'' a
senior foreign diplomat said. ``The situation right now is better
than anyone had thought conceivable.''
</P>
<P>
   The election is part of a process that will complete the
transition of power that began when Suharto resigned on May 21,
1998, following riots and student demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on June 7 will elect 462 members of Parliament, the
bulk of a 700-seat assembly that will choose the next president
before the end of the year. No party is expected to win a majority
and few analysts are bold enough to predict the shape of a future
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The post-election time is going to be the most dicey,'' said
Sarwono Kusumaatmaja, the environment minister under Suharto.
``It's going to be a time of wheeling and dealing and plotting.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate to beat has become Megawati Sukarnoputri, the
longtime symbol of opposition to and victimization by Suharto. Her
popularity derives largely from the fact that she is the daughter
of Indonesia's founding president, Sukarno, whom Suharto deposed in
1967, and from Suharto's more recent attempts to silence her.
</P>
<P>
   The two other most prominent candidates, with whom she has
forged a tactical opposition alliance during the campaign, are
Amien Rais and Abdurrahman Wahid, both of whom have large Muslim
bases here in the world's most populous Islamic nation, with more
than 200 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   The election is an experiment and a learning process as well as
a crucial moment in the country's history. Nobody knows how
Indonesians vote when their vote belongs to them. And with a tangle
of complex new procedures, some of which are still being worked
out, election experts foresee the possibility of confusing and
anomalous outcomes and widespread protests.
</P>
<P>
   There is already a fair level of confusion in rural areas, said
David Timberman, an American expert on elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the villages people say, `Why are we having elections
again? We just had them in 1997. And why are there all these
parties? How are we supposed to choose?'''
</P>
<P>
   Already, many analysts seem to have been proved wrong about this
election. Almost everybody, judging by past history, had predicted
violence during the three-week campaign. With one week to go, the
relative lack of violence, said one diplomat, ``is fully consistent
with Indonesia's pattern of unpredictability.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, Indonesian and foreign analysts list a number of
scenarios for possible post-election chaos, and foremost among them
is a big win by Habibie's ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   This is partly because Mrs. Megawati's party, the Democratic
Party for Struggle, has cultivated a sense of inevitability aided
by huge, enthusiastic rallies through much of the main island of
Java and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Its momentum grows in part from the reform movement that ousted
Suharto and that continued through the end of last year to pressure
Habibie for more liberalizations. Its supporters demand victory as
the culmination of their long campaign for change.
</P>
<P>
   If the ruling party, Golkar, outdoes the opposition in the
election, many people are sure to cry foul and the demonstrations
and violence of last year may well resume in a new attempt to bring
down the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's Golkar, people are going to be hopping mad,'' said
Sarwono, the former environment minister.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if Golkar loses, some analysts foresee a
struggle as an incumbent power structure resists giving up its
patronage and perks. And the removal of Golkar officials at all
levels would strip Indonesia of virtually all the people who have
experience in actually running a government.
</P>
<P>
   For all the uncertainties of the process and for all the novelty
of an electoral choice, there seems to be a common theme among
people at the campaign rallies here: They want a new Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   For all the country's ethnic, religious, social and geographical
divisions, Suharto left behind a surprisingly united electorate,
even among supporters of Golkar. They want ``reformasi,'' or
reform, a break with the past in a nation whose political growth
has been stunted and whose freedoms have been limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reform means new faces, a new system, more justice, a better
economy, everything,'' said Retno, a real estate agent.
</P>
<P>
   For Hadi Sunaryo, a driver, reform means ``changes in the
structure, in the culture, in the legal system.''
</P>
<P>
   For Eman, a student, it is ``total change, in the Cabinet, in
the Parliament. Erase the old regime.''
</P>
<P>
   An office manager named Eky said, ``I don't care who is my
president. The important thing is to make my country better than
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, with this election campaign, those changes have begun,
Ms. Eky said. The difference is freedom, both for those who give
orders and for those who must obey. For both, the yellow shirts of
Golkar are no longer obligatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before,'' she said, ``my village chief pushed us to choose
Golkar. If not, you can have trouble. Oh, he was very strong.
Before, he was afraid and he made everyone else afraid. Now he is
not afraid anymore, and he is walking around in a green shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Green is the color of the Moslem parties that oppose Golkar. Ms.
Eky noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Oh, you changed your shirt,''' she said, ``and he
just smiled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
