<SLUG> BC-SLOVAKIA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOVAK ELECTION OFFERS CHOICE OF REFORM OR ISOLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRATISLAVA, Slovakia _ Slovaks faced a simple choice in the
second round of their presidential election on Saturday: vote for
further democratic progress and joining Europe, or slide back into
international isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolf Schuster, the official candidate of the four-party
coalition government and the popular mayor of eastern Slovakia's
industrial hub, Kosice, faced Vladimir Meciar, the ebullient former
prime minister. In his years in power, Slovakia slipped behind the
Czechs, Hungarians and Poles in the postcommunist scramble to join
NATO and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The latest polls indicated that Schuster, who finished first in
the first round of the presidential race two weeks ago, was leading
with 55 percent support, while Meciar had 44 percent. Although such
polls in Slovakia have proved chronically inaccurate in the past,
political analysts predicted a smooth victory for Schuster in
Saturday's runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Schuster finished less than three percentage
points short of the 50 percent threshold required for outright
victory in the crowded first-round field of eight candidates. The
candidate who finished third, a former actress and diplomat, Magda
Vasaryova, urged her supporters to vote for Schuster on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Voters here in Slovakia's capital brimmed with optimism about a
victory for Schuster, 65, a former communist who since the
anti-communist revolution in 1989 has served as ambassador to
Canada as well as mayor of Kosice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meciar doesn't stand a chance,'' said Robert Jahn, echoing
other passers-by. ``What would happen if he won? It would be a
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   During his six years in power, with a nine-month hiatus in 1994,
Meciar tarnished Slovakia's reputation abroad and made enemies at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Corruption and cronyism flourished at the expense of democracy
and freedom of the press. One of the journalists most critical of
Meciar narrowly escaped death when his car blew up. The police
recently arrested the former director of the Slovak Intelligence
Service, Ivan Lexa, and charged him with kidnapping the son of the
former Slovak president, Michal Kovac.
</P>
<P>
   The police are also investigating Meciar's former interior
minister, Juraj Svec, for allegedly stalling a 1997 referendum
about NATO membership and direct presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Meciar, 57, dropped from the Slovak political scene after his
opposition, led by Mikulas Dzurinda, won parliamentary elections
last September. In a theatrical appearance on Slovak television,
Meciar performed a tearful song with impromptu lyrics, singing
``Goodbye, I am leaving you, I have never hurt any of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuster portrays himself as a hard-working servant of the
public and says that was also what he was during the communist era,
when he at one point was head of Slovakia's communist Parliament,
which then was subservient.
</P>
<P>
   Some voters reproach him for that past. Others brush it off,
noting that he held the prominent post in 1989 to 1990, during and
after the collapse of communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the important thing is what he has accomplished,''
said Karol Ferstl, a Bratislava teacher. ``Last summer I went to
Kosice, and when I saw how much the city has flourished since he
became the mayor, tears ran down my face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
