<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6023 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESIDENT-SALARY-ART-     05-29 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENT-SALARY-ART-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES SEEM INDIFFERENT TO SALARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The people who want to be president seem almost
indifferent to an issue of public policy that could affect one of
them personally: How much should the next chief executive be paid?
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated requests, fewer than half the candidates
commented the week before last on a proposal in Congress to raise
the pay of the president to $400,000. The salary has been $200,000
since Richard Nixon took office in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has spent his career in public service to help people,
not to go after a pay raise,'' said Melissa Ratcliff, a spokeswoman
for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's rival for the Democratic
nomination, had a similar view. ``You don't run for this job for
the annual salary,'' Bradley said through his spokesman, Tony
Wyche. ``I think we should leave it up to Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   The leading Republican candidate agreed entirely. ``It's the job
of the Congress to decide,'' Gov. George W. Bush of Texas said
through his spokeswoman, Mindy Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   One of his rivals for the Republican nomination, former Gov.
Lamar Alexander of Tennessee, also declined to involve himself in
the debate. ``I shouldn't help to set the salary I will receive as
president,'' Alexander said through his chief press aide, Bo
Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, another Republican candidate, opposes a raise for
the next president, said his spokeswoman, Juleanna Glover Weiss.
The wealthy Forbes, of course, does not have to worry about money.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, a social and religious conservative, is regarded by
pollsters as the longest of long shots for the Republican
nomination, but on the issue of presidential pay his views _ as far
as they go _ are in line with those of his countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that Gary opposes doubling the president's
salary all at once,'' Bauer's spokeswoman, Jessica Morris, said.
</P>
<P>
   So do most Americans, according to a recent survey by the Pew
Research Center for the People and the Press in Washington. Only
one person in four thought the president's pay should rise by more
than $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of those surveyed said the president should get
a raise at least once a decade. Told that the president's pay had
not gone up since 1969, 49 percent said the next one should get a
raise, while 39 percent said no.
</P>
<P>
   But when those surveyed were told that the president now makes
$200,000 (a fact only 19 percent of the respondents knew
beforehand), plus $100,000 for travel and $50,000 for expenses,
only 41 percent favored a raise, while 55 percent opposed one.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was based on telephone interviews of a nationwide
sample of 1,179 adults from May 12 through May 16 and had a margin
of sampling error of plus or minus four percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The public's feelings notwithstanding, witnesses who appeared
recently before a panel of the House Committee on Government Reform
were ``nearly unanimous'' that the president's pay should go to
$400,000, said Russell George, chief counsel and staff director of
the Subcommittee on Government Management, Information and
Technology.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Former presidential aides who might agree on little else,
politically or historically, were united in their view that the
president's compensation (even with its many fringe benefits) ought
to go up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not even a close call,'' said Kenneth Duberstein, a
former chief of staff to President Ronald Reagan. ``This needs to
be addressed now. It is a case of simple equity.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Haig, one-time chief of staff to Nixon, agreed, as did
John Sununu, who held the job under President George Bush, and Mack
McLarty, former chief of staff to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   McLarty said that other high officials, unlike the president,
are eligible for congressionally approved cost-of-living increases
but that those increases were becoming minimal out of fear that the
pay of some officials would overtake the president's. For instance,
the vice president, the chief justice of the United States and the
speaker of the House make $175,400.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress does not act on a presidential raise in 1999, it may
be even less likely to do so in 2000, since the pay of public
officials is a sensitive issue to take up in an election year. If
nothing is done before noon on Jan. 20, 2001, the next president
will not get a raise.
</P>
<P>
   Five Republican candidates, former Vice President Dan Quayle,
Elizabeth Dole, Pat Buchanan, Sen. Robert Smith of New Hampshire
and Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, declined comment on whether the next
person in the White House should be paid more.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a safe bet that they agree with Bush and Alexander on
one point. ``He'd take the job either way,'' Ms. Tucker said of
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our position, too,'' Harmon said for Alexander.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
