<P>
   _ The company that makes ``The Jerry Springer Show'' announced
last week it would edit out the show's infamous fights. The show
made the exact same pledge a year ago, but when ratings went down,
they restored and even promoted the brawls. In May sweeps this
year, with the fights, ``Springer'' was drawing 6.6 million viewers
nationally, a very healthy number for a syndicated show.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reality TV shows like ``Cops'' may be tamed by the Supreme
Court's decision last week that police violate people's rights when
they bring TV crews and journalists into private homes.
</P>
<P>
   _ The WB postponed the season finale of ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' because it contained fantasy violence at a high school;
the WB felt that was inappropriate after the shootings in
Littleton, Colo., and Rockdale County.
</P>
<P>
   _ CBS took a violent Mafia drama, ``Falcone,'' off its fall
schedule. ``This wasn't the right time to have people getting
whacked on the streets of New York,'' CBS president Leslie Moonves
told advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme TV has its defenders, but they tend to be more
half-hearted than those who attack it. ``You don't necessarily want
to rely on that stuff for the long term,'' says Doug Herzog, Fox's
entertainment president. ``You could probably say maybe we've been
doing a bit too much of that lately. But there is a place for it, I
do believe, on Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an identity crisis in the industry itself,'' says
Robert Thompson, director of Syracuse University's Center for the
Study of Popular Television. ``The left hand is doing one thing and
the right hand is doing another.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV industry seems willing to _ and perhaps must _ try
anything to attract viewers, an increasingly difficult task.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average home now receives more than 50 channels,'' says
Rash. ``Now programming appeals to specific audiences, from MTV to
the Food Network. Because of audience fragmentation, the measure of
success has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning: You used to have to get 20 million or 30 million
viewers to be a success in TV. With fragmentation, particularly if
you dwell in the fringes of cable and syndication, you can be a
success with 5 million, or even fewer if they're the right viewers
for advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, television has always been about tapping viewers'
wallets. But overall community standards have changed, Thompson
says. In addition, a voluntary broadcasters' code was jettisoned in
the early '80s, and the networks down-sized their Standards and
Practices departments (censors) in economic cutbacks in the late
'80s and early '90s. All of that helped feed the anything-goes
atmosphere of Extreme TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've established the economic logic, it's just a matter
of seeing how far down you can go,'' Lichter says.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Extreme TV, the further down you go, the more
the ratings rise. ``WWF Raw'' is considered much nastier than ``WCW
Nitro,'' and when the two go head-to-head on Monday nights, ``Raw''
slams ``Nitro,'' 4.3 million homes to 3.3 million homes. Fox's
``World's Scariest'' specials virtually always out-peform the tamer
series they pre-empt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People sit with their remote controls, thumb poised, and
anything that makes their attention go away for a minute makes them
flip,'' Thompson says. ``You're flipping through and you see a
train wreck and it's arresting. A long, drawn-out dramatic scene
doesn't have that impact.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all about arousal, says Paul Klite, executive director of
Rocky Mountain Media Watch, an advocacy group that monitors local
TV news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence attracts people's attention and produces a strong
emotional reaction that advertisers covet,'' Klite says.
``Marketers call it arousal. ... Arousal helps move merchandise.''
</P>
<P>
   Extreme TV has even spilled over into news, particularly local
TV news and the network newsmagazines. Barry Glassner is the author
of ``The Culture of Fear'' (Basic Books, $25), a new book that
looks at the media's over-hyping of stories that push viewers' hot
buttons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start watching the screamer shows in the afternoon,
then the local news, then the extreme shows, then a newsmagazine or
two, then the local news again, you're pretty much guaranteed to
have nightmares,'' says Glassner. ``It's a shortcoming of the
people who put together local TV news that they can't tell a story
without extreme violence and fear-mongering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Violent topics consistently comprise 40 to 50 percent of all
the air-time devoted to (local) news,'' Klite says. ``Crime rates
are down across the U.S., but not on local TV news. Murder, one of
the least common crimes committed, is the No. 1 topic on
newscasts.''
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts that Extreme TV is here, it's big, and it's ugly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to go away in the future,'' says
Thompson of the Center for the Study of Popular Television. ``Like
it or not, there's something about watching a real car chase that's
exciting, an adrenaline charge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actions have eventual reactions,'' counters ad buyer Rash.
``There's already a hue and cry about the media role in the recent
incidents in high schools. The subsequent decade could be a
reaction to the cultural excesses of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll look in the mirror and decide to become more class
than crass.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
