<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6029 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIVALS-MAIN-COX     05-29 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVALS-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrestling rivals no-holds barred battle means violence, sex _
and now death
 &HT;    Packages with: RIVALS -TIMELINE and EXTREME-TV
 &HT;    With: 1-column chart
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott and Harry Thomas
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The battle between the two major wrestling leagues, Time
Warner's World Championship Wrestling and Vince McMahon's World
Wrestling Federation, may not have killed wrestler Owen Hart, as
his family claims, but it has shaped the ``sport'' to become, in
many ways, the sport of the '90s: An unruly, high-hokum,
high-ratings hybrid of athletics and entertainment, sex and
violence, melodrama, good, bad, evil _ and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   From its humble beginnings, with overweight men sweating and
grunting in shorts too tight, professional wrestling has attained
the tawdry gloss of a slickly produced TV soap opera with the box
office appeal of a Schwarzenegger film.
</P>
<P>
   It's a billion-dollar industry. And two titans of pop culture
are divvying it up, pitting in the ring two of the more daring
pioneers of cable programming.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner Vice Chairman Ted Turner is the entrepreneur who was
cable before cable was cool. And McMahon is the wrestling
impresario who made gross grossly profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Turner came to wrestling from TV; it was a mainstay on his
flagship WTBS, and that led to his purchasing what's now the WCW in
1988. McMahon came to wrestling through his father, also a
promoter, and blazed the trail of glitzy, overwrought events into
America's living rooms as the WWF's leader and the producer of
NBC's ``Saturday Night's Main Event'' from 1985 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon has characterized his role this way: ``My job is to
entertain the masses at whatever level they want.'' And for more
than a decade, McMahon ruled the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the mid-90s, WCW raided WWF for some of its marquee
talent (Hulk Hogan, Scott Hall, Kevin Nash) with the allure of
million-dollar contracts. WCW's TV ratings ``began to skyrocket,''
says Bill Apter, editor-in-chief of World of Wrestling magazine.
For 83 weeks straight, WCW won the war for America's living room.
</P>
<P>
   WCW's growth didn't bankrupt the WWF, however. Instead,
wrestling's rising tide of popularity, caused in part by the hoopla
over the rivalry, lifted both federations. Last year the
Atlanta-based WCW and the Connecticut-based WWF each turned at
least $500 million in revenues, according to Journal-Constitution
research. The weekly audience for the federations' 15 hours of
programming is estimated at 35 million.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, McMahon chafed at Turner's talent raid as he watched
WCW become the premier wrestling federation, and he decided to
settle the battle in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (WWF) had to do something,'' Apter says. ``Nothing made
their ratings rise until they tried some of the borderline stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``borderline stuff,'' meant ratcheting up the violence. In
``hard-core'' matches wrestlers beat one another with chairs,
tables _ even forklifts. Sex and theatrics (such as crucifixion)
became central to the scripted story lines in and out of the ring.
</P>
<P>
   After WWF's Hart fell to his death from a cable last week, his
family claimed that the federation's desperation for extreme stunts
was to blame. Others, however, have pointed out that hanging by a
cable is not so extreme _ a staple of Broadway shows and circuses,
and something other wrestlers have done without a problem.
</P>
<P>
   With its new approach, WWF caught and passed WCW in the ratings
about a year ago. Today, Apter contends, the gap between the WCW
and the WWF televised matches is so wide ``it's like comparing a
classy kids show to Jerry Springer.''
</P>
<P>
   WCW president Eric Bischoff says his federation will continue to
be the class act, despite the WWF's recent successes.
</P>
<P>
   WCW bases some of its strategy on a report it commissioned, by a
Northwestern University professor of marketing and cultural
anthropology, to figure out the appeal of wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he told us is that wrestling is for young males what soap
operas are for women,'' says Joe Uva, TBS President of
Entertainment Sales and Marketing. ``The need for heroes, conflict
resolution, action and adventure vicariously through television.''
</P>
<P>
   Bischoff, displaying the bluster that once prompted him to
challenge McMahon to a grudge match, predicts McMahon's antics will
eventually undo him: ``He's going to self-destruct, although he has
lasted a lot longer than I would have expected. He's a TV version
of a cockroach. Just when you think you've got the problem licked,
it comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bischoff says WCW won't waver from its ``family oriented''
standards, and there are provisions in place to keep its wrestlers
in check _ including fines. The network uses a seven-second delay
during cablecasts in case a WCW wrestler, in the heat of a match,
gets carried away.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF declined to comment on the rivalry, citing a mourning
period for Hart.
</P>
<P>
   At least one advertiser _ Wrigley's _ says that because of
risque programming it isn't renewing its advertising contract on
WWF. And there are indications of a wider backlash against
professional wrestling, generally.
</P>
<P>
   Boston pediatrician Dr. Howard Spivak, chairman of the American
Academy of Pediatrics task force on violence, says wrestling is
``totally unfit to be watched by children _ of any age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's especially dangerous to very young children, because they
can't tell the difference between reality and fantasy,'' he says.
Atlantan Tom Holder shares those concerns. His sons Danny, 7, and
Michael, 4, are big fans.
</P>
<P>
   Danny returned from a week at a YMCA camp and blurted something
about oral sex, Holder says. ``I thought 'Whoa, where did he hear
that?''' It turns out Danny was repeating an oft-used WWF
buzzphrase.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the moment, putting a submission hold on this
billion-dollar business of men in shorts will be difficult.
Advertisers see it as a main vehicle for reaching young males, ages
12 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the only way to reach that group that doesn't watch
a lot of TV,'' says Keith Wachtel, a buyer with Zenith Media
Services in New York. ``Almost every other sport skews too old.''
WCW President Bischoff says he expects the furor surrounding Owen
Hart's death will soon pass, and the federations and fans will
return to their ever-expanding world where sweaty guys and gals in
tight clothing rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has wrestling peaked?'' he says. ``No. It's just going to get
bigger. Do I think there could be 50 million viewers every week?
Yes. But it will take something different, another type of
wrestling program.''
</P>
<P>
   The real reach, he says, will be deeper into the culture:
``Movies, TV, animation, themed restaurants _ all forms of
entertainment. Anything that's character-driven.''
</P>
<P>
   So all this stuff on TV may be just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at our shows,'' Bischoff says, ``as the most
entertaining infomercial of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
