<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIVALS-TIMELINE-COX     05-29 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVALS-TIMELINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PRO WRESTLING SINCE THE BEGINNING
 &HT;    Packages with: RIVALS -TIMELINE and EXTREME-TV
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mid-1800s: An early form of professional wrestling begins in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   1950s: The new medium of television makes pro wrestling a
mainstay. Gorgeous George, who sprays the ring with perfume before
each match, is a star.
</P>
<P>
   1964: Andre the Giant makes his pro debut.
</P>
<P>
   Early '80s: Vince McMahon buys regional wrestling promotions and
consolidates them into the World Wrestling Federation.
</P>
<P>
   July 1982: Comedian Andy Kaufmann and wrestler Jerry ``the
King'' Lawler engage in a highly publicized shouting match on
``Late Night With David Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   1984: Hulk Hogan joins WWF. He and other stars make WWF the top
league in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   July 1984: WWF takes over the airtime of the rival National
Wrestling Alliance on Atlanta station WTBS. The station receives
hundreds of complaints and reinstates the NWA, along with WWF.
</P>
<P>
   March 1985: WWF's first ``Wrestlemania'' is held at New York's
Madison Square Garden. It is broadcast to 135 closed-circuit
locations.
</P>
<P>
   May 1985: Pro wrestling returns to network TV after a nearly
30-year absence, as WWF's ``Saturday Night's Main Event'' premieres
on NBC. It runs until 1992.
</P>
<P>
   November 1987: WWF runs its ``Survivor Series'' in direct
competition with NWA's ``Starrcade,'' forcing distributors and fans
to choose between pay-per-view events. WWF succeeds in taking the
Thanksgiving tradition away from NWA.
</P>
<P>
   November 1988: Ted Turner buys NWA from Jim Crockett Promotions,
calls it World Championship Wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   September 1992: WTBS celebrates 20 years of wrestling on the
station with WCW's ``Clash of the Champions.'' The show marks Andre
the Giant's last U.S. appearance.
</P>
<P>
   January 1993: WWF debuts ``Monday Night Raw'' on the USA
Network.
</P>
<P>
   June 1994: Hulk Hogan (above) defects to WCW.
</P>
<P>
   July 1994: McMahon is acquitted of conspiracy to distribute
anabolic steroids to wrestlers.
</P>
<P>
   May 1996: WCW's first two-hour ``Monday Nitro'' airs on TNT. It
later expands to its current three hours. WWF superstar Razor Ramon
(Scott Hall) appears on the show.
</P>
<P>
   June 1996: After Hall and another WWF star, Diesel (Kevin Nash),
continue to appear on WCW's ``Monday Nitro,'' the WWF files suit
against WCW for unfair competition and trademark infringement.
</P>
<P>
   July 1996: Hulk Hogan, until now a good guy figure, becomes the
villainous Hollywood Hogan, lifting WCW's ``Nitro'' ratings.
</P>
<P>
   January 1998: WCW premieres its ``Thursday Thunder'' program on
WTBS, giving the league two shows on prime time cable.
</P>
<P>
   April 1998: For the first time in 83 head-to-head meetings,
``Raw'' defeats ``Nitro'' in ratings.
</P>
<P>
   July 1998: WWF adds ``Sunday Night Heat'' to its weekly
broadcast roster on USA.
</P>
<P>
   May 1999: UPN announces it will air a new WWF show,
``Smackdown''. The two-hour show, to air next season, marks the
return of pro wrestling to network TV.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: The Wrestling Page; Gary Will, author of ``Wrestling
Title Histories''; WCW; WWF
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
