<HEADER>
A6038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAG-BURNING-AMENDMEN     05-29 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-BURNING-AMENDMENT-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAN ON FLAG BURNING: IT'S TIME AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Ill., Ohio, N.Y., N.C., N.D., Utah)  (lb) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of these days _ not on Flag Day, June 14, and
not even by the Fourth of July, but probably sometime this year _
Republicans in the Senate will bring up a proposed constitutional
amendment that would permit laws banning flag-burning.
</P>
<P>
   Every nose has been counted, and the outcome is known in
advance. The amendment will fail, most likely by two votes, to get
the necessary two-thirds majority, just as it has been rejected
every other time it has come up since the Supreme Court ruled in
1989 that laws prohibiting flag-burning are unconstitutional
infringements on free speech.
</P>
<P>
   But the amendment's certain defeat and the fact that
flag-burning is rarely in the news nowadays have not lessened the
passion on both sides of the issue. Nor have they diminished the
delight of the sponsors, mostly Republicans, as they watch the
opponents, mostly Democrats, squirm when they speak and vote
against a measure that polls show has the support of about 80
percent of the public.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments on both sides are familiar. At a Judiciary
Committee hearing last month, Sen. Robert C. Smith, R-N.H., made
the case in favor of the amendment. With an array of flags on
display _ one that was carried by the Rainbow Division in World War
I, one made by a prisoner of war in World War II, one carried by
U.S. troops that liberated Kuwait _ Smith called flag-burning ``an
act of violence against the symbol of America _ our flag'' and also
``an act of violence against our country's values and principles.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., said that the
amendment would violate one of the basic rights that the flag
represents, the right of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we prohibit people from criticizing the government by
burning a flag,'' Leahy asked, ``why not stop them from burning a
cross, or a Bible, or a copy of the Constitution? Why not prohibit
other forms of political expression?''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed amendment, only 17 words long, would be one of the
shortest and simplest in the Constitution. It states, ``The
Congress shall have power to prohibit the physical desecration of
the flag of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate approval is the only obstacle in the way of its becoming
the 28th Amendment. In 1997, the proposal was approved by the House
of Representatives by a vote of 310-114, much more than a
two-thirds majority, and a similar vote can be expected this year.
An amendment must also be adopted by the legislatures of
three-quarters of the states, but 49 states _ all but Vermont _
have in one way or another expressed support.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Senate voted on the amendment, in 1995, the
margin in favor was 63-36, or three votes short of a two-thirds
majority. There was one vacancy in the Senate at the time. Last
year a head count showed that the measure was still three votes
shy, and no vote was taken.
</P>
<P>
   In November, three new senators who favor the amendment were
elected to replace senators who had voted against it. The new
supporters are Blanche Lincoln of Arkansas, a Democrat, and Peter
Fitzgerald of Illinois and George Voinovich of Ohio, both
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But two opponents of the amendment, Charles Schumer of New York
and John Edwards of North Carolina, both Democrats, defeated
senators who had voted in favor of it. So the proponents gained a
net of one vote and needed two more.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, it looked as if the two Democratic senators from
North Dakota, Kent Conrad and Byron Dorgan, who have been heavily
lobbied by veterans and who have spoken out about their disgust at
flag-burning, might change their votes and favor the measure. But
last month they announced they would not do so.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of emotion,'' Dorgan said in an interview,
``when a veteran comes to me and says, `I was lying on Omaha Beach
with dead buddies all around me, and in the first light of day, I
saw the flag, and it meant the world to me.' That's what makes it a
very difficult thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Constitution is a marvelous document, and this doesn't
rise to the extraordinary level required to change it.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Dakota senators and several other opponents of the
amendment are sponsoring an ordinary bill that would outlaw
flag-burning if it was intended to incite violence. They believe
this would be constitutionally acceptable under the Supreme Court's
doctrine that ``fighting words'' are not protected by the
free-speech clause.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, the bill offers some political cover, but
other senators and many legal scholars are not so sure the Supreme
Court would allow it to stand.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the chief sponsor of the
constitutional amendment, said Republican leaders had promised him
a vote this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the eyes of the veterans' groups,'' Hatch said, ``it's
important to have a vote to get on the record who's with them and
who's against them.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he was under no illusion he could win.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the two North Dakota senators stayed off the
reservation,'' Hatch said, ``that made it very problematic for our
side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
