<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-780&AMP;A     05-29 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK GROUPS IN FLORIDA SPLIT OVER SCHOOL VOUCHER PLAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Exposing the sharp debate over school vouchers
among black people, two long-time allies from the civil rights
struggle in Florida find themselves on opposite sides on whether
the state should help pay for some children to attend private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, passed last month by the Florida Legislature and
awaiting the expected signature of Gov. Jeb Bush, would permit
pupils from the lowest-rated public schools in the state to attend
private schools, including religious ones, with vouchers paid by
taxpayers' money. Florida would become the first state to have a
statewide school voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
and several other liberal groups have vowed to sue to block the
voucher plan, contending that it would reduce support for public
education and violate the constitutional separation of church and
state.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the Urban League of Greater Miami, breaking with
its national headquarters, supports the voucher plan, and has
retained a Washington law firm to intervene in court on the state's
side in defense of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that healthy?'' T. Willard Fair, president of the Miami
Urban League, said, referring to the differences of opinions among
civil rights leaders. ``It shows that we are now getting to the
point where we can behave like human beings. We can like and
dislike. We can select and reject. We are not bound by color the
way we used to be bound where people said, `You can't think that
way because you're black.'''
</P>
<P>
   Most prominent civil rights leaders and organizations, including
the National Urban League and its president, Hugh Price, remain
firmly opposed to school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's New York headquarters issued a statement in
the name of Price, who was on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Urban League of Greater Miami affiliate must do what it
feels is best for the communities it serves,'' the statement said,
``and the National Urban League will continue to do what we feel is
best for our constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the NAACP, which insists that its local chapters hew to a
policy line worked out at its convention or by its board, the
National Urban League is much more decentralized. Local affiliates
have their own boards, raise most of their own money and can take
independent positions.
</P>
<P>
   While describing Fair as ``one of the most successful Urban
League directors in the country,'' Leon Russell, president of the
Florida Conference of NAACP Chapters, sharply disagreed with his
stand on school vouchers. Russell and other critics assert that
vouchers would damage the public schools by siphoning off the best
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be correct in terms of wanting to do something to
improve public education,'' Russell said. ``But I think his concept
of how to do it is all wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The split between the two civil rights groups in Florida mirrors
the divisions among black people over the voucher issue. While
liberal civil rights groups generally oppose school vouchers, polls
show that many low-income African-Americans, especially those with
children in poor-performing public schools, support the concept.
Conversely, more affluent and college educated black people are
much more wary of such programs.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 survey by the Joint Center for Political and Economic
Studies, a research organization specializing in issues involving
black people, found that 48.1 percent of African-Americans favored
allowing state money to be used for private school tuition while
39.8 percent opposed it. The poll also indicated that whites oppose
such vouchers by a margin of 50.2 percent to 41.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fair of the Miami Urban League is a strong ally of Bush's and,
like the Republican governor, an enthusiastic advocate of using
changes in education policy to put pressure on public schools to
improve, for example, the vouchers plan and charter schools, which
are public schools licensed by local school boards to pursue
innovative teaching methods. In 1996, Fair and Bush founded the
Liberty City Charter School in a poor black neighborhood in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we plan to make the system do things it's never done
before,'' Fair said, ``we have to be prepared to do things that
we've never done before.''
</P>
<P>
   The voucher program, if signed by Bush, is expected to go into
effect in September. The plan calls for all public schools to be
graded A through F, based on statewide standardized test scores,
attendance, disciplinary actions taken against students and
graduation rates. All pupils in public schools that received a
grade of F in two out of four years would be eligible to receive a
voucher worth about $4,000 to pay tuition at private schools.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fair's group has also angered some liberal civil rights groups
by retaining the Institute for Justice, a conservative legal
foundation, to represent it in any litigation involving the Florida
school voucher program. The institute has been an outspoken critic
of affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Bolick, the institute's director of litigation, said he
approached Fair's group two weeks ago and persuaded it to join in
the defense of the school voucher program if the NAACP carried
through its threat to file suit. Bolick said he wanted to ensure
that any judge hearing the case did not have the impression that
black opinion was ``monolithic'' when it came to school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the first name you see on a lawsuit is the NAACP,'' he
said, ``that unquestionably creates an impression that the black
community is on one side of that lawsuit. That image in this case
would be demonstrably false. Having the Urban League on the other
side evens the equation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
