u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-TEEN-MURDER-46     05-29 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-TEEN-MURDER-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DETAILS EMERGE ABOUT CANADIAN TEEN-AGER'S MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ Once, the polite and courtly city
of Victoria was known principally as a choice destination for
honeymooners and retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Then in November 1997 a 14-year-old social outcast named Reena
Virk was burned, beaten and drowned in a frenzy of teen-age rage.
</P>
<P>
   Six girls were convicted of assault charges, but publication of
details was banned under Canada's young-offender laws.
</P>
<P>
   Now the gruesome facts are emerging as charges of second-degree
murder against Warren Paul Glowatski, 18, and Kelly Ellard, 16, are
pursued publicly in adult courts. Victoria's youth culture is once
again under scrutiny, particularly in light of the fatal school
shootings in Littleton, Colo., and in the Alberta city of Taber,
which also concentrated media attention on bullying.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict in Glowatski's trial is expected in early June. Ms.
Ellard is scheduled to be tried in November.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Virk's killing was reported throughout North America and
Europe. Britain's GQ magazine published a feature story on the
victim and the ways of teen-agers in the city on the southern tip
of Vancouver Island. A teen drama, ``The Short Life and Lonely
Death of Reena Virk,'' written by two British Columbian teen-agers,
is performed in schools and at public events.
</P>
<P>
   Her death has become a catalyst in British Columbia for programs
and conferences about youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the case created a stir because people are shocked
when girls kill. ``We still have this unfounded belief that females
are incapable of violence,'' said Dr. Sibylle Artz, director of the
School of Child and Youth Care at the University of Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony in Glowatski's trial suggests that on the night Ms.
Virk died, girls posing as friends lured her to a park near the
Gorge Inlet. There, watched by as many as 50 other teen-agers, one
girl accused Ms. Virk of trying to steal a boyfriend, and six to
eight of them, ages 14 to 16, swarmed around her.
</P>
<P>
   Using a cigarette, someone burned Ms. Virk, whose ancestry was
East Indian, in the middle of her forehead; another tried to set
her hair on fire. She was kicked, punched and scratched until she
eventually stumbled away, dazed and bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend that Glowatski and Ms. Ellard followed, beat
her again and then drowned her in the Gorge.
</P>
<P>
   Although the cause of death was drowning, Ms. Virk's brain
injuries were so severe that she could have died from them, a
forensic pathologist, Laurel Gray, testified at Glowatski's trial.
</P>
<P>
   No one reported the attack. The police responded to school
rumors about a dead girl and, more than a week later, found Ms.
Virk's body floating in the cold water of the Gorge, naked except
for a bra and a shirt up around her neck.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although Ms. Virk and some of her assailants knew each other
from group and foster homes in which they had lived, others,
including Glowatski, had never met her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Virk was unpopular, according to her peers. In a rebellion
against her parents _ Jehovah's Witnesses who refused to let her
smoke and objected to teen-age sex _ she once told child-welfare
officials that she had been beaten and sexually assaulted at home
(she later recanted her allegations), so she could live in
relatively unsupervised group and foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   On the Friday that Ms. Virk was killed, she told her parents
that she would return for the night. When she did not show up, they
assumed she had gone to her foster home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      05-29 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA UNRESPONSIVE IN TALKS, U.S. ENVOY REPORTS
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Former Defense Secretary William Perry said Saturday
that during his just-completed trip to North Korea, he had
``clearly and firmly'' expressed concern about North Korean
military programs, but that he did not get any definitive response.
</P>
<P>
   Perry spoke in Seoul, South Korea, after concluding a four-day
visit to North Korea, where he apparently outlined a Clinton
administration proposal to offer North Korea a major expansion of
economic and diplomatic ties in exchange for the North curbing its
nuclear and missile programs.
</P>
<P>
   If accepted, the arrangement could eventually lead to a
far-reaching relaxation of tensions in northeast Asia, but there is
widespread skepticism that the deal will work smoothly, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   One inauspicious sign was that the North Korean leader, Kim Jong
Il, declined to meet with Perry, despite American hopes for such a
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Kim almost never meets foreigners, so it was not a great
surprise, but it reflected a lost opportunity to signal a new start
in relations.
</P>
<P>
   Perry did pass on to North Korean officials a message to Kim
from President Clinton, as well as from South Korean and Japanese
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Although former President Carter visited North Korea in 1994 on
his own, Perry as a presidential envoy was heading the
highest-ranking delegation to North Korea since the Korean War, yet
his North Korean counterparts were mostly at the vice minister
level.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said in Seoul that he had spoken to officials close to Kim
and had tried to convey to them ``clearly and firmly U.S. and
allied views and concerns,'' The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   But he said ``it will take some time'' for each side to reflect
on the visit and decide what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   From Seoul, Perry flies back to Washington to brief Clinton and
to put the finishing touches on his review of policy toward North
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the review is to achieve a more bipartisan policy,
with backing from Congress, dealing more consistently with North
Korea and seeking a way out of the existing stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   One underlying problem in achieving any breakthrough in
relations is the deep distrust with which each side views the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans, including a number in Congress, see North Korea
as a Communist menace that does not keep its bargains and is
starving its own population, yet has somehow become the largest
recipient of American aid in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   North Koreans argue, however, that they have kept their side of
the landmark 1994 agreement to improve relations, and that it is
the United States that has backed out of its promises to lift
economic sanctions and normalize ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 1554EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
