<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOFFA-CAR-HAULERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOFFA FACES HIS FIRST BIG TEST AS TEAMSTERS' PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Va.)  (rk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a Monday night strike deadline, James P. Hoffa is facing
his first big test as teamsters president in seeking to secure
higher wages and pensions and beat back concessions for 12,200
drivers who haul new cars to dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   Having assumed the union's presidency in March, Hoffa has
promised the nation's unionized car haulers their best contract
ever. And they are looking to him to show the same bargaining
prowess for which his father, James R. Hoffa, was famous when he
headed the International Brotherhood of Teamsters three decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his first major contract, and I'm sure he will be judged
significantly by that,'' said Michael Belzer, a professor of
industrial relations at the University of Michigan. ``He seems to
be taking it at that level. It certainly is going to be a measuring
stick, and unfortunately that makes it rather difficult to
negotiate this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a year when auto sales are booming, the threat of a strike is
worrying the Big Three automakers because a walkout that lasts even
a week or two could cause shortages of the hottest-selling cars.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the union and management acknowledge that
negotiations have been difficult. The teamsters are demanding
stronger job security, higher wages and a better pension for
drivers with 25 years of experience. Negotiators for 17 unionized
car-hauling companies are demanding a lower starting wage for new
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   As the two sides negotiate in Arlington, Va., union officials
are talking tough, insisting they are serious about striking, while
noting that 96 percent of the drivers who voted favored a strike if
talks broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car-haul companies are making record profits, they're
making record deliveries, and in spite of that, they are demanding
concessions,'' said Chip Roth, a union spokesman. ``The members are
united behind Jim Hoffa on this.''
</P>
<P>
   The union's four-year contract expires at 12:01 a.m. Tuesday,
and both sides say it is possible the talks could be extended
without a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Hunter, executive director of the National Automobile
Transporters Labor Division, which bargains for the car-haul
industry, said the companies ``fully expect to meet the teamsters'
reasonable expectations to improve their health plans, pensions and
wages.'' But he added, ``We have to get some win-win approach to
preserve the work we have.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the number of unionized car haulers had fallen to 12,200
from 14,100 since 1994, while the number of miles driven by
unionized haulers had dropped 23 percent since then. The cause, he
said, was lower-cost nonunion truckers and railroads that have
greatly increased the share of cars they transport from factories.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said a starting wage 25 percent below the standard wage,
rising to the standard level in three years, would make the
unionized industry more competitive and help keep it from losing
work to railroads and nonunion drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said unionized car haulers averaged $68,000 in wages and
benefits last year; the union said they averaged $55,000 before
benefits. Union officials say the drivers often work far more than
40 hours a week and have a dangerous job, often risking falls when
they climb on the trucks to load and unload cars in the snow and
sleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make good pay, but they're often away from their family
six and seven days a week,'' Roth said. ``And this is the most
dangerous job in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to car haulers last week, Hoffa promised he
would not return from the negotiations without a significant
increase in pensions. He also insisted that a two-tier wage system
was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   With the North American Free Trade Agreement expected to allow
more Mexican trucks into the United States, Hoffa also said he
wanted job-security language to protect teamster car haulers from
losing work to Mexican truckers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
