<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIAR FACES ON THE MARCH: GRAF, SELES AND DAVENPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ They don't exactly resemble dowager's row, but Steffi
Graf, Monica Seles and Lindsay Davenport have had their rackets
full trying to remain formidable in the face of an invasion by
minimally deferential teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   The three women have been smacked around, and off, the hard
courts by teen-agers this year, but here on the slow and staid clay
at the French Open, the old hands have been having their say.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, a five-time Roland Garros champion, Seles, a three-time
champion who was last year's runner-up, and Davenport, the
defending U.S. Open champion, all advanced to the round-of-16
Saturday, joining a select list of their contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the fourth round are the defending champion Arantxa
Sanchez-Vicario; Conchita Martinez; Jana Novotna, the 30-year-old
defending champion of Wimbledon; the comebacking Jennifer Capriati
and 27-year-old Mary Joe Fernandez, whose third-round upset of
10th-seeded Serena Williams was an inspiration to the entire bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like we've been written off,'' Graf said after
collecting her 80th victory, a Roland Garros record, with a cursory
6-1, 6-4 dismantling of Sweden's Asa Carlsson. ``We've just been
around so long that the story's gotten a little boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf, 29, became the youngest player ever to win a main draw
match here in 1983, when she qualified at 13 and reached the second
round. Now appearing in her 16th French Open in the last 17 years
(she missed the 1998 French Open because of left knee surgery),
Graf was 17 when she won the first of her 21 Grand Slam titles here
in 1987. Her record as the youngest French Open champion was
eclipsed by Sanchez-Vicario in 1989, a record that held up only
until the following year when Seles, then 16, won the first of
three consecutive titles here.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday Seles, seeded third, won her 10th straight match and
improved her 1999 clay-court record to 11-1 with a 6-1, 6-4
pummeling of Maria Antonia Sanchez-Lorenzo, a 52rd-ranked player
who is a clay specialist from Spain. Ever the perfectionist, Seles
was annoyed with herself for not applying the same stultifying
pressure in the second set that she had used in the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a little bit off my balls, and that was enough for her
to start retrieving better,'' Seles said. ``Then I got a little bit
uptight and just started missing a few shots: that will be an area
for my next match that I plan to improve upon.'' Seles then gave
herself a first-week grade of 5 on a scale of 10.
</P>
<P>
   The second-seeded Davenport wasn't quite as charitable with
herself after needing to pull off an excavation job against Fabiola
Zuluaga of Colombia to avoid being upset for the second match in
succession. ``You know, you can't keep sliding along just by barely
winning matches and getting breaks,'' Davenport said. ``I have to
be at a higher level if I want to stay in the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, 16-year-old Justine Henin, the 1997 French
Open junior champion from Belgium, served for the match against
Davenport before succumbing to stage fright at 5-4 of the third set
and submitting, 6-3, 2-6, 7-5. Saturday, Davenport had to repair a
5-2 opening set deficit, and save a trio of set points, before
overpowering Zuluaga, 7-6 (7-5), 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was down 3-love in just like six minutes, just getting
killed,'' said Davenport, whose French Open preparation was limited
because of a lingering wrist injury. ``You just have to keep
hanging in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport did, and won the tie-breaker thanks to a net cord that
fell her way and a double fault from Zuluaga at set point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things really went my way on the big points today,'' Davenport
said, ``but you know, when I won the Open last year, every match I
was playing really well and carried the momentum through.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport's next opponent, Capriati, is performing at her
highest level in six years, and Saturday she reached her first
Grand Slam round-of-16 since 1993 Wimbledon with a 6-2, 4-0 victory
against Sylvia Farina of Italy, who defaulted with a leg injury
after being pelted with a furious succession of ground-stroke
winners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6049 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-EXPECTATIONS-COX     05-29 1670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EXPECTATIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candidate Bush's first obstacle: slaying the expectation dragon
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ As he emerges from the cocoon and morphs into a
full-fledged presidential candidate, Texas Gov. George W. Bush is
about to run head-first into a formidable foe who hasn't raised a
dime, doesn't have a bumper sticker and has been even less specific
on issues than he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations,'' said Bush political adviser Karl Rove, not
missing a beat when asked to name his guy's most challenging
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, proclaimed the front-runner by poll and press, is about to
try to meet those expectations, an effort that has derailed more
than one high-flying politician.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign will go public shortly after the legislative
session is gavelled to an end Monday. Though he won't formally
declare his candidacy until later in the summer, the campaign's de
facto start will come June 12 when he heads to Iowa, home of the
nation's first caucuses of 2000. Then it's off to New Hampshire,
home of the first primaries, and the next week, South Carolina,
Virginia, Pennsylvania, Michigan and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Though the pent-up demand is great for Bush to begin active
campaigning _ he has taken some direct hits for offering few
details on some issues _ don't look for these first trips to be
heavy on specifics. For Bush, the opening trips will be part first
date, part job interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too premature'' for specific policies, Rove said.
``People say, `Wait a minute. Before you lay out the detail, I want
to get the general principles.'''
</P>
<P>
   That will be disappointing to people like Alida Weergang of
Hudson, N.H., president of the state's Federation of Republican
Women. The organization is expecting 1,000 people at its June 14
Lilac Luncheon in Manchester, N.H. Bush is the long-awaited
featured speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to know specifics, where he stands on a lot of
things,'' said Weergang, who has not picked a presidential favorite
for 2000. ``I would and a lot of other people would. We've had the
opportunity to hear other candidates, some with specifics and some
not.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rove believes most voters are interested in image before
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a point where they'll say, `I want to hear your
plan on tax cuts, and I want to hear your program about
modernization of Social Security. But let's start off by telling me
why you're running. What are your principles? Do you understand
what the job is all about? Do you seem to know how to operate? Are
you competent at it? Are you going to be able to handle the job?'''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, slaying the expectations dragon will be a work in
progress as campaign 2000 evolves. Rove believes there is no way to
do it quickly. The plan is to get voters personally comfortable
with Bush and then begin fleshing out his stance on issues.
</P>
<P>
   Rove says high expectations are neither a blessing nor a curse.
``It's a reality. Things are blessings or curses if you can do
something about them. We can't do anything about it. So it's just a
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove said nothing in the principles that Bush will espouse in
the first trips should surprise anyone who has paid attention to
Bush's two Texas campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be phrased in a different way because they apply to
a different stage and a different responsibility,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Bush's successful gubernatorial campaigns have been
longer on concept and philosophy than on specific proposals. He
laid out a short list of policy priorities ranging from improving
public education to reforming welfare to cutting taxes while
hitting hard on core values of limiting government and encouraging
individuals to behave responsibly.
</P>
<P>
   Rove believes voters in Iowa and New Hampshire, states where
presidential politics is 'up close and personal,' are keenly
interested in getting a line on Bush as a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you somebody I can like and relate to? Are you somebody
who can convince me you are going to be a good campaigner and that
you are going to be able to win this thing?'' said Rove, ticking
off a list of questions he thinks are out there.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Morin of Nashua, N.H., president of her local Federal of
Republican Women, is hearing questions like that about Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are waiting for him to be him,'' Morin said. ``They
want to see what he is like and compare that to his father. He
still doesn't have his own identity in the masses' mind. He is a
Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush team is well aware of that sentiment as part of the
challenge the candidate faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the expectations are going to be here,'' Rove
said, gesturing high, ``and it's going to be hard to satisfy
them.''
</P>
<P>
   And the expectations are being fueled from within the Bush
campaign with comments like these from supporter U.S. Rep. Henry
Bonilla of San Antonio: ``George W. Bush is the kind of leader who
comes along once in a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has a plan for handling those expectations. He jokes that
he will ``tell people I'm not as cool as they think.''
</P>
<P>
   He will also tell people what makes him tick, using stump
speeches and as much one-on-one as the trips, with as many as 100
media members in tow, will permit.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa and New Hampshire voters demand retail politics,
small-group gatherings in which body language can count as much as
positions on global warming. By reputation, developed in his two
gubernatorial campaigns, Bush is a good retail politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing when you're the governor of the state of Texas
and you are campaigning in those towns,'' Rove said. ``And it's
another thing when you are a presidential candidate. I do think
they're transferable, but the expectations _ again, I repeat, the
expectations _ of his abilities are so high that that's the
obstacle he faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Rival Lamar Alexander, who has been to New Hampshire and Iowa so
many times that he might soon qualify to vote in one of those
states, knows from experience that being a governor is not always
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a pretty good governor,'' Alexander said recently at his
Manchester headquarters. ``All of us who were governors think we
were pretty good governors. But going from being governor to being
president is like going from the playground to the NBA finals, and
the people of New Hampshire know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush will hit the road as a candidate for whom the planets seem
to be fortuitously aligned. Stout poll numbers have helped fuel
successful fund raising. Successful fund raising adds to the
inevitability quotient that is attracting Republicans eager to
regain the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has landed so many major GOP endorsements (114 Republicans
in Congress, more than half, gathered on the U.S. Capitol lawn last
week to line up as Bush backers) that the other candidates' best
gambit is to paint Bush as the establishment candidate.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to the expectations problem about which Rove is
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The natural process is you can't lead from the starting gate
to the finish line. You just can't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some can, but not without stumbles. In 1996, Bob Dole was the
early GOP front-runner and eventual nominee. But along the way he
took some hits, including Steve Forbes' wins in Arizona and
Delaware and Pat Buchanan's triumph in New Hampshire, that
temporarily dulled Dole's star.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's first major stumbling block could come in the Iowa
caucuses. In a field that could have 11 candidates, it will be hard
for anyone to pile up a killer advantage, especially somebody
measured against high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, with nine major contenders, Dole won support from 26
percent of the Iowans who attended GOP caucuses. Pat Buchanan was
second at 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, the 1996 Iowa caucuses went a lot further in
determining who would not be president than who would be.
Traditionally, the top three finishers move on to New Hampshire.
The others return to real life. Alexander, who ran third with 18
percent in 1996, could be the surprise in Iowa. He has a solid
organization there, led by Terry Branstad, a former 16-year
governor.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, as the effort moves to the next step, the Bush camp
is quietly, but supremely, confident. The months leading up to the
campaign have, in general, been good ones for Bush. Endorsements
and cash poured in as he passed enough of his legislative program,
including tax cuts, a plan to end social promotion in public
schools and parental notification before minors get abortions, to
declare the session a success.
</P>
<P>
   Probes into his background have yet to produce a silver bullet.
Several major newspapers dispatched journalistic SWAT teams to
scour Bush's past. The Wall Street Journal, in a peculiar effort,
printed a lengthy front-page story detailing some of the many
rumors and how the newspaper could not confirm any of them.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bush _ who maintains a reputation as something of a
hothead despite showing no public evidence of it since taking
office _ is taking the rumor-mongering in stride.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point from a recent Q-and-A session with Salon, an
Internet magazine: Salon: ``I'm sure you've heard the scurrilous
rumors that you were once a party animal, perhaps even the one who
danced on a table naked. Can you put these to rest or do you wish
to plead the Fifth Amendment?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush: ``I'll just say those questions are ridiculous, and I'm
not going to participate in that kind of gossip. There's no picture
of me, but it's trying to disprove a negative. It's just
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Salon: ``What can you tell us about your successful battle to
overcome alcohol abuse and are you willing to use this personal
experience to help fight America's No. 1 drug addiction?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush: ``One time I was dancing on a table naked, and got drunk,
and fell off. Just kidding. Say that again, now.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com or
445-1718.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
