<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      05-29 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIONS DIAL SANDERS, BUT THE PHONE KEEPS RINGING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, mum is the word in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Sanders is not talking. The Lions have tried reaching
Sanders at his off-season home in Wichita, Kan. _ Coach Bobby Ross
has dialed for four months now _ but Sanders won't bother picking
up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Hear no evil.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead, Sanders' father, William, has done plenty of
talking. He has said he believes his son is ``sick of losing'' in
Detroit, desires a new offense and has contemplated retirement at
age 30 and in his prime. Mind you, Barry said none of that. Dad
did. Nonetheless, the Lions have been turned upside down.
</P>
<P>
   Ross says he would like to hear from Sanders by Tuesday. The
Lions, Ross says, need to know what Sanders' plans are, especially
if he is going to retire, so the team would have time to acquire a
new big-time running back.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Sanders is making 'em sweat _ the team, the franchise, the
entire city. A swift juke. A deep freeze. Sanders missed a
mandatory minicamp in late April. He has not returned Ross' calls.
His fans are antsy.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanders is silent. He is enjoying his off-season, as he
always does. He is reflecting. Reflecting on 10 years laced with
teasing moments of hope and sullied by the realities of ineptness
and failure with Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions could think of it this way: Sanders' being silent is a
plus. Think of the alternatives. He could nearly blow the franchise
to bits with a volcanic display of his displeasure. He could wax
forever about the Lions' inability to field a Super Bowl-caliber
club in nine seasons. He could talk about coaching changes and
offensive coordinator changes and quarterback changes and
offensive-line changes and poor drafts and game-day decisions.
</P>
<P>
   He could bark and say what a lot of the Lions' National Football
League brethren often say about them: too little vision and not
enough dynamic leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if this were Michael Irvin. Or Bryan Cox. Goodness
grief, just think if this were Ricky Watters, or even Troy Aikman
or Brett Favre. Any of those guys might have blown the roof off the
place long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, though, is silent. He is not talking about the fact
that the Lions are 78-82 since he arrived in 1989. How they only
twice have won the NFC Central. How they are 1-5 in playoff games,
including two blowouts and five consecutive losses. How they were
5-11 last year and 5-11 a year before that. How, despite being
misused at times and seemingly always amid turmoil, he is 1,458
rushing yards from becoming pro football's career rushing leader,
beating Walter Payton's record of 16,726 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Ross says he and Sanders do not have a problem. Well, this isn't
exactly Earl Campbell and Bum Phillips and a new-wave version of
Luv Ya Honolulu Lions Blue.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders was pampered by Wayne Fontes, the previous Lions coach.
The Lions were notoriously slow starters who finished fast, and
Fontes would absorb the criticism and fight for his players and
stand tall with Sanders. Fontes nurtured the relationship. Though
Sanders hated the way the Lions would eventually wilt, he loved
Fontes' fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, who arrived two seasons ago, was supposed to provide
ironclad leadership and vision.
</P>
<P>
   In his first two games under Ross, Sanders got the ball 15 times
for 33 rushing yards against Atlanta and 10 times for 20 yards
against Tampa Bay. Off on the wrong foot, even though Sanders would
finish that 1997 season with 2,053 yards and Detroit would finish
with a 9-7 record and a first-round playoff loss.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders could have said that if Ross knew what he was doing all
along, had he believed in Sanders from the start, Sanders would now
be the career single-season rushing leader rather than second to
Eric Dickerson, who holds the record with 2,105 yards. But Sanders
did not say that. He was silent on that one.
</P>
<P>
   Hear no evil.
</P>
<P>
   The Sanders-Ross relationship took its greatest hit last season
when Ross benched Scott Mitchell for good in the second game. That
wound up killing the Lions' chances to make the playoffs. Later, in
Ross' biggest gaffe, he distanced himself and his coaches from his
team's poor play. It's them, not us, he said in effect. Bad move.
Sanders could play football another 40 years and never forget that.
Ross is no-nonsense and he is tough, and the Lions are still
adjusting to his bluntness. Can Sanders? Yes. But this relationship
is still very bruised.
</P>
<P>
   And so is Sanders' with the Lions' front office. He is being
paid the highest salary among all running backs in the NFL _ $6
million this year as part of a six-year, $36 million deal that
includes a $12.75 million signing bonus. It runs through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lions have ridiculously clawed and scratched during
every negotiation with Sanders. They have never come to him like
other owners have for Aikman and Favre and Steve Young and Terrell
Davis. The Lions have never come and said, ``Hey, let's rework your
deal for all you've done for us, and with all the new TV money
intact let's always work together.''
</P>
<P>
   True, the Lions inserted a clause in Sanders' current contract
that says he will be paid more than the game's highest-paid back in
the last year of his deal. Nice move. But if the Lions had done
more in a more readily appreciable fashion over the last 10 years,
if they had had an aggressive vision for his contracts and his
psyche and for winning teams, this situation would not be as
strained as it is now.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders will eventually call.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking here is he will play in Detroit in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   No voice from Sanders, but loud messages still ring.
</P>
<P>
   You won't trade me, he appears to be saying. Retirement goes too
far. Is there any hope for a new image, a winning atmosphere, a
Super Bowl? Can we work as one, as a team, with vision and daring
and boldness? Do you have any idea how frustrating this
merry-go-round has been? Get serious or let's part for good. Time
is short.
</P>
<P>
   No evil intended.
</P>
<P>
   In silence, can you hear?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
