<HEADER>
A6054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES-COX     05-29 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FALCONS NOTEBOOK
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the fuss about Falcons running back Jamal Anderson
missing offseason workouts, only one of the five players absent is
cause for outright alarm. And Anderson's not the one.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, right guard Gene Williams, snapper Adam Schreiber, and
wide receivers Tim Dwight and Ronnie Harris are not in Suwanee.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is training at home in Salt Lake City. Dwight is
running track at the University of Iowa, with the coaches'
blessing. Schreiber has a record for fitness. And Harris checks in
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Williams doesn't, and his absence is the largest concern,
largely because of his ``largeness.''
</P>
<P>
   He was fined more than $2,000 during training camp last season _
more than any other Falcon _ for being more than 20 pounds over his
assigned 315-pound playing weight.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Anderson are starters, creating a greater sense of
urgency to participate in a program that coach Dan Reeves believes
had a lot to do with the team's paucity of injuries last season.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries forced Atlanta starters to miss just 16 of 352 combined
games, or 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 30, lives in Cleveland, his wife's hometown, where he
played for the Browns in 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
   He has told friends he'll report in great shape. There are
skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say anyone who is not here is falling behind,'' pro
personnel chief Ron Hill said, ``and the people who are here are
moving ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta carried three guards last season, plus guard/centers
Schreiber and Dave Widell, who has been cut. Seventh-round draft
choice Todd McClure, a center, could fill Widell's spot.
</P>
<P>
   Schreiber, recently signed to a one-year, $425,000 contract, is
by far the best deep snapper.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta also gave former Giants guard Greg Bishop a two-year, $4
million contract with a $1.2 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's second-round choice, Bob Hallen, has been working
more at right guard.
</P>
<P>
   Also, last year's starting left guard, two-year veteran Calvin
Collins, is scheduled to make just $325,000, while Williams makes
$1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns, by the way, have penciled in offensive-line starters
everywhere but right guard.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: Medical Report
</P>
<P>
   Running back Byron Hanspard's surgically repaired left knee is
improving, and his limp appears gone, but he's still not a lock for
the July 29 start of training camp. ... Backup quarterback Danny
Kanell had laser surgery Tuesday to correct cornea problems. He
said he now has 20/15 vision without contact lenses.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: Fiscal forecast
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are about $1.5 million under the salary cap.
Although their rookie allotment is nearly $2.9 million, because of
the way the cap is calculated in the offseason Atlanta will be
about $400,000 under the cap once all draftees sign.
</P>
<P>
   That minimal breathing room makes difficult the idea of
extending the contracts of some of the 10 starters who will become
unrestricted free agents after the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Six will command contracts that probably would increase modest
'99 cap charges, ranging from $807,700 for fullback Bob Christian
to $1.63 million for center Robbie Tobeck.
</P>
<P>
   Two exceptions are middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle, with a
team-high charge of $3.85 million, and Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's cap charge of $1.6 million grew to more than $3.6
million, the second-highest, because incentives earned last year
count against this year's cap.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a $10 million signing bonus, his cap charge could be
lowered with a contract of at least four years.
</P>
<P>
   There's been little progress, though, as Anderson's agent, Jim
Sims, and Atlanta officials have differing interpretations of the
average salary numbers of the game's highest-paid backs.
</P>
<P>
   The cap charges of defensive end Chuck Smith ($2.8 million) and
wide receiver Terance Mathis ($2.1 million) are modest relative to
their peers, yet they could be lowered with extensions.
</P>
<P>
   One problem for the Falcons is that large annual salary
increases could accelerate their future cap charges quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials have made minimal progress on Mathis, although
they want to keep him around, and none on Smith, who will fetch
more than $4 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   A factor with Tuggle is his age; he will be 34 this season.
Atlanta might begin signing draftees this week, perhaps beginning
with seventh-round wide receiver Rondel Menendez.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: Standing pat
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are not expected to make cuts on Tuesday, when teams
can waive players with multiple years left on their contracts and
spread the residual effect on the salary cap over two years instead
of one.
</P>
<P>
   They could be interested if the right player were released
elsewhere, particularly if a wide receiver with deep speed and/or
size _ and modest price tag _ became available.
</P>
<P>
   Few, if any, projected cuts by other teams meet those criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Passing camp, not mandatory but strongly encouraged, begins June
14. ... Right offensive tackle Ephraim Salaam, who began last
season at 290 pounds, now weighs 310 and is noticeably thicker from
neck to waist. ... Two-year veteran safety Chris Bayne signed a
$325,000 contract. ... The Falcons are now a Nike team, having
switched from wearing Reebok shoes and apparel. Tuggle still wears
Reeboks because he has a contract with the company. ... With the
Falcon Inn hotel closed, rookies are living at a hotel next to
Gwinnett Place Mall. ... Ninety-eight percent of last year's 29,715
season-ticket holders have renewed, and the team has sold about
8,200 new season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
