<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INSIDE THE NFL NOTEBOOK
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The date talent-needy teams are waiting for, June 1, arrives
Tuesday and personnel directors leaguewide will be scouring the
waiver wire for players cut loose by clubs in desperate need of
salary-cap relief. Among those looking hardest will be New Orleans
team president Bill Kuharich. The Saints had a one-man draft _
tailback Ricky Williams _ and signed just one veteran of note,
guard Wally Williams, as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got about half the teams in the league with less than
$1 million (in cap room), so there are going to have to be some
veterans coming free,'' Kuharich said at a league meeting here last
week. ``We're hoping we can find a couple guys who will help us.''
</P>
<P>
   While speculation persists that Deion Sanders will be released,
Dallas owner Jerry Jones is apt to take a few more weeks to
evaluate the cornerback's rehabilitation from toe surgery. Several
veterans who will be cut _ QB John Elway (Denver), OT Jeff Criswell
(Kansas City) and DE Chris Doleman (San Francisco) _ already have
announced retirement plans. So, while Kuharich seems convinced
there will be some quality in the post-June 1 market, others insist
it probably will be no better than in past years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year at this time, people act like flood gates are going
to open,'' New York Giants GM Ernie Accorsi said. ``But it's
usually more like a trickle.''
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: The list
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at veterans who could be released or asked to
accept pay reductions in coming weeks: FB Kimble Anders (Kansas
City), OT Harris Barton (San Francisco), RB Mario Bates (Arizona),
WR Billy Davis (Dallas), DT Reuben Davis (San Diego), OT Andy Heck
(Chicago), OG Corbin Lacina (Carolina), LB Dixon Edwards
(Minnesota), CB Deon Figures (Jacksonville), LB Ken Harvey
(Washington), DT Marcus Jones (Tampa Bay), WR James McKnight
(Seattle), OT Zefross Moss (New England), WR Mike Pritchard
(Seattle), CB Thomas Randolph (Cincinnati), DE Neil Smith (Denver),
OT Jamain Stephens (Pittsburgh), FB Nicky Sualua (Dallas), CB Dave
Thomas (Jacksonville), RB Harvey Williams (Oakland), LB James
Willis (Philadelphia), FS Tito Wooten (Giants) and SS Toby Wright
(St. Louis).
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: The Deion watch
</P>
<P>
   Last week's report by Chris Mortensen that the Falcons could be
interested in Sanders if he's cut was more than speculation by
ESPN's crack NFL insider. Agent Eugene Parker noted last week that
it ``would be extremely premature'' to discuss options. ``He's
still in Dallas, and the team hasn't given us permission to talk
with interested (franchises),'' Parker said. But Sanders still owns
a home here, along with a tract of land in Lawrenceville, and the
relationship between him and Falcons president Taylor Smith is
solid. Also, Parker represents Atlanta's other corner, Ray
Buchanan, and thinks that a more mature Sanders would be a smash
here.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead: Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   Still seeking a reliable deep threat, Baltimore coach Brian
Billick talked with former boss Dennis Green about a deal for
Vikings wideout Jake Reed. Billick was told that Reed, thought to
be expendable with the emergence of Randy Moss, isn't available.
... Scratch Tennessee from the teams interested in tailback
Lawrence Phillips, who continues to lead the NFL Europe League in
rushing. GM Floyd Reese would like him as a backup to Eddie George
but probably can't convince owner Bud Adams that Phillips is worth
the risk. Reese fought a similar losing battle with Adams when he
wanted to sign free agent linebacker Jamir Miller, a two-time
offender of the league's substance abuse policy. Marco ColemanMike
Nolan ... Zefross MossBruce ArmstrongAntwan Edwards Former Alabama
corner Antonio Langhamand guard Jim PyneChris PalmerDale Carter
Darrien Gordon Eric Brown Steve AtwaterTyrone BraxtonDarrius
Johnson George Coghill Ray CrockettSubhead: Passing fancyJimmy
Johnson Craig EricksonDamon HuardJim DruckenmillerSteve
StenstromBill Walsh Neil O'DonnellDave KriegSteve McNairBobb
McKittrick Fritz Shurmur was diagnosed last week during a routine
physical. The 24-year veteran assistant returned to his home in
Green Bay and is expected to undergo lengthy treatment.
McKittrick's situation is believed to be grave. Doctors canceled a
liver transplant Monday when they discovered cancer had spread from
his bile duct.
</P>
