<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-ART-     05-29 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH AILING EWING, THE SPIRIT IS WILLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing is as stubborn as a grass stain on white linen. As
he marched defiantly down a set of stairs leading from the practice
floor to a locker room last week, he shook his head ``no'' like a
toddler to every question floating in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   He was not in the mood to give in; he never is. For the 14 years
Ewing has been in the frustrating pursuit of an elusive National
Basketball Association championship, this inflexibility has
sustained his confidence through errant finger rolls and Michael
Jordan's reign.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 12 months, this quality has saved him from breaking
beneath the most difficult year of his career. The year has seen
him rising from each physical and personal wound like the star of a
horror movie, surviving to stagger to a dramatic ending that could
make everything worthwhile. Now, seemingly without warning, a
Knicks team recently labeled least likely to succeed will tip off
Game 1 of the Eastern Conference final series with Indiana Sunday
at Market Square Arena.
</P>
<P>
   One more chance for Ewing. One more try at posting up the ghosts
that have defended him well over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never my last chance,'' a typically adamant Ewing barked
out with a smile as he crossed the threshold of the Knicks weight
room. ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be his last chance in a Knick uniform, though. If there
is failure, there could be an opening for Phil Jackson's arrival to
replace Jeff Van Gundy as coach. Ewing wants no part of this
transition, and has made it clear that he would like to be traded
if it happens, preferably to some place warm for his old bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miami,'' Ewing said recently. ``I'm moving to Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned this remote option with a wide grin, as if
tantalized by the thought of palm trees and ocean breezes. But
those closest to this most aloof of superstars, the ones who
understand his loyalty to Van Gundy and his distaste for Jackson,
take him seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he says to me that he won't play for Phil, he's not
smiling and he's not joking,'' said Herb Williams, Ewing's
long-time friend and teammate. ``He's for real. He's not budging.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Ewing to the core. When many feared he would never find
his touch again, after a wrist injury that doctors said they had
seen only in car accident victims, Ewing made a gallant but futile
return last May in Indiana for Game 2 of the Knicks' second-round
series. He shot 3-for-11, and scored 10 points in 27 laborious
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to go out, have a great game and score
50,'' Ewing said at the time, confident as always.
</P>
<P>
   This unwavering attitude helped him push through the tedium of
rehabilitation and lead him to where he is now, with excellent
range of motion in his wrist and the return of his touch. But just
when the wrist began to flick smoothly, his legs failed him in
March. As he prepares to face Indiana's towering Rik Smits _ the
man of a thousand shot fakes _ Ewing's lateral movement will be
limited by a sore left Achilles' tendon. The injury did not stop
him from putting on a dominating performance in Game 5 of the
Knicks' first-round victory over Miami, or an endless array of
jumpers over Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one expected him to come back from his wrist injury,''
Williams said. ``Everyone thought it was career-ending. He started
to feel good, and then the Achilles' injury came. Mentally, he went
back down a little bit. And he may still be down. I think he's just
pushing his way through it right now because he has to.''
</P>
<P>
   For a fleeting moment, that desire to push ahead was flat at the
start of the season. His best friend, John Starks, had just been
traded for Latrell Sprewell, and his protector, Charles Oakley, had
been cast away as well. There was talk about his role diminishing,
and the need for his ego to be submerged.
</P>
<P>
   All of this on the heels of a summer and fall spent in the
thankless role of union president. He took an unpopular stand,
endured the heat for suggesting players were ``fighting for our
livelihood,'' but was left out of the eleventh-hour meeting that
ended in an agreement he did not support.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything else, he was upset at how things turned
out,'' said Williams, an officer in the union. ``He thought we
should have held together as a body and been a lot stronger. But
some of the players started to rattle, and he pretty much had to do
some things he didn't agree with. I don't think he knew that job
was going to be as tough as it was. He didn't know it would be so
draining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you looked around, there was a meeting and then no
meeting. Or we thought we were making progress, and we weren't
making progress. It was his first time going through anything like
that. He was disappointed when all was said and done.''
</P>
<P>
   When the vote was over, and the new proposal was put in place in
mid-January, Ewing stood outside a Manhattan office amid the snow
flurries looking weary and overweight. In a matter of a few days,
he had to gather himself and go to training camp. His conditioning
was poor, his wrist was stiff and his mind was still on the
lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season came, and he just wasn't there,'' said Don Chaney,
the assistant coach who shoots with Ewing every day. ``He'd been
through a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   There was still more to come. After 14 years as the team's major
name, Ewing had to make the glacial movement to auxiliary star. He
is still capable of dominating a game _ and may have to against the
Pacers to give the Knicks a chance _ but more often than not he is
the looming figure spotting up for 15-foot jumpers. He is the one
trailing the fast break for the sleek, redesigned Knicks, the one
focusing on the rebound. It's just another adjustment he has had to
make over a difficult 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been through the grind, the wringer, I should say,''
Chaney said. ``There was the wrist, the focus on him as president
during the lockout, the pressure of whether he is still the `Man'
to carry the team; is it Allan Houston or is it Latrell Sprewell
now? Then another injury after last year, and the compressed
season. It takes a big man to stay afloat through all that. And he
has.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is not looking for sympathy as an amendment to his
legacy. Those who know him say this most private of players wants
to be accepted by the public, longs to be embraced fully by New
York, but understands why there's been a reluctance to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The championship,'' Williams said. ``He knows that embrace
won't come until he wins the title. Why do you think he wants it so
badly? What people don't understand is that he doesn't care what
his role is, and he doesn't care how much pain it takes to get
there, he just wants to win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you want to win a championship, you'll put your body and
life through anything. I think that is still what's burning in the
back of his mind. He's still got something to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   He's still stubborn enough to keep trying after 14 years, a span
capped by a tumultuous 12-month span that led him back for another
attempt _ whether it's his last or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance,'' Ewing said. ``Another chance. That's all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
