<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 FRIENDS, STARS IN COLLEGE, ARE ROLE PLAYERS IN THE SEMIFINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   All three were taken in the first round of the 1991 draft, and
all asked to wear No. 2 jerseys with their new teams. They also
entered the NBA after a bitter Final Four experience.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after Larry Johnson, Stacey Augmon and Greg Anthony
left the University of Nevada-Las Vegas, the three have, in a way,
returned to the national semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   When they were humbled by Duke in 1991, Johnson, Augmon and
Anthony were stars on the nation's most explosive team. This time,
they come as role players: Johnson a starter at small forward with
the Knicks, and Augmon and Anthony coming off the bench in
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the first pick in the draft and the eventual rookie of
the year, thrived in Charlotte before souring on the franchise and
being traded to the Knicks. His selflessness and leadership are big
reasons they are in the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Augmon, taken ninth by Atlanta, never developed offensively. But
he has stayed in the league because of his ability to change games
with his defensive tenacity and wingspan.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony, the former Knick and the 12th pick, was a large part of
Portland's Western Conference semifinals victory over Utah. He
hounded John Stockton and Howard Eisley, exerting full-court
pressure on the Jazz guards and not allowing Utah to get set
offensively until about 10 seconds had expired on the shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   UNLV had a reputation as a fun-loving, carefree program when
they attended the school, and Johnson, Augmon and Anthony have all
remained friends. If the Knicks and Trail Blazers somehow reach the
finals, pity the poor hotel clerk who has to tell them to keep it
down.
</P>
<P>
   Draft Talk ... and Rumors
</P>
<P>
   It's about six months early to forecast an NBA champion for the
millennium, but the Charlotte Hornets almost make you want to go
out on that limb.
</P>
<P>
   The team has apparently set its sights on Steve Francis with the
No. pick in the draft, opting for the skywalking Maryland guard
instead of players like Corey Maggette and Elton Brand of Duke and
Lamar Odom of Rhode Island, who could be taken before the Hornets
choose.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago has the No. pick and is said to be leaning toward
Maggette. There is also talk that the Bulls are interested in Miami
University's Wally Szczerbiak, perhaps enough that they would make
a trade in which they use the No.1 pick for another team, which
would then pick Szczerbiak for the Bulls. Vancouver has the No.2
selection.
</P>
<P>
   If Francis is Charlotte's choice, he will join a potent Hornets
roster that features Eddie Jones, Anthony Mason, Derrick Coleman, a
rejuvenated Elden Campbell, David Wesley and Bobby Phills.
</P>
<P>
   Throw Francis into the mix and you have one of the most athletic
teams in the league, with a nice blend of youth and experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a part of me that didn't want to leave L.A. because
of all the talent and youth we had,'' said Jones, who was traded by
the Lakers to Charlotte along with Campbell at the trading deadline
this season. ``But then I started realizing what we have here, all
the building blocks for something special. You had that in L.A.,
too, but the rumors just got to me after a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just a good situation for me. If you look down the
road in a couple of years, it's going to be a good situation for
everyone here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Makes His Point
</P>
<P>
   To fill their void at point guard since 1992, the Knicks have
tried six-month stopgaps, long-term contracts and even Gary Grant.
And while Charlie Ward and Chris Childs have combined to bring
respectability to the position, little the Knicks have done has
worked since the day they got rid of Mark Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   He does not gloat anymore, or chastise the team he grew up with
for trading him. Jackson merely goes about his job of leading the
Indiana Pacers toward the NBA finals, the job that resumes Sunday
in Indianapolis in the Eastern Conference championship series
against the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   He is not fast, and he cannot jump high. Along with John
Stockton, he is merely the last of a dying breed: the pass-first
point guard who worries about his own points last.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at me and you don't see anything special,'' Jackson
said recently. ``I pass the ball, but there's nothing that's going
to knock you out. But later you look back and say, `Hey, when this
guy's on the floor, his team is a better team.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was traded to the Clippers in 1992 for Doc Rivers and
Charles Smith, two players who helped the Knicks return to
prominence in the early 1990s. The Pacers traded him once, too. But
in one of the great moves of the last decade, the team's president,
Donnie Walsh, realized he had erred, swallowed his pride and
reacquired Jackson from Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing once called Jackson his favorite teammate, a
player who could deliver the ball to his teammates at just the
right moment as they were streaking toward the basket.
</P>
<P>
   His defensive liabilities aside, Jackson's gift of impeccable
court sense never received its due in New York until all the
helter-skelter play at the point after he was traded.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report in The Indianapolis Star, after the Pacers
lost to the Bulls in the conference finals last season, Jackson was
invited to Coach Larry Bird's house to watch one of the
Utah-Chicago games. As they march toward the finals together, the
two have formed a strong bond built on mutual ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was limited as a player, but he got the most out of his
ability with heart and desire,'' Jackson said of Bird. ``He saw a
poor man's version of that in me _ a guy who's limited, who's
supposed to not be able to play defense. But for some reason, I was
still getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven years after he was traded.
</P>
<P>
   Don't Expect Van Gundy Back
</P>
<P>
   A hunch: No matter how far the Knicks advance in the playoffs,
Jeff Van Gundy will not return as the Knicks' coach.
</P>
<P>
   It has little to do with Dave Checketts' cloak-and-dagger
dealings with Phil Jackson, Van Gundy's off-the-court disagreements
with Ernie Grunfeld or even the most quantifiable reason of all:
his winning percentage as Knicks coach.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling comes from the notion that most 10-year employees
move on when they don't feel that their bosses value their loyalty
enough to trust them through hard times.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of Madison Square Garden executives, Van Gundy is
still very much the mail-room clerk who just happened to be in the
right place at the right time. Even if he were to be rewarded with
a more lucrative, multiyear, multimillion-dollar contract after the
season, Van Gundy's tenure on the firing line would begin all over
again if, say, the Knicks were 10-8 in December.
</P>
<P>
   And as Van Gundy may have found out this season, no amount of
money is worth that grief.
</P>
<P>
   If he were Pat Riley or Lenny Wilkens, Van Gundy would have been
labeled a visionary for stubbornly insisting that Latrell Sprewell
come off the bench and Marcus Camby earn his minutes _ hard
decisions that the players finally embraced and that have paid off.
Instead, he is portrayed as the petty coach who's been burying his
talent to spite the former general manager.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Van Gundy became a Garden shark for a
couple of weeks this season, regretfully swimming in management's
cesspool to get his points across instead of merely coaching the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he doesn't trust his bosses, and they don't trust him. It
would not be surprising if management and the coach went their
separate ways for good after this thrilling playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this league, coaches always take the brunt of everything,''
Larry Bird, the Indiana coach, said last week. ``If your team is
not doing well, that's part of the game. I'm sure Jeff, if he's not
in New York next year, he'll be somewhere. He's a fine coach. He's
a very good coach. He'll survive it.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be more interesting to see the Knicks survive without
him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
