</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-MILLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS' MILLER ENJOYS PLAYING THE ROLE OF THE NBA VILLAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ In Salt Lake City last week, Cheryl Miller
confronted a woman who kept directing profanities toward her during
the Western Conference semifinals between the Utah Jazz and the
Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   The insults had nothing to do with her skills as a courtside
reporter for TNT or as a coach in the Women's National Basketball
Association. They had everything to do with her brother, the lanky
and loquacious Indiana Pacers guard who plays many miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just wouldn't stop,'' Cheryl Miller said. ``The second
time she started in on Reggie, I couldn't handle it anymore. I
finally went over and said: `What is your problem? You know what
most people would do to you if you insulted their family member?' I
told her I'm saving her life right now by letting her know that.
Usually, I don't mind some of the stuff. But sometimes, they just
go too far. There's a fine line.''
</P>
<P>
   The Delta Center in May. Madison Square Garden in June. It does
not matter where or when he plays, or even whether he is playing.
Reggie Miller is an equal-opportunity villain, despised from coast
to coast for the last 12 seasons. He has been enflaming passions in
the National Basketball Association for nearly that long, running
his mouth while running through screens and delivering devastating
3-pointers in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is he more reviled than in New York, whose basketball
team he will face, and have a chance to shoot down, for the fifth
time in the last seven postseasons beginning Sunday at Market
Square Arena. In Game 1 of the Eastern Conference finals, the man
who authored ``I Love Being the Enemy'' will return to his favorite
role, again assuming his alter ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do love it,'' Miller said earlier this week after a Pacer
practice. ``Everyone can't be applauded or the fan favorite. Not
everyone can be Kobe or Michael Jordan _ the smile, the glitter and
the commercials. There has to be some guys that wear black hats. I
just happen to relish in it. I just happen to like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys wear black hats and that's not their persona. I
think Karl wears a black hat, but he wants people to believe he's a
good guy,'' Miller said of Karl Malone. ``I'm a black hat and I
don't care what people think. You don't have to like me as long as
you respect me. That's all I ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his bravado, Miller has been uncharacteristically
subdued before the conference finals, saying little to intensify
the Knick-Pacer rivalry. After Game 7 losses to the Bulls in 1995
and the Magic in 1998 prevented his team from making its first NBA
finals appearance, he seems to understand his best opportunity to
win a title is near.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird, the Indiana coach, regulated his minutes during the
regular season, and Miller missed his share of potential
game-winners. But he has returned to the cocksure marksman of
playoffs past in the last three weeks, dropping in knifing jump
shots and taking off on scoring binges for several minutes at the
ends of games against Milwaukee in the first round and Philadelphia
in the second.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, it's the same old Reggie _ poised to flap his gums
and make teams that sag off him pay. But in other areas of his
life, a more reserved and private Miller is evolving.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Marita, lost their dream home to arson two
years ago. Though they had not yet moved into the three-story,
14,000-square foot lakefront house in the city's Geist area, it
contained many of their possessions when it burned down on May 15,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   With no suspects or leads, the fire is still under
investigation. Among the losses were Marita's wedding ring and
almost all of Miller's memorabilia from his playing days. Though
Marita, a model, was away in California, Reggie had considered
sleeping in the house the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I told him I was moving out and not coming back
to Indianapolis,'' said Marita. ``It was traumatic. You wonder who
would do that. You start looking in the rearview mirror, wondering
if someone is following you. That little inkling of concern is
still there for me. It's why I have trouble living here. I feel if
you don't want me there, I don't want to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cheryl Miller: ``I remember the night it happened, and he
called me. His exact words were: `Cheryl _ it's gone. It's all
gone.' I just told him, `The main thing is, you're here.' There's
not a lot you can say because it's such a violation.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two years, Reggie Miller began to gain
perspective. Slowly, copies of the memorabilila began filtering in.
``Karl and Charles sent me back a copy of a behind-the-scenes
videotape I had made at the Olympics,'' Miller said, referring to
Karl Malone and Charles Barkley. ``They also sent some autographed
shirts and things.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's scary, because the person who did that is still
out there. I can take that one of two ways. That could have been an
attempt on my wife's life, my life. Was it a random hit because
they didn't know? I'm a little bit better now. The first year, I
was skeptical of everyone trust-wise. I've gotten a little bit
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the ashes emerged a charity sponsored by Miller. Three
weeks ago, he was host to an inaugural celebrity bowling party in
Indianapolis. The proceeds benefited a children's burn unit and two
burn camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't have the means to wait for the insurance
company after they've lost everything, so with that in mind we
started the foundation to help families that lose everything in a
fire _ more so kids that were ever burned in a fire,'' Miller said.
``It's definitely given me perspective about the losses we
suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   If the game was an emotional outlet before, it became even more
cathartic after the fire. At least on the basketball court, he
could control the environment around him. It's part of the reason
why his confidence is unmatched and he has essentially inherited
the role of the best clutch player in the game.
</P>
<P>
   At age 33, a more reserved and resilient Miller prepares for
another contentious series against the city and the team that loves
to hate him _ a gunner of great renown still looking to shoot the
Knicks down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like a Broadway play coming to New York,'' he
said. ``It's going to be electrifying going there. By already
hearing the chants on TV and everyone calling and saying, `Hey,
they really want you.' The papers are saying it's Miller time. I'm
really gearing up for it. The waiting is killing me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Miller added: ``The bigger the hatred, the more Reggie
thrives. If New York wants to do themselves any good, shut up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
