A6075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRESTLING-HART-FAMILY     05-29 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-HART-FAMILY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEIR LIFE WAS PRO WRESTLING, AND ONE OF THEM DIED FOR IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By TOM KEYSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost any Canadian who grew up during the 1950s or 1960s
remembers at least one otherwise dignified old gentleman _ a
friend's grandfather, perhaps _ who spent Saturday afternoons
feinting and jabbing at his television screen.
</P>
<P>
   The old man would have been a true believer whose heroes and
villains were nicknamed Bulldog, the Giant, the Butcher and the
Assassin. They starred in a TV morality play and cult ritual known
as ``Big Time Wrestling.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoted by the Calgary, Alberta, wrestler Stu Hart and his
Bronx-born wife, Helen, the shows _ later reborn as ``Stampede
Wrestling'' _ were syndicated around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   And a certain old gent would sooner have absorbed a body slam
from Whipper Billy Watson than skip an episode. Or admit to
anything dubious about the shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid, I remember Archie the Stomper mauling my dad in the
ring,'' said Bret ``the Hitman'' Hart, one of a dozen children of
Stu and Helen Hart and the elder brother of Owen Hart, who died on
May 23 in Kansas City after falling more than 50 feet while being
lowered onto a World Wrestling Federation stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then later, I'd see Archie the Stomper come to get his check,
and hug my mom,'' said Bret, a former WWF wrestler who is now a
star of Ted Turner's rival World Championship Wrestling. ``I
couldn't figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harts _ 84-year-old Stu, Helen, their 10 surviving children
and 34 grandchildren _ are the uncrowned first family of North
American wrestling. They remain in shock on the eve of funeral
services for the youngest of the children, Owen, 34, who leaves a
widow, Martha, and two children.
</P>
<P>
   Although Monday's service is private, thousands of mourners are
expected to surround the chapel in Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Glossy names from pro wrestling will be there, too _ maybe even
Vince McMahon, the WWF owner, against whom the Harts harbor a
grudge. ``I have hard feelings towards the WWF, because they
continued the show after Owen's death,'' said Bret, 42. ``It was
very cold-blooded.''
</P>
<P>
   Bret Hart, a premier drawing card in professional wrestling, is
that rare creature, a world-famous Canadian. In select circles,
he's better known than hockey's Wayne Gretzky or the singer Celine
Dion.
</P>
<P>
   But in the days since the death, he, his mother and his sisters
have spoken candidly, sometimes bitterly, of the theatrical
``sport'' which has dominated Hart family life since Helen and Stu
paid $50,000 Canadian for ``Big Time Wrestling'' in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   It's a game which several Harts have long regarded with mixed
emotions. ``When we were first married, I'd say, `Stu, how long are
we going to stay in this business?' and he'd say, `About two
years,''' recalled the former Helen Smith, born in the Bronx and
raised on Long Island. ``Twenty years later, I said, `Stu, we're
still in it,''' said Helen, who spent 45 years keeping the books
for ``Stampede Wrestling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother hates the wrestling business,'' said Alison, one of
four Hart daughters. ``We've all been uncomfortable with the way
the business was going.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen was horrified when WWF dream weavers created a story line
which required that Bret, a Civil War buff, incorporate
anti-American elements into his stage persona.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me, and said, `Mom, I hate to tell you. They want me
to turn against the United States.' I said, `Oh, God.' I was so
upset,'' Helen said. ``I still stand up when I hear either national
anthem.''
</P>
<P>
   Then WWF writers dreamed up bouts between Bret, an established
star, and his younger brother Owen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that broke my heart, too,'' said Helen, who couldn't bring
herself to watch. ``Bret and Owen both called me about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Owen saw the Hart-to-Hart battles as a chance to vault
into the big money, and his brother felt obliged to help. The
brothers fought for the WWF title in 1994, later reprising the act
in Italy, France and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Helen, sports-minded but never a wrestling fan, met Stu, a
Canadian amateur champion, during a wrestling circuit stopover in
New York. They married on New Year's Eve, 1947.
</P>
<P>
   As the years passed, the Harts' rambling Calgary home served as
hotel, dining lounge and watering hole of choice for an eccentric
parade of large, aggressive men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very bizarre childhood,'' Bret Hart said. ``When he was
little, I remember Owen was terrified of Bull Ramos. Bring up that
name, and Owen would go right to bed.''
</P>
<P>
   There was Killer Kowalski, the vegetarian wrestler who wolfed
salad from the Harts' 10-gallon silver bowl. There was Andre the
Giant, who threw furniture, and the Cuban Assassin, who pulled a
shiv.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most were more gentle than you'd think,'' said Helen, who
remembers discussing books and folding diapers with the hulking
Ivan Kalmikoff.
</P>
<P>
   Taught by their father, the eight Hart sons learned to wrestle
in the ``dungeon,'' a ring in the basement of the twin-gabled, red
brick home. Then they fought to defend the integrity of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be at school, taking my shirt off to defend wrestling
again, at the drop of a hat,'' Bret said, laughing. ``While I was
doing it, I'd ask myself why.''
</P>
<P>
   As teen-agers, both Bret and Owen were provincial high school
wrestling champs. But they swore they would never stoop to the pro
ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, positively, I will not be a wrestler,'' Bret
remembers insisting. ``My dad was on the road all the time, and we
missed him. We both never wanted to be away like that, but in the
end, that's all we ever did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just found me,'' Bret says of the career that has made him
a wealthy man. ``Same with Owen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hitman'' has never denied that pro bouts are tightly
scripted and choreographed, but he considers himself an
accomplished actor-athlete, a cross between Robert De Niro and Cal
Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw `Shakespeare in Love,' how the Elizabethan actors and
stagehands set up the stage and the set,'' Bret said. ``It sounds
bizarre, but wrestling's much like that.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``When Owen got the upset victory over me in
Wrestlemania, it was great drama, we took pride in it. Owen and I
created things nobody saw before. No words. Just the intensity in
facial expressions, a physical contest.''
</P>
<P>
   But before Owen's death, both brothers worried that pro
wrestling _ once a relatively harmless diversion, with relatively
harmless stars _ had reached perverse new lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have trouble with someone pointing at his crotch for two
hours,'' Bret said. ``There's no family aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   His sister Alison, speaking of the WWF and its fans, said:
``These people are absolutely desensitized. It would be nice for me
to say Owen's death could make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it would be like telling you Snow White really did marry a
prince, and she lives down the road. But the prince is gone _ our
prince.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
