<HEADER>
A6083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN     05-29 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE MONUMENT WHERE JOE LOUIS TRAINED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note; no other changes.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMPTON LAKES, N.J. _ When Joe Louis was the heavyweight
champion, he put this leafy little town on the map.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in the Pacific during the war,'' Russ Pagana, a
retired contractor, was saying, ``guys would ask me where I was
from. When I'd say, Pompton Lakes, N.J., they'd say, `Yeah, that's
where Joe Louis trains.'''
</P>
<P>
   And now the town has put Joe Louis on a monument.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Anthony Sgobba in glossy Italian black granite, Joe
Louis' life-size likeness is on a monument dedicated here yesterday
in what is now Joe Louis Memorial Park next to the Elks Lodge No.
1895, a left jab away from what was Doc Bier's training camp, where
Louis prepared to knock out Max Schmeling and Billy Conn (twice).
</P>
<P>
   ``As kids, we'd watch Joe train on Sunday,'' Pagana recalled,
``then we'd go to the movies at the Colonial theater on Saturday
and watch the Movietone news of what we had watched.''
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, Louis would go to the movies, too. If a few kids
were standing around outside, he'd tell the ticket-taker, ``Let `em
in. I'll take care of it.'' If the kids were standing around
outside the ice-cream parlor, he bought cones. And the Pompton
Lakes kids never had to pay to watch him train.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he did his roadwork,'' said Howard Ball, a former editor
of the local Suburban Trend newspaper, ``he'd stop to talk to my
grandmother in her rocking chair on our porch. I'd peek through the
window to see him.''
</P>
<P>
   After a local resident died in 1935 and before an ambulance
arrived from a nearby town, Louis boxed an exhibition that raised
$2,600 to buy Pompton Lakes its own white Packard ambulance. He
raised $2,000 to help build a police communications tower.
</P>
<P>
   And every so often, Lou Duva, then a teen-ager in nearby
Paterson, hitch-hiked here to watch the champion train.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody trained like Joe Louis,'' recalled Duva, the
77-year-old Hall of Fame trainer. ``He always wore white knit
trunks with a white tank top, black boxing shoes and white socks.
He was all business. On the weekends, there'd be as many as 5,000
people around the outdoor ring under the trees next to the big
house where he and his sparring partners lived.''
</P>
<P>
   For a big fight now, boxers don't train like that. They stay in
casino-hotels now. They spar in glitzy ballrooms with chandeliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now they all have their entourages,'' Duva said with a
smirk. ``Every lawyer, every accountant, every hustler is hanging
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Duva and Pompton Lakes Police Chief Al Ekkers were the
fund-raising co-chairmen for the Joe Louis Memorial Park and
monument.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing will probably cost $80,000 before we're
through,'' Duva said. ``We've raised a lot already, but I'll put up
whatever we need to finish it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming up here to see Joe Louis train is where I learned to
watch trainers train fighters,'' he said. ``I never learned
anything from fighters. I learned it all from the trainers.''
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1923, boxers began coming to the barracks-like house
next to the home of Dr. Joseph Bier, an eye-ear-nose-and-throat
specialist who operated what he called a Health Farm on the shore
of Pompton Lake in this tiny town of 3,000 in the woods and lakes
of northern Passaic County. The population is now 11,500.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best boxing names of that era trained here _ Benny
Leonard, Harry Greb, Pancho Villa, Ace Hudkins, Tony Canzoneri,
Jimmy McLarnin, Jackie (Kid) Berg, Lou Brouillard, and Primo
Carnera.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1935, when Louis was about to come here to train for his
first fight in New York, against Primo Carnera, at least one
resident objected to the presence of a black fighter along with
John Roxborough, a black manager, and Jack Blackburn, a black
trainer. Doc Bier never blinked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've rented the place,'' Doc said, ``and they'll be here.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of Louis' fights in New York, they returned here. He
considered Pompton Lakes his ``lucky camp,'' especially after he
trained at Lakewood, N.J., before being knocked out by Max
Schmeling in the 12th round at Yankee Stadium in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Before his 1938 title defense against Schmeling at Yankee
Stadium, Louis trained here, then knocked out Schmeling in 2
minutes, 4 seconds of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great place this would be for a training camp,'' Lou
Duva was saying now. ``That house over there, that's where Doc Bier
lived. I'd like to buy that house and use it as a training camp for
some of my young fighters. Put up an outdoor ring like they had
when Joe Louis was here.''
</P>
<P>
   And it would be only a left jab away from the Joe Louis
monument.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6084 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-TROUT-NYT &LR;      05-29 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-TROUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE BANKS OF THE DELAWARE, A REASON TO BELIEVE
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By PETE BODO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LORDVILLE, N.Y. _ We sloshed through the brook, in the cool
darkness of the tunnel beneath the railroad tracks, and emerged in
brilliant sunshine on the banks of the Delaware River. The ash and
cherry trees on the mountainside opposite us were not yet leafed
out. Their pale green buds appeared supercharged, nearly
fluorescent, in striking contrast to the opaque black surface of
the river at this place called Bouchoux Brook.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Franklin and I were joined by Frank Rodriguez, a mutual
friend from Portland, Ore., who had come east to fish with us. As
he beheld the Delaware for the first time, Frank remarked, ``This
is something I could believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   I met Frank nearly 20 years ago on the banks of a different
river, the rugged Deschutes in Oregon. I was communing with nature
in my own ecologically incorrect way, living out of a rented Ford
Taurus station wagon under a pile of fishing gear, books and empty
potato chip bags. Frank was the squared-away guy with the Volvo
wagon and a real folding chair and cookstove encamped 50 yards from
me. Being the only two people around, we got to talking.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that in a few days, Frank would be hooking up in
Montana with my friend Richard, a New Yorker, whom he had met the
previous summer on the Henry's Fork of the Snake River in Idaho.
Richard and Frank have camped and fished together out West for a
month every summer since then.
</P>
<P>
   In angling, the ties that bind are often rivers. As we walked up
the gravel bar, I pointed out a distinct feature of our river in
the spring, the bathtub-sized mounds of small stones built by
spawning lamprey eels. As far as sex appeal goes, lampreys are
right up there with moray eels. But the care and precision with
which they build their spawning nests is touching.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 seconds later, Frank said, ``Thank you, Peter.''
</P>
<P>
   I wondered what he was thanking me for, and realized it was
about the lamprey nests. It was a very Frank thing to do, and it
made me wish I saw him more often.
</P>
<P>
   Now and then, a March brown mayfly emerged from the edge of the
river and delicately spun away, upward, but there weren't enough
bugs to get the trout rising. So Richard and I set about making a
small fire. We were making one of our simple shore lunches in
Frank's honor. We cut three sticks from a maple sapling for cooking
the hot dogs. I put the unshucked corn at the edge of the fire. The
menu is always the same.
</P>
<P>
   Frank came back from the river with the cool beers. When I last
saw him, on the Missouri River in Montana last July, I noticed that
he wore a tiny white ribbon embroidered with red hearts pinned to
his vest. I remarked on it this time, and Frank said, ``Laura gave
it to me 15 years ago, for the first trout season after we started
dating.''
</P>
<P>
   I remembered meeting Laura in Portland one year. She was a
quiet, delicate, friendly woman. I was sad to learn that she and
Frank divorced about a year ago, but was cheered to see that the
ribbon had survived half a dozen fishing vests, and that Frank
still wore it.
</P>
<P>
   A trout rose about 40 yards out in the river, a silver pockmark
on the dark water. Nobody felt like fishing for it. Frank told us
about the Mankind Project, a movement to which he belongs, which
seeks to make men better and happier for all the right reasons and
in all the right ways. A stiff breeze kicked up out of the south,
and the air smelled of hemlocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this, here's one of our March brown nymphs,'' Richard
said. Frank and Richard squatted at the river's edge, peering at
the underside of the wet rock in Richard's hand. ``They migrate to
the shoreline before hatching, for survival reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank hunched further over, observing, ``They look a lot like
our western gray drakes, and they're the same size.''
</P>
<P>
   The men continued to talk about the bugs. The scene had been
enacted on dozens of rivers, in various parts of the country, on
occasions too numerous to count. It never gets old, and there's
something a little goofy about it. Common interest is the flexible
bond of a lasting angling friendship. It may be better glue than
having gone to school together, or even emotional empathies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you go out upstream of that rock and fish down along
that foam line?'' Richard suggested to Frank a while later. ``It
would be a good place to prospect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Frank replied. ``I wouldn't fish it that
way in this wind. Hey, Richie, I just saw a rise; it was a big
head, over near the far bank.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, a few fish were beginning to show. We waded out,
and soon all three of us were casting. A giant rainbow trout
engulfed my fly just 12 feet in front of me, leaped furiously and
snapped my fine 5x tippet before I understood quite what was
happening. Some good things develop slowly. Others are here and
gone in the blink of an eye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
