A6085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-INDY-500-NYT &LR;      05-29 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-500-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUYENDYK HOPES FOR A FAST FAREWELL AT INDY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ They know how to win, but just as important, most
champions know when to quit. Michael Jordan knew when it was time.
John Elway and Wayne Gretzky did. So now does Arie Luyendyk, who
will race around the Brickyard for the final time on Sunday, two
years after taking his second checkered flag at the Indianapolis
500.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk is leaving auto racing while still on top of his game.
At 45, his driving skills haven't eroded. His drive here last
Saturday, when he put his race car on the pole, proved that he
hasn't lost his skills. That qualifying effort showed his
competitors that Luyendyk, the Flying Dutchman, the 500 champion in
1990 and 1997, is ready to take flight once again. Driving the Fred
Treadway Racing G-Force-Aurora, Luyendyk is more than just a
sentimental favorite.
</P>
<P>
   So, why now?
</P>
<P>
   The thought of retiring first crossed his mind three years ago.
It was a crystal clear day here in May. Luyendyk was speeding
around the track during a routine practice session when the
trackside yellow caution lights began flashing. He pulled onto pit
lane. Scott Brayton, Luyendyk's close friend and former teammate,
had crashed at high speed into the Turn 2 wall after losing a tire.
Half an hour later, he was dead. At that moment, Luyendyk says, he
knew. He did not want to risk his life for a paycheck much longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now at my age, I decided I've had enough,'' said Luyendyk. ``I
believe I'm still competitive. And I think I would be two years
from now. But I don't want to find out that I've lost my reflexes
when I'm in the race car. I want to be ahead of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things change. You have different interests when you get
older. Now, on Sundays, I would like to be on my boat as much as
driving my race car.''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk's wife, Mieke, influenced his decision. She too was
devastated by Brayton's death. So before the 1996 500, Luyendyk
told her that he would retire if he won. He ran well, but was
caught up in a late wreck.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he told Mieke the same thing: He would quit if he won.
This time he did win, beating Scott Goodyear in the final lap, and
she reminded him of his promise. But he couldn't quit, he explained
to her. There were too many obligations to his team and sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk now is sorry he didn't quit. Last year was a bitter
one, as Luyendyk crashed five cars. His most serious crash came
during the International Race of Champions here May 1998 when he
spun, hit the wall and was pulled from the wreckage unconscious.
That accident cemented his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't been thinking about it much,'' Luyendyk said
on Friday when asked about his Indy car farewell. ``I've been
thinking mostly about going fast and being competitive. That's what
is really on my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Going fast has been on his mind at least since 1972, when he
began racing in Formula Vee series in the Netherlands. A year
later, he got his first victory, winning the Dutch Formula Ford
series. He won again in 1975 and continued winning championships on
small circuits in Europe until 1980, when he came to race in the
United States for the first time. In 1984, Luyendyk won the Bosch
Super Vee championship and made his Indy Car debut at Elkhart Lake,
Wis., where he finished eighth. The next May he was named rookie of
the year at his first Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk owns two Indy 500 qualifying records: 237.498 mph for a
single lap and an average of 236.986 mph for four laps, both set in
1996. He also holds the 500's average speed mark, 185.981 mph in
1990. He tops the list of money winners, having taken home more
than $5.2 million. He has seven Indy car victories in 166 starts
since making his American debut at Elkhart Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arie has had a wonderful career,'' said the driver Greg Ray.
``He's been a great spokesman for racing in general. He's a
gentleman. He races you clean on the track. He's very fast and he
certainly has that natural gift for the speedway. He's able to get
something out of the car that's not always there.''
</P>
<P>
   The city of Indianapolis has embraced Luyendyk. Last Thursday,
the final day of practice, was Arie Luyendyk Day, and Luyendyk,
long a fan favorite, was given a key to the city by Mayor Steve
Goldsmith.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's next for someone who seems to have everything?
</P>
<P>
   He's already a television commentator for Fox on its Indy Racing
League series. And he will work as a consultant with Fred Treadway
Racing when he is not coaching his 17-year-old son, Arie Jr., who
is a rising star on the Formula Ford series in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll race as long he wants to race,'' Luyendyk said,
referring to Arie Jr., the oldest of his four children. ``I won't
force him.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as no one forced him to quit. It is simply time. He was
given an ovation by the fans and the race crews when he drove down
pit lane after winning the pole last Saturday. Two days ago,
Goodyear, who lost to him in '97, presented him with a transparent
case, inside of which was the autographed driving gloves from every
driver in Sunday's race, one more item for his collection of racing
memorabilia at home in Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Known for his cool temperament and humility, Luyendyk hasn't
shown much emotion during the past week. But he knows when the
emotions will start flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the cool-down lap, I might take a long time to come around
so I can compose myself,'' he said with a sad smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
