<SLUG> BC-COMMERCIAL-REAL-810(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: THE MAKING OF THE CHRYSLER CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Tishman Speyer Properties acquired the
landmarked Chrysler Building, with its stainless-steel peak,
gargoyles and elaborate lobby, it also took possession of a far
less glamorous structure at the other end of the block on 42nd
Street, an office building with the address of 666 Third Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Chrysler building, which was built as a prestige
project from the start (and was part of a race in the early '30s to
build the world's tallest building), 666 Third Ave. was
relentlessly average, with a tiny lobby, plain brick walls and an
inefficient layout.
</P>
<P>
   Named the Kent Building after its former owner, the late Jack
Kent Cooke, the structure was generally seen as an annex to the
Chrysler Building. Indeed some tenants occupied space in both
buildings at lower levels on the 43rd Street side, although the
floor levels do not match.
</P>
<P>
   Although most attention focused on the Chrysler Building, the
purchase included the entire block between Lexington and Third
avenues and 42nd and 43rd streets, with some smaller buildings
occupying the midblock area on 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners decided that with suitable alterations they could
brand the entire block as the Chrysler Center, and promptly put up
signs proclaiming the new name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we could create a new neighborhood there, an
eastern anchor for the new 42nd Street,'' said Valerie Peltier, an
official of Tishman Speyer who is the project manager for the
Chrysler Center. Tishman Speyer officials say the budget for the
entire Chrysler Center project is on the order of $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Working with the architect Philip Johnson, company executives
decided to demolish the small midblock buildings, use some of the
air rights to add 130,000 square feet to the west side of what is
now being called the Chrysler East building, expand and embellish
the lobby and clad the entire building with a new metal and glass
facade.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining midblock space will be occupied by 85-foot-tall
triangular glass structures that Johnson calls trylons, that are
meant to evoke the distinctive shape of the top of the Chrysler
Building. Tishman Speyer officials say they expect to sign up a
first-class restaurant to occupy the space under the trylons.
</P>
<P>
   The addition to the east building was critical, said Ms.
Peltier. ``It was a side core building and it didn't work,'' she
said, referring to the section of a building that contains the
elevators, stairs and basic utilities that serve the adjacent
office space.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the addition to the western side of the building the
core area is now in the middle, and occupants of offices there can
walk easily from one side of a floor to another without bumping
into the core. Existing tenants have inquired about leasing space
in the new section of the building to unify their operations, said
Ms. Peltier, who is a daughter of Tishman Speyer's chief executive,
Jerry Speyer.
</P>
<P>
   The new space is column-free, so operations that require open
space, such as financial trading floors, can be accommodated.
</P>
<P>
   Although the project is far from complete, Tishman Speyer has
got an important vote of confidence. Credit Agricole Indosuez, a
French-based bank that is the product of the merger two years ago
of Credit Agricole and Banque Indosuez, is leaving two other
locations to occupy 130,000 square feet at Chrysler East.
</P>
<P>
   As a result they get to hang their name on the building, which
will become the Credit Agricole Indosuez building, its third name
in just a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Steir, a broker at Julien J. Studley who represented
the bank, said the decision to move to the Third Avenue site from
locations on Avenue of the Americas and Madison Avenue was made
after an extensive study of real estate options, including the
possibility of moving out of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Because operating in two locations made daily operations and
postmerger integration difficult, the bank wanted to consolidate
its operations in one location. And by moving the a new location,
the bank avoided the problems that might arise if one company moved
into the other's home office.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see this as a trail-blazing location for an
international bank,'' Steir said. ``But when you examine the
quality of the renovation, the efficiency of the 32,000-square-foot
floorplates and the ability to expand over time and the economics,
the deal makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   By moving to that location, brokers said, the bank can save as
much as $10 a square foot in rent compared with prime locations in
the upper 40s and mid-50s. The bank will initially occupy the
seventh through 10th floors with expansion rights for the fifth and
sixth floors available for growth.
</P>
<P>
   And by signing up while the project was under way, the bank was
able to exert influence over the design and save money by avoiding
a duplication of efforts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like most financial institutions with elaborate record-keeping
systems and trading operations, the bank wanted to install backup
generators to ensure a continued supply of electrical power in case
of a blackout. Since the building owners wanted generators for
other sections of the building, the prospective tenant and landlord
worked together on the installation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to open the sidewalk to lower in the generators, so
you don't want to have to do that twice,'' Steir said. ``They can
also share some things, like air shafts for the exhaust pipes. In
general, a tenant can significantly lower the cost of installing
power and telecommunications if it is done before the renovation is
finished.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank expects to move in next April. Its move was delayed
over complications involved with converting to the new European
currency, the euro, and preparations for dealing with the year 2000
computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Agricole Indosuez's metal sign will hang over a greatly
revised and enlarged lobby. ``There really wasn't a lobby there
before, just three hallways from street entrances to the
elevators,'' Ms. Peltier said.
</P>
<P>
   The enlarged lobby will be faced with white granite and graced
with art works and other Class A building touches. ``It is going to
look like a Park Avenue office building,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The building's other systems, the heating and ventilating, the
power and telecommunications are all being improved, she said, but
the elevators turned out not to be a problem. ``They had been
redone in the '90s,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the most obvious changes are being made to the east
building, there is plenty of work to do on the Chrysler Building
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Much of it involves the facade which, though protected as a
landmark, must be brought into compliance with city regulations
intended to prevent pieces from falling off buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to replace bricks in the facade due to deterioration,''
Ms. Peltier said. ``So we had some bricks made up and took them to
landmarks for permission to use them on the building. The bricks
that were in storage were useless.'' In addition to replacing
bricks, contractors are replacing lintels and repointing the mortar
on much of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes of the past are being repaired in the lobby of the
Chrysler Building, where temporary lights now help illuminate a
mural on the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   The mural had been hard to view, both because it had been poorly
coated in the past and because holes had been cut in it in the past
to accept recessed light fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to spend a couple of hundred thousand dollars repairing
the holes in the ceiling that had been cut for light cans,'' Ms.
Peltier said. She said the temporary lighting would eventually be
replaced by fixtures that produce subdued, but adequate light,
similar to the lighting at Rockefeller Center, which Tishman Speyer
also manages.
</P>
<P>
   One issue still under discussion is how to actually build
Johnson's trylons, which will tilt at odd angles to each other.
``It has taken months to do the engineering for them,''she said.
``The concept is cool, but the trick is to figure out how to make
them stand up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
