<SLUG> BC-BIKE-GIRO-ITALIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG-TESTING CONTROVERSY OVERSHADOWS GIRO D'ITALIA
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ That's some battle going on, isn't it, in the Giro
d'Italia, the world's second-most important bicycle race? Constant
attacks, challenges, everybody on the offensive, champions refusing
to yield.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just what's happening away from the race.
</P>
<P>
   The race? They're also having a race? This year's Giro is not
simply a three-week fight over drug testing, politics and turf?
</P>
<P>
   That's only the way it looks. The Giro is more than half over.
It finishes in Milan on June 6, and the drug issue has dwarfed
anything taking place on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Marco Pantani, the winner of the last Giro and the Tour
de France, and forget his victory last weekend when he simply rode
away from everybody. Forget Laurent Jalabert, ranked second in the
world, and the way he crushed the field last Sunday in the first of
two time trials, taking back the overall leader's pink jersey from
Pantani, who finished an unexpected third. Jalabert was still in
that jersey as the race took a day off Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Mario Cipollini, who has won three sprints and broke his
tie with the immortal Eddy Merckx for a record 25 victories in the
Giro. Cipollino now has 28 victories, and counting. Forget the
emergence of the sprinter Ivan Quaranta, at 24 eight years younger
than Cipollini and nearly his equal in this race with two victories
before he dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   Think, instead, Philippo Casagrande, ranked 183rd in the world,
who failed a doping test and continues nevertheless to ride for the
Vini Caldirola team from Italy. Think another unknown, Guido
Trombetta of Mobilvetta, who failed the same test and also remains
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Think Lampre, Saeco and Polti, three Italian teams that refuse
to take the tests that Casagrande and Trombetta failed.
</P>
<P>
   Their defense is that the tests are administered by the Italian
National Olympic Committee, which is seeking to re-establish itself
after it was discredited last year in a coverup of doping in
soccer. The riders, and their governing body, the International
Cycling Union, do not recognize the right of the Olympic Committee
to test them.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation began building as the race set off in Sicily
on May 16 and the International Cycling Union tested the number of
red blood cells _ the hematocrit level _ in each of the 162 riders.
A level above 50 percent is regarded as proof of doping with the
synthetic hormone erythropoietin (EPO), an illegal
performance-enhancing drug that is undetectable in standard tests.
EPO allows more oxygen to reach tired muscles by augmenting the red
blood cells that carry oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the riders exceeded the 50 percent norm and were barred
from the race, following a practice that has been in effect for
three years. Then the pack set off in sweltering heat for the usual
first week of mass sprint finishes.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened on the way to the Dolomites. On May
21, the Italian National Olympic Committee sent its doctors to
check two teams, or 16 riders, not for their hematocrit level but
for creatinuria, a substance that indicates diluted blood. When an
athlete has been using EPO and faces a drug test, a standard way of
passing it is to dilute his blood with a saline solution. The
Olympic Committee's reasoning is that diluted blood indicates EPO
use and thus it accused two of 16, not two of 162 as the
International Cycling Union did.
</P>
<P>
   Thereupon the riders rebelled. Pantani, their leader on and off
the road, promised that one more attempt by the Olympic Committee
to test them and they would all go home. ``We're racers, not blood
donors,'' he said. The race organizers looked elsewhere for
support.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, the International Cycling Union, through its
president, Hein Verbruggen, said in a letter to the organizers that
his group did not recognize the jurisdiction of the Olympic
Committee. That freed the teams to refuse further tests unless they
were administered by the cycling union. On Tuesday, 15 riders from
three teams passed such a test; nobody failed it.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Italian teams, only Mapei agreed to take further
Olympic Committee tests, and pledged to finish the Giro. As a
result, the team leader, Andrea Tafi, has been slurred and
threatened by riders from other teams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
