<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YACHT-AMERICA-CUP-NYT     05-29 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YACHT-AMERICA-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMALE YACHT MANAGER IS AN AMERICA'S CUP FIRST
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Dawn Riley, the skipper and founder of a
San Francisco America's Cup syndicate, introduced the mayor here at
her yacht's christening last Wednesday, she referred to him as
``Millie.'' His name is Willie.
</P>
<P>
   It was a slip of the tongue that made Willie Brown laugh. But
the gender flub probably had deeper meaning for anyone wanting to
delve into the psyche of the first woman in the 148-year history of
the America's Cup to manage her own yacht-racing syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, Riley's is the first coed team. Except for
token crew positions for women, and a failed attempt at an
all-women's crew in 1995, the America's Cup is a parapet of male
domination.
</P>
<P>
   For Riley, a coed team makes the most sense. ``The bottom line
is, every job on the boat has its own specific requirements,'' she
said last Thursday. ``If you look at both men and women, you have
the perfect combination _ power, agility, finesse and knowledge.
Together on a team, they become very efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   At 34, Riley is the only female sailor in the world with crew
experience in two America's Cup campaigns. With her team's new
75-foot yacht, America True, becoming the first U.S. boat to be
commissioned for the 1999-2000 races, Riley has moved from
contender to front-runner. At least until someone else's new boat
is christened.
</P>
<P>
   ``She certainly deserves a lot of credit here,'' said Buddy
Melges, the veteran America's Cup skipper who was her America3 boss
in the 1992 cup trials, and a current crew coach. ``If this boat is
fast, they've got as good a chance as anybody to win the cup back.
Boat speed is going to be the determining factor. But at this
point, Dawn's got a boat now to rally her team and crew with.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley did not actually launch America True at its christening
party. As a matter of fact, the yacht remained shrouded in a
blue-and-white tarp with shrink-wrap underneath, the slender hull
shape as hidden as a chocolate caramel still sealed in foil. But to
mark the official opening of her campaign, Riley had Melges throw a
bucket of San Francisco Bay water across the boat's topside.
</P>
<P>
   Riley apologized for the deception under the guise of America's
Cup secrecy. To catch a glimpse of the yacht's brightly painted
hull_ deep yellow with a linear graphic of peaks in red, black,
white and blue _ the audience of about 100 onlookers was allowed to
see only a swatch of color at the sailboat's stern. A poster
rendition of the yacht would have to do, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other team, Prada of Italy, has launched a new boat so
far. That leaves 11 other international syndicates still building
new boats, or planning on them. Four of those teams are American.
Yet even for Riley, sailing is a month away. The yacht will have to
wait until its arrival by ship in Auckland, New Zealand, in June
before the first waves pass its bow. The challenger trial races
begin Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Teams are spending millions to outfit and campaign one or two
new boats. Overall, design innovation is their most expensive
commodity. Already a stir is being caused by leaks that one or more
cup syndicates, including the New Zealanders, are testing out new
wing shapes for masts. The idea, used mostly by multihull
designers, improves sail efficiency and, ultimately, boat speed.
</P>
<P>
   Riley would not disclose whether America True would have one.
But with a budget of $20 million, her San Francisco Yacht Club
syndicate has pared itself down from early hopes for a $28 million
package. That has meant building one new America's Cup contender
instead of two, as the rules allow.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a one-boat program, it's critical to get down there and
get confidence,'' Riley said. ``We feel we could completely modify
this boat if we had to, but it's not something we are
considering.''
</P>
<P>
   Strategy, of course, is part of winning. Paul Cayard, Riley's
opponent across San Francisco Bay, is founder of America One, a
syndicate sponsored by the city's St. Francis Yacht Club. But he
sees no reason to take his team to Auckland so early.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no advantage to going to New Zealand now,'' Cayard
said. ``Their party line is they want to be practicing on the
Auckland race course. But not if it's blowing 50 knots. It's winter
down there, and half the time you can't go sailing at this time of
year anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley ignores the criticism. ``You have to rise above it,'' she
said. She hopes to do the same thing in competition in New Zealand
this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
