<SLUG> BC-RAC-LUKAS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUKAS MAKES HIMSELF HEARD AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Wis., Wyo.)  (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ He calls them box-office horses, superstars
that can put a stable on the racing map. D. Wayne Lukas found his
first one 26 years ago in a gray mare named Native Empress whom he
had claimed for $3,500. She was one of seven horses the
coach-turned-trainer showed up with at Los Alamitos race track in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Native Empress was a 5-year-old, which by quarter horse
standards meant her peak earning years had passed. Lukas was broke
and unknown, a trainer from El Paso, Texas, desperate to go big
time. For Lukas, Native Empress ran to the Los Alamitos horse of
the year award in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   And Lukas ran her in a way that would come to embody his
record-breaking, sometimes controversial career. He was part
horseman, part horse trader. Eight times, he sold the mare _ the
last for $250,000. But each time she remained in his stable.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Lukas leaned on a sawhorse outside his immaculate
barn at Churchill Downs with his cowboy hat pulled low and stared
from behind his ear-to-ear aviator shades and remembered Native
Empress.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, his latest superstar, Charismatic, shuffled in a stall,
one race from winning the Triple Crown. Three months ago, the colt
was running in a claiming race. Now, the chestnut has run four
times in the last eight weeks and won three major stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, Lukas was believed to be a second-string
player in the Triple Crown races he has thoroughly dominated. Now,
he is once again the star of the spring, and he has also been
honored with induction into racing's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have to have that big horse, that superstar, to get
noticed,'' Lukas said. ``To remind people we're still out here. And
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, 63, is a proud man who dislikes the suggestion that he
ever lost his touch _ as much as he dislikes the perception that
the Lukas way means pushing horses close to, and often past, their
breaking points. He was cordial but irritated as he ticked off his
accomplishments: The unprecedented 14 training titles for earnings.
The record 19 Eclipse Award winners. The 12 trips to the winner's
circle in the Triple Crown races.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an arrogant man,'' said John Nerud, the Hall of Fame
trainer of the 1957 Belmont winner, Gallant Man. ``He's got his
opinions, and they come out quick. He wants you to hear them and
listen to them. But I believe he has earned that right for all he's
done for the game.'' Nerud gave Lukas the 1980 Preakness winner,
Codex, to train and became his friend and mentor when Lukas made
the transition to thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas has made sure he has been heard, listened to and seen. He
pioneered a corporate approach with satellite stables coast to
coast manned by assistants to ensure he was represented at the best
races on any given day. It has helped his horses run off with a
record $199.4 million in purse earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas has worked the box seats and turf clubs at race tracks in
expensive suits and with burning zeal to woo potential owners. He
has seduced enough of them to spend close to $200 million at horse
sales. His clients have ranged from the late owner of the San Diego
Chargers, Eugene V. Klein, to the rap artist Hammer, to the
hard-boot Kentucky industrialist William T. Young, to Satish Sanan,
whose Padua Stables in Ocala, Fla., spent $22.4 million at yearling
sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Lukas flew in his own corporate jet to race tracks
and training tracks across the nation to check on his 250 horses.
He drove his Rolls-Royce to meet with owners. He offered stock in a
stable that ultimately failed at a cost of $4 million to investors.
</P>
<P>
   From 1985 to 1990, Lukas' owners bought 337 yearlings at a cost
of $104.6 million, according to the Jockey Club's Equine Line
computer service. They bought what he told them to, relying on an
eye first developed as a boy in Wisconsin who would purchase horses
intended for the slaughterhouse and resell them to local farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were living in fairy tale land,'' Lukas said. ``We were
compulsive buyers. I still am. You walk a good-looking saddle pony
in front of me, and I want to buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he turned his classy stock into a single-season
earnings record for a trainer, winning $17,842,358 in purses. But
in the '90s, the fairy tale faded into a parable about living too
large and too loud.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas lost $3.1 million of his own money when Calumet Farm, a
client and partner in ownership and breeding, went bankrupt in
1991. It was hardly his worst loss in a humbling decade.
</P>
<P>
   His integrity and horsemanship were savaged when Union City, a
horse some believed was not sound, fractured a leg during the 1993
Preakness Stakes and did not survive. Other breakdowns by Lukas
stars followed.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 Preakness winner, Tabasco Cat, was retired with a leg
injury at the age of 4; the 1994 champion juvenile filly, Flanders,
broke a bone in the Breeders' Cup and was retired. The 1995
Preakness winner, Timber Country, strained leg tendons and was
retired on the eve of the Belmont, and the 1995 Kentucky Derby
winner, Thunder Gulch, fractured a canon bone in his foreleg five
months after the Derby at the Jockey Club Gold Cup and was also
retired. In 1996, the Kentucky Derby winner Grindstone was injured
and retired while preparing for the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism of his tactics came as Lukas was losing owners and
remained mired in a slump. His horses did not win a Grade I race
for more than two years, and Lukas fell from the top of the
trainers' standings in 1993. In the midst of the professional
setbacks, Lukas almost lost his son and top assistant, Jeff, when
Tabasco Cat ran over and nearly killed him in the barn area at
Santa Anita in December 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff sustained multiple skull fractures, lapsed into a coma and
almost died when his brain swelled and nearly herniated his brain
stem. He spent months in the hospital and years in rehabilitation,
but has returned to the Lukas barn in an administrative role. ``I
have bounced a few times, but that was the hardest thing,'' his
fathep said. ``I'm just grateful he's b!ck with us.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been Jeff, after all, who had organized a surprise
intervention for his father after Union City's breakdown. The
trainer had become isolated and depressed as attacks on his methods
mounted. Jeff Lukas gathered friends of his father _ some from his
childhood in Wisconsin _ at his home in California. For seven
hours, they took turns telling Lukas what he had meant to them. And
Lukas told them his mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think I was down or anything, but it meant a
lot to have these people show they cared about me,'' he said.
``They supported me.'' He vehemently denies the charges that he is
hard on horses. Lukas attributes the breakdowns to the large size
of his stable and to his owners' interest in winning the lucrative
2- and 3-year-old races when the horses are developing and fragile.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas understands tha this bravado has alienated some rivals and
especially the news media. He points to the rough trips that the
Edward Plesa-trained filly Three Ring had in the Kentucky Derby and
another filly, the Bob Baffert-trained Excellent Meeting, had in
the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had trained those horses, I would have been absolutely
barbecued,'' Lukas said. ``Just ripped up because, I guess, I rub
people the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lukas has his defenders. Carl Nafzger, the trainer of the
Florida Derby winner Vicar, is one. The direct opposite of Lukas,
Nafzger is a real cowboy from Wyoming who prefers a smaller,
slower-developing stable.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Vicar, his only Derby horse was the 1990 winner,
Unbridled, who also went on to win the Breeders' Cup Classic that
year. In fact, Nafzger still bristles that Lukas' Criminal Type won
Horse of the Year over Unbridled in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne out-campaigned me. Old Criminal Type got sore ankles
before the Breeders' Cup and was retired so he couldn't race my
horse,'' he said with a disbelieving wink. ``It just shows Wayne is
smarter and shrewder than me. But he doesn't run unsound horses.
That's pure envy talking when anyone says that. He has a program
geared to winning early. He's a coach and he pushes his athletes _
that's the nature of the game. The thing about him is he's got
energy and goals. When he is on top he builds; when he is on the
bottom he builds.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Lukas' consistency, the Hall of Fame trainer Nerud says,
that has made him one of the best of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``A shed row is a hospital, and Wayne had the best of everything
_ feed, hay, wraps,'' said Nerud, now 86. ``Even when he didn't
have much he always acted like the first-class horseman that he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been a detail and image man ever since his days as a high
school basketball coach and in the backwaters of quarter-horse
racing. He still rises at 3 a.m. each day and expects his barn to
be raked in symmetrical rows when he arrives at 4:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stalls can be perfect, but if a saddle pony don't look
right or the pony tack isn't gleaming, he'll get all over you,''
said Randy Bradshaw, his California-based assistant. ``He always is
looking for a way to motivate you.''
</P>
<P>
   When Churchill Downs' Julian Wheat came by recently to tell
Lukas his workers had won barn of the month for upkeep and would
receive free pizza, the trainer stopped what he was doing. ``We
have the best barn every day of the year; it's nice of you to
recognize that once in a while,'' he hollered loud enough for his
employees to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas has toned down his superstar image, sort of. The
Rolls-Royce has been replaced by a pickup truck, the jet traded for
commercial flights. ``You can buy a whole lot of first-class
tickets for a million a year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has 160 horses in training _ one of them, Charismatic, will
try to become only the 12th Triple Crown winner. He concedes that
running Charismatic in a claiming race in which anyone with $62,500
could have bought him was his own mismanagement. So were a few
other things. But is he humbled? Not at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is like the NCAA tournament,'' he said. ``Coaches
rise up and win one now and then. But there was only one John
Wooden. I think I have proved I can sustain that high level of
excellence. And I believe we're going to be this good for a long
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
