A6095 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-USOPEN-COX     05-29 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big tournaments are big business in small towns
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the U.S. Women's Open comes to tiny West Point, Miss.,
population 12,500, and Old Waverly Golf Club this week, the goal is
to continue what's been a pretty good thing.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Golf Association and the LPGA Tour players have learned
the value of secondary-market areas for their showcase event. Bring
the tournament to a place where it's clearly the biggest deal in
town _ including the Columbus and Jackson area _ and the odds for
excitement are greatly increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``You definitely get a crowd that otherwise would be blase,''
said Atlanta's Bob Cupp, who designed Old Waverly with former U.S.
Open champion Jerry Pate.
</P>
<P>
   Cupp also is part of a formula that has worked successfully in
the past for the USGA and the U.S. Women's Open. Old Waverly is
Cupp's fourth course to be used for the tournament; the most recent
had been Pumpkin Ridge Golf Club near Portland, Ore., in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the women like them,'' Cupp said about his courses.
``There's not any kind of billy-goat action.''
</P>
<P>
   The courses have no mammoth hills to wear out players and
further slow the pace of play. Last year's site, windblown
Blackwolf Run in Kohler, Wis., a Pete Dye layout that had hosted an
Andersen Consulting World Championship U.S. final, proved too
difficult for many players. Cupp's Pumpkin Ridge Witch Hollow
course, where Tiger Woods previously won his third consecutive U.S.
Amateur, evolved as a fairer, picturesque venue. It found
additional fanfare from the near-win by the LPGA's living icon,
Nancy Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Cupp is not fond of the term signature hole, because it tends to
belittle the other 17, but he concedes that Old Waverly's par-4
18th, which the women will play to about 380 yards, has the
potential for pivotal peril _ especially with holes cut to the
green's left side, where water and bunkers crowd approach shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard hole,'' he said. ``The player who bails out takes
a real chance on a three-putt.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Se Ri Pak, who toured the 6,433-yard Old
Waverly course earlier in the spring, described the place as ``hot
and boring.'' But she probably meant that she was excited about a
Women's Open held at ``a quiet place where you can concentrate and
get more rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez has played the course several times; she has participated
in an annual pro-am tournament there.
</P>
<P>
   England's Laura Davies, the 1987 champion, likes the idea of a
longer, more demanding layout.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to hit 3-irons and 4-irons into some of the
par-4's,'' said Davies, the LPGA's longest hitter. ``It's nice to
be really challenged. I don't like all these easy courses we
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The process of actually getting the Women's Open to Old Waverly
was spearheaded by George Bryan, of hot dog and luncheon meat fame.
The presentation by Bryan and his family blew away the USGA
committee during the 1995 tournament at the Broadmoor in Colorado
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Why Mississippi? Why Old Waverly?''' said Mary Capouch,
chairwoman of the USGA Women's Committee. ``We've been asked that a
lot. We like to take the championships to as many regions of the
country as we possibly can. There's never been a national
championship of any sport in Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to hit a familiar reference point for the South,
television ads in the West Point area have billed the Women's Open
as being to women's golf ``what the Daytona 500 is to NASCAR.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament's usual July date was moved up a month,
attempting to avoid the most intense Mississippi summer heat.
Kendra Graham, the USGA's director of women's championships, said
the crowd might not equal the record 25,000 per day that attended
at Blackwolf Run, ``but if it isn't, it won't be for lack of
trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
