<SLUG> BC-BBO-CANCER-PROSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHING PROSPECT OVERCOMES CANCER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (rk) 
 By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greg Montalbano, the Northeastern University left-handed
pitcher, is virtually assured of being selected in the major league
draft Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Montalbano, a 6-foot-2-inch, 192-pound native of Westborough,
Mass., throws a fastball that surpasses 90 mph. In 64.2 innings
this season, he had an 8-2 record, allowed 44 hits, walked 24,
struck out 71 and had an ERA of 2.09, third best in Division I.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all his success, Montalbano is concerned about the
future. It has nothing to do with his pitching or his draft
position; Montalbano only hopes he stays out of the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Since February 1996, he has undergone five surgical procedures
to remove cancerous and noncancerous tumors. In addition, he
underwent two three-week sessions of chemotherapy, which cost him
hair and weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been mentally tough for me,'' Montalbano said. ``This
thing has been dragged out for three years and it gets difficult to
deal with after a while. But I think the process has made me
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   The first operation Montalbano had was when he was 18 years old
and a standout at St. John's High School in Shrewsbury, Mass.
Doctors discovered a cancerous tumor in his right testicle. In June
1996, he again underwent surgery after a nodule was discovered in
his right lung. After the procedure, he began the chemotherapy
treatments and redshirted his freshman year at Northeastern in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The third operation came in September 1996, when Montalbano had
two noncancerous tumors removed from his right lung. In order to
reach the tumors, doctors had to collapse his lung and make an
incision that stretched from his spine to his sternum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used my setbacks as motivation because I just wanted to get
back and play with the guys,'' Montalbano said. ``If the doctors
said it would take six weeks to get back, I would try to make it
back in five and a half, without putting myself at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Montalbano says his cancer has been in remission since March
1996 and he is looking forward to the draft. Scouts from the
Anaheim Angels, the Arizona Diamondbacks, the Boston Red Sox, the
Cincinnati Reds, the Colorado Rockies, the Milwaukee Brewers, the
Philadelphia Phillies and the Toronto Blue Jays have all come to
see Montalbano pitch at some point this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a good fastball, curve ball and a changeup,'' John
Brickley, a Reds scouting supervisor for New England, upstate New
York and Montreal, said. ``Montalbano is a very savvy pitcher and
he knows how to set up the hitters and battle the hitters while he
is on the mound. He is very poised and possesses great tenacity,
which I think is a part of his character and makeup that he got
from battling cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the scouts have inquired about Montalbano's
health, he does not take it personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ready and I am looking forward to the draft,'' Montalbano
said. ``A lot of things are being said about my draft position
right now, but it doesn't mean anything until I receive that phone
call from a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Montalbano made his Northeastern debut in 1997, posting a 4-2
record primarily as a reliever. His ERA was 2.56 in 56.1 innings,
and he struck out 51, allowed 49 hits and walked 13.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1997 and February 1998, Montalbano underwent surgery
to remove noncancerous tumors from his pelvic area.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern coach Neil McPhee said he and the players could not
help thinking the worst when Montalbano had surgery. But each time,
Montalbano had a positive outlook and promised that he would be
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teammates have been very supportive,'' Montalbano said. ``I
think the deal was that they were unsure because this is so unusual
for them. I did the best I could to explain the situation because I
wanted them to have more information than questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Montalbano made it back to the mound. In 1998, he
had a 3-2 record, with an ERA of 3.28 and 34 strikeouts in 35.2
innings, allowing 38 hits and 11 walks. In 1999, he was even better
and became a major league prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an incredible contrast as to what he has gone through
and what he has achieved,'' McPhee said. ``To make a full recovery
and have a year like this, a dream season, is incredible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
