<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-TEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE GRIM TEST SCORES, A SCHOOL MARKS ITS SMALL TRIUMPHS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The day was winding down in a hectic week for Magalie
Pierre's class of fourth graders at Public School 129 in Harlem,
and so a party was in order.
</P>
<P>
   Every party has to have a toast, and the duty on Friday fell
first on Juriel Gomez, who set aside his plate of pizza, grapes,
popcorn and macaroni, pushed back his tiny classroom chair, and
held aloft a plastic cup filled with soda.
</P>
<P>
   ``A toast, to everyone who did well on the reading test,''
Juriel said to applause, as other students rose to offer more
salutes to themselves, the school, Ms. Pierre, the principal _ even
the people who wrote the test _ so they could have this party.
</P>
<P>
   The students had not yet received their individual scores from
the first sitting of the state's new fourth-grade reading exam, but
the school did on Tuesday, along with the rest of the state. And at
first blush, the festive mood and the toasts might appear to
contradict the statistical reality.
</P>
<P>
   At PS 129, one of 97 city schools on the state's roster of
chronically low-performing schools, just 25 percent of the 95
fourth-graders met or exceeded the state standard. That was 8
percentage points below the citywide average of 33 percent, and 23
points below the state average of 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the school scored above other ``schools under registration
review,'' as those on the state roster are officially called; they
registered an average of 16 percent. And it ranked third among 13
schools in District 5, whose average was 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly N. Lewis, the principal, who had prepped her students
with extra tutoring over Christmas break and on weekends and wrote
a special reading curriculum with teachers, greeted the results
with a mixture of optimism and concern.
</P>
<P>
   The school may have fared better than its low-performing peers,
but it is still forever compared with schools across the state that
lack the social ills her pupils face.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every one of her 800 students in kindergarten through
sixth grade come to the school, at 425 West 130th Street, from
families poor enough to qualify for free lunch. A quarter of the
students live in a shelter for homeless families down the street.
</P>
<P>
   And on top of it all, the stakes are higher than ever. The
school system plans to begin holding back failing students in the
third, sixth and eighth grades as early as this year, and the
fourth through 12th next year. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, reacting to
the reading scores, has called for the dismissal of principals of
schools performing most poorly on this and other tests.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the fourth graders will take the state's new math
test, which like one on reading given in January, is said to be
more rigorous than previous standardized tests because it asks
students more analytic questions in addition to the usual
multiple-choice questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of our progress, but want everyone to be aware
we have a long way to go,'' Lewis said in her office, festooned
with slogans such as ``Readers Are Leaders'' and ``When You Believe
in Yourself, Anything is Possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone'' extends to the children, too. And so later on, in
Ms. Pierre's classroom, Lewis picked up a cup and offered her own
toast: ``I'd like to toast all the children. I'm very proud of you
and I know we are going to continue to make progress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
