<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADULT-SKATERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NEVER TOO LATE TO LEARN A LUTZ
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (rk) 
 By NANCY GAVILANES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After years of practicing her lutz jumps and lay-back
spins, Linda Frances is going to her first international figure
skating competition this weekend in Villard delans, France.
</P>
<P>
   As she fine-tunes her program set to the music of ``Titanic,''
Frances' goal is simply to ``bring the technical and artistic
elements together to give a good performance.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is nothing unusual about her goal, Frances is far
from being a typical skater. She first laced up skates when she was
in her late 30s and will be making her international debut at age
47.
</P>
<P>
   Perfecting her technique and interpreting her music is far more
important than winning medals or attempting triple jumps, said
Frances, who skates eight hours a week at Sky Rink at Chelsea Piers
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're not going to the Olympics,'' said Frances, who
started skating after watching the 1988 Winter Games in Calgary,
Alberta, on television.
</P>
<P>
   Adult skating exploded in the early 90s, in part because of an
increase in televised competitions as well as the exposure given
the sport by the Nancy Kerrigan-Tonya Harding incident, and the
result is a demand for competitive events for these
boomers-who-would-be-skaters.
</P>
<P>
   This year's adult nationals, in April in Ann Arbor, Mich., drew
600 competitors between the ages of 25 and 72. At this weekend's
Mountain Cup, the first international event for nonelite adults, 98
skaters are set to compete, with 67 of them Americans.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the Mountain Cup, competitors must have tested
before U.S. Figure Skating Association judges. Skaters are divided
into four levels according to the spins and jumps they execute
(there is a separate masters category for adults who were
competitive skaters as children) and into four age groups: 18-24;
25-35; 36-45; and 46 and above.
</P>
<P>
   Programs, both interpretive numbers without jumps and freestyle
routines which require them, last no longer than two minutes and
are performed in front of International Skating Union judges.
</P>
<P>
   While there are 44,000 adults registered with the figure skating
association, there are countless others who do not get tested or
compete. Also, adults not interested in jumping always have the
option of competing in ice dancing or trace figures.
</P>
<P>
   Many skate because ``it's an art, a skill and a sport all
wrapped into one,'' said Denise Beaumont, 38, who has been coaching
for 16 years and has choreographed programs for Frances.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps no coincidence that the skating association's
commitment has come as adult skating has become a big untapped area
of growth. Still, the competitive appetite of these elder skaters
and the response of organizations seeking to feed it has surprised
even those in the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in my mind did I think I'd be taking adults to
international competitions,'' said Kenny Moir, 41, who has been
coaching for 14 years at Sky Rink.
</P>
<P>
   Moir plans to accompany four New Yorkers to France, and there he
will also be coaching Karla Morales from Ecuador, who taught
herself how to skate through books and videos. ``That somebody is
skating in Ecuador, and an adult no less, is a really great sign,''
Moir said.
</P>
<P>
   His New Yorkers _ from Frances to Laura Moore, 42, a designer
who skates at 5:30 a.m., to Rose Auslander, 44, an attorney who
practices at 8:30 a.m., to Helen Chan, 46, an architect who is on
the ice 10-15 hours a week _ have found ways to balance family
life, careers and their love of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't skate I would get depressed,'' said Chan. Chan has
found ice time easier to come by now that her two children are
teen-agers and she can work from home. Along with providing Chan
``a new physical challenge which is much harder than my work,''
skating has helped her bond with her daughter, Jordan, 15, who also
takes lessons.
</P>
<P>
   There is always a risk of injury, of course, especially to older
skaters. Just last year, Chan and Frances had accidents. Chan broke
her ankle and tore two ligaments while swerving to avoid a
collision with another skater, and Frances broke her leg when she
landed wrong after a jump. Did either skater contemplate quitting?
No way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just worked very hard to come back,'' Frances said.
</P>
<P>
   They are spending ``their own hard-earned money,'' as Beaumont
points out, and it's an expensive passion. There is ice time,
lessons and choreography. Costumes begin at $100, custom boots are
$500 and blades cost $300. And this doesn't even address travel
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it keeps us sane,'' Frances said of skating, ``it's worth
it.''.
</P>
<P>
   Chan said, ``As long as I can walk, I can skate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
