A6101 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT &LR;      05-29 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 REAL ESTATE: 2 IMPORTANT CASES UPDATED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two subjects previously addressed in this column _
one that affects many rental tenants in New York City co-op and
condominium buildings and another that will change the way buyers
and sellers of real estate in Westchester County do business with
one another and their brokers _ are now in need of updating.
</P>
<P>
   The first has been affected by two recent Housing Court cases
that are at odds with a controversial 1998 ruling by Judge Marc
Finkelstein in an eviction case in Housing Court in Brooklyn known
as Paikoff vs. Harris.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 case involved an eviction proceeding against a rental
tenant in a six-unit co-op in Park Slope. The tenant, who rented
his apartment from the co-op's sponsor nearly five years after the
conversion had taken place, contested the sponsor's decision to
decline to renew his lease after it expired.
</P>
<P>
   The tenant argued that he was covered by the Martin Act _ a
section of the state's General Business Law that protects
nonpurchasing tenants in co-op or condominium conversions from
eviction except for cause.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Martin Act was widely believed to apply only to
tenants who occupied their apartments at the time of conversion,
lawyers for co-ops and condominiums were stunned when Finkelstein
extended Martin Act protection to the tenant even though the rental
occurred long after the conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Weinstein, a Manhattan co-op and condominium lawyer, said
at the time that the implications of the decision could be
``enormous'' and that it could render ``thousands of apartments in
hundreds of buildings virtually unsalable'' by giving protected
status to tenants who rented from sponsors subsequent to
conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Miller, a Queens lawyer who specializes in co-ops and
condominiums, said that most co-op and condominium lawyers believe
that Finkelstein's decision was flawed because it was based on an
erroneous interpretation of a critical term in the law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Martin Act, Miller said, tenants who rent apartments
from a ``purchaser under the plan'' subsequent to a conversion are
not entitled to protected status. In practice, he said, that has
generally been interpreted to mean that tenants occupying their
apartments at the time of conversion are protected by the Martin
Act, while those who rent subsequent to the conversion are not,
regardless of who they rent from.
</P>
<P>
   Miller explained, however, that what Finkelstein did in his
decision was to declare that a sponsor _ who is, in legal
terminology, a ``holder of unsold shares'' _ was not a ``purchaser
under the plan.'' The judge then concluded, Miller said, that
tenants who rent from sponsors _ even those who rent after the
conversion _ are protected by the Martin Act because they are not
renting from a ``purchaser under the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Housing Court judges in two recent cases, however, declined to
adopt Finkelstein's interpretation of the law.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision issued last month in a case known as Pembroke
Square Associates vs. Coppola, Judge Ellis Franke of the Housing
Court in Queens ruled that a sponsor could indeed be considered a
``purchaser under the plan'' because of the way that phrase is
defined in the law itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That definition only requires that the `purchaser' be one who
owns the shares to the apartment,'' Franke wrote in his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, he ruled, a tenant who rents from a sponsor
subsequent to conversion is not protected by the Martin Act.
</P>
<P>
   A similar conclusion was reached by Judge Bruce Kramer in
Manhattan in a decision issued on May 12. In that case, Kramer
pointed out that there was no evidence of any legislative intent to
provide Martin Act protection to tenants who rent sponsor-owned
apartments subsequent to the conversion of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the Queens lawyer, said that given the clear language of
the statute, as pointed out by Franke and Kramer, it was unlikely
that either case would be overturned on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, while the original Paikoff case is currently
being appealed, it likely that the appellate court will overturn it
for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we're back where we started,'' Miller said. ``And
that's good news for co-ops and condominiums.''
</P>
<P>
   The Westchester County matter concerns a 1997 attempt by real
estate brokers to prepare contracts of sale for their clients. The
column, which appeared on Feb. 16, 1997, reported that as a result
of a legal opinion issued by then-Attorney General Dennis Vacco in
November of the preceding year, brokers could legally prepare
``fill-in-the-blanks'' contracts for their clients without engaging
in the unauthorized practice of law.
</P>
<P>
   The use of broker-prepared contracts, however, was put on hold
after the Westchester County Bar Association filed for an
injunction against the practice in court. ``The form the brokers
were trying to use was not appropriate for New York,'' said Ira
Goldenberger, co-chairman of the Unlawful Practice of Law Committee
of the Westchester County Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   Goldenberger said that over the last year or so, lawyers for the
brokers and the bar association had negotiated a different form of
broker-prepared contract that was just now being put to use. The
contract, he said, consists of two parts _ the form contract itself
and a ``cover sheet,'' which the buyer and seller will sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cover sheet is the actual form the brokers will fill
out,'' Goldenberger said, adding that it was a
``fill-in-the-blanks'' form that contains all pertinent information
about the deal when all of the blanks have been filled in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contract itself is never touched by the broker,'' he said.
``But when the cover sheet is completely filled out and signed, it
becomes part and parcel of the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that once the cover sheet was completed and signed by
the parties, the broker then had three business days to deliver the
documents to the lawyers for the buyer and seller and must sign a
certification that the documents were, in fact, delivered on time.
After that, the lawyers have five business days to approve or
disapprove the contract. If no action is taken within the five
days, Goldenberger said, the contract is considered binding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The broker is also required to deliver various other
significant documents to the lawyers along with the contract,'' he
said, including a copy of the deed, the survey, the current
certificate of occupancy and, if available, a copy of the seller's
title insurance policy. Moreover, Goldenberger said, under the
terms of an agreement between the bar association and the
Westchester County Board of Realtors, brokers and sales agents must
go through a training procedure and obtain a certification from the
bar association before they can prepare contracts for clients.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Bell, chief operating officer of Balch Buyer's Realty, a
Mamaroneck, N.Y.-based agency that represents only buyers, said
that the ability of brokers to prepare contracts would benefit
buyers more than sellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's great because we can at least get the parties to
put their signatures on a piece of paper,'' he said, adding that in
the current robust seller's market, deals can easily fall apart if
a new buyer makes a higher offer between the time the seller
verbally accepts the first buyer's offer and the contracts are
ultimately prepared by the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least now we can keep the deal together for a few days
while the lawyers review the contracts,'' Bell said. ``That's
better than nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
