<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE SENTENCES AID WORKERS AS SPIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia)  (lb) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Two Australian aid workers and a Yugoslav
colleague received long prison sentences on Saturday from a
military court after being found guilty on charges of espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pratt, the director of CARE Australia in Serbia and
Kosovo, was sentenced to 12 years, and Peter Wallace to four years.
Branko Jelen, the Yugoslav worker, received six years. CARE
officials said they would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The sentences were passed down by the military judge after a
three-day closed trial. The men sat with their heads bowed, each
guarded by two Yugoslav army soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and supporters, including Jelen's mother, were allowed
into the court for the reading of the verdict. Jelen's mother broke
into sobs when she heard the sentence. As the men were led from the
room, Jelen was allowed briefly to embrace his mother. ``Why?'' she
cried out as he was led away.
</P>
<P>
   In a twist not explained by the Yugoslav authorities or the
court, the men were found guilty of a new charge, simple espionage,
after the original charges of forming a spy ring were dismissed for
lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, a Sydney native in his 50s who was once a major in the
Australian army, had been accused of running a spy ring through a
group of employees. The other men had been accused of supplying
information to that ring.
</P>
<P>
   They were convicted of a new charge, straight espionage, which
is a lesser crime but in this case carried a heavier sentence. The
Australians were also fined about $1,000 each and Jelen was fined a
lesser amount.
</P>
<P>
   The men have denied the charges, although Pratt appeared after
his arrest on Serbian state television, saying he had used his
Yugoslav employees to gather intelligence. Friends and colleagues
have said they are convinced that the statement was made under
duress. The court subsequently ruled that his taped confession was
inadmissible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand their main work was humanitarian, but in the
process they committed criminal offenses,'' the judge said Saturday
in passing sentence.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what evidence the prosecution presented against
the men. The two Australians were arrested at the border with
Croatia on March 31, just days after NATO began its airstrikes
against Belgrade. They were on their way from Belgrade to relocate
their office to Montenegro, which along with Serbia makes up
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The police apparently found their belongings, mobile phones,
laptop computers and maps suspicious, and confiscated them along
with their vehicles. Jelen was arrested a week later on April 8.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues have suggested that the grounds for official Yugoslav
suspicion may have been doing something as simple as visiting
former military barracks during CARE's work with refugees in
Serbia. Many Serbian refugees from Croatia are living in old
military buildings and CARE Australia was working to improve their
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the sentence surprised officials at CARE
International and Australian diplomats present at the court. While
they had been banned from the proceedings, they had expressed
satisfaction that the trial appeared to be working well, and the
judges were calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``From all reports, the trial has been professionally conducted,
in a calm atmosphere,'' CARE Australia said in a news release given
out on Friday. ``The men have been able to present their cases
strongly, clearly and convincingly.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials raised the issue of the detained workers with top
Yugoslav officials during a recent visit to Belgrade, as did the
U.N. commissioner for human rights, Mary Robinson, pointing out
that Belgrade could not expect assistance in caring for refugees
while it treated aid workers with such harshness.
</P>
<P>
   The men will be allowed to appeal once they have received the
written, translated verdict. Meanwhile they will remain in
detention, the judge said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The harsh sentence comes as the authorities have cracked down on
dissent in Serbia. The police arrested some 28 army reservists in
Krusevac who had been resisting military orders to report for duty
in Kosovo, according to reports published in Montenegro, where the
press is more independent than in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The men and their families have been demonstrating for over a
week against the war in Kosovo and have demanded that others serve
in the province before they themselves return for a second tour.
Two Serbian reporters covering the protests in Krusevac were also
arrested four days ago and remain in detention.
</P>
</TEXT>
