<SLUG> BC-NY-APARTMENTS-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: THE ELUSIVE NEW YORK APARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With all the scarcity, hysteria, back-stabbing and
astronomical prices in the real estate market, it would hardly seem
possible for young people just out of college to find apartments.
</P>
<P>
   But while apartments go quickly, they can be found, even for
those more interested in what they do than in what they earn.
Regardless of whether they are making $20,000 a year as editorial
assistants or $45,000 (before bonuses) as starting investment
bankers, this year's class of graduates will find ways to live in
New York, even in Manhattan. But they have to be flexible about
where they will live and ruthlessly efficient in their approach.
There is no time to think things over, or to get to the bank for a
certified check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people to bring a briefcase with cash,'' said John P.
Burke Jr., a realtor at John P. Burke Realty on Seventh Avenue in
Brooklyn who specializes in Park Slope and neighboring areas.
</P>
<P>
   Although brokers say the first or second person to see an
apartment nearly always takes it, they also say new places are
continually coming on the market, and that any new college graduate
with a job _ and without a dog _ who is also relatively presentable
as well as realistic about prices can find an apartment. The market
has even loosened a bit, because of new buildings going up and
people leaving rentals for co-ops and condos, making it slightly
easier than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't quite as hysterical this year,'' said Soozy Katzen,
director of relocation services for Fox Residential Group. ``If
somebody is looking for a one-bedroom, you can actually keep them
busy for a day, show them eight to 10 properties.'' Although it has
never been easy or cheap to find places in New York, it was only 12
years ago, she said, that there was a surplus of apartments and
clients could be offered dozens in every part of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Although brokers say that many young people want to live on the
Upper West Side or in the West Village, those are among the most
expensive areas. And while they probably associate the Upper East
Side with the un-young and the un-hip, it is the neighborhood with
the largest supply of bargains. They tend to be rent-stabilized
places in old walkup buildings around York and First and Second
Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, agreeing to a request to show his best picks in
Manhattan for less-expensive apartments, Gordon Golub, a manager at
Citi Habitats, showed a small but sunny one-bedroom apartment in
the 70's near York Avenue, for $1,015; a one-bedroom in the same
neighborhood on the sixth floor of a walkup building for $1,400
that could be shared by two people; a basement studio apartment on
32nd Street between Fifth and Madison Avenues for $1,250 in an
elevator building; a minuscule apartment with no kitchen and a
shared bath, at Broadway in the 20s, for $595 a month, and a large
and airy studio apartment on West 34th Street between Ninth and
10th Avenues, in a doorman building with elevator, for $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   That neighborhood, he said, has some relative bargains, just
like the Upper East Side. He said he had nothing he considered
well-priced for typical new graduates either downtown or on the
Upper West Side.
</P>
<P>
   The Hecht Group, a brokerage company that specializes in
rent-stabilized apartments on the Upper East and Upper West Sides,
recently could list a number of apartments available on the Upper
East Side, including a studio at Lexington Avenue and 96th Street
for $899, a one-bedroom that could be shared for $1,350 at 91st
Street and Second Avenue, and a two-bedroom at York Avenue and 84th
Street for $1,550.
</P>
<P>
   Amnon Hecht, an immigrant from Israel who started the company
three years ago with his brother Oded, said the company has access
to 300 apartments on any given day. Deciding who gets them, he
said, often involves a lot of intuition. ``When I'm sitting with a
person,'' he said, ``I see if they're a nice human being.''
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, brokers say, people get the most modern apartments
for the least money in the financial district, where a number of
buildings have been converted from commercial to residential use. A
two-bedroom apartment that would be $4,000 on the Upper West Side
might rent for $2,600 in the financial district.
</P>
<P>
   Most new graduates share apartments with friends from college or
home. Studios, brokers say, are more likely to be rented to people
in their mid to late 20s. One-bedroom apartments in Manhattan newly
occupied by only one person have become the province of the
well-heeled, of a single person making more than $100,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The sharing of apartments never meant to be shared has spawned
its own language, including the elegant and totally mystifying
``one-bedroom convertible.'' What that means is that a temporary
wall costing about $800 can be used to divide the living room,
creating another bedroom. It's really a continuation of dorm life,
because the living room almost disappears and becomes a place
holding little more than a couch and a television.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Kekesi, a Corcoran Group broker, recently rented an
apartment in the financial district to three men who will divide a
two-bedroom renting for $2,600. ``They would rather sacrifice space
than location,'' Ms. Kekesi said. ``I had somebody who was willing
to put bunk beds into a one-bedroom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
