<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-490&AMP;ADD     05-29 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SKEPTICAL OF RUSSIA'S EFFORT TO SWAY BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The NATO allies on Saturday reacted with skepticism
to the outcome of the visit by the Russian envoy, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, to Belgrade where he aired ways to end the war in
Kosovo with President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   As he left Belgrade late on Friday, Chernomyrdin pronounced
himself pleased with the results of his talks but gave no details.
In Moscow on Saturday, there were no public announcements on what
he had achieved.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters on Saturday, a spokesman, Peter Daniel,
said there would be no pause in the NATO air campaign until
Yugoslavia accepted its ``non-negotiable terms.''
</P>
<P>
   With little sign of a breakthrough on the diplomatic front, the
Pentagon announced that the air campaign against Milosevic would be
reinforced this week with 68 additional U.S. Air Force aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The official Yugoslav news agency, Tanjug, announced after
Chernomyrdin left Belgrade that Milosevic had accepted the
``general principles'' for a settlement agreed to by the seven
richest industrial countries and Russia last month.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic made a similar pledge after Chernomyrdin's previous
visit to Belgrade but took no concrete steps, such as withdrawing
troops from Kosovo, to show he was serious. There was no sign from
Belgrade on Saturday that Milosevic had agreed to a key demand that
NATO be permitted to send a well-armed force, with the alliance at
its core, into Kosovo to help the ethnic Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, described the
dialogue between Chernomyrdin and NATO as running into trouble
because of NATO's refusal to grant a pause in the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russian efforts and the direct efforts of the special
representative of Russia for Yugoslavia, Viktor Chernomyrdin, have
not found the understanding of the leadership of NATO, which
continues to insist Belgrade accept the alliance's demands,''
Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
   France and Germany, in a joint statement, said that the Yugoslav
statement about accepting the ``general principles'' should be
examined to see whether it ``could lead to a political
settlement.'' France and Germany suggested that the political
directors of the so-called G-8 group of eight countries, including
Western allies along with Japan and Russia, should meet shortly to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   But the State Department was less enthusiastic about such a
meeting, saying that it was waiting to learn the details of
Chernomyrdin's trip and doubted that a new meeting of the political
directors of the G-8 was necessary. ``We think it would be
premature to make any procedural steps until we have a report,''
said the department spokesman, James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the foreign ministers of the G-8
were scheduled to meet on June 8 in preparation for a summit
meeting in Cologne, Germany, on June 18 where President Clinton and
President Boris Yeltsin will meet.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Pentagon said that the 68 aircraft being sent were part of
the additional 176 that Secretary of Defense William Cohen,
approved on May 6 after a request from the NATO commander, Gen.
Wesley Clark. The new aircraft included the deployment of 12
F-16Js, 36 F-15Es and 20 KC-135s from the Air Force Air Mobility
Command.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters, the spokesman, Daniel, said that good
weather allowed the alliance to fly 600 sorties on Friday, about
half of them striking targets or suppressing enemy air defenses.
``Our strategy certainly has not changed,'' Daniel said. ``We have
heightened the pace of the campaign in the last few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade and Novi Sad, Yugoslavia's second-largest city, were
plunged into darkness overnight during the latest wave of NATO
airstrikes, which hit at the electricity system of Serbia,
Yugoslavia's main republic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 1805EDT &QL; 
