<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIRL-SLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONX WOMAN IS CHARGED WITH MURDER OF NIECE, 10
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Bronx woman tied her 10-year-old niece to a bed
with garbage bags and beat her repeatedly until she lost
consciousness and died, the authorities said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, identified as Eileen Rodriguez of 645 Van Nest Ave.
in the Parkchester section of the Bronx, was charged with murder
late Friday, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police had originally said the girl suffocated after her aunt
gagged her, but the city medical examiner's office revised the
cause of death Saturday after an autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She died of blunt impact injuries to the head, torso and
extremities,'' said Ellen Borakove, a spokeswoman for the medical
examiner. ``She was beaten to death, and there was no
suffocation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rodriguez called paramedics to her home shortly after 5 a.m.
Friday, telling a 911 operator that she awoke to find the girl
unconscious in her bed, according to police. Ms. Rodriguez was the
legal guardian of the child, Christina, as well as of the girl's
twin sister and her brother, 11.
</P>
<P>
   At first, police believed that Christina might have died of
natural causes. The girl's mother had died of complications from
AIDS several years before, according to police investigators and
neighbors, and it was believed that Christina also might have had
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   After an investigation, detectives found evidence that Ms.
Rodriguez had tied Christina to the bed on Thursday night and
gagged her when she became unruly. They said that it appeared the
girl had vomited and choked to death.
</P>
<P>
   The medical examiner, however, concluded that Christina had not
been gagged but that a towel had been placed over her face. Her
body also showed signs of a severe beating, Ms. Borakove said.
</P>
<P>
   After Ms. Rodriguez's arrest Friday night, workers from the city
Administration for Children's Services took custody of Christina's
sister and brother. Police said those children showed no signs of
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Most neighbors in the five-story brick building where Ms.
Rodriguez lived with the three children described her as always
pleasant. They said the children were clean and well dressed when
they went to school, and that the family had lived there at least
since December.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Administration for Children's Services said
there had been no complaints about the family.
</P>
<P>
   But one neighbor, Juan Cancell, 36, who lived two doors down
from the Rodriguez family on the fourth floor, said there had been
recent signs of strain in the household. A social worker often
checked on the family, he said, and a teacher had recently come
over to ask why the children had been missing school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought they were being punished, so I never said
anything,'' he added. On Thursday night, he said, ``I heard the
girl screaming a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
