</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-POINT-COMMENCEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST POINT COMMENCEMENT INCLUDES SON OF CAMBODIAN PRIME MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ All 934 cadets who graduated Saturday from
the U.S. Military Academy received applause and encouragement, but
only one was trailed by television crews who nearly interrupted the
orderly procession.
</P>
<P>
   Cadet Hun Manet, 21, the son of Cambodia's prime minister,
smiled and gave the thumbs-up sign to the television cameras before
climbing the dais and receiving his diploma from Gen. Dennis J.
Reimer, the Army's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to grad school for two years,'' he said, ``and after
that I have a four-year commitment back home, just like my
friends.'' He said he planned to get a master's graduate degree in
economics at New York University before returning to Cambodia to
serve in the military.
</P>
<P>
   The cadet's father, Hun Sen, 47, was elected prime minister of
Cambodia last year after a violent coup, and some Republican
legislators protested his visit to the United States for the
graduation because of allegations of human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Benjamin A. Gilman, a Republican from Middletown, N.Y., who
attended Friday's ceremony, said, ``As a father, I guess he's
certainly entitled to be here, but we have to be concerned about
his past.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the State Department said the Cambodian leader's
visit to the United States was personal, not official. A State
Department spokeswoman said: ``Hun Sen is here strictly on a visit
for his son's graduation. He's here for no other reason but that.''
</P>
<P>
   During Saturday's ceremony, Reimer warned the graduates that,
like generations before them, they would be responsible for leading
troops into battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that in this modern era, every class that has
graduated from West Point has led soldiers into harm's way,'' he
said, ``and there's no reason to think you will be any different.
No one can predict the future, but as one of the great
philosophers, Yogi Berra, once said, `The future ain't what it used
to be.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reimer alluded to the Kosovo conflict, saying that despite
21st-century technology, the graduates would still have to deal
with ethnic and religious hatreds that go back hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, most of the graduates hugged on the
Astroturf at Michie Stadium here and posed for photographs with
their families, but Hun met with his parents in shaded bleachers
under the guard of Secret Service agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fortunate. It is a pride for the nation as a whole,''
the prime minister said through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister, wearing a blue business suit, was
accompanied by a large entourage, including his wife, his father
and several members of his Cabinet. He congratulated his son, not
with a hug, but with his hands clasped as if in prayer and with a
slight bow.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Manet was one of seven foreign students to graduate
Saturday. West Point has spots for up to 40 foreign students, 10 in
each class, said Andrea Hamberger, a spokeswoman for the academy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
