<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-A     05-29 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: 2 FRIENDS AND THE PUZZLE OF THE KNICKS' POPULARITY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  
 (ATTN: Ind.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They have partied together, and lived together, and
cried together. Mark Jackson confides in his best friend, Dave
Snowden, and so he has logged on to his computer several times this
past week and e-mailed his unexpurgated forecasts of how the New
York Knicks-Indiana Pacers showdown will go.
</P>
<P>
   Snowden, in turn, has responded with his own playoff prophecy,
brief, but directly to the point guard: ``Knicks,'' he says,
defiantly, ``in six.''
</P>
<P>
   He loves Mark Jackson like a brother but has found it impossible
to relinquish the Knicks as his team. Madison Square Garden is
where he served as a ballboy, where he is currently and gainfully
employed. Of course, he will celebrate with Jackson if the Pacers
advance, but he is for the Knicks, as he says he was long before he
became the Garden's director of disabled services in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   His best friend is just one familiar piece to another city's
puzzle but, as Snowden said, ``I'm a New York guy and I've rooted
for the Knicks, no matter who they've had.''
</P>
<P>
   Who these Knicks have and what kind of organization they
represent is a subject that could make world-renowned sociologists
sound like sports talk radio. It is difficult at times to
understand the Knicks' popularity, and, at least for some,
uncomfortable to defend. I know more than a few Knick fans who
wonder if there will be a judgment-day price to pay for Latrell
Sprewell, who cringe at the ``Big L'' preening of Larry Johnson,
who have been appalled by the locker-room proselytizing of Charlie
Ward.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years at least, Knicks officials have been squabbling and
stabbing each other in the back, while the corporate bosses have
unaccountably hid behind well-groomed caretakers like Dave
Checketts. The basketball team that will seize hold of the city
late Sunday afternoon and not let go until its work is complete
also happens to be one that operates beyond the affordability of
most families, and whose parent company has positioned itself to
further propagate its earnings from television as well.
</P>
<P>
   Yet beyond the broadcasting rights, which Charles Dolan's
Cablevision has monopolistically pursued in partnership with Rupert
Murdoch, has come ownership of the uniform, the history, the
memories. No matter how objectionable and dysfunctional these
Knicks have been, they are an extension of the legacy created by
Red Holzman's championship teams. Mark Jackson and Chris Mullin and
Sam Perkins are Pacers who could tell us more about the outer
boroughs than any current Knick, but the Garden is midtown, and
represents the heart of the beloved city game.
</P>
<P>
   As Dave Snowden said in so many words, the roots of Knick
rooting run much deeper than Penn Station. Besides, the comportment
of their fans has often been as distasteful as the behavior of the
most insufferable Knick.
</P>
<P>
   Snowden, 33, was a ballboy for the Knicks in the mid-1980s, on
the night the Garden handed out Patrick Ewing posters and the fans
returned them as projectiles, using Ewing and his then-hapless
teammates as targets. It was Snowden's job to help clear the court,
but what he remembers most was the astonished look on Ewing's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a human being with a family,'' Snowden said. ``At some
point, you've got to realize it's just basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Snowden has been too close for too long not to know that is not
going to happen anytime soon. Agonizing over the Knicks has become
a rite of New York spring, like hungrily consuming a thick deli
sandwich with fatty meat that leaves behind an aching heart. The
debate over the Knicks and their 26-year pursuit of a third
championship reached new discord levels this volatile season,
raging on in the organization and the stands and along press row
like so many cab drivers honking away at each other in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   It all reminded Snowden of a decade ago, when a Jackson not
named Phil was being hailed as the savior, when his friend was a
hot, young Knick and Snowden became business adviser to the
homegrown point guard from St. Albans, Queens, and St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   They had met in college, when Jackson was a sophomore and
Snowden a freshman, and Jackson's parents invited him to stay at
their home to alleviate the weekday commute to Amityville, N.Y.
Snowden shared Mark's early highs and later lows, until one fateful
night, July 9, 1991, when a car crawled along 197th Street and the
window rolled down and bullets sprayed all around the street near
the Jackson home.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a parked car, an innocent bystander, Snowden never
saw the gun. Five bullets left him in a wheelchair and the Jacksons
inconsolable, but it was one of those random acts in a city then
overrun with violent crime and a basketball team coincidentally
earning its reputation for thuggish play. In the years since the
shooting, since Mark Jackson left the Knicks, the friendship
remained a constant in Snowden's radically altered life, Mark there
for him, Snowden there for Mark when Jackson's father, Harry, died
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, after Snowden underwent rehabilitation of the body
and mind, Madison Square Garden gave him a job. The cold and
calculated corporation does have the leverage to command attention,
loyalty, and sometimes it can even convince the masses it is worthy
of their love.
</P>
<P>
   After he put Meg Ryan's children's book shop out of business in
the film ``You've Got Mail,'' didn't Tom Hanks wind up with her in
his arms? The superstore is what these Knicks remind me of,
spending wildly, wreaking havoc with mom-and-pop values, but
finally, forcefully, making everyone in the neighborhood admit that
they've got game.
</P>
<P>
   The small-market Pacers wanted to believe that their
championship plans in the post-Jordan season would not involve
shopping for a victory in New York. There was a Sunday afternoon
late last month when the Knicks, in a calamitous slump, were losing
in Miami by 20 points, with the Pacers glued to their television
sets in a New Jersey hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Snowden was visiting in Mark Jackson's room, where the
telephone would ring every few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was Reggie Miller calling, poking a needle through the line.
``He kept saying, `Your boys are done,''' Snowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Which at the time matched the sentiments of most Knicks fans.
Surprise. The Knicks were about to evolve into a more artistic
team. They rallied to win in Miami that day. They reopened the
possibility of lasting achievement, or leaving the city with fresh,
deeper wounds. Love is too simple an emotion to describe the area's
relationship with its pro basketball team. It is more love-hate,
the inherent paradox of daily life in New York, New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
