New York Times Photo Package, moving 05/29/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 29, 1999 -- BKN-ARATON-COLUMN, 5-29 --
David Snowden, head of disabled services for the Knicks, is Mark
Jackson's best friend but a New York fan. ``I'm a New York guy and
I've rooted for the Knicks, no matter who they've had,'' he says.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) POMPTON LAKES, N.J. -- May 29, 1999 --
BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN, 5-29 -- From left, Russ Pagana, Howard Bell,
Lou Duva and Lou Cuccinello flank the new monument to the champion
in Joe Louis Memorial Park in Pompton Lakes. Louis used to train at
Doc Bier's camp nearby. (Frank C. Dougherty/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- May 29, 1999 -- OBIT-MESERVE-B&AMP;W, 5-29 --
Kathleen Kellogg Meserve with one of her holly cultivars in 1978.
Mrs. Meserve, an amateur horticulturist from Long Island who
produced a series of hardy holly hybrids that have become standard
in nurseries and gardens in the United States and Europe, died last
Sunday at her home in Vero Beach, Fla. She was 93. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- May 29, 1999 -- BAXTER-BOOK, 5-28 -- Gloria
Bley Miller holding the manuscript of the book that she helped to
organize for 75-year-old Freddie Mae Baxter after recording
conversations with her. A hardcover edition of Miss Baxter's
stories and opinions, titled ``The Seventh Child: A Lucky Life,''
was released on May 4. With an announced print run of 125,000,
Knopf is touting it as one of its biggest books of the year.
(Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HARLAN, Iowa -- May 29, 1999 -- FARM-PSYCHOLOGIST, 5-29
-- Dr. Michael Rosmann is a clinical psychologist who knows first
hand the desperation that many rural Iowans are facing. That helps
him counsel his fellow farmers, whom he visits in fields or at
fishing holes, if necessary. (Rodney White/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MORINI, Albania -- May 29, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MISSING-MEN-2,
5-29 -- In the last week, ethnic Albanian men reported missing in
Kosovo expulsions have been arriving at Morini several hundred at a
time. One group is overcome with emotion while crossing the border
into Albania. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MORINI, Albania -- May 29, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MISSING-MEN-1,
5-29 -- Groups of Albanian men who had been rounded up by Serbian
forces are crossing the border into Morini, Albania, with accounts
of mistreatment in a jail in Smrekovnica, north of Pristina. Beslim
Selimi, center, shows injuries he says resulted from beatings by
Serbian captors. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- May 29, 1999 -- KOSOVO-PENTAGON, 5-29 --
President Clinton's top military advisers, Gen. Henry H. Shelton,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, and Defense Secretary
William S. Cohen in Cohen's office. Although President Clinton is
commander in chief, responsible through Cohen and Shelton for
American forces, the war is not being run at the White House or at
the Pentagon. Instead, General Clark, an American, is has been
running it from Belgium. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) TORREON, Mexico -- May 29, 1999 --
MEXICO-LEAD-POISONING-2, 5-29 -- Families like Claudia Elena
Arellano and her four daughters, who live downwind from a lead
smelter, suffer symptoms of lead poisoning. Recent tests of
children from one corner of the neighborhood were so high that
authorities ordered 393 families to be evacuated and their houses
demolished, in what has become one of the most severe environmental
emergencies Mexico has ever faced. (Keith Dannemiller/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) TORREON, Mexico -- May 29, 1999 --
MEXICO-LEAD-POISONING-1, 5-29 -- Mounds of lead-laden dirt wait to
be refined at the Met-Mex Penoles plant in Torreon. Winds blow dust
from them into a neighborhood where children tested by public
health officials had lead levels considered unsafe. (Keith
Dannemiller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- May 29, 1999 -- BRONX-ZOO-GORILLAS, 5-29 --
Tunko, foreground, and Paki taking in their new home at the Bronx
Zoo's Congo Gorilla Forest. The 6.5-acre exhibit will open next
month, and in the meantime the zoo's gorillas are adjusting to the
place. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
