<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-BALLFIELD-NYT &LR;      05-29 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-BALLFIELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, A FIELD OF DREAMS CAN BE A NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore.)  (Eds., also filed in `a' category)  
(rk) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEWKSBURY, N.J. _ As a story, it was too good to write without a
snicker: all-American dad builds a full-size ball field in his
backyard for his son and his son's friends, snooty neighbors take
dad to court.
</P>
<P>
   When the story of Bill Ingraham's backyard ballpark ran on the
networks and in the papers across the country last summer, a lot of
people got a good chuckle about the magic of the national pastime
and shook their heads about the cluelessness of some people.
</P>
<P>
   But as Kathy DeSerio, 42, found out when she joined a lawsuit
against Ingraham, the truth is more complex than funny stories
sometimes suggest, and the costs of taking on the myths and magic
of the national pastime are counted in more than legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   In her quest to reclaim the peace and quiet of her carefully
restored house, which sits out by Ingraham's short left field, Ms.
DeSerio has felt portrayed as the lady who hates children and
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when I went into this that I would subject myself to
ridicule, because the story was just too perfect _ dad and baseball
and `Field of Dreams' and all,'' Ms. DeSerio said. ``Now I have to
ask myself, do I really need this?
</P>
<P>
   Do I need letters from a dentist in Oregon asking why I'm taking
the national pastime away from these little boys?'' Or, she
wonders, does she need the whispers at the supermarket about the
childless, unmarried woman who hates children? Or the anonymous,
threatening phone messages?
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, the Township of Tewksbury, Ms. DeSerio and
another neighbor are charging that the field, which has cost
Ingraham $75,000 to build and $1,500 a month to maintain, violates
zoning and is a public nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   Final written arguments were presented Friday after three weeks
of testimony. And what came out in the trial is evidence that the
diamond behind Ms. DeSerio's house is no field of dreams, and that
Ingraham, a barrel-chested, blunt-talking businessman who made his
fortune with peel-and-stick shipping labels, is no Kevin Costner.
</P>
<P>
   Ingraham confirmed under cross-examination that he has called
opponents of his ball field ``white trash'' and homosexuals. In a
letter admitted into evidence, he told the mayor of Tewksbury that
``you can't decide if you want to be a man or a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, he has said that anyone trying to take away his
ball field will have to go through him personally. In testimony
about the kind of people he allows to use the field, Ingraham was
asked _ hypothetically _ whether he would invite even a Little
Leaguer who had beaten up his 11-year-old son, Brian. ``Yes, I
would,'' Ingraham replied, ``to give Brian a chance to beat him
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked in an interview whether people might be getting a negative
impression of him, he said, ``When somebody attacks me or my
family, I attack back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingraham's personality has been mostly lost in articles
straining to be lighthearted, and the lights and noise of the
practices, parties and games behind Ms. DeSerio's house have
largely been left out.
</P>
<P>
   ``People write letters to the paper _ `I like it when kids play
ball in my backyard' _ like this was just Johnny and Timmy
playing,'' Ms. DeSerio said. ``If it was just a couple of kids
playing and an occasional ball falls in my yard, who the heck would
care? I certainly would not. But these are men hitting balls into
my backyard, and the `ping ping ping' of aluminum bats, and the
pitching machine, and it's hard for people to understand the extent
of it all. So I come off looking like Mrs. Crabtree.''
</P>
<P>
   So the letters have come. ``This is America, land of the free,
home of the brave,'' a dentist in Astoria, Ore., wrote to Ms.
DeSerio. And the anonymous phone calls have come as well, some
supportive, and some bad enough to make her upgrade her home
security system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is who I am, this is my dream,'' she said, taking in the
house and its carefully landscaped yard and patio while a red
tractor groomed the outfield 100 feet away. ``I came here to live
in the country, in open, quiet farmland, and now I have an active
ball park in my backyard. Is this how my dream ends?''
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision on that could come as early as this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
