<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL LAKERS, ALL THE TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's ``NBA Notes'' column has been pre-empted in favor of
``Laker Chatter,'' which we join in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Host: Let's go to Kazaam on a car phone.
</P>
<P>
   Kazaam: Thanks for takin' my call, bro.
</P>
<P>
   Host: Please speak up, Kazaam, and ixnay on the rap music.
</P>
<P>
   Kazaam: Sorry, bro. OK, I know how to fix the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Host: I'm listening.
</P>
<P>
   Kazaam: Cool. Well, I think Jerry West should trade up and draft
Baron Davis to play point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Host: Really? The Lakers have the 23rd pick. You package that
and what, exactly? Sean Rooks? Robert Horry? Sean Rooks, Robert
Horry and Travis Knight? Who do you think these other GMs are, Dan
Quayle?
</P>
<P>
   Kazaam: None of the above, bro. All you have to do is trade Kobe
Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Host: Seriously?
</P>
<P>
   Kazaam: I'm serious as a heart attack, bro. The only thing Kobe
can't jump over is his ego. So ... trade him.
</P>
<P>
   Host: I have two words for that, Kaz. Stu and pid. Let's go to
Jack in Hollywood. You there, Jack?
</P>
<P>
   Jack: I'm here. Hey, get a load a this ... About 10 minutes ago,
I saw Shoeless Phil Jackson and that Knicks guy, Dave Checketts, at
a Winchell's.
</P>
<P>
   Host: We just deal in the truth here, Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Jack: You can't handle the truth. Oh ... you got any ``Phantom
Menace'' tickets?
</P>
<P>
   Host: No, but we do have a traffic report. Let's go to Roy in
Chopper I.
</P>
<P>
   Roy: We got heavy delays on the northbound 405. It seems that
Kobe Bryant is driving wildly in the diamond lane with nobody else
in his car. Back to you.
</P>
<P>
   Host: Too bad we can't get Glen Rice to drive more. Anyway,
let's go to Barry in Inglewood. What's up, Barry?
</P>
<P>
   Barry: My patience. Everybody wants the Lakers to trade up for
Baron Davis, but nobody offers any suggestions on how to do that.
Or they want the Lakers to go out and just ``find'' a power forward
to match up with Tim Duncan. There's no cap room and we ... I mean
the Lakers ... don't pick until 23, like you said, and the draft is
about as deep as an episode of ``Walker, Texas Ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   Host: I'm sorry, my headset went dead. Could you repeat that,
Barry? Barry? OK ... our next caller is, uh, Burt ... Burt
Incognito.
</P>
<P>
   Burt: Yeah, I'm a first-time caller, first-time listener and I
think I know what the Lakers should do ... they should keep Kurt
Rambis as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Host: But he sucked.
</P>
<P>
   Burt: Given the situation, what first-time coach wouldn't?
</P>
<P>
   Host: Larry Bird, last year.
</P>
<P>
   Burt: Larry Bird took over a Pacers team with defined roles and
a deep bench. Kurt, who happens to be way handsomer than Bird, as
well, needs an entire training camp. Remember, Rome wasn't built in
a short season, and if NBA players can learn to accept a balding
weasel like Jeff Van Gundy, I think they'll follow Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   Host: Sorry, you're out of time, Burt, and so are we. Stay tuned
for ``Clipper Banter.''
</P>
<P>
   CLIPPER BANTER
</P>
<P>
   What does falling from the second seed to fourth position in the
draft rotation mean to the Clippers?
</P>
<P>
   It means they could be in an ugly predicament on draft night
(June 30).
</P>
<P>
   At the top of their prioritized wish list is the job of point
guard. Two swell suspects for that role are Maryland's Steve
Francis and Baron Davis of UCLA. But both may be goners before the
Clippers choose at No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   There are other playmakers available, but they (at this time)
seem dreadfully unworthy of the fourth pick. This could inspire the
Clips to trade down (in the unlikely event they can fleece someone
else out of a proven player) to get one, or pray that two of the
teams picking 1-3 bypass either Francis or Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago has the first pick, but unless coach Tim Floyd decides
to bury the triangle offense, the Bulls may not be in the market
for a point guard. Vancouver, home of rookie playmaker Mike Bibby,
has the second pick, but may try to unload it in exchange for a
veteran who can rebound and score.
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte Hornets, whose point guard, David Wesley, would
rather shoot first and ask questions later, figure to stay put and
draft a new floor leader.
</P>
<P>
   One nasty threat to trade up and pluck a point guard is
presented by the Toronto Raptors. The Raptors have two lottery
picks (5 and 12), and are waving them in front of Bulls personnel
poo-bah Jerry Krause. By the way, putting the first pick in
Krause's hands could be as tricky as giving Jerry Springer a
nuclear launch code.
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors reportedly are lusting after Francis, an aerial
maniac who would team with rookie of the year Vince Carter and his
cousin, Tracy McGrady, to give Toronto more style points than a
victory lap at Spago.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' guest list for this week includes Arizona point
guard Jason Terry, Miami of Ohio forward Wally Szczerbiak and
Davis. They also are attempting to bring in Francis, Duke deserter
Corey Maggette and Lamar Odom of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case Francis and Davis are history before it's their
turn to strike, the Clippers are exploring all options. On
Thursday, for instance, they conducted an audition that included a
high-brow two-on-two series involving William Avery, Trajan
Langdon, Shammond Williams and God Shammgod.
</P>
<P>
   Avery is the point guard who's leaving Duke after his sophomore
season and has been known to become derelict in his duties when
he's not scoring in bunches. Langdon is a deadeye 6-foot-3 shooting
guard who's leaving Duke after five years (one redshirt), and has
the pedestrian quickness that could keep him on the board until the
Clips make the second pick of the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is a 6-2 combo guard who finished his senior year at
North Carolina in 1998, was drafted by the Bulls in the second
round, acquired and dumped by Atlanta, and cut his playmaking teeth
this season in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Shammgod is the former New York City prep star who spent one
season at Providence and one on the end of the Washington Wizards'
bench. The Wizards cut God, who is a ballhandling revelation,
before this season.
</P>
<P>
   Should events conspire to bring Shammgod into the Clipper fold,
it could present a serious dilemma for broadcast great Ralph
Lawler. Unless he's Catholic, Lawler may find it unholy to shout
``God!'' and ``Bingo!'' in the same sentence.
</P>
<P>
   SHOT-CLOCK VIOLATIONS
</P>
<P>
   The Utah Jazz, who could use another young turk or two, have
three first-round picks next month. OK, the earliest is 19 (the
others are 24 and 28), but they did find Bryon Russell and Shandon
Anderson in the second round. Then again, if the newcomers require
a similar incubation period, Karl Malone (the No. 13 pick in 1985)
and John Stockton (16th in 1984) will be in rocking chairs before
the kids are ready to help. ... The Atlanta Hawks have four
first-round picks (17, 20, 21 and 27), but they haven't exactly
killed in the draft lately. Their three best players -- Steve
Smith, Mookie Blaylock and Dikembe Mutombo -- were drafted by other
teams. In fairness to the Hawks, making the playoffs for seven
consecutive years ruins your opportunities to score with the
college kids. ... Alexsandar Radojevic, the 7-3, 245-pound prospect
from Barton County (Kan.) JC (by way of Montenegro), is making
pre-draft visits and is expected to be chosen in the middle of the
first round. ...According to our source in Roswell, N.M., Phil
Jackson and Dave Checketts, king of the Knicks, were seen swilling
espresso at Denny's. Could be a bogus report ... we're pretty
certain Denny's doesn't serve espresso.
</P>
</TEXT>
