<P>
   GUNS-BUYBACK _ On Saturday, in response to recent school
shootings, the SCLC resumes its gun buyback program, paying $50 for
all guns turned in. Parents of Isaiah Shoels, killed at Columbine,
will be on hand.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EXPECTATIONS _ As he emerges from the cocoon and morphs
into full- fledged presidential candidate, Gov. George W. Bush is
about to run head-first into a formidable foe who hasn't raised a
dime, doesn't have a bumper sticker and has been even less specific
on issues than Bush. ``Expectations,'' says Bush adviser Karl Rove,
without missing a beat when he's asked to name his guy's most
challenging opponent. Bush, proclaimed the frontrunner by poll and
press, is about to try to meet those expectations, an effort that
has derailed more than one high-flying politician. As he hits the
road, don't look for Bush to offer much in the way of specifics on
issues. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WRIGHTS _ One hundred years ago today, Wilbur Wright, 32, sat
down at his desk and wrote a letter to the Smithsonian Institution
in Washington. ``Dear Sirs,'' he wrote, and in typical Wright
fashion, he got to the point: ``I have been interested in the
problem of mechanical and human flight ever since as a boy I
constructed a number of bats (toy helicopters powered by rubber
bands) of various sizes . . . My observations since have only
convinced me more firmly that human flight is possible and
practicable...'' Wilbur was writing to ask the Smithsonian to send
any papers that could help him in a ``systematic study'' of flight
that he expected to undertake apart from his regular business,
selling bicycles. He wanted the Smithsonian to know he was sincere.
In a sentence that became famous _ in a letter that Wright
biographer Tom Crouch calls ``the most important exchange of
correspondence in the history of the Smithsonian'' _ Wilbur wrote:
``I am an enthusiast but not a crank in the sense that I have some
pet theories as to the proper construction of a flying machine.''
(Kline, Dayton Daily News). 19.
</P>
<P>
   KASICH _ DERRY, N.H. _ John Kasich will not simply read a
speech. Or he can't. Or both. ``When I read,'' he said, ``it just
doesn't come from the heart.'' If you're looking for a single word
to explain why this modestly well-known congressman from Columbus,
Ohio, is campaigning for the Republican nomination for president,
this is it. Heart. (Montgomery, Cox News Service). 70. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Moved Monday in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   BARR-WITCHES _ Bob Barr faces toil and trouble as witches,
wounded by his slings and arrows, stir up his town meeting
Saturday. (Visser, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-PREVIEW _ Preview of the 1999 hurricane season that
begins June 1, focusing on worries in the main target of recent
years_the Florida Panhandle. (MWilliams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WHITEWATER-REOPENS _ White water opens for the season this
weekend. What has changed there, how is the public's confidence in
white water, how are ticket sales going, etc. Walt Weiss is being
used as a way to get us into the story. (Farber, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WHITEWATER-WEISS _ Walt Weiss, most visible relative of a
Whitewater victim and unofficial leader of the parents, talks about
life a year after the e coli scare. (Farber, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EXTREME-TV _ Television is both more violent and less violent
than it used to be. Top-rated prime-time shows have very little
violence, yet Extreme TV grows around the fringes: pro wrestling,
Fox's violence-verite, Jerry Springer (they promised to tone down
the violence before, and didn't) and even local TV news and network
newsmgazines. What's causing Extreme TV? The audience
fragmentation, the hard-to-capture but lucrative market of young
men and teenaged boys, and overall social trends. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   RIVALS-MAIN _ The battle between the two major pro wrestling
groups, WWF and WCW, may not have killed Owen Hart, as his family
claims, but it has helped shape the ``sport'' in the '90s, its most
prosperous era. WWF is on top for now, but both it and Ted
Turner-owned WCW are doing very, very well. (Thomas/Scott, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30-35. MOVED.
</P>
