<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-PLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US FINDS NOTHING NEW IN LATEST STATEMENTS FROM BELGRADE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A declaration by Yugoslav leaders that they would
accept the outlines of a Western peace plan revived a familiar
debate among leaders of NATO countries Saturday, as two European
nations urged fresh diplomatic efforts and US officials
characterized the Yugoslav statement as meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   The prime ministers of Germany and France called for a meeting
of the G-8, consisting of the world's top industrialized countries
and Russia, to assess last week's talks between Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and Russian envoy Viktor S. Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   But Pentagon officials, who dispatched a new unit of planes to
the Balkans Saturday to step up airstrikes, said they had ``not
seen any signs'' Milosevic was ready to submit to key NATO demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not seen any signs of an end to the fighting,''
Pentagon spokesman Captain Michael Doubleday said. ``We have not
seen any signs of troops moving out of Kosovo. We have not heard
from him in a very direct way indicating that he is looking for an
international peacekeeping force.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NATO warplanes pounded Yugoslavia with bombs for a
67th straight day. The Pentagon announcement that 68 additional
planes are heading to the Balkans will swell a NATO force that
already has more than 1,000 aircraft. With the arrival of the 20
KC-135 tankers, 12 F-16 jets and 36 F-15 jets, the United States
will account for more than two-thirds of the allied air power in
the Balkans, with 769 planes.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright addressed the high
number of mistakes that NATO warplanes have made, admitting allied
forces have killed civilians during the 10-week attack. But she
said that NATO, unlike Yugoslavia, has taken ``great pains'' to
avoid civilian deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best that can be said for Milosevic is that he doesn't
kill people by accident,'' Albright told graduates of Georgetown
University's School of Foreign Service. ``On the contrary, the
death and destruction of Kosovo's Albanian community is the whole
point of Milosevic's war.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   --The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees continued to
move Kosovar refugees in Albania away from the border, where
fighting between Serb troops and the Kosovo Liberation Army and the
Albanian Army has intensified in recent days. Some 30,000 of the
approximately 450,000 Kosovar refugees now living in Albania still
remain in the camps near Kukes, close to the border of their
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to convince them to move,'' said the Albanian
government's coordinator for human affairs, Kaspriot Islami. ``So
far, we have been successful.''
</P>
<P>
   --On Friday afternoon, NATO planes bombarded targets on the
Adriatic coast of Montenegro, the small and largely autonomous
Yugoslav republic to the west of Serbia. Military leaders had been
trying not to hit the republic out of concern for its pro-Western
government, but were drawn in by Yugoslav antiaircraft radar along
the coast. NATO said it was the largest attack on Montenegro in a
month.
</P>
<P>
   --Australian officials called the imprisonment of two Australian
aid workers ``incomprehensible.'' Steve Pratt and Peter Wallace,
who work for the aid agency CARE, were arrested March 31 along the
border of Croatia and Serbia. Australian authorities said the men
were trying to bring food and supplies to Serb refugees, but were
arrested when Yugoslav border guards mistook their humanitarian
reports for spying material.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt was sentenced to 12 years in jail, and Wallace was
sentenced to four years, after being found guilty by a Yugoslav
military court.
</P>
<P>
   --The Japanese prime minister, Masahiko Komura, issued a public
plea for the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia to stop. During a visit to
Moscow Saturday, Komura's spokesman said the prime minister was
``very worried'' about the air campaign after meeting with Russian
leaders, who vehemently opposed the bombings from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although our possibilities are limited _ we are not a
permanent member of the UN Security Council _ Japan appeals to NATO
to halt its attacks,'' the spokesman, Masaki Ikada, said, according
to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Komura met with Russian Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin and
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   But a meeting with Chernomyrdin, who had just returned from
talks with Milosevic in Belgrade, was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin is expected to return to Belgrade this week. Both
he and Yugoslav officials emerged from the latest round of talks
expressing optimism, with sources close to Chernomyrdin saying he
was ``very satisfied by his visit to Belgrade'' and members of the
Yugoslav government saying the meeting was ``positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials also said they were amenable to the basic
outlines of an earlier plan drawn up by the G-8. Milosevic's office
issued a statement saying it wanted the United Nations Security
Council to deal with ``the entire problem.'' But the statement did
not explicitly agree to the central tenets of the peace plan: the
withdrawal of Serb troops from Kosovo and the acceptance of an
international peacekeeping force to protect Kosovars as they return
safely to their homes inside the province.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, France and Germany, which have been reluctant to
assemble the invasion force repeatedly requested by Britain,
reacted warmly to the development. Issuing a joint statement,
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany and President Jacques
Chirac of France asked for a meeting of the G-8 to assess the
latest talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``France and Germany consider it necessary to examine whether
the content of this declaration can lead to a political solution on
the basis of our principles,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials were far more skeptical. Spokesman Peter Daniel
reiterated NATO's commitment to continuing the bombardment, saying
that ``Milosevic's military commanders and the troops they direct
should understand that there will be no relief until Yugoslavia
accepts the non-negotiable demands of the international
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The warning was accompanied by reports from Yugoslav media that
NATO airstrikes Saturday killed three people and wounded 20,
including three children who were seriously hurt when a missile
struck their house.
</P>
</TEXT>
