<SLUG> BC-TRIAL-AID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE HUMANITARIAN WORKERS CONVICTED OF SPYING IN YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Three humanitarian aid workers Saturday were
convicted by a Yugoslav military court of spying and given
sentences ranging from four to 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   The lengthy jail sentences could have a chilling effect on the
ability and willingness of various humanitarian groups to bring in
the aid workers needed in all parts of Yugoslavia, including
Kosovo. But CARE, the humanitarian group for which the three men
work, vowed to appeal the sentences, insisting the men were
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   After a four-day trial, the presiding judge, Ratko Korlat,
simply read out that Australian aid workers Stephen Pratt and Peter
Wallace had been sentenced to 12 and 4 years, respectively. Their
Yugoslav colleague, Branko Jelen, was sentenced to six years. They
had faced up to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Australians showed no emotion when the sentences were read,
but Jelen's mother, watching in the gallery, screamed that her son
was innocent. Jelen then wept.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the court, the Australian ambassador to Yugoslavia,
Christopher Lamb, said he could not fathom the conviction, and
thought the sentences were unusually harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Because the court was closed to reporters and international
observers while evidence was heard, it was unclear on what basis
the five-judge military panel had ruled. The men were originally
charged with organizing a spy ring, but their conviction was for
simple espionage. Their lawyers were studying whether that
discrepancy was fertile ground for an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   A legal source said that the military officers who presided over
the trial had said they did not consider Pratt's alleged confession
to spying, which had been shown on government-controlled television
April 11, nearly two weeks after Pratt and Wallace were seized at
the Croatian border.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, 49, who is the chief of operations for CARE Australia in
Yugoslavia, and Wallace, 30, were headed to neighboring Croatia
when they were arrested by Yugoslav border guards who apparently
became suspicious of the maps, laptop computers, and computer disks
carried by the pair. Authorities have not said why or how Jelen was
subsequently arrested.
</P>
<P>
   When they were arrested, the two Australians were en route to
the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro to help set up a camp for
Kosovar Albanians driven out by Milosevic's forces, according to
former Australian prime minister Malcolm Fraser, who is the head of
CARE Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers in other parts of the Balkans who know Pratt said he
kept copious notes about the location of military checkpoints so
that his workers could avoid them if necessary, and suggest that
information may have been seized upon by Yugoslav officials as
evidence of spying. A friend of Pratt's suggested that his status
as an Australian Army veteran was also held against him, even
though Australia is not a member of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Tapp, head of CARE Australia, said the verdict was ``a
political decision. It has no basis in justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb predicted that the men would be acquitted on appeal,
hinting that diplomatic efforts behind the scenes were trying to
win the men's release on the basis of an amnesty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
