<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-LEDE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Coca-Cola bubbling with anticipation
</P>
<P>
   By Al Levine
</P>
<P>
   c 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Kyle Petty ripped the state of Winston Cup stock
car racing the other day, testifying that it has become ``boring.''
Boy, did he pick the wrong weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's Coca-Cola 600 at Lowe's Motor Speedway has a
garage-full of storylines, including one of the tired old ones
involving Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   It's the big-league debut of Dale Earnhardt Jr., the most
heavily hyped introduction in years, starting in the eighth
position in the No. 8 Chevrolet. He did nothing to diminish the
hype Saturday with the third-fastest lap in morning practice,
179.533 mph, and the second-fastest in happy hour, 176.321 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them guys are tough,'' Junior said of his new running mates.
``I just got my car running pretty good in practice this morning.
At least we'll be competitive with some of these guys. It's a
different program over there, the cars drive different.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the second leg of Tony Stewart's iron-man effort:
Indianapolis 500 in the afternoon, Coke 600 in the evening. He'll
be bumped to the back of the field (he qualified fourth) if he
misses the 4:15 p.m. driver's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But there he was late Saturday afternoon, running the fastest
lap in the final Cup practice, 176.528 mph, before jetting to
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   There's the Jeff Gordon factor: He's going for his third
consecutive win in the Coca-Cola 600. He qualified 10th. Bobby
Labonte starts on the pole for the second time in two weeks at this
track.
</P>
<P>
   Points leader Dale Jarrett will try to pick his way through the
field _ as he did to win at Richmond _ starting 28th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long day and the main thing we're trying to ensure is
that we're gonna be there all day,'' Jarrett said. ``I just want to
make sure I take the time to get it up in the top five and then get
it adjusted at night because the track is probably gonna change
more the last 200 miles compared to what we see the first 300 or
400.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than all that, it's just another NASCAR weekend. The
results may well bear out Petty's contention: ``It's a homogenized
sport. Everybody looks the same, does the same, talks the same and
gives the same answers. The bigger it gets it seems to lose a
little bit of its character.''
</P>
<P>
   But the pre-race anticipation is anything but routine. Perhaps a
Little E can make a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, after beating Earnhardt Jr., in the Busch Carquest
300, Mark Martin said he wouldn't be surprised to see Little E in
victory lane today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might win this thing,'' Martin said. ``One of his (team's)
greatest assets is they don't know for sure how hard it's going to
be, and that's good. They'll just go out there and do it. Nothing
will hold them back if they go with what they feel and no history
to consider. I have no idea how he'll finish but he`s obviously an
incredibly talented young man.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
