<P>
   LIBERTY-CONCEPT-2TAKES (Kansas City, Mo.) _ More than 80 years
later _ as Americans prepare to celebrate the last Memorial Day
before 2000 _ the definition of liberty has extended far beyond
many people's notion of freedom from tyranny. By ERIC ADLER. Story
will move in the ``a'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIANS-LIBERTY (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Sidebar to
LIBERTY-CONCEPT. Eighteen years ago, Alex Kucherovsky emigrated
from Kiev in the former Soviet Union with $500 in his pocket. He
came to Kansas City with his wife, Anna, and two daughters,
Svetlana, 7, and Maria, 5 months. He had family here but little
else. Today, the owner of Alex's Shoe Repair in Blue Springs, Mo.,
owns a fine home in Overland Park, Kan., mortgage paid. Svetlana,
26, is applying to dental school. Maria, 18, is married and having
a baby. By ERIC ADLER. Story will move in the ``a'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIANS-LIBERTY (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Sidebar to
LIBERTY-CONCEPT. Jasmin and Izeta Hadzibegovic arrived in Kansas
City as Bosnian political refugees just over a year ago with their
daughters, Erna, 11, and Belma, 14. Before that they spent six
restless years in a refugee camp in Germany, never quite sure
whether they might return home. So now they are in America, where,
to Jasmin and Izeta, liberty is about having the opportunity to
work hard, raise a family, earn a living and afford their daughters
a good education and a better future. By ERIC ADLER. Story will
move in the ``a'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIANS-LIBERTY (Kansas City, Mo.) Sidebar to
LIBERTY-CONCEPT. At 2 a.m. one Saturday, 18-year-old Sambath Ngek
switched on the lamp in her room. Her mother, Sambo Prom, was
already awake. Thirty minutes later, as the city slept, the two
were on the highway driving from their bungalow to a local
supermarket 20 miles away in the suburbs. Work in the bakery begins
at 3. Sambath would never say the hours are ideal. But she knows,
from her parents' tales of Cambodia, that ``ideal'' is relative. By
ERIC ADLER. Story will move in the ``a'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIANS-LIBERTY (Kansas City, Mo.) Sidebar to LIBERTY-CONCEPT.
Thirty-two-year-old Prince-Will Neebani of Nigeria yanked off his
sneakers and pulled his jacket off his naked shoulders. Every
morning he got 50 strikes with cable, he said, pointing to the
scars on his feet, shoulders, back and chest. Ten months he was
imprisoned with no trial for being a youth organizer. Prince-Will's
mother, Salome, is 47. The Nigerian government tortured her in
prison and killed her husband for speaking out and demanding
compensation from the Nigerian government for the environmental
destruction of the Ogoni people's once-fertile tribal land.
Prince-Will and Salome escaped to a refugee camp and was relocated
to Kansas City. By ERIC ADLER. Story will move in the ``a''
category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-SCHOOLS-2TAKES (Chicago) _ Beethoven Elementary is
indicative of how far this city had to go to turn around its deeply
troubled public school system. In 1990, just 5 percent of
Beethoven's nearly 900 students scored at or above national norms
in reading. Only 11 percent scored at those levels in math. In many
cases, the problems Beethoven and Chicago faced were representative
of those faced by Kansas City, Mo., and other major U.S. cities
that are failing to educate their children, especially poor
minorities. By PHILLIP O'CONNOR. Story will move in the ``a''
category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPY-2TAKES (Washington) _ The furor over Chinese spying
overlooks one fact: everyone does it. Espionage is simply the way
of the world, and it has been at least since the Bible. Joshua used
spies. So did Moses. By DAVID GOLDSTEIN and RICK MONTGOMERY. Story
will move in the ``w'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NO-MONEY (Sweet Springs, Mo.) _ Five years ago folks here
decided they needed to replace their 40-year-old, book-jammed
library, which _ with just 700 square feet of space _ was smaller
than most convenience stores. The cost? Estimates came to $70,000.
Over the years the city had squirreled away $40,000 for just such a
project. The rest seemed easy _ the federal Library Services
Construction Act would pony up the remaining $30,000 in the form of
a grant. When the grant was approved, Sweet Springs turned the
federal money down flat. By JIM FISHER. Story will move in the
``a'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOBILE-ETIQUETTE-2TAKES (Kansas City, Mo.) _ As wireless phones
become more popular, the chance of someone's call interrupting your
enjoyment is increasing. And a backlash is growing against those
who do not consider that their calls can be an annoyance to others.
Call it ``phone rage.'' By ROBERT A. CRONKLETON. Story will move in
the ``a'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
