<HEADLINE>
MUSINGS ON RUBIN, MUSER AND MORE TO LAST THE LONG WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marketplace musings for a long holiday weekend: Nothing about
the stock market has been more reassuring than the way investors
have begun to rediscover honest-to-goodness, real-world value.
</P>
<P>
   - Reasonable minds may disagree on what performance rating to
give outgoing Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, but a grateful
nation should be thankful to him for his probity in office.
</P>
<P>
   - Speaking of performance, those who theorize that a baseball
manager doesn't have much effect on a team's fortunes should pay
closer attention to the what the Royals' Tony Muser is doing with
the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   - Why are the chips at the bottom of the package always so
crumbly?
</P>
<P>
   - Wake me when the ``Star Wars'' wretched excesses have run
their course.
</P>
<P>
   - John McCain is so far the only presidential candidate to
emerge with anything remotely resembling the leadership qualities
Americans once demanded of candidates for the nation's highest
office.
</P>
<P>
   - Whatever happened to Robert Blake?
</P>
<P>
   - ``Law &AMP; Order'' is the best prime-time drama on television.
</P>
<P>
   - You're getting old if you can remember when men's billfolds
were routinely referred to as wallets.
</P>
<P>
   - You can bet that when a television program opens with a
``warning'' about adult language and situations, what follows isn't
likely to have anything to do with how reasonably mature adults
behave.
</P>
<P>
   - Is it my imagination, or were Kansas and Missouri legislators
particularly unproductive during this year's sessions?
</P>
<P>
   - The seeming progress in the push to abolish boarding
restrictions at Missouri's riverboat casinos is certainly good news
for everyone who thinks adults should be treated like adults.
</P>
<P>
   - With all the high-tech gizmos television stations blather
about to woo viewers, surely some resident genius could come up
with a way to show the weather-alert graphic without superimposing
it over the on-screen score and clock display during NBA playoff
games.
</P>
<P>
   - My goal in life is to spend my entire existence on the planet
without ever seeing a ``Star Wars'' movie, and so far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   - You know the new era on Wall Street has finally been
recognized as such because nobody gets spastic anymore when the Dow
Jones industrial average suffers a low triple-digit loss.
</P>
<P>
   - Even though Jeff King's retirement didn't cost him his entire
'99 pay package, the former Royal still wins this year's Diogenes
Award for being honest enough to walk away instead of faking it
just to keep the big paychecks coming.
</P>
<P>
   - The big-money television match pitting Tiger Woods against
David Duval as prime-time entertainment risks making golf a trash
sport.
</P>
<P>
   - Forget about it if you're expecting the same magnitude of
media reaction over Chinagate that it showed over Iran-Contra.
</P>
<P>
   - Are African violets still as popular as houseplants as they
were during my youth?
</P>
<P>
   - The decision by Ford to build another new vehicle model at its
Claycomo plant is yet another big vote of confidence in Kansas City
and its labor force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
