<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-SCHOOLS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO SCHOOLS HELD AS A MODEL FOR WHAT KC COULD DO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Beethoven Elementary is indicative of how far this
city had to go to turn around its deeply troubled public school
system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, just 5 percent of Beethoven's nearly 900 students
scored at or above national norms in reading. Only 11 percent
scored at those levels in math.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were struggling,'' said Frances Oden, who worked at the
school 30 years before becoming principal in 1994. ``We were
struggling for parental involvement, for children to achieve, to
get teachers to go back to school for additional degrees. We were
struggling for repairs, to get more money for things we wanted to
do. There was a lot of instability.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the problems Beethoven and Chicago faced were
representative of those faced by Kansas City, Mo., and other major
U.S. cities that are failing to educate their children, especially
poor minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see in America now is urban flight because of
schools,'' said Chicago Mayor Richard Daley, who took over
responsibility for the schools in 1995. ``Any city over 100,000 (in
population) is in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade after reform began in the 430,000-student
Chicago Public Schools, things are much different at Beethoven.
</P>
<P>
   More than 35 percent of Beethoven's students now score at or
above national norms in reading. Math scores show similar
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   And while academic performance at Beethoven and districtwide
still trail national standards, a steady trend of improvement is
evident. Truancy is down across the district. By 1997, test scores
had shown a seven-year upward trend at 157 of the district's nearly
560 public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Graduation rates are also up slightly. Expectations are high.
And people are moving back into the public schools in the nation's
third-largest district.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is sold on the Chicago way. Nor are they convinced
that the changes enacted there can work for every city.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chicago's progress is drawing the attention of political
leaders and educators across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mayor Emanuel Cleaver even flirted with the idea of a
mayoral takeover of the Kansas City School District, similar to
what happened in Chicago, before he left office in April. Mayor Kay
Barnes says she has no interest in running the district.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Chase, the district's interim chief administrator for
curriculum and instruction, said Kansas City planned to introduce a
summer school program based on the Chicago model. The district also
plans to require third-, fifth- and eighth-grade students to pass
mandatory tests before advancing to the next grade. Chicago already
requires such tests.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said the Chicago reforms provided hope for improving the
Kansas City district.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a system as large as Chicago can initiate some of these
positive changes, I certainly think it is possible in a smaller
district like Kansas City,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of Chicago's reform movement were planted more than a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of turmoil and bolstered by educational and business
studies detailing the failure of the schools, Chicagoans in 1988
descended on the state capital to demand change.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers responded with the Chicago School Reform Law.
</P>
<P>
   The law stripped much of the power and money from a highly
politicized central bureaucracy and redistributed it to every
school through local school councils. The councils have six
parents, two teachers, two community members and the principal; in
high schools, one student sits on the council.
</P>
<P>
   They meet about once a month and are responsible for developing
school improvement plans, making budget decisions, and hiring and
evaluating the principal.
</P>
<P>
   For the first several years, however, reforms moved forward
unevenly, with many schools showing no progress. Most agree it
wasn't until 1995, when the state gave Daley sweeping authority
over the troubled system, that true reform took hold.
</P>
<P>
   Daley immediately appointed his chief of staff to head a reform
board. And he chose the city's budget director, Paul Vallas, to
take over day-to-day administration of the district.
</P>
<P>
   Daley's team immediately overhauled a bloated budget, made peace
with the teachers union, and invested millions of dollars of city
money in school building repairs and construction.
</P>
<P>
   The district next turned its attention to academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the district put on probation 109 schools that had 15
percent or less of their students scoring at or above national
norms. The district then gave those schools intensive help to
improve. Seven high schools that continued to fail were
reconstituted. Three principals were fired, and nearly 200 teachers
were removed from the schools.
</P>
<P>
   The system also extended the school day and added preschool
classes, tutors and after-school programs. Schools once again
became the centers of community activities. Some schools now stay
open until 10 p.m. on weeknights and 6 p.m. Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   The district also ended the practice of social promotion by
requiring students to pass tests in reading and math in the third,
sixth, eighth and ninth grades before being allowed to advance to
the next grade. In 1997 alone, the district held back 16,000
students. Students held back must attend summer school. &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6179 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICAGO-SCHOOLS-2NDTA     05-29 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-SCHOOLS-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO SCHOOLS HELD AS A MODEL FOR WHAT KC COULD DO 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The community also responded.
</P>
<P>
   The philanthropic community pumps about $20 million annually
into the district, and businesses now routinely provide services,
mentors or supplies. Local universities aid the district by doing
in-depth research to determine which reform initiatives are working
best.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is sold on the Chicago model, and problems
still exist.
</P>
<P>
   High school reform has not gone as well. Many schools still
struggle academically. Teacher training needs to be improved. Some
worry that teachers may be focusing too much on the high-stakes
tests and not enough on instruction. Others are concerned that
holding back so many students could lead to a surge in dropouts
later on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree that it has really worked at anything more than
a cosmetic level,'' said Arthur A. Benson II, attorney for the
plaintiff schoolchildren in the Kansas City desegregation lawsuit.
``Some of the things they've done promise short-term gains at the
expense of long-term improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Chicago, Benson said the Kansas City School District
didn't need help from City Hall, but from a qualified
superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most in Chicago are convinced that Daley has the city's
school system headed in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no simple formulas or miracles,'' Daley said. ``Our
performance is doing much better. Not great, but better.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Beethoven, Principal Frances Oden said the effect of reform
was obvious and immediate.
</P>
<P>
   New paint. New furniture. New books. A new gymnasium. Dingy and
scratched plastic windows replaced with glass.
</P>
<P>
   City workers fixed the school's balky heating system.
</P>
<P>
   The school eventually used its new discretionary money to extend
the school day and hire more teachers to reduce class sizes. The
building focused intensely on reading. Students now spend 90
minutes on language arts each morning and an additional hour
reading in the after-school program.
</P>
<P>
   Oden said the reforms also brought about accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew they had to produce _ principals, teachers and
children,'' Oden said.
</P>
<P>
   Ending social promotion also seemed to make children more
focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``They realized that at the end of the year, they might not get
promoted,'' Oden said.
</P>
<P>
   The school also tried to make parents accountable. All are asked
to sign a contract agreeing to help with their children's homework
every night. The school also sends home a progress report every
five weeks so parents are constantly aware of their children's
school performance.
</P>
<P>
   Oden also began emphasizing teacher training.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the best change, according to Oden, is the ability to pick
up the telephone and reach a decision-maker in the administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're able to talk to people, get answers and get things
done,'' she said. ``You don't get the runaround anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Parent volunteers now roam the hallways. Teachers willingly work
longer hours and are motivated to take additional training because
they see the positive results in student test scores.
</P>
<P>
   A health clinic opened in the school. A recreation program was
added. The school now serves dinner to many of its students.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, the changes in the building also have created a change
in the students, nearly all of whom live in the Robert Taylor Homes
public housing project, one of the city's poorest and most
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Today, gangs still roam and gunfire still echoes through the
concrete canyons of the project. But for children accustomed to
despair, Beethoven now serves as an oasis of hope and high
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come in with aggressive tendencies because they have to
fight in the Homes,'' Oden said. ``They live in a society totally
different in the projects than what's acceptable here in a school
setting. They may have their gangs outside, but not in here. This
is a safe haven for the children.''
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
