<HEADLINE>
RED SOX AWAIT MARTINEZ DUO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The surprising Boston Red Sox got more good news
this past week when former Dodger Ramon Martinez
</P>
<P>
   threw two simulated games and reported no problems in his
rehabilitation from right shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez pitched four innings and threw a total of 60 pitches.
He is scheduled to undergo a similar workout in five days as he
continues toward a July return to the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' said brother Pedro Martinez , who leads the
majors with 10 victories. ``I am very excited for him.''
</P>
<P>
   It is still early, but on a team already encouraged by two
recent victories over the Yankees by minor-league call-up
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rose , plans are being made.
</P>
<P>
   The first has Martinez pitching in his first minor-league game
by the middle of June. Such a timetable could have Martinez
pitching for the Red Sox just before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Boston still wants Martinez to throw live batting practice or
simulated games at least three times before his first minor-league
start June 16. He will make at least three or four appearances in
the minors before pitching again in the majors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RAFFY IS IFFY
</P>
<P>
   Interleague play begins Friday and the Texas Rangers will be at
Dodger Stadium the following Monday. There is no DH in the National
League parks, meaning Rafael Palmeiro must either be ready to play
first base or sit the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a decision to make pretty soon,'' said Palmeiro, off to
a great start offensively but limited to DH duty because of a
spring-training knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how I feel when I get home. We'll make an evaluation
to see how I am and see if I can get out there. I might play before
then. You never know. This stuff is day-to-day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are 16-9 away from home, which could be a good sign
for them since they play 20 of 28 on the road during June. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WILD THING
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the White Sox's red-hot John Snyder drop his last
two starts before Saturday's win, their closer Bob Howry has walked
10 over his last 41/3 innings. Howry, who for now has lost his job
to veteran Bill Simas , openly compares himself to Mark Wohlers.
``It's Pitching 101,'' said Howry, 8 for 10 in save situations.
``Learning how to throw strikes.'' The White Sox believe the
problem began May 4 at Camden Yards when Howry got caught up in
having the speed of his pitches shown on the stadium scoreboard. It
ruined his focus and mechanics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NUMBERS GAME
</P>
<P>
   With two more RBI on Wednesday, Cleveland's Manny Ramirez
</P>
<P>
   had 59 in the Indians' first 45 games. He's on pace to drive in
212. ``The way Manny has produced last year and this year, says a
lot about his maturation,'' said Indians manager Mike Hargrove.
``If he stays on the road, people have to look at him as a major
force in baseball. He's not there yet, but he's on a road very few
of us get to travel.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   In six games against the Twins over the past two weeks, the
Seattle Mariners hit 23 homers. ``Go ask them what they're
eating,'' Twins DH Marty Cordova said, ``besides pitchers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND GETS AN A
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics are planning a special day to honor Hall of Fame
pitcher Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter on June 12 before the A's play the
Dodgers in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, ace of the 1970s A's World Series championship teams,
has been diagnosed with Lou Gehrig's Disease _ Amyotrophic Lateral
Sclerosis _ and the day will be dedicated to raising money for the
Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter ALS Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   During pre-game ceremonies, Hunter, a four-time 20-game winner
with the A's and the owner of three World Series rings, will be
joined on the field by his family and a number of former teammates,
including Reggie Jackson, Bert Campaneris, Ray Fosse, Rick Monday,
John ``Blue Moon'' Odom and Joe Rudi in addition to former A's
manager Dick Williams . This is the 25th anniversary of the A's
third consecutive World Series win, a five-game victory over the
Dodgers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2001EDT &QL; 
