<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6182 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOBILE-ETIQUETTE-2NDT     05-29 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBILE-ETIQUETTE-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOBILE PHONES CREATE ETIQUETTE QUANDARY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Steven Robertson of Atonement Lutheran Church in
Overland Park said he never had a phone ring in a service. He would
be concerned if such a problem started.
</P>
<P>
   ``No person is that indispensable that they need to have a phone
around them all the time,'' Robertson said. ``In some ways it is
arrogant to think that we are that indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are so focused on work, why are you at worship anyway?
You certainly are not focusing on God.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennie Smith, managing partner of Newcomer-Smith Memorial Chapel
&AMP; Crematory in Olathe, Kan., however, knows just how distracting
and inappropriate a ringing phone can be.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent grave site committal service, an attendee's phone
rang. The person answered and walked away from the tent to take the
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It immediately drew people's attention away from the message
being sent,'' he said. ``The minister did continue with the
committal, but it was disruptive.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the problem had not become an epidemic, but that it
was only a matter of time before signs or messages would be printed
asking people to be sensitive to the grieving family by turning off
communication devices.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell has joined forces with Peggy Post,
great-granddaughter-in-law of Emily Post and author of the 75th
anniversary edition of Emily Post's Etiquette, to promote wireless
etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``By combining common sense and consideration for others, and
letting the phone features help us out, there is a right time and
place for using a wireless phone,'' Post said. ``They are a
terrific thing.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cross, president of Cross Manufacturing Inc. of Overland
Park, knows just how intrusive a phone can be. So when he had to
make two calls while at lunch, he made sure that he did not talk
louder than the ambient noise of the outdoor dining area and that
his calls were brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't routinely use the phone in the restaurant,'' he said.
``Normally, I will use it in the car. This time was an exception.''
</P>
<P>
   He put the phone away after making the necessary business calls.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Martin wrote in Miss Manners' Guide to the Perfectly
Proper Use of Cellular Telephones, published by the cellular
industry association: ``Interruptions are interruptions, no matter
how much they cost to make, and it is rude to interrupt people or
activities. While it is true that emergencies override this rule,
emergencies are, by definition, so rare that they are unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``At those rare moments when fate hangs in the balance, ordinary
invitations should not be issued or accepted. For people who have
jobs where crisis is the rule, there are usually arrangements for
others to cover when one takes time for the normal business of
life.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS COURTESY  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans are growing increasingly frustrated with the behavior
of some wireless phone users. As more and more people get wireless
telephones, the chance for the devices to offend will increase.
Here are some etiquette tips to remember:
</P>
<P>
   When riding public transportation, avoid loud, animated
conversations by speaking in quiet or normal conversational tones.
Also, avoid extended calls.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the ringer as low as possible to avoid disturbing others.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely, if ever, is it appropriate to have conversations during
lectures, concerts, plays, movies, funerals, church services or
other social gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the people you are with usually take priority over a
phone call. Having a conversation in their presence implies they
are not important.
</P>
<P>
   If you must take a call, excuse yourself to a less-disruptive
area.
</P>
<P>
   Inform the person you call that you are using a wireless phone,
so if the connection fades or drops, the person will know to wait
to see if clarity returns.
</P>
<P>
   Focus on safety first. Do not use wireless phones when they
would interrupt your ability to drive or walk.
</P>
<P>
   Use caller ID, voice mail or vibrating batteries to limit
disturbing others. Source: Peggy Post, great-granddaughter-in-law
of Emily Post and author of the 75th anniversary edition of Emily
Post's Etiquette. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
