<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6184 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SPY2NDTAKE-KAN &LR;      05-29 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SPY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUROR OVER CHINESE SPYING OVERLOOKS ONE FACT: EVERYONE DOES IT 
</HEADLINE>
 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By By DAVID GOLDSTEIN and RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week a report from the House committee headed by Rep.
Christopher Cox concluded that the Chinese had obtained data on
every thermonuclear warhead currently being deployed by the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 20 years, they also acquired information on building
high-tech aircraft, launching their missiles and detecting our
submarines.
</P>
<P>
   But there are questions still about the guilt of the central
character of the saga, Wen Ho Lee.
</P>
<P>
   It may be true that Lee, the former nuclear-weapons scientist at
Los Alamos National Laboratory, downloaded classified data, but was
it to forward these secrets to the Chinese?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Cox report's assumptions, that is not certain.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he's a spy, a dupe or just a sloppy keeper of secrets,
Lee for now is a free man living out his forced retirement not far
from the New Mexico lab. While the moving of data from computer to
computer violated lab security rules, no criminal statute on
espionage covers the act.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be the first time a mole got away with it. U.S.
spycatchers have never figured out who all the agents were in an
earlier Los Alamos spy ring run by the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   And although Julius and Ethel Rosenberg were executed for their
role in leaking atomic secrets, at least one known spy (an American
physicist living comfortably in England today) in the network was
not pursued for fear it would tip off Moscow's spymasters that some
of their codes had been broken.
</P>
<P>
   Weak security at weapons labs was not the only problem, the Cox
report notes. Lax export laws and squishy satellite-licensing
regulations were behind some leaks. Fingers are being pointed at
American businessmen who wanted to keep their expensive satellites
from blowing up atop Chinese commercial rockets or avoid losing
contracts to Europe on supercomputers or aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the secrets came from declassified articles
published in scientific journals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liken it to those Roadrunner cartoons, where the coyote runs
off a cliff and doesn't realize he's suspended in midair until he
looks down,'' said intelligence expert Treverton. ``Our
counterintelligence system just hasn't kept up with the radical
pace of technology and changes in international relations.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
While China took advantage of security lapses, several observers
said America also had trouble dealing with the way the Chinese
cloaked their clandestine operations.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Russians, who operate in the ``classic espionage
manner'' _ recruiting agents and paying them for their disloyalty _
Chinese spies are said to ingratiate themselves with the people who
have the information they need, and then they play a waiting game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans find it hard to understand the way the Chinese
operate,'' said Paul Redmond, former director of
counterintelligence for the CIA. ``We're the Kmart society: instant
coffee, fast food, instant replay. Instant gratification. American
business thinks just to the end of the next quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese think in decades culturally, and they're willing
and patient and able to have somebody sitting there, gradually,
working their way in.''
</P>
<P>
   They also spread a wide canvas. Thomas Allen, who co-wrote Spy
Book: The Encyclopedia of Espionage, says China exports students as
spies. Allen wrote that on a tour of a French photographic firm,
students were seen ``dipping their ties into chemicals to acquire a
sample.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts counter that such intriguing behavior means little
in the context of some unromantic truths: China _ even with four
times as many people as the U.S. _ remains a relatively primitive
nation, both economically and technologically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the U.S. that has all the weapons,'' said Robert Weil,
author of Red Cat, White Cat: China and the Contradictions of
Market Socialism. ``It's the U.S., not China, that maintains the
largest spy agencies in the world. And it's the U.S. that used
atomic bombs a few hundred miles from China's border during World
War II.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts note that even with some of our secrets in hand, the
Chinese have built fewer than 25 ICBMs capable of reaching any
American city. All of those weapons are less advanced than the
6,000 warheads that the United States could fire back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese would get obliterated, and they know it,'' said
Weil. ``I don't think they feel in any sense a threat to the U.S.
They think the United States does anything it wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the anger seen outside the U.S. Embassy in Beijing after
the NATO bombing of China's Embassy in Belgrade was because Chinese
refused to believe that the American intelligence apparatus _ with
its huge ``black budget'' funding expensive spy submarines and
satellites _ could have contributed to such a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Weil, among others, attributed American distrust of China to ``a
strong element of racism'' similar to sentiments that spurred the
internment of Japanese-Americans in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyt Zia, a Chinese-American who serves as chief counsel for
export administration in the U.S. Department of Commerce, hinted at
this in a recent column for The New York Times: ``For reasons I
cannot fathom...Asian-Americans continue to be accused of having
dual loyalties to a degree far greater than any other immigrant
group.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions that remain from the Cox report, Weil thinks
the Chinese people have their own: ``Why are you setting us up as
the enemy?''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of China offer one swift answer: The issue is not the
way Americans treat the Chinese, but the way the Chinese treat the
Chinese, from Tiananmen Square to Tibet to Taiwan. The Clinton
administration's effort to engage Beijing on different levels, from
diplomacy to commerce, has been naive, they say, and the spying on
us simply proves it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I missing something here?'' said Rohrabacher. ``We're
dealing with Communist thugs.''
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
