<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6185 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBERTY-CONCEPT2TAKES     05-29 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERTY-CONCEPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVER THE CENTURIES, THE CONCEPT OF LIBERTY HAS CONTINUED TO
CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC ADLER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By all accounts Harry Butters _ a young, rich Californian in
love with fast cars and polo _ was enjoying all the fruits of
privilege when he dedicated his life to a cause greater than
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Entrenched in the battlefields of France, the World War I
soldier wrote to his parents:
</P>
<P>
   ``It may seem to you that for me this is all quite uncalled for.
(But) never will I have an opportunity to gain so much honorable
advancement for my own soul, or to do so much for the cause of the
world's progress, as I have here daily, defending the liberty that
mankind has so far gained....
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, my dear folks, we are indeed doing the world's work over
here, and I am in it to the finish....`For God, for Liberty, for
Honor.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   At 24, Butters was killed in action.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than 80 years later _ as Americans prepare to
celebrate the last Memorial Day before 2000 _ the definition of
liberty has extended far beyond Butters' notion of freedom from
tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, just as Kansas City's Liberty Memorial and museum are
set to undergo an $80 million reconstruction (a campaign to raise
the final $21 million begins today), the very definition of liberty
has been undergoing reconstruction from the time of its conception.
</P>
<P>
   Women in the military? Civil rights? In Butters' day, women
still could not vote and African-Americans, only 50 years out of
slavery, would face 50 more years of sanctioned segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Porn on the Internet? In his day, even socialists and union
organizers were denied rights of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Self-incrimination? The criminal Ernesto Miranda was not even
born. A half-century would pass before the U.S. Supreme Court would
rule that criminal suspects must be read their rights upon arrest.
</P>
<P>
   As for affirmative action, school prayer, same-sex marriages,
abortion, sex discrimination, the right to carry concealed weapons
and other issues, one can only guess what Butters would think. He
would know, though, that when it comes to liberty's age-old drama _
the rights of the individual vs. those of the community _ the
dialogue has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred years ago, individual liberty might have included
the right to dump trash into the stream that runs along your
property, because it's your property,'' said University of Kansas
law professor Richard E. Levy. ``But today we no longer recognize
that right.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberty, scholars say, invariably reflects the values of every
society that invokes it. As such, it has changed so many times that
only at its foundation _ freedom _ does liberty today resemble
notions of the past.
</P>
<P>
   To the ancient Greeks, liberty meant civic duty, moral duty and
freedom from foreign domination: the needs of the city before the
needs of the citizen.
</P>
<P>
   But in Rome, Stoic philosophers and early Christians later
propounded an idea that centuries afterward would have a profound
influence on the course of history: By nature, and under God, all
men are created equal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it died,'' said Barry Shain, a political theorist at
Colgate University in New York. ``The idea that all people are
created equal comes out of Rome, but for the next 1,400 years we
have discrimination and slavery.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most of Europe for a thousand years, no one had any notion
of political or personal liberty. You had a reasonable expectation
of what the law was going to be, that the law should treat you
fairly, and you had the right to follow God. That was about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the notion of almost unfettered personal rights _ what
19th century philosopher John Stuart Mill called the right to
pursue ``our own good in our own way, so long as we do not attempt
to deprive others of theirs''_ is deemed elemental to Americans'
modern notion of liberty.
</P>
<P>
   It is over the bounds of such personal liberties that, in the
United States, countless court and rhetorical battles continue to
be waged:
</P>
<P>
   Rights of privacy. The right to bear arms. The right to free
speech, due process and religious expression. The right not to be
denied housing, employment or other civil rights because of race,
religion, gender, disability or sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The common presumption is that these liberties naturally extend
from the Founding Fathers and the proclamation in the Declaration
of Independence that ``all men are created equal'' and have an
unalienable right to ``Life, Liberty and the Pursuit of
Happiness.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( MORE )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
