</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERTY-CONCEPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVER THE CENTURIES, THE CONCEPT OF LIBERTY HAS CONTINUED TO
CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC ADLER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But while the tie is certain, scholars insist that over time it
has been given a twist. They point out that not even the Founding
Fathers believed in absolute equality. At the time the phrase ``all
men are created equal'' was penned, it did not apply to women,
nonlandholders or a vast population of slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liberty has come to mean much more than it did to the Founding
Fathers,'' said New York University law professor John Phillip
Reid, author of The Concept of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, ``they expected liberties to be expanded as new
definitions came along,'' he said. But Reid and others believe that
even the Founding Fathers might have raised their 18th century
eyebrows at the direction in which the definition of liberty _
particularly personal liberty _ has been expanded.
</P>
<P>
   To John Adams, Thomas Jefferson, James Madison, Benjamin
Franklin and other early patriots, the definition of liberty was
narrow and specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Patrick Henry said, `Give me liberty or give me
death!' &UR; '' said George Carey, professor of government at Georgetown
University, ``he meant self-government.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Carey writes in An Uncertain Legacy, Essays on the
Pursuit of Liberty: ``The essence or core of liberty during the
founding period was felt to be the absence of arbitrary and
capricious government.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the framers of the Constitution _ whose
subjugation by the British crown made them naturally wary of
authoritarian government _ defined liberty not as what every
individual has the right to do or have, but by what the government
has no right to do to its people.
</P>
<P>
   The best evidence of their thinking is the Bill of Rights. The
U.S. Constitution's first 10 amendments are, for the most part, a
list of restrictions on government:
</P>
<P>
   Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of
religion. It cannot abridge the freedom of speech, of the press, of
the right of people to peaceably assemble or petition the
government. It shall not infringe on the right of people to keep
and bear arms. It cannot require excessive bail, impose cruel and
unusual punishment or deprive any individual of life, liberty or
property without due process of law.
</P>
<P>
   At least one political group, the National Libertarian Party,
maintains that the founders' definition of liberty _ popular
sovereignty and freedom from government interference _ is, by all
rights, the only definition under which the nation should operate.
That it does not operate that way, they believe, has debased the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our liberties have grown so large and rapidly, it has
perverted the Constitution to the point that our Founding Fathers
wouldn't recognize it,'' said the party's press secretary, George
Getz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liberty is the right to be left alone. And the government
really isn't leaving anybody alone today. They are attacking our
income, the right to use your property in the way you see fit, the
right to own a gun. They are telling you who to hire, forcing you
to put money into Social Security. They tell you what size toilet
bowl you have to have in your house. It's preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most prevailing shift in the American notion of
liberty is more subtle and philosophical. Where liberty once meant
popular sovereignty, self-government and freedom from government
interference, more and more Americans in the 20th century have come
to believe it means doing whatever they please. And any
infringement on that liberty is considered a violation of one's
unalienable rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today our sense of liberty, in the most contemporary sense,
means liberation,'' said C. Bradley Thompson, a professor of
political science and history at Ohio's Ashland University and
author of John Adams &AMP; the Spirit of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   ``And liberty today also means liberty from all authority. It
means not only having the right to do something, but that you have
the right to do something and shouldn't be criticized for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as professor Carey of Georgetown put it: ``Many of the people
who argue for individual rights, what they're often arguing for is
entitlements.''
</P>
<P>
   The right to do, say, print or broadcast what they want. The
right to a good job, a good home, a good education and a living
wage. If one does not have these things, it is not because he has
not earned them, it is because he has somehow been denied them. And
it's up to the government to make amends. Or so the thinking goes.
</P>
<P>
   And that troubles many scholars. Because if there is one
significant threat to liberty, it is those who take their liberties
too far.
</P>
<P>
   Absolute liberty has never existed. There are laws against
libel, restrictions on religion and commerce. And even though the
First Amendment prohibits the abridgement of free speech, it is
still illegal to incite a riot, urge someone to commit a crime or
yell fire in a crowded movie theater, unless there really is a
fire. The price of living in a society is that everyone gives up
some liberties.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why it is those who refuse to exercise their liberties
responsibly who put liberty most at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a perfect analogy,'' said KU's Richard Levy, ``but
as a parent, I deal with two children who are approaching the age
of being teen-agers. I am confronted with the question of how much
liberty I give them. I think most parents agree that the more
responsibly they deal with the liberties they are given, the more
you give them. The more they abuse them, the less you want to give
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think society acts that way.''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, as some individuals push the bounds of liberties,
others inside and outside of government feel compelled to push
back. Proposed restrictions on both words and deeds appear. What
was once a liberty becomes less of one.
</P>
<P>
   And, for better or worse, the nature of liberty changes again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
