<SLUG> BC-RUSSIANS-LIBERTY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEX KUCHEROVSKY: `GO TO RUSSIA. YOU WILL SEE THE DIFFERENCE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC ADLER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ``Do right for this country,'' said Alex
Kucherovsky, ``and this country do right for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Armed with his own definition of liberty _ ``For me, able to
support family, pay bills, raise children'' _ he has done just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen years ago, Kucherovsky emigrated from Kiev in the
former Soviet Union with $500 in his pocket. He came to Kansas City
with his wife, Anna, and two daughters, Svetlana, 7, and Maria, 5
months. His parents and sister had arrived two years earlier. A
great-uncle and aunt came in 1920 after the Bolshevik Revolution.
He had family here but little else.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the owner of Alex's Shoe Repair in Blue Springs, Mo.,
owns a fine home in Overland Park, Kan., mortgage paid. Svetlana,
26, is applying to dental school. Maria, 18, is married and having
a baby.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months ago, Svetlana's fiance and Anna opened Taste of
Russia, a Russian market, bakery and catering business on 79th
Street off Metcalf Avenue. The business is growing so fast that
it's about to expand for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, America has been so good to Kucherovsky that for the
last 17 years he has observed Jan. 26 _ the day his family set foot
in Kansas City _ as a family holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year we celebrate,'' he said, ``because to me this was
very big step of my life. And I know I did right decision move to
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, he said, individuals have rights _ to express themselves,
to get an education, to improve their stations and to enjoy the
fruits of their labors.
</P>
<P>
   As a Jew in the former Soviet Union, Kucherovsky often felt the
sting of discrimination. In America, he said, ``I am American.
Jewish, Christian, Muslim. Doesn't matter. This freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   He has little tolerance for those who complain about the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `Go to Russia. You will see the difference,''
Kucherovsky said. `` `Don't forget your toilet paper, soap,
everything. 'Cause you will never have.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I am sad because I know old people come to my store,
have food stamps, and complain. They say, `You know in Russia I was
this. I did something. I was main man or woman.' I say, `Who cares
who you was? You come into the United States. America give you
room, give you food, your children do very well. Why do you
complain?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kucherovsky does not complain. He came to the United States with
nothing. He was given the freedom and liberty to make a life and
educate his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are Americans. Real Americans,'' he said. ``How people
don't like this country, I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
