<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIANS-LIBERTY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF CAMBODIAN HORROR SHARPEN FAMILY'S APPRECIATION OF
AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC ADLER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ At 2 a.m. one Saturday, 18-year-old Sambath
Ngek switched on the lamp in her room. Her mother, Sambo Prom, was
already awake.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes later, as the city slept, the two were on the
highway driving from their bungalow to a local supermarket 20 miles
away in the suburbs. Work in the bakery begins at 3.
</P>
<P>
   Sambath would never say the hours are ideal. But she knows, from
her parents' tales of Cambodia, that ``ideal'' is relative.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast High School senior was 11 months old when her
parents arrived in Kansas City in 1981 as political refugees. By
then, the Communist Khmer Rouge had already murdered a million of
its countrymen, including Sambath's uncles and aunts.
</P>
<P>
   To her, her parents' memories of abrogated rights and government
brutality at times seem incomprehensible. ``You can't imagine it,
unless it happens to you,'' she said. But she knows the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me liberty is being able to do things without the
government telling you to do this or do that,'' she said. ``A lot
of people here think it's doing whatever you want as long as you
don't get in trouble or break the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But to her it means, at the lowest level, having the opportunity
to haul yourself out to the suburbs every Saturday and Sunday to
earn $7 an hour frosting and filling doughnuts. Her mother has done
it nearly every day for five years. Her father's first job here was
cleaning the seats at what was then called Royals Stadium. Now he
works in manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to the United States,'' her mother said. ``We happy. A
lot of food. Nobody kill.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ngeks have a house. They feel safe. Sambath has saved $4,000
in this job. She ranks fourth in her high school class. She has a
car, she has gone to the prom, and in the fall she will be a
freshman at MidAmerica Nazarene University with hopes of becoming a
stockbroker.
</P>
<P>
   Sambath recognizes that the American notion of liberty has its
drawbacks, especially when people define liberty to mean the
freedom to do as you please without obligation. For her, liberty is
rooted in her obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Because she is the oldest of three children and because her
parents have difficulty with English, ``I'm like the eyes and ears
of the family,'' Sambath said.
</P>
<P>
   So it is Sambath who reads the mail and pays every bill. It's
she who balances the checkbook, talks to the gas company, phone
company, dentists, doctors. By herself, she navigated through high
school and got into college.
</P>
<P>
   It's OK. A small price, she figures, for the freedom to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   `My mom tells me stories,'' she said. ``I don't take what we
have for granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
