<SLUG> BC-BOSNIANS-LIBERTY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BOSNIAN REFUGEE FAMILY, AMERICA OFFERS THE FREEDOM TO TRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC ADLER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Erna Hadzibegovic knows clearly that she owns
one Calvin Klein T-shirt, has seen ``Titanic'' three times, thinks
Leonardo DiCaprio is dreamy and hopes one day to become a
translator.
</P>
<P>
   What is less clear in the mind of the North Kansas City, Mo.,
sixth-grader is the day in 1992 when a Serbian bomb fell in
Sarajevo and blasted her Bosnian family from its home.
</P>
<P>
   She was only 4 then, and her memory of the day is hazy. And
that's fine with her parents.
</P>
<P>
   Jasmin and Izeta Hadzibegovic arrived in Kansas City as
political refugees just over a year ago with their daughters, Erna,
11, and Belma, 14. Before that they spent six restless years in a
refugee camp in Germany, never quite sure whether they might return
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I call home,'' Jasmin said. But the news never
changed. No food. No energy. No jobs.
</P>
<P>
   So now they are in America, where, to Jasmin and Izeta, liberty
is about having the opportunity to work hard, raise a family, earn
a living and afford their daughters a good education and a better
future.
</P>
<P>
   Because when it comes to the lack of liberty, the children need
no lessons. Every school day, the children in their
English-as-a-second-language class offer living reminders. There's
13-year-old Neghar Mamaamin of Kurdistan, who shyly shows the
bullet scar in her left elbow, a remnant from when Iraqi soldiers
stormed her home. Classmate Jasmina Tahirovic of Bosnia tells how a
bomb exploded outside her home and forced her family to flee into
the woods.
</P>
<P>
   So if Erna doesn't quite remember that April afternoon when the
bomb burst, that's all the better.
</P>
<P>
   Izeta, who had bought into a clothing design business before
fleeing Sarajevo, works six days a week cleaning rooms and making
beds at the downtown Doubletree Hotel. Jasmin, who did home repair,
has a night job at a company that stitches logos onto baseball
caps.
</P>
<P>
   As Izeta works, Jasmin sleeps. When he is at work, the family is
in bed. They see one another only hours a day. But it doesn't
matter.
</P>
<P>
   They have a car and an apartment, and they are saving for a home
``with a flower garden,'' Izeta said. ``Good for the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, too, Belma graduates from eighth grade. To Jasmin and
Izeta, that is something to celebrate and what liberty is about _
the freedom to try.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work hard and do our best,'' Belma said.
</P>
<P>
   Erna said, ``I like it how here I could be what I want to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
