A6190 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIANS-LIBERTY-KAN     05-29 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIANS-LIBERTY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NIGERIA, FAMILY SUFFERED FOR SPEAKING OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC ADLER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ You ask about freedom? Human liberty?
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two-year-old Prince-Will Neebani of Nigeria yanked off
his sneakers and pulled his jacket off his naked shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every morning I get 50 strikes with cable,'' he said, pointing
to the scars on his feet, shoulders, back and chest.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months he was imprisoned with no trial, chained at the
wrists and feet for being a youth organizer.
</P>
<P>
   Prince-Will's mother, Salome, is 47. Her mood is heavy, her face
tired. The Nigerian government tortured her in prison. They killed
thousands, she said, including her husband, shot as a protester.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, for that, for speaking out and demanding compensation from
the Nigerian government for the environmental destruction of the
Ogoni people's once-fertile tribal land.
</P>
<P>
   Time was when Ogoniland, along Nigeria's coast, was a rich place
for fishing and growing yams. Then, 40 years ago, oil and natural
gas were found. Leaking oil and gas lines poisoned the land.
Government officials grew rich while the people stayed poor.
</P>
<P>
   So the people of Ogoniland spoke out.
</P>
<P>
   Told to stop protesting or die, Prince-Will and Salome _
pregnant with her seventh child _ escaped to a refugee camp in the
republic of Benin along with two of her children, Rosebella and
Kenneth. Her three adult daughters remained in Nigeria. She does
not know whether they are alive or dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were eight. We are five here now,'' said Salome, who in the
refugee camp gave birth to a boy, Precious, his name reflecting
their freedom and his survival.
</P>
<P>
   The Don Bosco Center relocated the Neebanis to Kansas City nine
months ago. Since then they have seen President Clinton sued,
impeached and his sex life dissected. They think it is wondrous _
not out of enmity, but because it speaks of a country whose
government and leaders are accountable to its people and laws.
</P>
<P>
   Prince-Will, who worked stocking food at a restaurant, is about
to begin a $9-an-hour job in Lenexa. Salome, a former nurse's aide,
is looking for work as she cares for Precious, now 3. Kenneth, 15,
attends Westport High School and stocks groceries at an Apple
Market. Rosebella, 14, is in the seventh grade at Northeast Middle
School.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years she spent at the refugee camp in Benin,
Rosebella dreamed of something better.
</P>
<P>
   When the family fled Nigeria, Rosebella took one item with her:
a book, a thin paperback novel that she has read more than 30
times.
</P>
<P>
   The book, its pages yellow, its cover falling off, is now with
her in America _ a small reminder that something better is at hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
