<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6191 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-LONE-STAR-RACES-T     05-29 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LONE-STAR-RACES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLEBITLIVELY LEADS HANDICAP FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ The seven stakes races composing
tomorrow's inaugural Lone Star Million Day took shape with
yesterday's post-position draws.
</P>
<P>
   Littlebitlively got the No. 1 post in the $300,000 Lone Star
Park Handicap, the most lucrative of the big events. The two-time
Texas Mile winner returned Friday on a full flight from Kentucky
and is the early 2-1 favorite in the 11/16-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   Also entered are Allen's Oop (3-1), Truluck (7-2), Mocha Express
(9-2), Burbank (6-1), Nite Dreamer (8-1) and Houston Slue (15-1).
</P>
<P>
   Mocha Express was last year's horse of the meeting at Lone Star
Park, and Burbank is a former grass champion at the local track.
Allen's Oop will be ridden by Maryland-based Edgar Prado, the
leading U.S. rider in races won this year.
</P>
<P>
   Littlebitlively has won $766,040 in his career, but the leading
money-winner tomorrow is Stop Traffic, a $788,018 earner and the
5-2 favorite in the $100,000 Wild Flower Stakes at six furlongs for
fillies and mares.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three grass races _ the $250,000 USA Stakes,
$150,000 Prestonwood Distaff and $100,000 Lone Star Park Turf
Sprint _ has a capacity 12-horse field with a mix of popular local
runners and talented invaders.
</P>
<P>
   The seven races total $1 million in purses, and attracted horses
that arrived on flights from Kentucky, California and New York.
Lone Star Park is offering a Pick-7 wager (minimum bet $1) on the
Million Day features, which will be carded as races four through 10
on the 11-race program. \Nsubheds:Microsoft party Lone Star Park
took group sales to new heights Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The racetrack was host to the annual Microsoft Corp. convention,
with 7,000 employees arriving from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Guests at the private party _ which occupied the west end of the
track property, including the Post Time Pavilion _ were entertained
by more than just horse races. Performing live at the function were
country-music stars Tim McGraw and Faith Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft founder Bill Gates was not in attendance.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
