<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6193 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-INDY-LUYENDYK-TEX     05-29 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-LUYENDYK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUYENDYK: EXIT OF A HUMBLE CHAMPION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ His sobriquet is ``The Flying Dutchman,'' a neat
fit for the man who owns the most coveted speed entries in the
Indianapolis 500 record book.
</P>
<P>
   Arie Luyendyk's 15-year tour around the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway has taken him from rookie of the year to two-time champion
to three-time pole-winner to elder statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Luyendyk races into retirement, fittingly enough, from
the pole position of the 83rd Indianapolis 500. ``Arie's Final
500'' could end with one last left turn into Victory Lane. Whether
or not it does, Luyendyk plans to exit the Speedway with the same
humility he first brought to the corners of 16th Street and
Georgetown Road 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here the first time as a spectator, it almost
scared me what I saw,'' said Luyendyk, a long-haired road racer
from Holland in search of an Indy-car ride in 1984. ``I saw the
cars going into Turn 1, flat-out, and I'm thinking, `Man, I've got
to do this next year?' I felt so little and so small when I walked
into this place, and to become a part of Indianapolis history is
pretty neat for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In qualifying or during the race, no driver in Indy 500 history
has hustled a car around The Brickyard any faster than Arie. At 45,
Luyendyk's name stands next to these IMS track records:
</P>
<P>
   One-lap qualifying mark, 237.498 mph, set in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Four-lap qualifying mark, 236.986 mph, also set in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   500-mile average speed mark, 185.981 mph, set in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   All-time prize-money mark, $5.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arie has a natural talent for speed,'' said Eddie Cheever Jr.,
defending champion of the Indy 500 but a rookie here when Luyendyk
won for the first time in 1990. ``Sometimes when you look at a
driver, you can see the speed on their face. With Arie, you look at
him, and he's just smiling away. He's so comfortable. Almost
laughing at us all. He is very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk outran 1986 Indy 500 champion Bobby Rahal to the
checkered flag in 1990, the capper to a workmanlike month of May.
Sort of like this month of May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being successful here has made my name in American racing,
especially when I won it the first time,'' said Luyendyk, who had
made his Indy-car debut in a Championship Auto Racing Teams event
at Elkhart Lake, Wis., in August 1984. ``And then I had to come
back here and prove that wasn't just a one-time \Rdeal\S. I think
we've done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Competing under the banner of the Pep Boys Indy Racing League in
1997, Luyendyk won at IMS again over Treadway Racing teammate Scott
Goodyear by 0.57 seconds. Luyendyk became only the second foreign
driver to win two Indy 500s, and established himself as the
fledgling IRL's marquee personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is one of the true celebrities here. A Hollywood
celebrity,'' Goodyear said. ``Competing here, he's brought a lot of
fan interest. I think he's one of the reasons I understand the
Speedway.''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Lazier, the 1996 Indy 500 champion, said Luyendyk always
has shared his time and knowledge with rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very humble fellow,'' Lazier said, ``but he has a
tremendous temper on the racetrack. I remember when he flipped-off
a driver, knocked his headrest off and the whole field went yellow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll miss him a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Reigning IRL champion Kenny Brack said Luyendyk qualifies as an
Indy 500 legend _ a tag Arie said ``is really not necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's an honor when people bring up great achievements
at the Speedway, that my name is in that list,'' said Luyendyk, who
qualified his No. 5 Sprint PCS/Meijer G Force-Aurora at 225.179
mph. That is, fittingly enough, the four-lap track record for
normally aspirated IRL V-8 engines.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk announced last November that, for a variety of reasons,
this would be his final Indy 500. And his final Indy-car race. The
decision came with the blessing of his wife, Mieke, who after today
will only have to concern herself with the racing career of the
couple's 17-year-old son, Arie Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I can't wait until the end of the month,'' Mieke
Luyendyk said. ``I always liked the racing scene. I just didn't
like to worry. And I don't want to worry anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk has been involved in four crashes over the past two
years in the all-oval IRL series. But his decision to step away
actually was accelerated in May 1996, when friend Scott Brayton was
killed in a crash while practicing for the race. Brayton, who had
qualified on the pole, was working on a setup for a race-day he
never saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know racing is a dangerous sport. But Scott's crash
really hit us hard,'' Luyendyk said. ``To me, the risks now vs. the
rewards don't pay off at this stage of my career. I'm still
competitive when I get in the car and I'll probably be competitive
in the next couple of years. But I don't want to wait for the signs
_ your timing is off, your reflexes are off _ I don't want to
discover that while I'm in the race car. And I also don't want to
wake up in the hospital anymore, wondering where the hell I am.''
</P>
<P>
   A resident of Scottsdale, Ariz., Luyendyk is planning to spend
more time with Mieke and their four children _ ideally on their
boat. While this will be his final open-wheel race, Luyendyk plans
to compete in the classic 24-Hour endurance sports car events at
Daytona Beach, Fla., and LeMans, France. He is booked to attend IRL
races as a consultant to team owner Fred Treadway and his
replacement driver, Sam Schmidt. Luyendyk has a personal services
contract as spokesman for Sprint PCS, and a TV career beckons as
analyst for IRL telecasts on the Fox Sports Network.
</P>
<P>
   He will exit with all those Indy 500 records, and a total of 167
Indy-car starts _ including 131 in the CART FedEx Championship
Series, 11 in the U.S. Auto Club and 25 in Tony George's IRL.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk's seven career victories include a memorable night, and
morning-after, at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth. Moments after
Billy Boat won the inaugural and scoring problem-plagued True Value
500K night race in June 1997, Luyendyk headed for Victory Lane to
question the lap-counting and his result. A.J. Foyt _ Boat's car
owner, Indy-car icon and full-blooded Texan _ promptly slapped the
intruding Luyendyk and shoved him to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler heads prevailed, and after Treadway filed an official
protest, an overnight audit by red-faced USAC officials discovered
that Luyendyk incorrectly had been docked two laps. Luyendyk was
declared the race-winner, wherever he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``That incident made me more famous than winning the Indy 500,''
said Luyendyk, who patched it up with Foyt last year. ``It's funny,
he still doesn't know how to say my first name properly. He has
such a heavy accent I have a hard time communicating with him. I
almost need a translator _ and I'm the foreigner here.''
</P>
<P>
   But not at Indy. For ``The Flying Dutchman,'' the Speedway is a
neat fit.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
