<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6196 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVILWAR-LETTERS-COX     05-29 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILWAR-LETTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CIVIL WAR LETTERS HONOR A SOLDIER ON MEMORIAL DAY
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By William G. Schmidt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I hasten to pen you a few lines to inform you that I am well
or as well as might be expected. . . . I will go back and tell you
some of the trip down to this place. We went rapidly down to
Cincinnati, arrived at Cincinnati between 8 and 10 o'clock, marched
to the river and went over to Covington. Slept in the freight
car.'' David F. Rohrer, Aug. 25, 1862.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Fogle of New Lebanon held the old cigar box that had been
in the attic of her husband's mother, Lulu Shollenberger, for many
years. When she died in 1981, her belongings were divided among the
family.
</P>
<P>
   Fogle's husband, Richard, eyed the wooden box at the time.
``What a neat cigar box,'' Joyce remembers him saying. But she
wanted what was inside. She remembered her mother-in-law once
saying the family had old letters, still affixed with sealing wax.
</P>
<P>
   When Joyce pulled out the bundles of letters, some from as early
as 1840, the life of her husband's early relative, Simon Rohrer,
poured out onto her lap.
</P>
<P>
   She pulled out the brittle paper, and the lifetime of family
unfolded. They were mostly mundane, letters from relatives still
living in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Then, she found David's letters.
</P>
<P>
   On July 21, 1862, David, the son of Simon Rohrer, went to
Dayton, along with many other local youths, and joined Co. I of the
93rd Ohio Volunteers to do his part for the Civil War. On Aug. 20,
he left the family farm, the brick house, which still stands on
U.S. 35 just west of New Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   He would not return.
</P>
<P>
   Using the cigar box of letters, Joyce began a several-years-long
quest for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were aroused out of our sleep by the report of firearms.
The regiment was called into ranks and some of the men loaded their
guns and everything looked like a fight but in a short time we were
commanded to lie down again.'' DFR Aug. 25, 1862.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce had already followed her own family history. With the
discovery of the letters, she had a chance of uncovering some of
her husband's family history.
</P>
<P>
   Richard was a New Lebanon boy, actually from west of New
Lebanon, along U.S. 35, in Johnsville. It was there, too, that
David lived with his father, Simon, mother, Harriet, a brother,
Joseph, and two sisters. Another brother, Frederick, came later.
</P>
<P>
   The cigar box yielded property taxes from Jackson Twp. in the
1840s, each hand-written and signed. But more importantly there was
an envelope marked simply, ``David F. Rohrer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know you had an uncle in the Civil War?'' Richard was
often asked. He wasn't interested. ``Why do you want to dig this
up?'' he asked Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is your history,'' she told him. ``Stood in the streets
about half an hour and marched about two miles. Laid in the wet
grass. Monday morning came finding us about half dead . . . and lay
down a short distance from our camp. I fell out and laid down, the
sun was so hot that I could scarcely bear it. My lips are sore. My
nose too.'' DFR Sep. 6, 1862 . ``He thinks I'm strange going to
cemeteries,'' Joyce said.
</P>
<P>
   At Farmersville's old United Brethren Church cemetery, she
quickly found David's grave. The old weathered tombstone is near
Center Street, but a few steps from the road. It is tall and
stately and the letters have begun to fade.
</P>
<P>
   The stone is rough to the touch. The years, it seems, were no
more rough than the life of these Rohrer boys. Joseph, when he was
young, fell out of tree and caught his leg. He was lame for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``State of Ohio, Montgomery County, Jackson Township
</P>
<P>
   Be it remembered that we the undersigned this day exempt Joseph
J. Rohrer from the performance of military duty under the militia
law passed April 14, 1863. His complaint being laziness of the left
leg. J.F. Thompson John Fuls Trustees Jackson Township July 11,
1863'' . When Joyce opened the packet of seven letters, almost a
century and a half later, David again had a voice. She had found
the grave, but more importantly she had found the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am getting very impatient because I don't hear from you. We
have not heard from home since we left Dayton. There's no place
like home. We have been rushed through so fast that we are half
sick. I feel so indisposed, so mean that I cannot bring my thoughts
upon any subject.'' DFR Sep. 10, 1862.
</P>
<P>
   David's letters are sprinkled with references to friends, even a
neighbor boy, David Toby, who was with David in the 93rd O.V.I.
</P>
<P>
   He asks how the garden is growing, about a send-off party for
other boys, and complains about his food. He talks about eating a
breakfast of coffee, hard crackers, boiled salted pork. He tells of
guard duty, of marches, of rebel assaults.
</P>
<P>
   When his camp is burned by rebels, he asks that the young girl
living next door be told that ``the nice notion book was burned
with the pocket handkerchief that mother gave me.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion book was a going-away gift.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a final letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun is just rising and I want to write a few lines to let
you know that I am well . . . the air is chilly. I received the
package of medicine on the 18th. The express wagon brought it to
camp. . . I will have to stop writing and see to things.'' DFR Sep.
20, 1862.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining about ``the flux,'' he asked for two types of
medicines. Joyce wondered what happened. The tombstone records his
date of death as Nov. 21, 1862, adding simply, ``died in hospital
in Nashville, TN.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce has binders full of notes, collected over the years. One
reads, ``died of wounds.'' It came from a grave registration card
at the Montgomery County Administration Building. But the roster of
Ohio Soldiers, compiled in the late 1800s, says only that David
``died Nov. 21, 1862, at Nashville, Tenn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rohrer family letters added another tantalizing question. On
Dec. 6, 1862, Simon Rohrer writing from Bowling Green, Ky. to his
wife, reports, ``I have seen a good deal of the effects of the war,
not as much though as I had expected.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, he adds, ``I don't know where I will find our Dave.
They have been shifting some of the Nashville sick. It may be Dave
is one of them. I will find out tomorrow or Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   The heartbreak, looking upon this story pulled from the cigar
box, is that David has been dead fifteen days. The cigar box also
contains camp passes given to Simon on his journey.
</P>
<P>
   It is thought that Simon brought the body home. At the time, the
Rohrer's next door neighbor was Henry Toby, father of campmate
David, and pastor of the same church where David was buried. David
Toby is listed on the 1880 census, having returned safely from the
war.
</P>
<P>
   The cigar box yielded another piece of paper, dated July 27,
1863, and boldly written in pen. ``Received of Simon Rohrer
thirty-five dollars amt. in full for a set of gravestones for
son.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this sandy white stone that marks David's grave.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, the National Archives finally filled in the
missing pieces of David's last days for Joyce. Copies of the old
documents arrived, bearing official military scroll. A Lt. Kline
notes the cause of death: celebritis. Inflammation of the brain.
Yet other papers say ``disease'' and one states, ``left sick in
Nashville, Nov. 14, 1862.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is a Record of Death and Interment. It says, ``brought
to hospital insane. Nothing more could be learned.''
</P>
<P>
   It lists a plot at the Nashville City Cemetery where the body
was buried. Records at the Tennessee State Archives agree but also
show hospital reports of David noting he was ``sent home.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon Rohrer returned to the farm with his son's body and spent
the rest of his life in Johnsville.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Joyce has the Rohrer's family clock in her living room.
The dark wood case, with a class door painted with pink roses,
still works. But Joyce has lost the key.
</P>
<P>
   David must have stood before it and watched it tick. He must
have watched time fall away, a tick at a time before he went off to
battle.
</P>
<P>
   After the Civil War ended, the final Rohrer son was born just as
troops returned along the dirt road. A family story says that
David's sister, Elizabeth, was sent across the road to get her
grandmother for the impending birth.
</P>
<P>
   But the convoy was long and she could not get across the road.
``It came for hours,'' said Joyce. ``I can just see mules and
wagons coming down the road while Frederick is being born.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederick was the final brother, the final member of the family
to die. He never married, and lived in the ``Rohrer House'' until
his death in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce looks upon Memorial Day as a time to honor David Rohrer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (the Civil War) was even more horrible because we were
fighting against ourselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She is left with a poem on the outside of one of David's
letters:
</P>
<P>
   The Soldier's Dream of Home At the dead of night, a sweet vision
I saw, And thrice e'er the morning I dreamt it again But sorrow
returned with the dawning of morning And the voice in my dreaming
'ear melted away ``Write soon and tell me everything that happens
about Johnsville.'' DFR Sep. 18, 1862
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
