<HEADER>
A6199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-INDIA-PAKISTAN-TALK     05-29 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-INDIA-PAKISTAN-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO HALT TO KASHMIR STRIKES, EVEN FOR TALKS, INDIA LEADER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING for all needing; story is only one take)  (kd) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee said
Saturday that India would continue air strikes against what he
described as Pakistani-backed infiltrators dug into Indian
territory, and would only be willing to hold talks with Pakistan
about the conflict if they were not conditional on a halt to the
air raids.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee's remarks came in response to a telephone call on
Friday from Pakistan's prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, who offered to
send Pakistan's foreign minister to New Delhi to meet with his
Indian counterpart. Sharif said India and Pakistan, as the world's
newest nuclear powers, should try to resolve their dispute over
Kashmir, where India is now battling the infiltrators, through
diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear, however, whether Sharif had made such talks
conditional on the suspension of air strikes. Pakistan's minister
of information, Mushahid Hussain, said Saturday in Islamabad that
Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz would be going to New Delhi next week
for talks.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in Karachi on Friday, Sharif said he had warned
Vajpayee that if any more Indian fighter jets ventured into
Pakistan-held Kashmir, they would be shot down, just like two
Indian jets that Pakistan says t downed on Thursday. Sharif said
he had told Vajpayee, ``Come and sit around the table to resolve
the Kashmir issue.''
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan have been squabbling over Kashmir since they
were carved from British India in 1947. India claims Kashmir as one
of its states, while Pakistan maintains that the Kashmiris should
be allowed to choose whether to join India or Pakistan through a
plebiscite.
</P>
<P>
   In this latest permutation of an old feud, India has asserted
that in early May, Pakistan sent almost 700 infiltrators, including
Pakistani soldiers and Afghan mercenaries, across the boundary that
separates Indian- and Pakistan-held portions of Kashmir to seize
control of a swath of Indian territory.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee spelled out India's position during a meeting Saturday
morning with leaders of the major political parties. Afterward, the
government's parliamentary affairs minister, P.R. Kumaramangalam,
told reporters that the prime minister had explained to Sharif that
the air raids would continue until the guerrillas were driven out
of India.
</P>
<P>
   India cannot be expected to stop air raids on intruders in its
own country, Indian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth day Saturday, India pounded the icy hideouts of
the guerrillas with air strikes in an attempt to drive them back
into Pakistan, kill them or force them to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. J.J. Singh, an Indian Army spokesman, said India had
found incontrovertible proof that Pakistani soldiers were among the
``intruders'' trying to hold a chunk of Indian territory.
Originally the disputed area was about 90 miles long and 4 to 5
miles wide, but it has shrunk considerably under the Indian air and
ground assault.
</P>
<P>
   He said the proof, found by Indian troops on Friday, is a
Pakistan army identity card for Sepoy Abdul Ayub, a soldier in the
4th Northern Light Infantry, that was tucked into a rucksack
abandoned at a site of fighting in Indian-held Kashmir. The army
will soon display this document for the press, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani officials could not be reached for comment Saturday,
but they have denied involvement with the guerrillas, whom they
describe as indigenous Kashmiri freedom fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The tally of Indian dead rose to 29 Saturday. On Friday Pakistan
returned the body of a pilot who died after ejecting from his jet
in Pakistan-held Kashmir. Indian officials said Saturday that it
appeared the pilot had bullet wounds and might have been killed
after he parachuted to the ground. A full autopsy will be
performed.
</P>
<P>
   Indian officials said that one of their pilots inadvertently
strayed over the cease-fire line Thursday after he developed engine
trouble, and that a second jet was shot down when its pilot tried
to see where his compatriot had landed. Pakistan has said it shot
the jets down in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   General Singh also said that Pakistan had increased its troop
and arms strength all along the cease-fire line with India. ``These
are probably precautionary, defensive measures,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
