<HEADER>
A6200 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONVICTION-SLAYING-BO     05-29 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVICTION-SLAYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON GANG LEADER CONVICTED IN SLAYING OF PROSECUTOR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Gang leader Jeffrey L. Bly Saturday was convicted of
first-degree murder for the 1995 killing of Assistant Attorney
General Paul R. McLaughlin, who made bitter legal history when he
became the first state prosecutor murdered while doing his job.
</P>
<P>
   A racially mixed jury delivered its verdict in a Suffolk
Superior courtroom crowded with McLaughlin's father, siblings,
fellow prosecutors, Special Assistant Suffolk District Attorney
Thomas Brennan, and a team of Boston and State police officers who
pieced together the case against Bly.
</P>
<P>
   Suppressed cheers echoed softly through the chandeliered
courtroom as the verdict was announced. Tears of relief ran down
the faces of many of McLaughlin's friends as nearly four years of
waiting for justice for a friend finally ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won his last case,'' McLaughlin's older brother, Rick, said
after the verdict. ``He died doing it, but he won it.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk Superior Court Judge James D. McDaniel Jr. sentenced Bly
to the mandatory life without parole.
</P>
<P>
   Bly tried to leave as McLaughlin's father, Edward F. McLaughlin
Jr., prepared to give a victim impact statement, but was ordered to
stay by Judge McDaniel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hurt and damned angry. My natural instinct is to lash
out,'' Edward McLaughlin said as Bly fidgeted in his seat, hands
cuffed behind his back. ``But I won't do anything to denigrate
Paul's memory. I can only hope and pray that he has now found peace
with God, to whom I think his dedicated work . . . has so richly
entitled him.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict ended an extraordinary chapter in state law
enforcement history in which the pursuer became the prey, the
dogged prosecutor targeted for assassination by the ruthless gang
member who broke the unwritten rules of law enforcement officers
and criminals.
</P>
<P>
   While police routinely face the possibility of dying on the job,
prosecutors were considered insulated from the fury of the street
by the passion-draining rituals of the courtroom, where personal
contact between prosecutor and defendant rarely occurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that happens in Mexico or Colombia,'' said
Suffolk District Attorney Ralph C. Martin II, for whom McLaughlin
was working gang cases when he was killed. ``Not in America, much
less Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin was one of McLaughlin's many friends who had been drawn
to the 42-year-old by his passion for politics, his desire to help
tougher Boston neighborhoods rid themselves of crime, and by a
sense of decency that often saw McLaughlin search out an
alternative to prison for defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The elder McLaughlin noted that a scholarship has been set up at
Suffolk University Law School in his son's name, and that an
addition to the Daniel Marr Boys and Girls Club in Dorchester has
been named for him. A tree has been planted outside the West
Roxbury Library in his son's memory as well.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin said he last saw his son in August 1995, about a
month before the murder. He gently urged McLaughlin to consider
getting a more lucrative job in private practice. ``Not yet, Dad,''
the father quoted the son as saying. ``I still think I can make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly, a friend and co-worker of
Paul McLaughlin's for 15 years, was asked after the verdict if he
wished the death penalty was available for Bly. He waved away the
question and said only, ``I want Paul back.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan C. Stanley, Bly's lead attorney, said in court that the
murder was a ``terrible tragedy'' for both the McLaughlin and Bly
families. Bly's mother, whom Bly appeared to ignore even though she
faithfully attended each day of the monthlong trial, left after the
verdict was announced.
</P>
<P>
   The assistant attorney general and Dartmouth College graduate
was shot about 7 p.m. on Sept. 25, 1995 _ the night before he was
to prosecute Bly a third time, a pursuit that his superiors later
thought was a mistake because two earlier trials had ended in
acquittals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not my DA no more,'' a prosecution witness quoted Bly as
saying the night McLaughlin was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   According to testimony, Bly plotted and carried out the
audacious killing with the same cold-eyed ferocity he displayed as
he rose to the top of the Theodore Street Posse, a loosely
organized drug-dealing street gang whose home turf was a few
hundred yards from the Morton Street police station in Mattapan.
</P>
<P>
   One week before Bly's third trial _ for armed robbery and
carjacking _ he was searching for a way to get at Dana Alston, a
carjacking victim who had already survived a murder attempt by a
Bly associate.
</P>
<P>
   According to testimony, Bly could not find Alston and decided
that killing McLaughlin would buy him more time to take care of
Alston.
</P>
<P>
   Three days before the murder, Bly sent 16-year-old fellow gang
member Anthony Houston to tail McLaughlin as he left the Suffolk
district attorney's office in downtown Boston for his home in West
Roxbury. With $5 in train fare, a notebook, and a pen, Houston
shadowed McLaughlin as he rode the commuter rail to the Highland
station in West Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, Houston followed McLaughlin to the parking lot,
where he saw him get into his rust-colored 1982 Toyota. They
exchanged nods, Houston recorded the prosecutor's license plate,
and reported back to Bly.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the murder, Bly and his associates, including
Ricardo Gittens, gathered at a second-floor apartment on Theodore
Street. Bly, according to prosecution witness Sandra Brown, told
his allies that McLaughlin had to die that night.
</P>
<P>
   Bly was driven to West Roxbury by Gittens, accompanied by a
younger gang member who was later told by Bly to leave. They
stopped in a bowling alley parking lot across from the station and
spotted McLaughlin's car parked on Railroad Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Gittens and Bly mapped out an escape route and drove over to
Clement Avenue, which parallels the railroad tracks. Gittens parked
at a bend of the street, while Bly returned to Railroad Avenue, hid
in the bushes, and was ready when McLaughlin got off the train
shortly before 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed as a combination Wild West outlaw/modern urban assassin,
with a bandana covering the lower half of his face, a knit wool cap
on his head, brown cotton gloves on his hands, and an oversized
black hooded sweatshirt drawn over his face, Bly called out to
McLaughlin as he got into his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted Paul McLaughlin to know who shot him,'' Brennan told
the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Bly then pounced on the prosecutor, pinned him against the car
door, and fired one .38 caliber bullet into the prosecutor's left
temple. McLaughlin, his left eye shattered by the bullet, collapsed
into his car. Bly leaned in and fired again.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn by the noise, another commuter shouted and Bly ran down
the tracks. About 150 yards from the station, he shed the clothing
that he believed would conceal his identity, but which actually
ended up tagging him as the murderer.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin's blood was found on the outside of the discarded
clothing and a tiny piece of human tissue inside the ring finger of
the left glove was linked to Bly through DNA tests.
</P>
<P>
   After the murder, Bly raced into a nearby backyard, tossed the
gun under a camping trailer, and rode off in Gittens' car.
</P>
<P>
   The massive investigation that began that night spent a year
focusing on a Jamaica Plain gang member, Jesus Carrasquillo, before
DNA testing excluded him but not Bly.
</P>
<P>
   With relentless pressure from the Boston and State police
detectives on the McLaughlin ``team,'' Bly's onetime allies began
to implicate him in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   And Bly himself aided detectives when Murray and Sergeant
Detective William Mahoney visited him in prison in 1996. They let
him smoke cigarettes, which were used to confirm DNA tests.
</P>
<P>
   Bly was finally indicted in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He had been imprisoned since late 1995, after a colleague of
McLaughlin's, Michael Pomarole, took over the carjacking case
following his murder and won a conviction with the help of Alston's
testimony. Bly was sentenced to 10 to 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Judge McDaniel ordered Bly's life sentence to begin
only after he has completed his current term. The Supreme Judicial
Court will automatically review the case.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Police Lieutenant Detective Stephen Murphy, one of the
investigators, said there was special significance that the verdict
came on the weekend when Americans honor fallen servicemen and
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a war,'' Murphy said of McLaughlin. ``He was in a
war on drugs. He was in a war against crime. And he paid for his
service with his life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
