<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6205 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN     05-29 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS NEED TO WORK ON ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Remember how seamlessly the great Lakers teams of
the '80s seemed to know and relish their roles?
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson ran the offense. Kareem Abdul-Jabbar was the No. 1
scoring option. James Worthy ran the break. Michael Cooper played
defense. None of these guys were exactly saints, but they knew how
to play as a team.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, the Lakers have imploded precisely because no
one seems to understand what their role is. Actually, the problem
is that today's Lakers all believe they have the same role.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal thinks it is his team.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant thinks it is his team.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice, for some reason, thinks it should be his team.
</P>
<P>
   And they all believe it without offering one iota of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   These stars might be able to operate in the same biosphere if
they had a forceful, experienced leader to meld the egos. Instead,
Kurt Rambis tried to juggle all of these personalities while still
learning how to be a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Add it all up, and it's another dreadful postseason exit for the
Lakers, with little reason to believe that next season will be much
different.
</P>
<P>
   The O'Neal-Bryant feud seems to be simmering during the best
times, and boiling when things go bad. They're both terrific
players, but too stubborn to figure out a way to get the Lakers to
the finals. O'Neal continues to be viewed as a joke because of his
atrocious free-throw shooting, while Bryant turns into a black hole
in the playoffs, incapable of passing the ball, especially to
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   And if that weren't enough, there's Rice, who seems happier
being a mad-gunner for mediocre teams rather than sacrifice a few
points in the name of a championship.
</P>
<P>
   If Rice returns next season, he'll probably be complaining on a
daily basis about not being featured enough in the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in Jerry Buss' meddling and Jerry West's commitment
issues, and the Lakers have little leadership on any level.
</P>
<P>
   Where does this leave them with Rambis?
</P>
<P>
   So far, he's just a taller version of Del Harris, with a lot
more to learn in the X's and O's department. He didn't understand
the rules when you foul in the final two minutes away from the
basket during an embarrassing loss to Golden State at the Forum in
April, and didn't use a foul the Lakers had to give in Game 2
against the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   More troublesome, there were rumors he had a falling out with
Derek Harper, one of the few Lakers willing to offer some
leadership skills.
</P>
<P>
   The only real answer to what the team misses is Johnson, who
could fill the void at point guard, and knock some heads in the
locker room. But his playing days are over.
</P>
<P>
   Magic still might be the answer if he became the Lakers head
coach. But his ill-fated attempts to coach in 1994 and play in 1996
demonstrated that he's no Larry Bird when it comes to relating to
``today's players.'' Both times, Johnson got out because he
couldn't understand the selfish attitude so pervasive in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The options are limited, leaving the Lakers destined to flail
for another season unless some massive personality adjustments take
place.
</P>
<P>
   Reality Checketts: Knicks president Dave Checketts is such a
devout Mormon that he did not attend last Sunday's Game 3 between
New York and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop him from lying on such an important day.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts said around tipoff Sunday that he had never contacted
Phil Jackson about the Knicks coaching job. An hour later,
Checketts admitted he had ``reached out through an intermediary''
to Jackson. A couple hours after that, Checketts admitted he had
actually met with Jackson for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Then he said he had also talked to reps for Doc Rivers and Dave
Cowens about the job.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, last we checked, Jeff Van Gundy is still the Knicks
coach, at least through the end of the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Here they come: The Clippers wasted no time scouting players for
their first-round pick, which is fourth overall.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's Trajan Langdon and William Avery worked out at the Sports
Arena this week. UCLA point guard Baron Davis and Arizona's Jason
Terry are expected to work out for the Clippers this week.
</P>
<P>
   Around the league: With Orlando needing a coach, the early
favorites to replace Chuck Daly are Phoenix assistant Scott Skiles,
a former Magic player, and Doc Rivers, currently a TV analyst. Also
getting some interest is former Charlotte coach Dave Cowens.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto, which finished fifth in the draft lottery, is actively
listening to trade offers for two reasons. The draft is weaker than
usual this year and the Raptors have the option to claim
Minnesota's pick at No. 14 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Minnesota, which has the sixth pick, is trying to
figure out how to move up and grab either Davis or Maryland's Steve
Francis. If they can grab one of the rookies, they will sign and
trade veteran point guard Terrell Brandon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NBA column appears Sundays in the Daily News. Staff Writer
Scott Wolf can be reached via e-mail at Scwolf1aol.com. &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
