NYT-05-29-99 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6208 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-BILLYPAYNE-COX     05-29 3545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BILLYPAYNE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Olympics Chief Billy Payne profited from land deals near
horse park
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Billy Payne's career path diverged dramatically one
Monday morning in February 1987, about the time Alton Housworth
drove into the city from nearby Conyers for a visit.
</P>
<P>
   Housworth apologized for missing the dedication of the sanctuary
at St. Luke's Presbyterian Church in Dunwoody, an Atlanta suburb,
the day before. The ceremony was gratifying and inspirational for
Payne, a real estate lawyer who had been the moving force behind
fund-raising for the new building.
</P>
<P>
   Housworth, a real estate broker, came to chat about the land
deals he was putting together for Payne near Atlanta in Rockdale
County.
</P>
<P>
   But Payne wanted to talk about his epiphany. The dedication
ceremony was the most exciting thing that had ever happened to him.
``Alton, I've got to find another challenge,'' he told his friend.
``I stayed awake all night trying to come up with something that
would benefit the community and the state. I've got an idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea, of course, was bringing the 1996 Summer Olympics to
Atlanta. Payne asked Housworth what he thought. ``Hey, I don't know
nothing about the Olympics,'' he responded. But he figured if
anybody could take such a fanciful scheme and convert it into
reality, his friend Billy could.
</P>
<P>
   Payne saw possibilities where others didn't, whether they were
in delivering the Olympics to his hometown or in risky land
speculation in rural Rockdale, where he and his partners had just
purchased hundreds of acres of undeveloped farmland and forest.
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone knows the legend of Payne, the intrepid volunteer
who gave up everything to win the Games for his city. Few are aware
that Payne never really gave up his real estate pursuits _ even
borrowing money against his land while chasing his Olympic dream,
patiently waiting for the day it would be worth something big.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer still are aware that his two pursuits collided in 1991,
when the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games decided to move
its equestrian venue from Stone Mountain Park to a 1,100-acre site
in sleepy Conyers, the county seat of Rockdale _ minutes from the
tracts of property Payne held an interest in _ despite formidable
competition from other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of visitors ventured to Conyers for the Games.
Commercial development fired up. And now, while the city negotiates
to unload its Olympic landmark, the czar of Atlanta's Games is
cashing out of the area, his land deals bringing him and his
partnership more than a $1 million profit.
</P>
<P>
   In both dreams, the possibilities played out just as Payne
predicted. But did his private interests in Rockdale bump up
against the state's interests in putting on the best Olympics
possible?
</P>
<P>
   Payne would not comment for this article. His chief lieutenant,
A.D. Frazier Jr., says he was aware of Payne's property holdings
and he, not Payne, selected the equestrian venue.
</P>
<P>
   But others believe that had Payne been an elected official, more
scrutiny would have been applied. ``I think, rightly or wrongly,
ACOG officials _ and, in this case, Billy _ were given the benefit
of the doubt, which was characteristic of the time,'' says Michael
Lomax, former Fulton County Commission chairman and member of the
Metropolitan Atlanta Olympic Games Authority, the state oversight
authority set up to protect taxpayers' interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did not get the level of consideration that it would have
had it been an elected official owning property near a site that
was about to be significantly increased in value as a result of a
decision he would make.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockdale deals
</P>
<P>
   Rockdale, about 25 miles due east of downtown Atlanta, is the
second-smallest county in the state. It had yet to be swallowed up
by the suburban development wave when Billy Payne discovered its
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Payne, who specialized in risky land speculation, had done quite
well in Gwinnett County, when the new Gwinnett Place mall turned
rural pastures into small fortunes for speculators who had bought
the acreage years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1986, Payne was looking for the next diamond in
the rough. He responded to a classified ad placed by Alton
Housworth in the Atlanta newspapers. Housworth was selling some
property on Big Haynes Creek in north Rockdale. Payne was looking
for some land where he and his son could fish and shoot skeet.
After riding the property, Payne told Housworth it wasn't quite
right.
</P>
<P>
   But Housworth, who knew the county and its biggest landowners
like the back of his hand, had turned Payne on to Rockdale's
upside. For one thing, talk had swirled for a few years about the
Turner Hill Mall going up a couple of exits toward Atlanta on I-20.
It could be another Gwinnett Place explosion in the making.
</P>
<P>
   That very afternoon, Housworth showed Payne a 56-acre tract at
the northeast corner of the interchange at I-20 and Ga. 138.
Fronting on the expressway, it would be a good location for one of
the so-called ``power centers'' eating up the suburbs once the
development boom hit Rockdale. Payne put a contract on it for $1.5
million. Then he turned to a longtime client, Ellis Godshall, who
had grown wealthy in the convenience store business, to become his
limited partner and put up all the necessary cash.
</P>
<P>
   Rockdale ``had become pretty stagnant as far as people making
investments,'' Housworth recalls. ``Billy was willing to step up to
the plate and make a commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Within months, Payne put contracts on two more tracts, with a
combined 123 acres, adjacent to his property. Mostly forest and
wetlands, they, too, fronted on the interstate. As before, he
needed partners with ready cash to support his vision.
</P>
<P>
   So, Housworth introduced him to A.R. ``Gus'' Barksdale, whose
family name is synonymous with Rockdale. Local legend has it that
he owned half the county and ran the other half. The Barksdales and
Vaughns, Rockdale's two most prominent families and related by
marriage, ran an important law firm, held seats in city and county
government and typically bought up most of the investment property
in what was essentially their county.
</P>
<P>
   Until Payne showed up. ``When Billy came on the scene and began
putting all the pieces of property under contract they had an eye
on for years, it was exciting for me,'' Housworth says. ``When
someone comes in from out of town and starts gobbling up the
county, it stirs things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne persuaded Barksdale to put up the $2.1 million required to
buy the two additional tracts and agree to cut Payne in for 35
percent of the profits when they sold. Payne told him that with his
real estate contacts, he could find a developer and they would make
a killing.
</P>
<P>
   Payne kept gobbling up land. He found an additional 116 acres of
scrub and pine forest along Gees Mill Road on the backside of the
big tract and put it under contract for about $1 million. Barksdale
declined to ante up all the money this time, so he assembled a team
of investors and gave Payne a 20 percent interest. Since the land
was not on the interstate, they decided to develop the tract into a
business park.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale apparently wasn't interested in the 50 acres across
the street picked up by Payne. So Payne sold the contract for a
profit to an Atlanta group headed by software entrepreneur Robert
Cramer.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year later, Barksdale died. His widow and children
became Payne's partners.
</P>
<P>
   With an interest in 300 acres of Rockdale County's best real
estate, Payne decided to sit tight and wait for the expected
commercial boom. Then the land could be worth millions.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after filing the deeds on the Gees Mill property,
Payne told Housworth of his newest interest. They had one last
piece of Rockdale land to close on. Payne told Housworth to deal
with it; he was moving on to other opportunities. ``I'm going to
make some phone calls,'' he told Housworth, ``and see if I can't
get something started on the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   The venue switch
</P>
<P>
   Not a month after Atlanta was awarded the Games in September
1990, Roland Vaughn, Conyers' young city manager and chief of
police, was plotting to attract an Olympic venue to his town of
8,000.
</P>
<P>
   The city planned to purchase a 1,139-acre farm bordering the
Yellow River to dispose of treated waste water. He hoped to find a
recreational use for the rolling, woodsy landscape and had hired a
consultant to come up with options. Michael Plummer recommended a
horse park modeled after the successful Kentucky Horse Park.
</P>
<P>
   Stone Mountain Park, which the Atlanta Olympic bid team had
originally designated as the site for the equestrian venue, wasn't
interested in a permanent facility. Plummer had shared a plane ride
with Payne, who told him during the flight that a key consideration
for any potential Olympic site was the legacy _ what would remain
for the public after the Games ended.
</P>
<P>
   By January 1991, Conyers and Rockdale leaders had formed a task
force to go after the Olympics. Payne's real estate partner _ the
late Gus Barksdale's son, Wales _ was a member of the steering
committee. ``I had known Billy, but not as well as Wales,'' recalls
Vaughn, like Payne a former football player at the University of
Georgia. ``He was a senior when I was freshman. He was an idol. I
sat on the bench'' when he was an all-star.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Atlanta Olympic committee announced that it was
reconsidering having Stone Mountain Park as equestrian host. The
sport's international officials feared that the bright granite
mountain would attract too much heat for the horses' comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals poured in from a dozen municipalities and private
interests. Although Olympic officials never identified any bids but
the four finalists, records housed in the nine boxes of documents
released at the Atlanta History Center indicated other serious
contenders, including Callaway Gardens; Hall County's Chicopee
Woods Area Park, which had recently built a new equestrian center
with an arena and stables; and Rabun Gap, where the Atlanta
Steeplechase is now held.
</P>
<P>
   Many were quickly eliminated because the site, financing or
planned use after the Games was inadequate, Frazier says. The
Rockdale location made the final cut, along with:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bouckhaert Farm in Murray County, an up-and-running
international equestrian competition site preparing to host part of
that year's Pan American Games, as well as trials for U.S. riding
teams headed to the 1992 Barcelona Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Berry College in Rome, which hoped to use the Games to expand
its equestrian education program.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cochran Mill Park in rural south Fulton County, an 800-acre
county-owned nature preserve.
</P>
<P>
   The Conyers/Rockdale Equestrian Task Force put forth a
persuasive communitywide bid. Townsfolk wore ``We share the dream''
buttons. Schoolchildren wrote letters to Payne. A 1984 gold medal
rider helped make the pitch. The city and county offered to throw
in $3.5 million toward capital costs.
</P>
<P>
   During the official site visit, Atlanta Olympic and equestrian
officials had lunch and mint juleps at Wales Barksdale's family
farm at the horse park's back entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn says Payne's status as a big landholder in Rockdale was
irrelevant to the bid. ``It wasn't a factor in any way in us
considering it as leverage,'' he says. ``In fact, we thought it
might work against us because of Billy's absolute desire to make
sure everything was perceived to be appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, Payne's chief operating officer and now president of
the management firm Invesco Inc., says, ``We had a group of people
(in Rockdale) who desperately wanted this thing and were willing to
put up infrastructure to do it. It was public property and a public
benefit. It was an easy choice to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many were stunned, none more so than Carl Bouckhaert, a
wealthy carpet company owner and horse enthusiast. He pointed out
that ACOG's cost at Bouckhaert Farm would have been $8.9 million,
about one-third of its $24 million tab in Conyers. ``It was the
most unbelievable thing,'' Bouckhaert says.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier contends that Olympic officials were reluctant to spend
any amount to improve private property such as Bouckhaert's. ``The
capital savings is far outweighed by the legacy,'' Frazier asserted
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Bouckhaert also made a personal offer to Payne _ less than two
weeks before the winning bid was announced _ to stage the three-day
endurance event at his farm at no cost to ACOG if the venue went
elsewhere. Bouckhaert estimated his offer would save ACOG up to $8
million by eliminating the need to build a cross-country course
that would be used only once. His offer was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lomax, now the president of Dillard University in New
Orleans, supported Cochran Mill Park but considered Bouckhaert Farm
the most serious competition. He had regarded Rockdale as ``an
improbable choice. They never had any equestrian venues. It was not
what you called horse country. It just seemed peculiar they moved
to the top of the loop.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Lomax was so surprised at the selection of the
Rockdale site that he raised the issue of Payne's property
holdings. Nobody, including the news media, paid much attention.
``Public officials who raised legitimate issues were treated as
pariahs,'' Lomax recalls. ``There was this sense of extraordinary
gratitude to Billy for bringing the Games to Atlanta and also a
view that they (Payne's team) were really above public review and
accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Payne said in 1994, when he was first questioned
by the media, that he disclosed his Rockdale property holdings to
Frazier and ACOG's board of ethics and that the board saw no
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Echols, a spokesman for Payne, says Payne did not wish to be
interviewed for this article. ``He isn't talking about anything
Olympics these days,'' Echols said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the ethics board's chairman, former Emory University
President James T. Laney, nor board member Johnnetta B. Cole,
former president of Spelman College, said they recall the matter
coming before the board.
</P>
<P>
   The board was appointed in April 1991. ``Our principal concern
was to establish the guidelines for conflict of interest and how to
ensure there would be objectivity and no favoritism involved,''
says Laney, who became the U.S. ambassador to South Korea upon
leaving Emory in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The third board member, G. Conley Ingram, was out of the country
and unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Sinkfield, attorney for the ethics board, said the
matter was discussed at an Oct. 16 meeting, one week before the
move to Rockdale was announced. According to the minutes provided
by Sinkfield, Laney was not present. Minutes that Sinkfield faxed
to this newspaper indicated that Payne provided an affidavit
disclosing ownership of land in the Rockdale area and the board
concluded that because Payne's property was not to be acquired for
the venue, it saw no conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I'm surprised he even bothered to bring the matter
before us,'' Sinkfield said. The board's ruling was not disclosed
to the public.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear if other Atlanta Olympic records could shed more
light on the matter. Payne's private foundation, the Georgia
Amateur Athletics Foundation, claims it owns the records and is
fighting in court to keep some of them from the public.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier says Payne told him about his interests in Rockdale. The
former banker started work at ACOG in April 1991 after the
committee had already begun seeking a new home for the venue. Known
as a straight-shooter, Frazier acknowledges he was concerned about
the appearance of a conflict and says the choice of
Conyers/Rockdale was ultimately his, not Payne's.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier says of Payne's Rockdale property, ``He certainly
disclosed it to me and stayed out of the decision. And, frankly, it
was a no-brainer choice anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Lomax contends the final call may have been Frazier's but
speculates that Payne surely had some influence. ``I don't believe
any of the decisions that were made by ACOG were made without his
knowledge or involvement,'' Lomax says. ``Billy ran that place with
an iron hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Venue changes had to be approved by MAOGA, the state oversight
panel, which included Lomax. Its chairman, George Berry, a
respected and longtime municipal administrator and now senior
executive at Cousins Properties, recalls reviewing two bids _
Conyers/Rockdale and Bouckhaert Farm. ACOG recommended the former;
MAOGA approved it.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, MAOGA sharply criticized Olympic officials after
they announced that public officials who owned businesses could
have Olympic contracts, an ill-conceived policy that was rescinded
later. Authority members argued that in an endeavor as
image-sensitive as the Games, appearances were crucial.
</P>
<P>
   But the state panel had nothing to say about Payne's real estate
interests. ``My recollection is that was handled by ACOG's ethics
board,'' Berry says. ``We were told there were no ethical
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good deal for Conyers and Rockdale County,'' Roland
Vaughn crowed when the venue contract was awarded. ``And it could
be a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the horse park a ``growth engine for our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will leave a huge legacy behind that we hope is going to
develop into a large tourist attraction,'' said Ed Thomas, then
chairman of the Conyers-Rockdale Chamber of Commerce. The horse
park would pump $90 million a year into the county and generate
2,514 jobs, consultants estimated.
</P>
<P>
   But it never lived up to expectations, and now the city is
hoping to sell the park rather than risking debt to support it.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Wales Barksdale negotiated the final draft of the
venue contract with ACOG, the engine began to sputter.
</P>
<P>
   When real cost estimates came in, Randy Poynter, chairman of the
Rockdale County Board of Commissioners, choked. Fearing the county
would go into debt to build the park, he pulled Rockdale out. It
turned out to be a fortuitous move.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers wanted the park so badly that Vaughn called Mayor
Charles Walker, who was vacationing in Europe. Could the city go it
alone? The mayor was game. But proposed soccer fields, softball
fields and a swimming pool would have to be scratched from the
master plan. And the Atlanta Olympic committee would have to kick
in the money the county was going to put up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hell of a good deal when we made it,'' Frazier says.
``It turned out to be less of a good deal and we had to live with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It became less of a good deal for Conyers, too. The horse park
cost the city substantially more than expected _ more than $20
million in all.
</P>
<P>
   When the Games closed, there was no clear marketing strategy
designed to bring in the profits to pay off the bank debt and the
bond issues needed to fund construction. After building a golf club
and apartment complex, the city had no money to develop the
remaining 900 acres. Efforts to attract world-class equine
competitions never panned out.
</P>
<P>
   Saddled with debt, the city sold its water and sewer system to
the county for $12 million _ less than half the original asking
price _ to pay off a horse park construction loan. After the sale
in 1997, Conyers residents were stuck with a 28 percent rate
increase in their water bills.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor retired last year, and Vaughn quit city government to
go to work for big Olympics contractor Beers Construction as
marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   But Billy Payne has done just fine in Conyers. Prior to the
Games, he and his partner pulled in an estimated $500,000 or more
in profit on deals on three sites, including the 56 acres at Ga.
138 and I-20 _ which would later become the primary access
interchange to the horse park.
</P>
<P>
   Payne did not receive his payoff on the site until 1994. Two
years later, the property was developed into Conyers Plaza, with a
Home Depot, Wal-Mart and Rhodes Furniture _ just as he had
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   That development and the widening of Ga. 138 _ in preparation
for Olympic traffic to the horse park _ enhanced the value of the
123-acre site along I-20 he still held with the Barksdales,
according to an independent appraisal in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 alone, 15 new hotels, restaurants and retail stores
opened in Rockdale _ primarily clustered around the Ga. 138/I-20
interchange _ fueled by the horse park and about 2,000 new
residents a year.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Payne was ready to cash in. In August, he sued his
partners, who he believed had sold some of their land at
below-market value without his consent. They agreed to settle.
Payne, who had never invested his own money, received $696,000,
according to documents filed recently at the Rockdale County
Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   That figure represents his return for assembling some tracts of
forest and wetlands nobody else wanted more than a decade ago.
During his six-year tenure, he also made $4 million in salary from
the Atlanta Olympic committee and, after the Olympics, cash from
the sale of his personal memorabilia to his private foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
