<HEADLINE>
IN SPORTS, THE SIZE OF THE HEART DETERMINES THE STATURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Locally, it's a big holiday weekend for the little guys of the
sports world.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, how tall is tall?
</P>
<P>
   Like that Game 5 this afternoon at Reunion Arena. Ever seen
Eddie Belfour in street clothes? Almost jockey size.
</P>
<P>
   But standing between the pipes during these Stanley Cup
playoffs, The Eagle has been one large man.
</P>
<P>
   Ever seen Marlon St. Julien in street clothes? He's a little
fellow, which makes Marlon just the right size for his chosen
profession.
</P>
<P>
   But dress him up in silks, and place St. Julien atop 1,200
pounds of thoroughbred muscle and fury. There is suddenly nothing
small about the skill, the courage and the talent that's required.
</P>
<P>
   You wanna see something tall for the Memorial Day weekend?
</P>
<P>
   See Eddie today at Reunion. Then see Marlon and an army of other
race riders tomorrow in Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   A million dollars in purse money goes on the line tomorrow at
Lone Star Park. It's easily the biggest day for thoroughbred racing
ever in the state. Seven stake events totaling a cool million in
purses reaffirms the continuing success Lone Star Park has quickly
carved out in our very crowded sports market.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we all know, the competition for the sports dollar in North
Texas is fierce,'' said Lone Star general manager Corey Johnsen.
``But as a newcomer, it gives us a challenge. We'd better be good,
and we'd better keep coming up with major events that provide
exposure for our product and our sport in general. That's what this
million-dollar day is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a strange, yet interesting year for thoroughbred
racing on the national scene. A former claimer, Charismatic, is
going for the Triple Crown next week, which is the equivalent of
the Fort Worth Fire playing for the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Charismatic's rider, Chris Antley, who in
January considered himself washed up in the profession.
``Charismatic is knocked for being a claiming horse, but I was
lower than him _ I had been turned out,'' laughed Antley during a
visit to Lone Star Park last week.
</P>
<P>
   St. Julien, in a different way, knows the feeling. When Lone
Star opened two summers ago, he was a struggling regional rider.
``I thank God for this place _ it's where it all began to happen
for me,'' said St. Julien, who had a strong 1997 season in Grand
Prairie, then won the Lone Star riding title in '98, and this year
is cemented as one of middle America's top jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Denise, has been here every step of the way, helping
supplement the family income as a mutuels teller at Lone Star in
'97. But with 4-month-old Jasmin being a new addition to the St.
Julien family, Denise is now strictly a mother and Marlon's No. 1
fan. Watch the winner's circle at Lone Star. When Marlon is posing
for a picture, Denise and daughter Jasmin are always there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thankful for the success I've had, but on a day like
Monday, when all that money will be on the line, I darn sure won't
be forgetting my days at Delta Downs \Ra small south Louisiana
track\S,'' said St. Julien. ``I was riding for nothing. I never had
to watch my weight _ there wasn't any money to buy food anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   From the $300,000 Lone Star Park Handicap, to the $250,000 USA
Stakes, to the $150,000 Prestonwood Distaff, and right on down the
line, St. Julien has mounts tomorrow in all seven stake races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that long ago when money was tight for Denise and
me, and I needed to win these kind of pots to make ends meet,'' he
said. ``Don't think that doesn't put you in a different state of
mind. It will mess with your attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``But since being blessed with some success, I can approach the
big races without that kind of thing pulling at me. Be it a
five-thousand-dollar claiming race, or one of these stakes, your
mind is clear. While you are nervous, it's a good nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   On the backside in Grand Prairie, or the Fairgrounds in New
Orleans, or wherever, St. Julien is also well-known as one of the
good guys in the business. Always upbeat and friendly, St. Julien
was a winner in personality and attitude even before he became a
leading rider. Better yet, nothing changed with success.
</P>
<P>
   On a holiday weekend that features some little big men competing
for high stakes, one size fits all _ the size of the heart is the
only measurement that matters.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
