<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDY IS KING TODAY, BUT DAYTONA RULES RACING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ The question is a foolish one, because there's
no doubt what the answer will be.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's being asked deep in the heart of stock-car
racing country, where the only sport that matters is sponsored by
cigarette and beer companies.
</P>
<P>
   And it's being asked of Dale Jarrett, who was born and bred in
Hickory, N.C., and nursed on Unocal 76 racing fuel, and as points
leader on the Winston Cup circuit clearly has an agenda.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's asked anyway: Dale, which is the bigger race
today, the Indianapolis 500 or the Coca-Cola 600?
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot that there was a race going on in Indy,'' Jarrett
says.
</P>
<P>
   The gist of the answer is expected. NASCAR's longest race, a
prime-time event at a Southern track with roots that extend to the
beginning of the sport, is more important to a driver who shares
those roots than a race at a Midwest track with those funny,
open-wheel cars.
</P>
<P>
   But it's surprising in its audacity. Five years ago, no one
would dare jest about forgetting the storied, historic, traditional
Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, five years ago no one would dare pose the question.
</P>
<P>
   In those five years much has changed in the world of
motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's popularity has soared, taking it from a regional, niche
sport for good ol' boys to a national success story.
</P>
<P>
   Indy-car racing's popularity has plummeted, starting when
Indianapolis Motor Speedway president Tony George formed a racing
league and restricted the guest list to the race at his track.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there was one open-wheel series, Indy played a
bigger role,'' said Michael Kranefuss, who was involved in
open-wheel racing as head of Ford's worldwide racing division but
now is a stock-car guy as owner of the No. 12 Ford driven by Jeremy
Mayfield. ``You had all the big names there. You had the Unsers,
the Andrettis. Today you've got a series with a bunch of people
that America cannot relate to.''
</P>
<P>
   The recognition issue is indeed a problem for the IRL, which has
too many guys named Sam Schmidt, Tyce Carlson, Jeff Ward, Steve
Knapp and Jimmy Kite. The drivers with the most star quality in the
IRL today are Arie Luyendyk, who's retiring after the race, and
Tony Stewart, whose real job is racing a stock car.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the recognition deal is also a problem for the other
open-wheel series. The top driver on the CART circuit is Juan
Montoya. Or is he the guy who beat Pete Sampras at the U.S. Open?
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR has no such problems. Its poster boy, Jeff Gordon,
appears in TV commercials and on billboards with a milk mustache.
Its stars, including Dale Earnhardt, Rusty Wallace, Mark Martin,
Terry and Bobby Labonte and Jarrett, are known to even casual fans.
</P>
<P>
   But does that make the NASCAR race the biggest of the day?
Doesn't tradition count for something?
</P>
<P>
   According to Texas Motor Speedway president Eddie Gossage _
whose track promotes NASCAR and IRL events _ it does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stars don't make Indy,'' he said. ``Indy makes the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Gossage is right. The drivers don't make Indy. Indy
makes the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The race is big for the same reason the Kentucky Derby is big.
</P>
<P>
   The horses change every year, but we watch the Derby every year
because it's an ``event.'' It's the tradition, the history.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true for the Indy 500. It has tradition _ the winner
drinks milk _ and history. It has a dignified trophy that means
something, unlike the cheesy thing with the plastic soft drink
bottle on it that they'll give the winner of the stock-car race.
</P>
<P>
   It's an event, much more likely to draw the casual fan who
doesn't care about things such as whether the No. 54 American-made
car is loose or tight.
</P>
<P>
   The Indy 500 is a spectacle. The Coca-Cola 600 is one of 34
races on the Winston Cup schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Indy 500 is the bigger race today.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Indy 500 no longer is the biggest race of the year.
That distinction belongs to NASCAR's Daytona 500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
