<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHLETES-WAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD WAR II FOCUSED ATHLETES ON A FAR MORE IMPORTANT CONFLICT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Roland ``Stormy'' Goss stood on the edge of the Rhine
River on a frigid night in 1945, preparing to help move General
George Patton's army deeper into Germany, when a scratchy voice
came over his walkie-talkie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stormy, I'm worried about this one,'' said Vince Avalone, one
of his closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong? We've been through this before and it will be
OK,'' Goss replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something's been bothering me,'' the Bronx native said.
``Eight years ago today my dad died, and it's been on my mind all
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, German soldiers began shelling. Goss and another
soldier jumped into a foxhole, as did Avalone. Too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out and there were my buddy's \RAvalone\S two legs
sticking out in the air,'' Goss said. ``A shell had killed him
instantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Goss' voice cracks at the memory of a war that took him from
SMU's football fields and put him on Europe's battlefields. Many,
such as Avalone, never returned. Others, such as Goss, had their
lives changed forever.
</P>
<P>
   From 1942-45, college football continued despite the absence of
thousands of athletes forced to abandon their dreams to serve in
the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   There were adjustments. On Jan. 1, 1942, for instance, the Rose
Bowl was played in Durham, N.C., for fear the Japanese would bomb
the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   One year later, after thousands joined the service, colleges
nationwide stopped fielding teams. In 1942, there were 525
four-year colleges that played football. One season later, there
were 146.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys played who were under the draft age or who had physical
problems that prevented them from being drafted, but they could
play football,'' said Pat Harmon, a retired sportswriter and a
historian for the College Football Hall of Fame. ``The quality of
play was down.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1943-44, Baylor was the lone Southwest Conference school to
cease play. Its administration felt it didn't have enough athletes,
and it wanted to support the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   With enlistment at a record high, service-academy teams thrived
with athletes who played in their spare time while training. In
1944, half of the programs ranked in the Top 20 were
service-academy teams.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 6, 1941, Goss, a senior lineman, played in all but one
minute of the Mustangs' 6-0 loss to Rice at Ownby Stadium. It would
be the last game of his football career.
</P>
<P>
   On June 6, 1944, Goss had three boats under his command
stationed off Omaha Beach, where the highest casualty rates of the
Normandy invasion occurred on D-Day. They supplied engineers with
explosives to clear mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the Germans were fortified, and they were waiting for
us,'' Goss said. ``I saw boats hit mines and explode. ... It was a
horrible experience. I said a few prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, 18-year-old Frank Denius, a former punter at the
Citadel and current Austin resident, landed on Omaha Beach. As a
field observer, he was in charge of locating enemy fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hit the ground running and you kept your eyes open and you
prayed, but not necessarily in that order,'' Denius said. ``We were
too scared to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war, both men returned to Texas. Goss went into
business and became a SWC football official for 27 years. Denius
practiced law in Austin for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Denius has returned to several of the places where so much of
the fighting occurred _ and where so many of his friends died.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are parts there I still know like back of my hand,''
Denius said. ``Going to the cemetery in Normandy or looking at
those beaches is very emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   Goss keeps in touch with the eight living members of the
original 15 men under his command and plans to attend a reunion in
June.
</P>
<P>
   He also kept a tie to the ones who didn't return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I named my oldest son after Vincent Avalone.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
