A6222 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTURY-1940s-TEX     05-29 2105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-1940s-TEX </SLUG>
 
TIME CAPSULE FOR THE 1940s 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1940 Jan. 1: 92,000 see Southern Cal upend Tennessee in the Rose
Bowl, 14-0. Jan. 21: Jack Nicklaus is born. March 14: Warner
Brothers Studios casts Ronald Reagan to play George Gipp in ``Knute
Rockne _ All American.'' March 29: Joe Louis defends his
heavyweight boxing title at Madison Square Garden, knocking out
Johnny Paychek in the second round. April 7: Jimmy Demaret wins the
Masters by four strokes. May 10: Winston Churchill, a critic of
British appeasement toward the Nazi regime before the start of
hostilities in Europe in September 1939, takes over as Prime
Minister of the United Kingdom. ``I have nothing to offer but
blood, tears, toil and sweat,'' Churchill says. May 30: Wilbur Shaw
wins his second consecutive Indy 500. June 4: The British royal
navy and countless private vessels as small as open motorboats
rescue 340,000 beleaguered British and French troops from Dunkirk,
France, in the greatest and most successful wartime evacuation in
history. German troops triumphantly march through Paris 10 days
later. Aug. 21: Exiled Bolshevik Leon Trotsky, Josef Stalin's most
ardent critic, is assassinated at his villa in Mexico City. Sept.
26: President Franklin Roosevelt inflames tensions with Japan,
closing off U.S. steel exports to any country but Britain and those
in the New World. Oct. 8: The Cincinnati Reds defeat the Detroit
Tigers, 2-1, in the seventh game of the World Series. Oct. 20:
Roosevelt again promises not to send Americans into the rapidly
widening conflict that will become World War II. Oct. 24: The Fair
Labor Standards Act makes the 40-hour work week standard in the
U.S. The Supreme Court rules the law constitutional in February
1941. Comp time is not mentioned. Nov. 30: Navy halts the Army
ground attack in the annual football rivalry, 14-0. Dec. 8: The
Chicago Bears win the NFL championship, 73-0, over the Washington
Redskins.
1941 March 13: The Boston Bruins clobber the New York Americans,
8-3, and take their fourth consecutive divisional hockey title.
June: Whirlaway, with Eddie Arcaro riding, wins the Belmont Stakes
and horse racing's fifth Triple Crown. Whirlaway is the first of
four in the decade. The others? Count Fleet (1943); Assault (1946);
and Citation (1948). June 7: Craig Wood dominates the field with a
score of 284 at Colonial Country Club, winning the U.S. Open by
three strokes over Denny Shute. July 17: New York Yankees center
fielder Joe DiMaggio has his 56-game hitting streak snapped. Third
baseman Ken Keltner makes two great stops of DiMaggio blasts down
the line. Sept. 28: Boston Red Sox outfielder Ted Williams enters
the final day of the regular season hitting .3995. He can sit out
the doubleheader and be credited with a .400 batting average. He
plays and goes 6-for-8 with a home run to finish with a .406
average.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 7: Warplanes from the Empire of Japan bomb the United
States Pacific Fleet at Pearl Harbor on Oahu, Hawaii, at 7:50 a.m.
The attack comes 30 minutes before the official declaration of war
is delivered to the president by the Japanese ambassador. Dec. 11:
Germany and Italy honor their signing of the Axis Alliance with
Japan and declare war on the United States. The U.S declares
against the other Axis powers on the same day.
1942 Cleveland Indians shortstop Lou Boudreau becomes the second
youngest manager ever at 24. Jan. 1: Twenty-five days after the
attack on Pearl Harbor, Oregon State defeats Duke, 20-16, in the
Rose Bowl. The game had been moved from Pasadena, Calif., to
Durham, N.C., because of fears that the Japanese might attack such
a large gathering on the West Coast. Jan. 1: Joe Louis defends his
heavyweight title for the 20th time, defeating Buddy Baer in the
first round. Jan. 20: Nazi officials codify the Final Solution, the
extermination of all ``subhumans.'' Among the many groups targeted
are Jews, gypsies, Arabs and Africans. Feb. 5: ``Captain Comeback''
Roger Staubach is born. Staubach will become the leader and
strong-willed quarterback for the Dallas Cowboys. June 7: A
pitifully outnumbered and patched-together American fleet turns the
tide of the World War II Pacific campaign, sinking four Japanese
aircraft carriers in a four-day battle near Midway Island. The U.S.
carrier Yorktown is sunk, but Japanese advances cease across the
Pacific. Oct: Boston Red Sox outfielder Ted Williams wins the
Triple Crown, batting .356 with 36 home runs and 137 runs batted
in.
1943 Jan. 31: The Soviet Union begins to turn the tide of World War
II in Europe, accepting the unconditional surrender of the German
Sixth Army at Stalingrad. Less than 1,000 of the 220,000-plus
German troops encircled at Stalingrad will survive the war and
return home. The Soviets win the biggest tank battle in history in
July at Kursk _ nearly a year before the American and British
invasion of Normandy _ and the Germans begin an unabated retreat on
the Eastern Front that lasts the rest of the war. Oct. 16: The
National Boxing Association declares a freeze on all boxing titles
for the duration of the war. Heavyweight champ Joe Louis was
serving in the army at the time. Nov. 11: The Chicago Bears' Sid
Luckman throws for seven touchdowns in a victory against the NY
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   1944
</P>
<P>
   Swimmer Ann Curtis becomes the first female athlete ever to win
the Sullivan Award awarded to the nation's top amateur athlete.
June 5: With jockey Johnny Longden riding, Count Fleet wins the
75th Belmont Stakes to become the sixth horse ever to win the
Triple Crown. June 6: In the largest amphibious assault ever,
America leads the Allied invasion onto the beaches of Normandy in
northern France. June 10: Fifteen-year-old Cincinnati Reds pitcher
Joe Nuxhall becomes the youngest player ever to pitch in the major
leagues. He pitches 2/3 of an inning in an 18-0 loss to St. Louis,
giving up five runs on two hits, five walks and one wild pitch.
Oct. 10: In an all-St. Louis World Series, the Cardinals defeated
the Browns, 3-1, in Game 6 to win the championship. Dec. 2: Army
beats Navy for the first time in five years, 23-7. Dec. 17: The
Green Bay Packers win the NFL title with 14-7 victory against the
New York Giants.
1945
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball cancels the All-Star game at the request
of the U.S. government. Jan. 1: Southern Cal blanks Tennesee in the
Rose Bowl, 25-0. Jan. 27: The Red Army liberates Auschwitz, a Nazi
death camp in Poland, finding 4,000 dazed and starving civilian
prisoners, most of them Jewish. April 12: President Roosevelt dies,
less than a month short of Allied victory in Europe. Vice President
Harry Truman assumes the role of President. May 7: A week after
Adolph Hitler commits suicide in his Berlin bunker, Germany accepts
unconditional surrender to Allied forces, ending the war in Europe.
July 15: In one of the most dominating streaks in sports history,
Byron Nelson wins the PGA Championship in match play against Sam
Byrd, 4-and-3. It is his ninth of 11 consecutive PGA Tour victories
during the year and one of a record 18 tournaments he wins in 1945.
Aug. 6: American Army Air Corps colonel Paul Tibbets pilots a B-29
bomber named ``Enola Gay'' above Hiroshima, Japan, dropping the
world's first atomic bomb used in war. A second atomic bomb was
dropped three days later on Nagasaki, Japan, by a B-29 dubbed
``Boxcar.'' Sept. 2: Japan officially and unconditionally
surrenders aboard the USS Missouri in Tokyo Bay as Gen. Douglas
MacArthur presides. World War II closes with the loss of an
estimated 50 million lives _ military and civilian.
Oct. 14: The Chicago Cardinals snap the NFL's longest losing streak
at 29 games, defeating the Chicago Bears, 16-7. Nov. 22: The
Cleveland Browns' Jim Benton has 303 yards receiving against
Detroit; the third-highest total in NFL history.
1946
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hogan wins the inaugural Colonial National Invitation
Tournament with a four-round score of 279.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Bob Feller of the Cleveland Indians strikes out 348
batters for the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Basketball Association of America, later to evolve into the
National Basketball Association, is formed.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Rams ushered in the era of major-league sports on
the West Coast when they moved to Los Angeles months after winning
their first NFL championship behind rookie quarterback Bob
Waterfield. The Rams, who played at the Los Angeles Coliseum, the
Rose Bowl and Anaheim Stadium at various times, remained in
Southern California until 1995, when they moved to St. Louis. Jan.
1: Alabama crushes Southern Cal in the Rose Bowl, 34-14. March 21:
The Los Angeles Rams sign former UCLA halfback Kenny Washington,
the NFL's first black player since the 1920s. The Rams also signed
end Woody Strode on May 7. In the rival All-America Football
Conference, Cleveland Browns coach Paul Brown signed guard Bill
Willis on Aug. 6 and fullback Marion Motley on Aug. 9. All four
played that season, becoming the first African-Americans to take
the field in the modern era of big-league sports. May 30: After a
four-year hiatus because of the war, the Indianapolis 500 is run,
with George Robson winning. Oct. 16: Gordie Howe scores his first
NHL goal. Dec. 15: The Chicago Bears win the NFL title, defeating
the New York Giants, 24-14.
1947
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hogan wins his second Colonial in two years, matching his
279 total of the year before. April 10: After having his contract
sold by the Montreal Royals of the International League to the
Brooklyn Dodgers, Jackie Robinson becomes the first black athlete
to play in the major leagues. He later wins the rookie-of-the-year
award.
</P>
<P>
   June 12: Babe Didrikson Zaharias is the first American to win
the British Women's Golf Championship. July 5: American Jack Kramer
wins Wimbledon, the first American to win since Bobby Riggs in
1939. (The tournament was canceled from 1940-1945). Aug: The first
Little League World Series is held in Williamsport, Pa., with the
hometown team of Maynard winning. October: Joe DiMaggio wins his
third American League MVP award. October: Ted Williams wins his
second Triple Crown, batting .343 with 32 home runs and 114 RBI.
October 14: Flying a Bell X-1 named ``Glamorous Glennis'' high
above the California desert, American test-pilot Chuck Yeager
breaks through the mythical ``Wall of Air'' and hits mach 1.07,
becoming the first man to break the sound barrier.
1948
</P>
<P>
   Denver's Mile High Stadium is opened. Feb. 8: The United States
gets its first gold medal in figure skating from Dick Button, but
still finishes third in the fifth Winter Olympics in St. Moritz.
Feb. 13: Dick Button becomes the first American skater to win at
the World Figure Skating championships in Davos, Switzerland. May
31: Mauri Rose drives a Blue Crown Special to victory at the Indy
500, with an average speed of 120 mph. June 25: Joe Louis defends
his world heavyweight crown against ``Jersey Joe'' Walcott in an
11-round bout. After the fight, Louis announces his retirement.
July 29-Aug. 14: The U.S. wins 33 gold medals at the Summer
Olympics in London. Aug. 16: George Herman ``Babe'' Ruth dies of
cancer at age 53. October: Stan Musial of the St. Louis Cardinals
wins his third MVP. Oct. 2: Oklahoma's 21-game winning streak in
football begins with a 42-14 victory against Texas A&AMP;M. Oct. 17:
The Chicago Cardinals defeat the N.Y. Giants, 63-35, and the 98
points are the fourth-most in NFL history. Nov. 25: Fred Wendt of
Texas Western scores 42 points in a football victory against New
Mexico State.
1949 Feb. 2: Ben Hogan is involved in a near-fatal car wreck. Feb.
22: George Mikan of the Minneapolis Lakers scores a record 48
points in a 101-74 victory against the New York Knicks. March 12:
The Paschal Panthers win the state boys' basketball title with a
41-40 victory against Milby. April 10: Sam Snead wins the Masters
by three strokes. May 29: Wilson Sporting Goods agrees to sponsor
the formation of the Ladies Professional Golf Association. Aug. 3:
The National Basketball Association is formed when the Basketball
Association of America and a Midwestern league called the National
Basketball League merge. George Mikan's Minneapolis Lakers wins the
first NBA title, 4-2, over Syracuse. He led in the league in
scoring, averaging 27.4 points per game. Oct. 10: Jackie Robinson
is voted World Series MVP, even though his Brooklyn Dodgers lose
the series in five games to the Yankees. Oct. 26: American rodeo
performers are expelled from Switzerland after they become
embroiled in a free-for-all with spectators and police. Forty
performers are escorted to the French border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
