<SLUG> BC-GOLFTOWN-1940s-TEX </SLUG>
 
HOGAN, NELSON HELPED FORT WORTH COME ALIVE AS A SPORTS TOWN IN
1940s 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Sobering updates of Nazi invasions, battle
casualties and global rebuilding efforts dominated front-page
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   But for residents of Fort Worth, a city rapidly building a
reputation as Golftown, USA, a welcome respite from real-world
horrors stood only a sports section away throughout the 1940s.
Southwest Conference football players dominated All-America lists.
The Fort Worth Cats returned to prominence after the war.
</P>
<P>
   And a couple of former caddies from Glen Garden Country Club
held the professional golf world by the scruff of the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Through the exploits of PGA Tour standouts Byron Nelson and Ben
Hogan, a teen-ager from south Fort Worth developed a heady opinion
of his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I lived in the sports capital of the world,'' said
Dan Jenkins, 69, who would go on to a career as an award-winning
sportswriter and author. ``Byron and Ben were just the latest in a
long line of athletes that made Fort Worth a great sports town. But
they were the ones who became larger-than-life figures. As much so,
if not moreso, than Arnold Palmer and Jack Nicklaus ever were.''
</P>
<P>
   John Payne, a longtime Colonial Country Club member who spent
World War II commanding a Navy freighter, recalled arriving at port
throughout 1945 with two objectives. First, he wanted to contact
his wife. Second, he wanted an update on Nelson's winning streak,
which would grow to a tour-record 11 consecutive triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any city that has had two players like those
boys,'' said Payne, 84. ``They made you proud to be from Fort
Worth, especially if you played golf. I think they had an influence
on the city as a whole. They put us on the map. A lot of people
learned about Fort Worth for the first time because of those two.
Being a fan of Hogan and Nelson made you feel like you belonged to
something worthwhile.'' DOMINATING DUO At the height of their
careers, Nelson and Hogan combined to win 67 PGA Tour events from
1944-48 (33 by Nelson, 34 by Hogan). Included were four major
championships _ three by Hogan, one by Nelson _ as well as four of
the six winningest seasons in tour history.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of either man could stop traffic in downtown Fort
Worth. Their triumphs were chronicled in banner headlines. Their
failures, in some ways, were even more newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to the point we were surprised when they lost,'' said
Jerre Todd, 67, who retired in January after 30 years as public
relations director for the Colonial tournament. ``That was more of
a shocker than having them pick up another trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson concluded his career with 52 victories and five major
championships. Hogan won 63 times, including nine majors. On the
tour's career-victory list, Hogan trails Sam Snead (81) and Jack
Nicklaus (70). Nelson is fifth, behind Arnold Palmer (60).
</P>
<P>
   Their names still dot the PGA Tour record book, with most of the
glory years in the 1940s. Nelson's record streak was in 1945, when
he finished with a single-season scoring average (68.33) that has
yet to be duplicated. He ended the year with 18 titles, a mark
likely to stand forever.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan responded in 1946 with 13 victories, the second-highest
total in tour history. With 10 triumphs in 1948, Hogan holds the
No. 4 spot on the season-victories list.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty good mark for a couple of old caddies from
Glen Garden,'' said Nelson, 87, a Roanoke resident. ``It's
something I'm proud of, for both of us. The game came fairly easy
to me. But Ben worked harder than anybody I ever saw to become a
good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan died in 1997, 70 years after he lost to Nelson by one
stroke in the finals of the 1927 Glen Garden caddies' championship.
Neither knew it at the time, but the decade of the '40s would
provide the defining moments in both men's careers.
</P>
<P>
   For Hogan, it was a near-fatal car wreck on Feb. 2, 1949.
Doctors predicted he would not walk again after sustaining a
crushed pelvis, fractured left leg, crushed shoulder and broken
ankle, as well as severe internal bleeding. Yet Hogan walked out of
Merion Golf Club in Ardmore, Pa. as the 1950 U.S. Open champion
after defeating George Fazio and Lloyd Mangrum in an 18-hole
playoff. Hogan's stirring comeback made him a national hero. A
STREAK TO REMEMBER Jenkins recalled the moment he fully understood
the depth of Hogan's single-minded pursuit of perfection, the trait
that drove him to win six of his nine majors after the 1949 crash.
The two had just completed a round at Colonial, with Hogan firing a
bogey-free 66. Jenkins attempted to offer a compliment. Hogan cut
him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `I didn't hit one shot that turned out the way I
wanted it to. If you can play a round of golf and hit three shots
that turn out the way you want, you've had a good round of golf,'
'' Jenkins remembered Hogan saying.
</P>
<P>
   For Nelson, his record-setting 1945 season made him a poster boy
for Wheaties, the self-proclaimed ``Breakfast of Champions.''
Although he understands why others fawn over his 11 consecutive
victories, Nelson said he does not consider that his crowning
achievement as a professional golfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I'm most proud of about my career is winning money
in 113 consecutive tournaments,'' said Nelson, who retired in 1946
with his tour-record mark for consecutive cuts survived, which
still stands. ``Most of those years, they only paid the top 20
places. Everybody wants to talk about 1945, but that 113 gets lost.
And it meant more to me. It meant my swing was repetitive. If I had
a bad day, I didn't let it upset me. I could tough it out and still
be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, Nelson and Hogan proved tough enough to dominate the
local golf landscape in a decade when the city boasted its share of
top amateur players.
</P>
<P>
   Aniela Goldthwaite, four-time winner of the Texas Women's Open,
reached the semifinals of the U.S. Women's Amateur in 1941 and won
the 1940 Southern Golf Association Championship at her home course,
River Crest Country Club. In 1986, she was inducted into the Texas
Golf Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Polly Riley, a six-time Curtis Cup participant, was runner-up in
the 1947 U.S. Women's Open. In 1948, River Crest was the site of
her most historic triumph: Riley defeated Babe Didrikson Zaharias,
10 and 9, in the 36-hole finals of the Texas Women's Open, the most
lopsided defeat of Zaharias' legendary career. Riley was a 1980
inductee into the Texas Golf Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Polly and I played in a big tournament, the Star-Telegram
usually would send someone to go along with us. So people knew who
we were,'' said Goldthwaite, 87, who sailed on the maiden voyage of
the Queen Mary after one of her Curtis Cup appearances in the
1930s. ``But it was nothing like Byron and Ben. They were
celebrities. They made things exciting.'' \Nsubheds:Finished where
he started Arguably, the excitement reached its apex when Nelson
won 11 in a row, shattering the previous tour record of four.
Appropriately enough, the greatest season in professional golf
history ended where it began _ at Glen Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson won his 18th event at the 1945 Fort Worth Open, held at
the course where he once caddied. His winner's check of $2,000
boosted Nelson's season earnings to $13,085, with another $48,689
in war bonds (worth 75 percent of face value).
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Nelson collected 14.5 percent of the total purses
offered at PGA Tour events in 1945. If a player won 14.5 percent of
the purses available in 1999, he would collect $19,096,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made me real happy to wind things up on the course where
I started, where they made me a junior member,'' Nelson said. ``I
really got a big kick out of that. Not many players have ever won a
championship on a course where they worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many cities have ever produced the likes of Hogan and
Nelson, either. Their legacy is such that each has a bridge at
Augusta National Golf Club named in his honor. In Fort Worth,
during the 1940s, they cast considerable shadows as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you weren't a golf fan, you know who they were,'' Todd
said. ``Just like, if you live in Fort Worth, you know who Van
Cliburn is even if you don't know who Beethoven is.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-century later, golfers and golf fans still revere the
names. Ben Crenshaw, the U.S. Ryder Cup captain and a two-time
Masters champion, said they will always hold a special place in his
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up in Texas, those two were always at the top of the
list. They had an ultra-respect,'' said Crenshaw, an Austin
resident. ``Because of what they accomplished, Fort Worth holds a
special place in the game that people still recognize today.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
