A6225 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADVISORY-BILLYPAYNE-C     05-29 0211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVISORY-BILLYPAYNE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION: NEWS EDITORS, NATIONAL EDITORS, SPORTS EDITORS
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service has moved the following story on Atlanta
Olympics Chief Billy Payne in the (a) General news and (s) Sports
categories. Two photos are also available to go with this story. If
you have any questions or need more information, call Cox News
Service in Atlanta at 404 526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BILLYPAYNE-COX _ ATLANTA _ Most everyone knows the legend of
Billy Payne, the intrepid volunteer who gave up everything to win
the Games for his city. Few are aware that Payne never really gave
up his real estate pursuits _ even borrowing money against his land
while chasing his Olympic dream, patiently waiting for the day it
would be worth something big. Fewer still are aware that his two
pursuits collided in 1991, when the Atlanta Committee for the
Olympic Games decided to move its equestrian venue from Stone
Mountain Park to a 1,100-acre site in sleepy Conyers, the county
seat of Rockdale _ minutes from the tracts of property Payne held
an interest in _ despite formidable competition from other
candidates. (Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
