<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS CAN'T GROW 'EM DOWN ON FARM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In big-league cities across the country, Wednesday
is a big, big day. The annual draft of amateur players breathes
life into troubled franchises and lets fans dream about the future
in places that don't really have one.
</P>
<P>
   The recent Baseball Weekly went so far as to put Texas high
school right-hander Josh Beckett, the expected top pick of the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays, on its cover with the headline, ``The Next
Nolan Ryan?''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, it's not that way around here anymore. There were small
pockets of interest when local high school guys like Mike
Lieberthal, Roger Salkeld and Jon Garland were drafted early in the
first round, but they always went to some team far away.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers aren't players in the draft and farm-system arena.
Once they fielded the teams of the 1970s from the 1968 draft, but
only six members of this year's 25-man squad were drafted by the
club. And Eric Young returned only after building his career in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros and Todd Hollandsworth did go on to win Rookie of
the Year awards and Darren Dreifort was the No.2 overall pick in
1993. And the Dodgers have six more players signed from Latin
America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But in the era of big money, expectations are high and the need
for results is quick. It's unlikely you will ever see the Dodgers
built by the draft again.
</P>
<P>
   They don't pick this year until No.37 due to having to
compensate for the free-agent signings of Kevin Brown and Devon
White. That sounds like a decent trade-off. And they only are
drafting that high because the St. Louis Cardinals signed Scott
Radinsky.
</P>
<P>
   You could say the draft hasn't helped the Angels become a winner
or particularly popular even though eight of the 10 expected
opening-day starters, including the DH, were products of their
draft.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a current running through yet another season of
Dodgers underachievement that belies the
``we'll-be-fine-once-we-get-to-know-each-other'' attitude and begs
for a few guys who knew each other back in Great Falls.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds like just another round of baseball's lost
innocence, but it is more than just romantic babble. It's good
business. The theory of building through the farm system, then
supplementing with a trade or free agent is as true now as it was
when the Dodgers got Dusty Baker and Pedro Guerrero by trades in
the '70s and signed Kirk Gibson in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Dodgers not only are a team filled with holes, they
are shackled with huge contracts that have many years to run.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question the Dodgers would love to have some
prospects in their minor-league system, but it's not what you
think. Players like Paul Konerko and Wilton Guerrero were prospects
_ but more importantly, they were the currency for future deals.
</P>
<P>
   It's less important that Albuquerque win the Pacific Coast
League than it used to be. The more young players you stockpile,
the more you have to offer for Curt Schilling or Kevin Appier at
the July 31 trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dodgers got Carlos Perez and Mark Grudzielanek from
Montreal last July, they gave up Guerrero, left-hander Ted Lilly,
Chatsworth's Jonathan Tucker and top outfield prospect Peter
Bergeron. New GM Kevin Malone certainly wouldn't mind having those
players back, if only to make more deals.
</P>
<P>
   Small-market teams want your prospects and the big guys are
willing to give them up to put them over the top. In the new
system, the sad thing isn't that Konerko didn't pan out, but that
the team didn't trade him to Florida for Brown in the winter of '97
when they had the chance. &QL; 
!hair! &QL; 
!ital!
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Sports Editor Matt McHale covers baseball for the Daily
News.!off! &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6326 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-29 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTLEY POUNDS HOME THIS WEIGHTY ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ When Chris Antley, the once and future Kentucky
Derby winner, returned to the races at Santa Anita in February, his
year-long battle with the jockeys-room scale wasn't over.
</P>
<P>
   Though Antley had shed most of the 30 pounds of fat he bore at
the depth of his despair, he still had to strain to get down to 118
on his first day back. On a few afternoons as late as April he
weighed out at 121, forcing his horses to carry as much as seven
pounds over their assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Big problem, right? You'd expect so, especially if you bought
all of those old-school notions about the effect a couple of pounds
of spare baggage have on a racehorse.
</P>
<P>
   But not really. The talented Antley was hired by reputable
trainers who didn't seem to mind the unofficial handicap, and
what's more, he won his share.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still had faith in me,'' said a magnanimous Antley, who
will ride Charismatic in pursuit of the Triple Crown in the Belmont
Stakes on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the weight) didn't matter, because Chris was just riding
unconscious,'' said his friend and rival Gary Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another explanation for Antley's success on the track in
the face of his struggle at the scales last winter: An extra pound
here and there makes little difference to a 1,000-pound horse.
</P>
<P>
   At least, nowhere near the painful difference the same pound can
make to a jockey trying to lose it.
</P>
<P>
   If the lords of thoroughbred racing want to recognize Antley's
1998 ordeal and his amazing '99 comeback, they'll use it as a cue
to relax their death grip on tradition and allow riders to weigh
more.
</P>
<P>
   The human race is getting bigger by the decade. Why not let
jockeys join the party?
</P>
<P>
   The weight a horse carries is assigned in a variety of ways:
according to a chart (the ``scale of weights'') that takes into
account its age and gender and the race's distance and time of
year; according to race conditions made up specially by track
executives; or, in the case of ``handicap'' races, by a track exec
attempting to even up the competition.
</P>
<P>
   If a jockey weighs less than the assignment, lead is added to
the horse's saddle.
</P>
<P>
   A champion handicap horse might have to carry 130 pounds. The
male 3-year-olds in the Triple Crown races all carry 126; fillies
carry 121. The highest any horse was assigned at Hollywood Park on
Saturday was 122. The lowest was 108; because that gelding's
jockey, Alex Solis, weighs 115, the horse had to carry seven pounds
of ``overweight.''
</P>
<P>
   It's in the middle area _ where jockeys must continually slim
down to 114 or so _ that the problems occur.
</P>
<P>
   Antley, who has had his own brushes with drugs, has seen rivals
abuse diet pills in order to ``make weight.'' He has seen them try
dangerous diets that damage their bodies. He has seen old jockeys
whose teeth have rotted away after years of self-induced vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   Antley has known the feeling of getting out of a steam box,
riding a race, and not being able to stop the sweating because his
body is in shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game's not supposed to be that cruel,'' Antley said this
week at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   On a less human level, American racing suffers when gifted young
athletes must pass up careers as jockeys because they can't
maintain riding weights, and when veteran stars leave to ride in
Europe under more lenient rules.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, a Southern California leader for 15 years, begins
riding in his wife's native England next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (weight) is definitely a big factor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who has been riding at 116 here, has told English
horsemen he'll never be less than 118 there, and will usually be
124 or 125.
</P>
<P>
   When Stevens rode in Hong Kong for three months in 1995, he rode
at 122. ``I felt 100 percent better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some stick-in-the-mud horsemen worry that an additional burden
will contribute to injuries for their animals. But there's no proof
that's true.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, what about the benefits of having a healthy,
clear-thinking jockey aboard?
</P>
<P>
   ``One pound for a human being feels like one ounce to a horse,''
Antley said.
</P>
<P>
   About the weight of a bag of candy, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I carried a pack of M&AMP;Ms and went out and ran a mile and a
quarter, I think I'd make it back in about the same time (as
without the extra ounce),'' Antley said. ``Unless I stopped to eat
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, they haven't raised the scale of weights since
1920. In California, there are signs of improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita raised the scale by a few pounds for its recent
winter season, so that in 90 percent of the races, the lowest
weight jockeys would have to make was 118. Del Mar also has
loosened the restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's an awakening to what the jockeys have to go
through,'' Santa Anita and Del Mar racing secretary Tom Knust said
of the attitudes among owners and trainers.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the scale won't solve the problem. You could let jockeys
carry 150, and the natural 155-pounders would be in the sweatbox,
torturing their bodies for the sake of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   But a little bit would help.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the whole scale goes up, nobody's losing and gaining,''
Antley said, ``except maybe in the length of a rider's life.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
