</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGISLATION </SLUG>
 ROUNDUP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TEXAS TAX RELIEF PLAN: SOMETHING FOR EVERYONE, BUT JUST A LITTLE
FOR MOST
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN W. GONZALEZ &QL; 
and POLLY ROSS HUGHES &QL; 
Houston Chronicle Austin Bureau
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A plan unveiled Saturday that grants $506
million in tax relief to consumers and businesses has something in
it for almost everyone, though the bottom line may be merely pocket
change for typical Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Spread among the state's 19 million residents, the relief would
average about $26 per person if the breaks were available to
everyone. Only the proposed sales tax exemptions for Internet
access and over-the-counter medicines and a brief sales tax holiday
on clothing and footwear would keep money in the pockets of average
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, supporters of the compromise said the pact would help
all Texans by easing the tax burden on businesses. Plans call for
granting tax credits to businesses that create jobs, conduct
research and development, process agricultural products or invest
in businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited about this piece of legislation. It's
really good for Texas and it sets us up for the next decade,'' said
House Ways and Means Chairman Rene Oliveira, D-Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate negotiator said the bill should be a boon to small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased about the small business franchise tax
cuts,'' said Sen. Troy Fraser, R-Horseshoe Bay. ``That one creates
a lot of jobs for the small mom-and-pop businesses. That is the
growth engine for our state.''
</P>
<P>
   The compromises embodied in Senate Bill 441 by Sen. Rodney
Ellis, D-Houston, face final votes in the House and Senate today.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the agreement _ at least in terms of dollars _
fairly divides the projected tax-break benefits between businesses
and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers could see $277 million worth of tax cuts while
businesses would gain about $229 million. Here are key features of
the tax-relief plan:
</P>
<P>
   Beginning April 1, 2000, over-the-counter medicine would be
permanently exempted from sales taxes. State fiscal experts
estimate the provision would reduce state sales tax collections by
$161.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also after April 1, a total of three sales tax ``holidays''
would be authorized per year on items priced below $100. This tax
break started out as an attempt to lower costs for back-to-school
shopping; instead, lawmakers left it open to all shoppers, for a
potential consumer savings of $69.3 million in sales tax. The dates
for the holidays have not been set.
</P>
<P>
   The first $25 per month spent on Internet access would be exempt
from sales taxes, a $46.3 million savings.
</P>
<P>
   For businesses, the biggest break _ worth $85.4 million _ would
go to small-income operations. Franchise tax exemptions would be
extended to corporations with gross receipts of less than $150,000
a year.
</P>
<P>
   A tax credit for research and development was worth $64.7
million, with special enhancements for ``strategic investment
areas,'' including the Mexico border. Also, credits for investment
and job creation would add another $68 million to the tally.
</P>
<P>
   A tax credit for businesses that provide day care for employees'
children was valued at $3.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and Senate adjourned until 2 p.m. today, with
both chambers facing midnight deadlines to approve negotiated
settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Any bill taken up in the final hours could easily be killed by
extended debate, along with any other bills waiting for
concurrence. The session ends at midnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the measures still alive Saturday, House Bill 3325 by
Democratic Rep. Pete Gallego of Alpine, would set 80 mph as the
speed limit on rural stretches of certain east-west interstates.
</P>
<P>
   It would also let speed limits rise to 75 mph on many other
Texas highways, ranch roads and farm-to-market roads. The bill
awaited finishing touches by conferees.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Madla, D-San Antonio, said the bill hit a speed bump
because of a related dispute over House Bill 676, which was sent to
Gov. George W. Bush on Saturday for his signature or veto. The
measure would allow semi-trailer trucks to drive as fast as cars,
currently 70 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some concern about allowing big 18-wheelers to go
80,'' Madla said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Saturday, lawmakers approved a bill making an extra $100
million available to state university students with the greatest
financial need.
</P>
<P>
   A provision was added to allow U.S. Army Spc. Steven Gonzales to
qualify for a grant as a former prisoner of war.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, a former student at Texas A&AMP;M University, is the
Huntsville man who was held captive by Serbs for more than a month.
On a final vote of 142-2, House Bill 713 by Rep. Henry Cuellar, was
sent to the governor for his signature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
