<DOCNO> NYT19990529.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6418 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANNEXATION-HNS &LR;      05-29 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANNEXATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL REFORMING HOW TEXAS CITIES EXPAND EXPECTED TO PASS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Residents in Kingwood and Clear Lake won't get a
vote on disannexing from Houston after all, but House and Senate
lawmakers said Saturday they hope city officials got the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the entire bill sends a lesson to the city,'' said
Sen. Jon Lindsay, R-Houston. ``I think it's a very good bill and I
think we need these provisions, such as requiring a long-range
plan, and I think it will eliminate some of these arguments we
have, in Houston especially.''
</P>
<P>
   A final version of Senate Bill 89, a comprehensive rewrite of
cities' annexation powers and responsibilities, is expected to win
passage from lawmakers by the close of the 76th Legislature on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate conference committee members worked out the
final version of the bill Saturday, and stripped an amendment added
last week in the House authorizing voters in Kingwood, Clear Lake
and other areas to disannex from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Although not unexpected, even lawmakers who supported the
amendment said they were surprised it progressed as far as it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you just have to make a statement,'' said Rep.
Jessica Farrar, D-Houston, and chair of the local delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Farrar was among 30 House lawmakers who supported the
disannexation amendment. Unlike the Republican bloc that
consistently opposes the city's annexation policies, the 30 votes
on the amendment included those from both parties representing
areas throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Orlando Sanchez, who chairs the city's
Legislative Affairs Committee, said he supports the final bill and
the reforms it embraces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this session has been used as a sort of
message-sending venue, and that is that the areas outside the city
are not happy with annexation,'' Sanchez said. ``We've gotten the
message, and I think with this bill there will be some relief for
the people out in the rural communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the bill seeks to correct inherent imbalances that
favor cities in the annexation process, in part by empowering
residents to negotiate aspects of annexation through arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bill imposes numerous new requirements on cities'
procedural handling of annexation, it would not restrict their
ability to annex.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Fred Bosse, D-Houston, sponsor of the bill in the House and
a member of the conference committee that resolved the final
version, said he is satisfied with the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of compromises made, and I don't think
anybody got everything they wanted out of the bill,'' Bosse said.
``But I think we've got a very progressive piece of annexation
legislation, and set the road map for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill includes a series of new checks and balances in
annexation procedures aimed at protecting the interests of
residents while still allowing cities to expand their boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, cities would be required to publicly maintain
long-term annexation plans. Specifically, outlining three years in
advance its plans for annexing territory.
</P>
<P>
   Cities would have 2{ years to begin providing full municipal
services to an annexed area, instead of the current 4{ years. More
time could be granted by mutual agreement of the city and targeted
area.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous safeguards are included to protect residents' services
after annexation, including a preannexation inventory to determine
the extent and quality of services in their community.
</P>
<P>
   A provision of the bill specific to Houston would require the
city to provide services in an annexed area comparable to what was
in place prior to annexation. Following the city's annexation of
Kingwood in 1996, many residents complained the quality of their
services declined.
</P>
<P>
   The city also would be prohibited from imposing any fees in an
annexed area that are also not imposed on city residents.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would allow strategic partnership agreements in
lieu of annexation, but stipulates such an agreement would have to
provide equitable benefits to both sides _ rather than just a
mechanism to avoid annexation.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also provides many more requirements for public notice
and public hearing, including supplying notice to a home buyer of
the potential for annexation and posting of the three-year
annexation plan on a city's Internet Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Although the inclusion of arbitration in the bill is aimed at
giving residents in targeted areas more voice in ensuring their
future quality of life, some concern still exists that arbitration
could be abused by opponents to intentionally slow the process.
</P>
<P>
   Still, backers said there are sufficient protections to provide
that future annexations do not replicate situations like
Bordersville, an area near Humble and the Bush Intercontinental
Airport that lacked adequate services years after it was annexed by
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the bill contend it does not go far enough, and short
of allowing residents in targeted areas to vote, the bill still
gives the major advantage to cities in the annexation process.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Kyle Janek, R-Houston, was among those who voted to allow
Kingwood and Clear Lake to disannex by referendum. Janek said he
has been frustrated by the city's ``heavy-handed'' tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Janek said city officials should not be able to annex an area
just for the revenue benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my feeling they shouldn't cherry-pick, they should go for
large areas and take the good with the bad,'' Janek said.
</P>
<P>
   Farrar echoed his concern, saying Houston's future annexation
efforts should target areas that need services, rather than areas
such as Kingwood that offer additional tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Farrar and others also cited concern about successive
annexations of affluent, Anglo communities by the city of Houston
and the effect it could have on minority voting strength.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, Senate Bill 89 will be the most complete overhaul
of statewide annexation policy in 36 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
