<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-MAPLELEAFS     05-29 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-MAPLELEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES' SUDDEN SURGE LEAVES LEAFS ON THE BRINK  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Pat Quinn, coach of the Toronto Maple Leafs,
worried before the Eastern Conference finals about how his team
would respond to its lofty status. After failing to make the
playoffs for two consecutive seasons, the Leafs had reached the
third round and felt good about themselves. But they had to face
the Buffalo Sabres, who lost last year in this round and vowed that
they had learned from their experience.
</P>
<P>
   Those foreshadowings seemed to be borne out Saturday night as
the Sabres took control of the series with a 5-2 victory at Marine
Midland Arena. Buffalo leads this series by three games to one, and
another victory will put the Sabres in the Stanley Cup finals for
the first time since 1975, when they lost to the Philadelphia
Flyers. Game 5 of the four-of-seven-game series will be Monday
night in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will meet either the Colorado Avalanche or the Dallas
Stars for the championship. Their Western Conference series, tied
at two victories each, will resume Sunday afternoon in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres got two goals from Geoff Sanderson and one each from
Dixon Ward, Brian Holzinger and Rob Ray. Dominik Hasek, Buffalo's
healthy-again goalie, stopped 31 of 33 shots, losing his shutout
early in the third period when Mats Sundin scored on a penalty
shot. Sundin also scored on a power play with 1 minute 57 seconds
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But the Leafs, who played respectably in the first three games,
performed terribly Saturday night, embarrassing themselves with
unforced errors and unprovoked penalties. Toronto goalie Curtis
Joseph was replaced by Glenn Healy after two periods with Buffalo
leading by 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's game was played in a raucous atmosphere, with
about a quarter of the fans cheering for the visiting Maple Leafs.
On a warm evening on a holiday weekend, spectators began arriving
several hours before the opening face-off, roaming the downtown
streets dressed in the sweaters of both teams and holding parties
in the parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   The cities are about two hours apart by car, and some Toronto
fans brought their national flag, waving it and singing their
national anthem on the sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Although they share a peaceful border, Canada and the United
States are two nations separated by a common language, the odd
referendum in Quebec notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek was back in Buffalo's goal for the second consecutive game
after missing the first two games of the series with a groin
injury. He did not have much to do early as the Sabres took the
first eight shots and the Leafs did little right.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's Tie Domi took an unprovoked obstruction penalty for a
run at Ray, Buffalo's veteran ruffian, and another Toronto penalty,
to Kevyn Adams, overlapped it by 19 seconds when he interfered with
Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   But when Hasek did a similar thing to Mike Johnson and got
penalized, it did not matter. During the Toronto power play, Hasek
got one of the assists when Ward put the Sabres up by 1-0 on a
short-handed goal. Ward chased down a loose puck at the Toronto
blue line and blasted a slap shot from the right-wing circle past
Joseph on the glove side.
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs continued to damage themselves, next with a roughing
penalty to Steve Thomas with 68 seconds left in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the period, when Garry Valk of the Leafs had his
stick on the puck, all alone in the Buffalo zone after a Sabres
turnover, he fell down, for no apparent reason. The Leafs were
lucky to be trailing by only 1-0 at the first intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto was ready to leave via Queen Elizabeth Way when it gave
up three goals in the first six minutes of the second period,
leaving the Sabres with a 4-0 lead and a 20-8 edge in shots.
</P>
<P>
   A Leafs turnover helped set up Holzinger's unassisted goal at
2:51. Ray, whose previous playoff goal came five years ago, made it
3-0 at 5:04 by turning in a shot while parked in front of the net
alongside the stationary Aleksandr Karpovtsev. Sanderson made it
4-0 just 22 seconds later, off the rush. Sanderson got his second
goal of the game at 14:10 during a Toronto turnover festival.
</P>
<P>
   With the red light flashing behind Joseph, Leafs defenseman
Bryan Berard rose from his knees, skated to the net and swung his
stick over the crossbar, breaking the shaft.
</P>
<P>
   With 11 seconds left in the period, Toronto's Thomas tried to
knock Rhett Warrener into the boards in front of the Buffalo bench.
He missed and rammed his own head into the wall, lying there dazed
until a trainer went to treat him. The period ended with Domi
trying to start a fight with Ray, and Ray ignoring him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
