<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6421 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      05-29 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAKE UP AND SMELL THE VERDICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzz. Huh? Whaa? Oh, sorry, I musta nodded
off. I was having a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   I dreamed I was in a room at the Maricopa County courthouse
while a guy who stabbed his wife 44 times, dumped her body in the
family pool, then hid the evidence tried to convince a jury to let
him off because he was sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   Really.
</P>
<P>
   In my dream the defendant, Scott Falater, hires a high-priced
mouthpiece to pitch this Wes Craven fairy tale to 15 helpless souls
in the jury box, hoping they'll release him.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Michael Kimerer, tells jurors that Scott is a loving
husband and good father who'd never do such a horrible thing on
purpose, and therefore the only possible explanation is that
Falater dispatched his wife while he was catching 40 winks.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in this case, 44.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that Yarmila Falater may have interrupted her
husband while he was in a somnambulistic trance and, his lawyer
said, ``He immediately went into a rage, a total frenzy, and
stabbed her 44 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Without waking up.
</P>
<P>
   Then, while continuing his visit to the land of nod, Falater
managed to locate a pair of gloves, put them on, drag his wife's
body over to the family pool, roll her in and hold her head under
water.
</P>
<P>
   And even that didn't interrupt his homicidal siesta.
</P>
<P>
   He then packed the knife, bloody clothes and more into a plastic
container, carefully wrapped it in a garbage bag and hid it in the
wheel well of his Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor then saw him walking around the house, and watched
him wash his hands.
</P>
<P>
   The defense attorney says Falater was under stress at work, and
was bothered as well because his pool pump was broken. He says his
client walked in his sleep to the pump, picked up the knife and
probably was startled by Yarmila. &QL; 
EXPERTS CAN EXPLAIN IT
</P>
<P>
   He's planning to bring in experts who'll testify that this
actually could have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this doesn't explain why his client didn't wake up as
his wife screamed for 30 minutes. The neighbors heard her. She had
self-defense wounds on her hands.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over and Falater supposedly learned what had
happened, his lawyer says he was ``devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   Which makes it difficult to explain why he showed so little
emotion during his taped police interrogation.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't asleep then, after all.
</P>
<P>
   An average guy waking up to find out that his beloved wife had
been brutally murdered might shed a tear or two.
</P>
<P>
   He might wail.
</P>
<P>
   He might collapse in sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Falater did none of this. &QL; 
TOSSED A SISTER
</P>
<P>
   Still, his lawyer says, he was sleepwalking. Supposedly, a
sister will testify that Falater tossed her across a room during a
sleepwalking episode 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What about recently?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps if Falater had gotten into an altercation with a record
store clerk who didn't believe he was sleepwalking when he
purchased a John Tesh album, his story might be easier to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, why would a sleeping man hide evidence? Unless he did
so after he woke up, and panicked.
</P>
<P>
   But then, why would an innocent man hide evidence?
</P>
<P>
   Falater's own children, ages 15 and 17, didn't know about their
father's supposed problem until after their mother's death, until
he needed an alibi.
</P>
<P>
   The ``sleepwalking'' defense will get you on the front page of
the paper, on all the TV news shows and maybe even into the
monologue of some late night talk show. It's impossible to hold off
on the jokes, at least at first, at least until you peel away the
wackiness and find beneath it the remains of Yarmila Falater.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's not funny anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Then you imagine yourself as a juror being asked to let a man
walk away from the body of a woman with 44 knife wounds.
</P>
<P>
   And you hear yourself saying, ``In your dreams.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
