<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-BLAZERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS OUTLAST TRAIL BLAZERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The last time these locals breathed such a sigh of
relief, Santa Anna had just pulled out of town and begun marching
toward Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting off several charges by the Portland Trail Blazers
yesterday at the Alamodome, the San Antonio Spurs finally escaped
with an 80-76 win in Game 1 of the Western Conference finals when
Rasheed Wallace's game-tying jumper bounced off the rim with about
five seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to see a guy that's rolling like that get a shot like
that,'' Spurs center David Robinson said. ``We kind of held our
breath and were a little bit lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   In a predictably ugly game between two of the league's best
defenses, Wallace kept Portland close with a game-high 28 points,
most coming on low-post moves over first-team all-defensive forward
Tim Duncan. But with his team trailing 78-76 and Robinson onto him
for the first time all game, Wallace settled for a 20-foot,
left-wing jumper off a pick-and-pop with guard Greg Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was good,'' said Wallace, whose Blazers will try
to avoid falling into an 0-2 hole an Game 2 at 4:30 p.m. tomorrow.
``But what can I say, it came up short.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy: ``That's a high-percentage
shot for Rasheed. I'd put money on that every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the NBA's irregular season and rugged series, the
game was a walk-it-up eyesore that had the crowd of 35,165 yawning
at times. Time and again the Spurs would push the lead to seven or
nine points, only to have Wallace knock down consecutive baskets.
</P>
<P>
   He so abused Duncan that, on the game's key possession, Spurs
coach Gregg Popovich gambled and switched Robinson onto him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to give him a different look, maybe a little
more length to shoot over,'' Popovich said. ``Of course if that
shot goes in, I look like an idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   Down by two, the Blazers actually had two chances to tie or take
the lead in the final minute. But Anthony, a late-game replacement
for Damon Stoudamire because of his experience, dribbled into a
24-second shot clock violation before audibling into the
pick-and-roll with Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Though Wallace had most of his success posting up, Anthony
sensed Robinson overplaying the post and called for his teammate to
set a pick on Spurs guard Avery Johnson. When Robinson briefly left
Wallace to help stop his baseline drive, Anthony whipped a
behind-the-back pass to an open Wallace. After the miss, Mario Elie
sealed San Antonio's eighth playoff win in nine games by sinking
two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tit for tat the whole way,'' said Popovich, whose team
committed seven turnovers. ``Neither team did anything amazing to
the other. We just played our butts off and hung in there.''
</P>
<P>
   With fans toting corny homemade signs and the rested Spurs
taking advantage of Portland's hangover from a topless mosh-pit
celebration 48 hours earlier against Utah, San Antonio threatened
to blow the game open by jumping to a 15-4 lead. The volatile
Blazers almost imploded when center Arvydas Sabonis, unable to
guard Robinson, began yelling at teammates, and Wallace picked up a
technical arguing a correct goaltending call.
</P>
<P>
   But, steadied by Wallace and the Spurs' pathetic shooting,
Portland regrouped and produced a dramatic, if not thrilling
climax.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be any blowouts in this series,'' Robinson said.
``Both teams are just too good and too deep to let that happen.
It's going to be like this every game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
