<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON'S PLANS TAKE A LEFT-HAND TURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dodgers manager Davey Johnson talked in spring
training about breaking up the right-handed bats in the lineup by
splicing in left-handers, but injuries and a lack of production
have severely hampered the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lefty Todd Hollandsworth spent three weeks on the disabled list
and now has a strained rib cage, and switch-hitting Jose Vizcaino
is on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   The only reliable left-handed bat belongs to pinch-hitter Dave
Hansen, and his role is too valuable to be changed.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is hoping the situation will right itself with the
current group of Dodgers. But if it doesn't, it could be time for
the Dodgers to shop for a left-handed bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things need to be tweaked,'' Johnson said of his current
crop of players before Saturday's game against Atlanta.
``Offensively, we've not jelled like I would have liked to.
Situationally, we need to be better. I'd still like to get a little
more balance in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we don't need more balance in the lineup, but I don't
know of any team in the past that was all right-handers and won (a
championship).''
</P>
<P>
   Switch-hitting Devon White leads off, followed by righties Eric
Young, Gary Sheffield and Raul Mondesi. When switch-hitting Todd
Hundley catches, he usually bats fifth _ followed by another string
of three righties and the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers lefties are hitting .286 with 10 homers, but without
Hansen's 9-for-18 pinch-hitting expertise figured in, they're
hitting .275.
</P>
<P>
   Among those are White and Hundley, who are hitting .257 and
.254, respectively, from the left side. Hundley was supposed to be
the main source of power but has just five homers and 14 RBI. His
numbers are hampered by not playing much in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Dodgers are 25-23 and trail Arizona by three games in
the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   But when Johnson was asked whether the Dodgers had enough talent
to reach the championship level management talked about early in
the season, he said: ``I hope so. For (the players') sake and a lot
of other good people's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the consensus is the Dodgers panicked and fired
pitching coach Charlie Hough after starting the season below
expectations, Johnson said he remains calm and patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not panicked about this team and I'm not discouraged about
this team,'' he said. ``A few injuries have made it tougher. I
haven't gotten the number of quality starts I thought we'd have,
but I think they will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Vizcaino return delayed: One thing Johnson misses is the
versatility offered by Vizcaino, who's been on the disabled list
since May 19 (retroactive to May 17) with a hamstring strain.
Vizcaino was hoping to join the Dodgers in Pittsburgh and be
activated Tuesday, but Johnson said that is no longer the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Vizcaino is still having trouble swinging from the
right side and is only jogging.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't make the trip to Pittsburgh,'' Johnson said. ``It's
looking more like Friday (against the Angels). He has to have
better days running.''
</P>
<P>
   Home cookin': The Dodgers' trip to Atlanta allows pitcher Kevin
Brown to stay at his Macon, Ga., home _ about 70 minutes from
Turner Field _ and spend time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a chance to see my son's graduation (Friday),'' Brown
said of 8-year-old Ridge's ceremony upon finishing second grade.
``It's nice. It's great to be there for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown planned to attend his son's baseball game Saturday before
his family joined him at Turner Field for the Dodgers-Braves game.
Brown faces Braves right-hander Greg Maddux in the finale of a
three-game series today.
</P>
</TEXT>
