<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS CAN ERASE GHOSTS OF FRUSTRATIONS PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Mavericks' last honest boogie in the NBA playoffs
came 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the Rangers' most recent postseason showing in Arlington,
they neglected to score a run.
</P>
<P>
   Think back. How long has it been since a truly meaningful and
memorable postseason game _ not involving Nate Newton _ has been
played in our metropolitan area?
</P>
<P>
   Too long.
</P>
<P>
   But today on a frozen slab of ice, where Derek Harper once
misread the scoreboard and let the clock run out against the
Lakers, the Stars will try to wake up the Reunion Arena echoes and
make some memories.
</P>
<P>
   Game 5 of their NHL Western Conference finals series with the
Colorado Avalanche is fraught with intrigue and possibilities. Win,
and Fort Worth-Dallas fans are on the threshold of their first
Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Lose, and it's Harper running out the clock all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Cowboys, perennial NFL postseason performers that they
once were, have played only two Super Bowl-or-bust football games
at Texas Stadium since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Think back. The Mavericks were the hottest thing going in town
in the mid-1980s. But on May 6, 1984, with a chance to knot the
Mavs' conference semifinal series at two apiece, the rookie Harper
thought the game was over and that the home team had won by one.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks ended up losing in overtime, 122-115, and the
Lakers whisked them from the playoffs two nights later in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Some people think the ghosts haven't left the premises since.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, lest we forget, have never won a postseason game in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Memorial Day weekend. The local hockey team's Stanley
Cup chances have never shined brighter. The stage is theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be a day to remember, or just another one to forget?
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom would tell you that the Stars have the upper
hand by being able to host two of the would-be final three games of
this series. But home ice has been anything but sacred to both the
Stars and the Avs.
</P>
<P>
   In front of a well-behaved and only sporadically boisterous
crowd in Denver's McNichols Sports Arena, the Stars never appeared
uncomfortable, even goaltender Ed Belfour when Avs faithful were
chanting his name.
</P>
<P>
   But recent history suggests that when the Avs pack a suitcase,
they bring along no fears.
</P>
<P>
   Think back. The last time that the NBA Mavericks won a playoff
game at home was June 2, 1988. The Cowboys last won one 2 1/2 years
ago. The Rangers have never won one.
</P>
<P>
   Wait. In the summer of 1987 at Reunion, the Dallas Sidekicks won
a memorable Game 6 to force a seventh and deciding game in the
Major Indoor Soccer League finals.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Preki and Steve Zungul? I didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, it's been a long, dry decade, as far as
home-court, home-ice, home-field playoff memories are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars thought they were going to have one almost exactly one
year ago _ a Game 5, Western Conference finals, at Reunion Arena.
They won, even. But they had already effectively dug their graves
in the previous two games at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Game 5, as it turned out, was fun, but quickly forgotten in the
din of Joe Louis Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It would likely be accurate, if unfair, to suggest that the
Stars have never played a home game with such consequence _ and I'm
talking about the Stanley Cup possibilities. It's important,
because the Stars need to feed the bandwagon. It's growing . . . in
some ways, still learning . . . and the Stars are on the verge of
finally marking their territory, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   They have the front page to themselves. The whole holiday picnic
table. In the throes of a playoff fever like this, a lifetime fan
can be made.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, you wonder. Have the Mavericks put an eternal spell on the
place? On Memorial Day weekend, will the Stars go crashing into the
wall?
</P>
<P>
   They shouldn't. The Stars' defensive persistence, coupled with
Ed Belfour's magic touch, make them still the favorites to survive
today and, in time, this series.
</P>
<P>
   But think back. How many memorable home playoff ticket stubs do
you have in your collection?
</P>
<P>
   I thought so. Shoot, Derek Harper, shoot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
