<SLUG> BC-GRADUATION-GUNSHOW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN SHOW NEXT TO GRADUATION EXERCISES DRAWS COMPLAINTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It was an unusual mix Saturday at the Fort
Worth Convention Center: graduating high school seniors in the west
wing, gun dealers in the east wing.
</P>
<P>
   As crowds streamed in, some carried caps and gowns into the
commencement hall and others toted unloaded pistols, rifles and
assault weapons into the gun show nearby.
</P>
<P>
   And in the wake of the shooting massacre at Columbine High
School in Colorado, not everyone was pleased that the city of Fort
Worth had booked a gun show next to graduation ceremonies for
Boswell High School during the day and Granbury High School in the
early evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's weird that, after all the shootings (at schools),
there's a gun show going on right next door to where we're
graduating,'' said Granbury senior Dedra Benitez, 17.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall at the gun show, vendor Dave Lee said the students
and their ``soccer moms'' should not be upset. ``I have my rights,
too, and I don't think I've done anything wrong,'' Lee said as he
sat behind a table full of handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Mayor Kenneth Barr said Saturday night that he did
not know that a gun show had been booked into the same building as
school graduation ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, ``I raised the issue several weeks ago that I
was not totally comfortable with leasing our facilities for gun
shows, and I continue to have my reservations about that.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 20, two students killed 12 schoolmates, a teacher, and
then themselves at Columbine High School in a Denver suburb. At
least some of the guns used in the rampage had been purchased at a
gun show in Denver, sparking a national debate on whether easy
access to weapons at such shows is partly to blame for a spate of
deadly school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Since the attack at Columbine, the Senate passed a bill
requiring background checks on everyone who buys a firearm at a gun
show. The House is scheduled to take up a similar bill in June.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth school district officials have stepped up security
and used metal detectors at this year's commencement ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   At the convention center Saturday, Kay Hague of Granbury said
she walked through a door expecting to find directions on how to
get to her son's graduation. Instead, Hague said, she saw a burly
policeman standing next to a large sign that read: GUN SHOW.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of shocking. I was taken aback,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Mekalip of Tyler said she was not happy that assault
weapons were being sold close to where her niece, a Granbury
senior, was about to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of unsettling to know that someone can get a gun
over there and come over here. They shouldn't be side by side. It's
inappropriate timing,'' Mekalip said.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a table covered with black-steel Glock pistols,
dealer T.R. Graham said concerns about the gun show were ``very
much unfounded'' and caused by ``ignorance brought about by media
hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Norman, coordinator of the gun show, said that, for the past
five years, he has held such events at the convention center
alongside high school commencement ceremonies. Until Saturday,
Norman said, nobody complained.
</P>
<P>
   He said he cannot help it ``if people are making something out
of this because of Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman said he also moved his show a little farther from the
main entrance to the graduation ceremonies ``so those kids could
not look through the glass doors and see the guns.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
