<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC DEFEATS PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They turned people away from Dedeaux Field before
the most important USC baseball home game in eight years Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the intrepid souls weren't denied when the stadium
reached capacity; they went atop a three-story parking garage
beyond the right field fence to watch the Trojans beat Pepperdine
5-3 in a thriller. Those fans got high marks for their creativity,
but it was the 2,384 in the grandstand who get partial credit for
USC's win.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the biggest crowd all year and definitely the
most intense,'' said Justin Gemoll, USC's first baseman who drew a
bases-loaded walk in the eighth inning with USC fans standing and
cheering. ``Especially in that at-bat, (the crowd) gets inside the
pitcher's head a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   USC, the defending national champion, needs to win only one of
two games played today in the double-elimination tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The standing-room-only crowd, USC's largest since the Trojans
played Pepperdine in the 1991 regional, was energetic throughout
the game, but especially in the crucial eighth. That's when the
Trojans (35-23) took a 4-3 lead on Gemoll's walk from Pepperdine
reliever Richard Sundstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Sundstrom also walked the next batter, Greg Hanoian, and the
Trojans fans cheered every pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge help to have a crowd behind you like that,'' USC
catcher Eric Munson said. ``I'm definitely grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   So was USC left-hander Barry Zito, the Pac-10 pitcher of the
year who gave up two runs and five hits in the first two innings.
Zito (12-2) settled down in the middle innings and was given a
standing ovation after retiring the side in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our crowd really helped me,'' said Zito, who has won 11
consecutive games. ``(The fans) really got behind me. They were a
huge advantage for our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Zito tried to stay loose in the bottom of the eighth when USC's
rally reached the 30-minute mark. The Waves used three pitchers in
the inning, and they issued four walks.
</P>
<P>
   Zito walked Austin Evans with one out in the ninth and was
replaced by Steve Smyth, who got Woody Cliffords to hit into a
game-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine coach Frank Sanchez didn't use All-American closer
Jay Gehrke in the eighth. Gehrke, who has 18 saves and a 0.62 ERA,
stood in the bullpen as the rowdy crowd rattled Dave Reed, who
walked one and gave up a hit, and Sundstrom, who didn't get an out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to get outs,'' Sanchez said. ``Unfortunately, a
couple of our guys, who have been clutch all year, at that point
struggled. We were just trying to put out the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waves (44-15) played their second consecutive game without
starting shortstop Tony Garcia, who pulled a hamstring in practice
Thursday. Garcia is hitting .320 with 10 home runs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
