u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-TRAILBLAZER     05-29 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-TRAILBLAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLACE HAD A LOOK, BUT SPURS SEE A 1-0 LEAD  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ There were seven seconds left in the opening game
of the Western Conference final Saturday night, and the San Antonio
Spurs were ahead by 2 points. But David Robinson, the Spurs'
center, was afraid.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, having slid away from his man to help out a teammate,
was near the baseline, and Portland's Rasheed Wallace, the hottest
player in the Alamodome, was alone inside the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace had torched the Spurs and their formidable frontcourt
all night, scoring 28 points on jumpers, hook shots and wicked,
jaw-dropping dunks. Now he was 20 feet away from the basket,
releasing a jump shot with picture-perfect form.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson knew the chances of Wallace hitting it were great.
``Boy, when a guy is rolling like that you hate to see him get a
look at the basket like he did,'' Robinson said. ``But we were
lucky that it went off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, who capped their 80-76 victory over the Trail Blazers
with two free throws by Mario Elie, might have been lucky near the
end, but their victory was not a result of chance. It was the
fourth time in five meetings this season that the Spurs outlasted
Portland in the final moments. This one gave them Game 1 in the
four-of-seven-game series. Game 2 is Monday afternoon. ``As one
might expect, it was a war,'' Spurs Coach Gregg Popovich said.
``Neither team dominated the other. We just went after each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   With Wallace, Robinson and Tim Duncan, the Spurs' candidate for
the most valuable player award, scoring more than anyone else, the
best battles were waged near the basket. Duncan, who entered the
game having outdone Shaquille O'Neal in San Antonio's four-game
sweep of the Los Angeles Lakers, quickly took a back seat to
Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-11-inch Wallace, who came off the bench for most of
the season before becoming a starter in the playoffs, scored 8
points in each of the first three quarters, then hit two 9-footers
in the final three minutes to chop 4-point deficits in half.
Duncan, a first-team all-league defender, had no answer for
Wallace. ``He's a monster,'' Popovich said of Wallace. ``With that
size, strength, quickness and touch, he's a handful. He's a great,
great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, it looked as if Wallace's notable temper would spare
the Spurs. Three minutes into the game, he was whistled for a
technical foul after arguing a call. The Blazers were playing
terribly, having already committed two turnovers. But Wallace's
outburst lifted his teammates, and soon thereafter Portland went on
a 13-3 run to cut an 11-point deficit to 1, 18-17.
</P>
<P>
   The clubs were never separated by as much as 10 points the rest
of the way. Duncan, bridled by the physical defense of Brian Grant,
who got plenty of help from his teammates, started slowly. He had
just 7 points and four rebounds at halftime, but with Robinson and
Sean Elliott scoring 10 points apiece, the Spurs took a 39-38 lead
into the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Portland's quick traps and athleticism had bothered Duncan in
previous meetings _ they held him to 13 points in the team's last
regular-season game _ but he solved their defense in the second
half to match Robinson with 21 points. He also grabbed a game-high
13 rebounds and blocked 5 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Consecutive layups by Duncan followed by a 15-footer by point
guard Avery Johnson put San Antonio ahead by 69-60 midway through
the final quarter. But the Blazers rallied again. Two backups, Greg
Anthony and Walt Williams, were the catalysts, combining for 10
points, including 6 on 3-pointers, to move the Blazers to within 3
points.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs increased the lead to 4 points twice, but each time
Wallace answered with short jumpers, the last of which cut San
Antonio's lead to 78-76 with 1 minute 40 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   After both teams committed turnovers, Portland ended up with the
ball and a chance to tie or go ahead with 20 seconds remaining.
Mike Dunleavy, the Blazers' coach, made the easy decision to run a
two-man game between Wallace and Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   When Anthony drove to the baseline, drawing Robinson away from
Wallace, the Blazers got the shot they wanted. ``I thought it was
good,'' Wallace said. ``The minute it left my hand, I thought it
was good. Unfortunately, it came up short.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
