</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ADAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN ADAMS, 85, EXPERT ON BRAIN DISORDERS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Edwin Adams, a California neurosurgeon and pioneer in the
use of radioisotopes to study brain functions and their disorders,
died on May 18 at the medical center of the University of
California at San Francisco. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Adams was the former Guggenheim Professor of Neurological
Surgery at the university. He gained an international reputation as
an expert on Parkinson's disease, cerebral palsy and epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
   He assembled an interdisciplinary team at the medical center to
treat such diseases, as well as intractable pain, with stereotactic
surgery, which focuses on specific groups of cells in deep-seated
brain structures that control specific functions.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, a descendant of the presidential Adams family, was born
in Berkeley, Calif., and graduated from the University of
California there in 1935. He received a master's degree at Harvard
University in 1939 and was training at Brigham and Children's
Hospital in Boston when war broke out.
</P>
<P>
   He served with the Marines in the Pacific as a battalion
surgeon. He was at Guadalcanal and aboard the first American ship
to enter Tokyo Harbor after the Japanese surrender.
</P>
<P>
   He resumed his training at the University of California at San
Francisco, joined the staff of the department of neurological
surgery in 1948 and rose to chairman in 1970. He retired from
teaching in 1984 but remained active as a researcher.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Sally Patterson Adams, died in 1995 after 60 years of
marriage. He is survived by two daughters, Abigail A. Campbell, of
Woodside, Calif., and Susan A. Engs, of Reno; a son, Henry P., of
Camarillo, Calif.; a sister, Cornelia A. Lonnberg, of Noce, France;
8 grandchildren; and 12 great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-99 2346EDT &QL; 
