</P>
<P>
   Brace, $25.) A man with cancer returns to the eastern
</P>
<P>
   Washington of his youth to commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   12. JOINING, by Johanna Lindsey. (Avon, $24.) In 13th-
</P>
<P>
   century England, a woman gradually changes her feelings
</P>
<P>
   about her partner in an arranged marriage.
</P>
<P>
   13. BITTERSWEET, by Danielle Steel. (Delacorte, $26.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman copes with a midlife crisis: Should she continue
</P>
<P>
   to raise a family or should she pursue her old career?
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) BEYOND THE GREAT SNOW MOUNTAINS, by Louis L'Amour.
</P>
<P>
   (Bantam, $16.95.) Ten short stories ranging from
</P>
<P>
   the Old West to Hollywood to Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE BEST AMERICAN SHORT STORIES OF THE CENTURY, edited
</P>
<P>
   by John Updike and Katrina Kenison. (Houghton Mifflin, $28.)
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-five stories published since 1915.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. EVERY MAN A TIGER, by Tom Clancy with Chuck Horner.
</P>
<P>
   (Putnam, $27.95.) The novelist and a retired Air
</P>
<P>
   Force general examine the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE GREATEST GENERATION, by Tom Brokaw. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) The lives of men and women who came
</P>
<P>
   of age during the Depression and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   3. TUESDAYS WITH MORRIE, by Mitch Albom.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $19.95.) A sportswriter tells of
</P>
<P>
   his weekly visits to his old college mentor,
</P>
<P>
   who was near death.
</P>
<P>
   4. BETRAYAL, by Bill Gertz. (Regnery, $27.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A reporter charges that the Clinton administration
</P>
<P>
   has undermined America's security. (b)
</P>
<P>
   5. BELLA TUSCANY, by Frances Mayes. (Broadway, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   An American writer recalls a spring and summer spent
</P>
<P>
   in the romantic sections of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   6. YESTERDAY, I CRIED, by Iyanla Vanzant. (Simon &AMP;
</P>
<P>
   Schuster, $22.) A counselor recalls how she turned
</P>
<P>
   painful experiences into feelings of hope.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE CENTURY, by Peter Jennings and Todd Brewster.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $60.) An account of the 20th century,
</P>
<P>
   complete with photographs and first-person narratives.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE ART OF HAPPINESS, by the Dalai Lama and Howard
</P>
<P>
   C. Cutler. (Riverhead, $22.95.) What Buddhist doctrines
</P>
<P>
   and common sense tell us about dealing with everyday
</P>
<P>
   problems.
</P>
<P>
   9. ALL TOO HUMAN, by George Stephanopoulos. (Little,
</P>
<P>
   Brown, $27.95.) The former adviser to President Clinton
</P>
<P>
   recalls his years in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE LEXUS AND THE OLIVE TREE, by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $27.50.) A journalist explains
</P>
<P>
   the instant electronic global economy.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) BUSINESS (AT) THE SPEED OF THOUGHT, by Bill Gates with
</P>
<P>
   Collins Hemingway. (Warner, $30.) The chairman of
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft discusses how new technology is changing the
</P>
<P>
   ways business is done. (b)
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) NO ONE LEFT TO LIE TO, by Christopher Hitchens.
</P>
<P>
   (Verso, $19.) A journalist's critical view of the public
</P>
<P>
   and private life of Bill Clinton. (b)
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) THE MAJORS, by John Feinstein. (Little, Brown, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist's account of the 1998 Masters, U.S. Open,
</P>
<P>
   British Open and PGA golf tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   14. SHY BOY, by Monty Roberts. (HarperCollins, $30.)
</P>
<P>
   The rapport that developed between a wild mustang and
</P>
<P>
   a professional horse trainer.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) COMFORT FROM A COUNTRY QUILT, by Reba McEntire.
</P>
<P>
   (Bantam, $19.95.) The country music star tells how she
</P>
<P>
   balances the demands of her career and her family.
</P>
<P>
   16. (x) WAKE UP, I'M FAT! by Camryn Manheim. (Broadway, $23.)
</P>
<P>
   The memoir of a television actress who has long contended
</P>
<P>
   with obesity and its stigmas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. CONGRATULATIONS! NOW WHAT? By Bill Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   (Hyperion, $15.95.) The television star offers advice
</P>
<P>
   for new college graduates.
</P>
<P>
   2. SUZANNE SOMERS' GET SKINNY ON FABULOUS FOOD,
</P>
<P>
   by Suzanne Somers. (Crown, $24.) A diet regimen
</P>
<P>
   to help people lose weight and remain healthy. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. SUGAR BUSTERS! by H. Leighton Steward et al.
</P>
<P>
   (Ballantine, $22.) A diet designed for losing
</P>
<P>
   weight, increasing energy and combating disease. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. ONE DAY MY SOUL JUST OPENED UP, by Iyanla Vanzant.
</P>
<P>
   (Fireside/S&AMP;S, $13.) How to raise one's morale and
</P>
<P>
   realize one's ambitions. (b)
