<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-29 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6457 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-LAWMAKERS-TEX     05-29 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-LAWMAKERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST TEXANS IN CONGRESS SPEAK FROM EXPERIENCE ON GUN ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When talk in Congress turns to guns, most Texans
don't just shoot from the lip. They come to the debate armed with
plenty of hands-on experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a bunch of guns,'' said Rep. Ralph Hall, D-Rockwall,
whose well-stocked gun cabinet is fairly typical of the 30-member
House delegation from Texas. ``If I laid them all out, I could have
held off one corner of the Alamo.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``Star-Telegram'' survey of Texans in Congress found that at
least 21 of the 30 House members and both Texas senators own
firearms. Some own many.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan fondness for firepower highlights the
complexities of the gun control debate as the House prepares to
take up Senate-passed restrictions requiring safety locks on
weapons and background checks for all gun show sales. The House is
expected to vote on a gun control package in late June as part of a
bill aimed at curbing juvenile violence.
</P>
<P>
   Although Democratic Party leaders like to characterize the
debate as a fight against Republicans and the National Rifle
Association, the battle lines are not so clear-cut in congressional
districts where the most common form of gun control is a steady
hand and a sharp eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my area of East Texas, just about everybody owns some kind
of gun. It's just part of the culture, part of life,'' said Rep.
Jim Turner of Crockett, one of five Texas Democrats who received
NRA contributions in the last election.
</P>
<P>
   The tradition isn't restricted to rural areas. Three of the four
House members whose districts include portions of Tarrant County
own weapons
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody in Texas has one, don't they?'' said Rep.
Kay Granger, R-Fort Worth, who keeps a pistol for self-protection
but does not accept NRA contributions.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Irving acknowledged that he
stretches the facts a bit when he tells audiences that if he ever
imitated President Clinton's personal behavior, he would find
himself looking up at his wife from a pool of blood while she
asked, ``How do I reload this thing?''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Armey said, his wife knows how to use her 20-gauge
shotgun, part of a family collection that includes a 12-gauge
shotgun, two rifles and a .45-caliber pistol.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Barton, R-Ennis, whose district includes Arlington and
Northeast Tarrant County, owns a shotgun and a rifle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know lots of people that keep loaded pistols and
semiautomatic weapons underneath their beds,'' Barton said. ``If
everybody kept a loaded gun in their house and knew how to use it,
we wouldn't be as violent a society.''
</P>
<P>
   The exception to the rule is Rep. Martin Frost, D-Dallas. But
Frost said he still has the medals he earned as an NRA marksman at
summer camp when he was a child.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of gun ownership among Texas lawmakers is even higher
than the rate among the voters they represent. A recent Texas poll
found that 53 percent of Texans have a gun in the house. Nearly a
third have more than one. The gun-owning tradition cuts across
racial, ethnic and gender lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up around pistols and rifles,'' said Rep. Charles
Gonzalez, D-San Antonio, whose father, former Rep. Henry B.
Gonzalez, had a habit of giving his sons .22-caliber rifles for
their 12th birthday. ``It's part of the Texas culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Eddie Bernice Johnson, D-Dallas, said she sometimes joined
her father on his hunting trips as a girl, although she never
developed a fondness for guns.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, who owns ``several shotguns and a
couple of handguns,'' has hunted doves with the state's senior
senator, Phil Gramm. ``I learned to shoot in summer camp. I was a
great shot,'' she said. ``I'm not as good now. Phil is a great
shot. I would be good if I did it more.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Houston, nephew of former Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen, had some of his first experiences with guns at his
grandfather's South Texas ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather had probably five guns in his car because a
deer might come up or you might need to a shoot a snake or
something like that,'' he said. ``I grew up around guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Max Sandlin, D-Marshall, who estimated that he has 15
firearms, has started teaching his 4-year-old son how to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   But some lawmakers' gun-related memories are not so pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-San Antonio, said he bought a .357-caliber
Magnum several years ago when his wife, a San Antonio TV
anchorwoman, was the target of threats.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Sessions, R-Dallas, took the same step when his
father, William Sessions, a former federal judge who later became
FBI director, was placed under 24-hour protection in the aftermath
of the 1979 assassination of U.S. District Judge John Wood of San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my right, and I'm not going to tell you what I've
got,'' the Dallas congressman said. ``I am a gun owner and I do
carry.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Sessions sometimes carries a gun for protection in his
Capitol Hill neighborhood, he said he never brings a weapon into
the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Barton saw the downside of the state's gun culture in one of his
previous jobs as manager of a printing plant in Crockett.
</P>
<P>
   His duties included dealing with a disgruntled, gun-wielding
employee; a jealous husband who came to the plant intending to
shoot his wife's boyfriend; and a woman who shot out the window of
her boyfriend's car _ with him inside _ in the plant parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Two Texas Democrats, Silvestre Reyes of El Paso and Solomon
Ortiz of Corpus Christi, wore guns daily in their previous careers
in law enforcement. Reyes was a Border Patrol agent. Ortiz was a
sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I packed a gun for many years. You get used to it,'' Ortiz
said. ``Without it, you feel naked.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ciro Rodriguez, D-San Antonio, said he bought a shotgun
years ago after his home was burglarized twice. On the third time,
the burglar stole the shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, two of the most ardent defenders of the right to
bear arms do not own any guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once my right to own a gun is threatened, I'll buy one. That's
when it will be necessary,'' said Rep. Ron Paul, R-Surfside.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Houston, is also unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally am very afraid of guns,'' Archer said. ``I don't
trust myself with a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, whose district is in East Texas, is at the other extreme.
He has so many guns he has lost count. His collection includes a
double-barreled, pistol-grip shotgun that was once owned by outlaw
Cole Younger, an ally of Jesse James.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got guns all over. I'm sure I haven't told you about all
of them,'' Hall said, after ticking off a list of more than a dozen
shotguns, rifles and pistols. ``I've got three sons. It would
probably take me two weeks to collect all my guns from them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hall said he is troubled by the spread of handguns,
especially when they are used against children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to admit that handguns give me some concern,'' he said.
``There's really no good answer for a mother who's lost a son to a
gun. That's a tragedy that never ends.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite their strong support for gun ownership, most Texas
lawmakers say they are willing to consider new restrictions in the
aftermath of the April 20 massacre at Columbine High School in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, voters in Southeast Texas tossed veteran Rep.
Jack Brooks out of office for support of the ban on assault
weapons. Despite that history, gun-owning Rep. Nick Lampson,
D-Beaumont, said he may support the Senate package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seriously concerned about what I see happening today that
didn't happen when I was young,'' Lampson said, referring to the
wave of school shootings. ``I think perhaps the whole country has
become more accepting of gun control.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
